(8, 45, 'Farmsecure Energy / Basil Read Energy', '27826730514', 'Werner van Wyk', 'Avanti South Block', '1', 'Carl Cronje Drive ', 'Tygervallye', 'Cape Town', '8001', 'werner.vanwyk@farmsecure.co.za', 'Lomati Energy', 'The Lomati Energy 9.59 MWe Biomass Project is a co-generation project which will feed into the Eskom grid.  The project will utilize waste wood chips, sawdust as well as off-cuts from the sawmill.  Additionally, waste wood from existing plantations will be collected and utilized to generate electricity to be sold under the medium term risk mitigation program as issued by the Department of Energy.\r\n\r\nThe Lomati Sawmill is located within the town of Barberton, approximately 43km south of Nelspruit and 360km to the east of Johannesburg, located in the Mpumalanga Province. The site is located at 25°46’16.25”S and 31°02’19.91” E.\r\n\r\nThe fuel specifications are: \r\n•	Biomass Price (Rand/ton): 190\r\n•	Biomass Feed (wet ton/day): 320\r\n•	Moisture Content: 40%\r\n•	Lower Heating value (MJ/kg as received): 10.57\r\n\r\nThe design output/objective of the plant is:\r\n•	8.73 MWe net/salable power into existing grid ~9.59 MW generated power\r\n\r\nThe total electricity that will be available for sale is 69 862 684 kWh per annum. The plant will commission in the first quarter of 2015. The income, in 2015, from the electricity generated and steam produced will be approximately R100 million at a selling price of R1.16/kWh (2013) and R90 per ton steam. The escalation for the electricity price is linked to the consumer price index (CPI) of 5% per year. The all inclusive total capex will amount to R242 million for this co-generation project and the annual operating expenses and cost of sales will be R46 million (2015, 5% annual growth).\r\n\r\nThe following direct agreements and approvals are in place:\r\n•	Long term Lease agreement on the Lomati Sawmill\r\n•	Long term Biomass Supply agreement for 100 000 ton/annum based on a Lower \r\n        Heat Value of 10.57 MJ/kg      \r\n•	Pre-Engineering Procurement, Construction and Commissioning agreement with KC Cottrell for the power island (off-shore)             \r\n•	Heads of Terms agreement for the Engineering, Procurement and Construction (on \r\n        shore) with Basil Read Matomo   \r\n•	Heads of Terms agreement for the Operation and Maintenance of the energy    \r\n        generation facility\r\n•	Positive Record of Decision on March 2012 for the waste management license application from the Department of Economic Development, Environment and Tourism (DEDET)\r\n•	Eskom approved grid connection point\r\n•	Signed Termsheet with Basil Read Energy for the equity investment into four\r\n        biomass to energy projects \r\n•	Debt Termsheet from Investec based on 70% gearing\r\n', 'Cogeneration', 'Integrated', 'BiomassCurrent', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '10', '10', '8.73', '79.7', '1.23', 'CPI Inflation (5%)', '', '46.7%', '', '', 'Quater1', '2015', 'EPC committed to 16 months from date of signature to commissioning.  Additional 2 months included to reach financial closure.', '18', 'baseload', '', '', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', ' 242', '20', '1230.00', '', 'CPI Inflation (5%)', 'yes', '', 'fastQ2-2013-24Month', '', '2', '18', 'Farmsecure Energy / Basil Read Energy JV', 'KC Cottrell', 'Basil Read Matomo', 'KC Cottrell', 'Basil Read Energy develops, funds, owns, operates and maintains utility scale power generation and energy storage assets in Africa.  As an integrated energy company Basil Read Energy believes that the key to electrical power generation in Africa is through utilising the renewable and other primary energy resources available in the region to create truly sustainable, efficient and cost effective power plants to provide electrical power to the African continent (company profile attached).\r\nBasil Read Energy flagship projects in the energy projects in Africa are:\r\n• Metrowind Van Stadens Wind Farm (27 MW) – under construction, COD February 2014\r\n• Beaufort West Photovoltaic Solar Plant (75 MW) – under development, COD Q1 2015\r\n• EOS Furnace Off Gas Power Plants (2 x 30 MW) – under development, COD Q3 2015\r\n• Biomass fuelled cogeneration plant (20 MW) – under development, COD 2015\r\n• Hydro 1 (4 MW) – under development, COD 2015\r\n• Hydro 2-4 (3 x 10 MW) – prefeasibility, COD 2016\r\n\r\nBasil Read Matomo is a leading design, project engineering, procurement and construction (EPC) company servicing the minerals processing, chemical and renewable energy sectors. We offer the full range of turn-key solutions for project implementation, ranging from concept development and feasibility studies through to final project execution. BRM has extensive experience in the practical implementation of projects including multi-disciplinary engineering, design, procurement, construction, project management and commissioning. We also offer post-implementation operating services (company profile attached)\r\n\r\nKC Cottrell is a global leader in Green technologies and flue gas cleaning as well as state of the art environmental technologies and engineering capability (company profile attached).', '400000', '7000000', '16000000', 'yes', '', '', '', '', 30, 'All un-skilled labour for the power plant will be sourced from the surrounding historically disadvantaged communities.  The project will further increase job opportunities for un-skilled labour as it is required for the harvesting and transportation of biomass to the power plant.  Job opportunities will be created at two levels: permanent jobs and through community involvement.  Permanent jobs will consist of truck drivers and biomass collectors, around forty jobs will be created at this level.  In addition it is envisaged that around sixty opportunities for self employment will be created in the surrounding informal sectors, where the community may collect biomass an earn an income.  This opportunity is linked to a Broad Based Black Economic Empowerment (BBEEE) initiative. The Proposed Lomati Community Trust will be a shareholder in the project on behalf of the community, where benefits from the trust will contribute to development programmes identified in the Municipal Integrated Development Plan. Between 1% and 2% of the project turnover is to be spent on economic and enterprise development which will result in more support to SMME’s, investment into community health, education and infrastructure development, and general improvement in the economy of the Umjindi Municipality. \r\n\r\nFurthermore, any enhancement of the sustainability of the forestry industry has a positive socio-economic effect on the region.  Additional economic activity generated by greater utilization of the biomass will contribute to the rural economy through increased income levels and greater employment.  Personnel reside in the rural communities in which the power plant is located.  This means that dividends, profits, higher-paid salaries, business skills, technical skills and entrepreneurial skills are retained in the local rural economy and contribute directly to further economic activity in the otherwise impoverished rural economy. \r\n\r\nIt is understood that the capacity for power delivery from the Eskom network is restricted and will be for some time to come. Due to the connection via the Umjindi power network, the surplus power generated in the proposed power plant will be available for consumption within the Umjindi Municipal grid. With appropriate electrical protection and islanding devices the new plant will provide security of supply to critical services during Eskom power disruptions. The envisaged islanding capability will also keep the saw mill in operation during power disruptions so that it can continue to supply fuel to the plant. Additional electricity capacity within the grid will also assist in providing electrification to the water works plant, sewerage plant, residences and businesses that currently remain without electricity or are affected by regular outages. ', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', '3', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', '01/12/2014', 'yes', '01/12/2014', 'yes', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '3', 'project', '', 'no', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'no', '', '3', '', 'finalised', 'yes', 'Yes. Lomati Energy will utilize plantation residues from forestry operations and sawmill residues from sawmill operations as feedstock for the power plant.  To evaluate the biomass availability for the plant, Sappi has compiled the following biomass assessment report: “Estimation of available biomass on Sappi land close to Lomati sawmill”.  With the planned expansion from 180 000 m3 timber processing per year to 240 000 m3 of timber intake at the Lomati mill, more than 90% of the biomass will be supplied accross the fence making this an ideal location for an energy generation facility and integration with the mill operations.\r\n\r\nThe municipality of Umjindi will supply the Lomati Energy project with water under the existing water use registration certificates issued by the Department of Water Affairs.  A desktop study for water supply to the Lomati project was compiled by BSL Mpumalanga Consulting Engineers. The documentation relating to the Water Court orders is also attached to the desktop study. \r\n\r\nNo additional studies are likely to be required by any lenders.\r\n', 'Barberton, Mpumalanga, South Africa', '31', '2', '19.73', '25', '46', '15.81', 'yes', 'Long term  lease agreement has been signed and attached. Site map included and attached. No additional rights and site location is required.', 'yes', 'yes', '', 'no', '', '', 'no', '', '', 'The Lomati Energy Project has received a positive Record of Decision on March 2012 for the waste management license application from the Department of Economic Development, Environment and Tourism (DEDET).  For the waste management license application it was necessary to undertake a Basic Assessment and to submit a Basic Assessment Report to DEDET  \r\n\r\nThe municipality of Umjindi will supply the Lomati Energy project with water under the existing water use registration certificates issued by the Department of Water Affairs.  A desktop study for water supply to the Lomati Energy project was compiled by BSL Mpumalanga Consulting Engineers. The documentation relating to the Water Court orders is also attached to the desktop study.\r\n\r\nFarmsecure Energy has engaged with Nersa and has reached a stage where the Power Purchase Agreement (PPA) needs to be submitted to Nersa by Farmsecure Energy in order to start the 120 day generation licence finalisation and award period.', '1', '31', '2', '34.22', '25', '46', '15.39', 'Lomati substation', 'no', '', '', '', 'ESKOM grid connection is not applicable as the connection will be within the Umjindi Municipal grid. Umjindi municipality will allow the Lomati Energy project to connect into the local grid.', 'No upgrades required.  Load study has been concluded.', 'Connecting to Umjindi Municipal grid', '4', 'Not applicable. Project within the borders of South Africa.', '75-85', '100', '41.32', 'The project will create opportunities for local South African manufacture companies that can supply the project with fuel handling systems, water treatment plant, condenser set, HV electrical system, LV electrical, MCC''s instrumentation and controls, piping, valves and on-site reticulation.  Local South African companies also have the opportunity to do all civil works, shipments, local transport and the grid connection for the project.  ', '65', 'The project will create opportunities for local South African companies to be contracted to do maintenance on imported and local equipment.  All un-skilled labour will be sourced from the surrounding rural communities.  Employees will be trained over a period of two years under the supervision of O&M manager to eventually run the plant together with the O&M manager.  ', '2013-06-21', '2013-07-11', 'true'),
