(10, 34, 'Nerina Burger', '0113815775', 'Nerina Burger', 'Hans Merensky', '9', 'Eton Rd', 'Parktown', 'Johannesburg', '2193', 'nerinab@hmh.co.za', 'Weza Biomass', 'The project entails a 15MW biomass to energy project, situated on the site of an existing softwood sawmill.  Waste from the saw mill will be the raw material for the project.', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '2013-06-21', '0000-00-00', ''),
(11, 55, 'Colenso Power (Pty) Ltd', '0828784824', 'John James', 'c/o Steve Leach, SIVEST', '51', 'Wessel Road', 'RIVONIA', 'N/A', '2128', 'johnj@inala-energy.com', 'Colenso Power', 'The Colenso Power Project is a fully integrated coal mine-to-generator project, utilising fuel from its own resources as well as from nearby independent established mining operations.\r\n\r\nIt will be situated east of and near to the town of Colenso and the Blaaukrans Eskom 275kV transmission substation in Kwazulu Natal.\r\n\r\nThe project will be developed in at least 2 phases dependent on the opportunities afforded by the Department of Energy. \r\n\r\nThe first phase will be a 300 - 350 MW baseload generator utilising either FBC technology or super critical PC with Arch fired Boiler in order to provide flexibility of quality of coal supply, efficiency of power production and to cater for the high calorific values and low volatile content of the fuel resources available.\r\n\r\nThe second phase will be another 300 - 350 MW baseload generator.\r\n\r\nThe main cost drivers are: cost of fuel, capital cost, exchange rate and to a lesser degree, the interest rate on debt. By utilising access to our own fuel resources, we are able to lessen the impact of the fuel cost. We anticipate that we can to some degree control the capital cost (we have one of China''s largest developers of power stations as our partner in development and O&M).There is little we can do about the exchange rate, but the interest rate has some degree of flexibility.\r\n\r\nWe are proceeding with development through bankable feasibility, detailed design, EIA and the obtaining of ancillary licenses and approvals completely on risk as we believe the location is strategic for stability of the provincial grid, and the local government and communities in and around Colenso need the project to proceed to enable economic empowerment and general social development. \r\n\r\nAs far as we are concerned, the only next decision points will occur when a PPA is negotiated and the terms of financing from third parties.\r\n\r\nThe project will have a high level of BBBEE and BEE corporate ownership to facilitate the community development process.\r\n\r\n', 'Thermal', 'Coal', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '350', '350', '320', '90', '0.36', 'PPI on fuel, water and sorbent inputs', '41%', '', '', '', 'Quater3', '2017', 'Assumes, loan finance agreements in place prior to signature and ROD for EIA.', '42', 'baseload', '', '', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', '6224', '25', '790', '', 'Fuel, water, sorbent , chemicals, diesel according PPI or other agreed. Labour costs etc.', 'yes', '', 'commitQ2-2014-Phased', 'Q1/2 2014 Fast track with commitment and COD Q3/4 2017', '6', '42', 'Colenso Power Joint Venture', 'Shandong Electric Power Corporation & Foster Wheeler', 'Industrial Development Corporation', 'Shandong Electric Power Corporation - SEPCO', 'SEPCO (Profile included): Accumulated installed capacity of 116,000 MW. International projects completed outside of China: 28 projects with 28,000 MW of installed capacity. Power stations completed in 9 different countries: India, Sudan, Hong Kong, Bangladesh, Nigeria, Saudi Arabia, Jordan, Brazil, Oman. Currently building a total of 16,400 MW in: India, Saudi Arabia, Zambia, Egypt, Mongolia, Indonesia, Malaysia, Pakistan and Brazil. Colenso Power''s team consists of Mott MacDonald, (who has engineered over 100,000MW of power plants around the world, going back to their first major projects in the late 1890s) and Cresco Project Finance (who have completed and/or currently are, providing project development assistance to 22 power projects in the Southern African region including 4 baseload power stations).', '29000000000', '44000000000', '44000000000', 'yes', '', '', '', '', 40, 'BBBEE structures still to be finalised. IDC will finance these.', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'no', 'yes', 'no', 'no', '3', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', '01/03/2017', 'no', '', 'yes', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '3', 'project', '', 'yes', 'no', 'no', '', '', '', '4', '', 'none', 'no', 'More drilling, Engineering and Planning work is required from both suppliers in order to satisfy lenders. Additional work will be completed by Q2 2014. Both fuel suppliers have to update mining plan and reserve statement to the standards required by the international and local lenders.', 'Colenso Kwazulu Natal', '29', '57', '41.3', '28', '31', '45.5', 'yes', 'Site is owned by local community and also falls under mining lease area. The local community BBBEE structure will be a shareholder of the power station in exchange for the land. This will be completed this year. Site Plan attached.', 'no', 'yes', '11/07/2013', 'yes', '30/11/2013', '30/06/2014', 'no', '', '', 'Water use, Waste water, Air Emmision, Roads  building and upgrading, Mining, Use of Rail. Heritage and Biodiversity. Grid Connection, Transmission corridor.', '9', '29', '52', '17.45', '28', '43', '54.36', 'Bloukrans', 'no', '', '', '', 'Numerous meetings with Dr D. Gampel - GM New Business at ESKOM - since 2009. Initially, ESKOM wished to JV with us, but were unable to. Acknowledged by them that our location is strategically important (vital, even) for grid stability and capacity on the provincial grid.', 'Other than the link up, we have not been advised of anything.', 'ESKOM', '36', 'South Africa', '75-85', '1620', '30.00', 'Roads, housing, security, transmission, civils, structural, conveyors, haulage, water pipeline, reservoir, treatment and disposal, ash disposal.', '1000', 'Local maintenance of most things. Training facilities and programmes for artisans, technicians, engineers. Educational and medical facilities.', '2013-06-21', '2013-07-11', 'true'),
(12, 59, 'Tongaat Hulett Limited', '083 265 6628', 'Wolfgang Fechter', 'Tongaat Hulett Head Office', '1', 'Amanzimnyama Hill road', 'Tongaat', 'Tongaat', '4400', 'wolfgang.fechter@tongaat.com', 'Amatikulu Biomass Fired Power Station', 'Historically sugar mills were designed and are currently operated on the basis that the fuel supply (sugarcane fibre) is matched with the demand for steam and electricity.  The sugar mill has its own power plant (boilers and turbo-alternators), which uses all of the bagasse fuel (sugarcane fibre) to generate steam.  This steam is used to generate electricity for use by the mill, and exhaust steam from this process is used to provide heat for the sugar manufacturing process.  Combined Heat and Power (CHP), or Cogeneration, and has been the standard for sugar mills for decades.  \r\n\r\nIn order to take advantage of the opportunities presented by electricity generation from sugarcane fibre, a project is proposed to establish a new power station, with the objective to export the maximum amount of electricity.  The project is planned for the Amatikulu sugar mill owned by Tongaat Hulett Limited.  The project includes the improvement of the energy efficiency of the sugar mill in order to make more fuel available for electricity export.  Additional biomass fuels in the form of sugarcane leaves and other woody biomass will be included to extend the utilization of the power station.\r\n\r\nRefer to the attached supporting documents for a more detailed description of the project.', 'Cogeneration', 'Integrated', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '105', '69.7', '95', '48.9', '0.92', '78% of fuel cost at index reflecting agricultural escalation and 22% of fuel cost at index reflecting South African electricity escalation.  Other operating costs indexed at agreed engineering indices.', '', '23.3', '', '', 'Quater2', '2018', 'COD will be aligned with the start of the sugar crushing season which is typically in the beginning of April every year.', '36', 'none', '8.3', '252', '24', 'no', '', 'yes', 'The existing PPA with Eskom is based on the premise that only the marginal cost of generation is rewarded and is applied to marginal spare capacity from the sugar mill available for limited operating periods.', 'yes', 'The project constitutes an improvement of the energy efficiency within the boundaries of the sugar mill, hence generating more fuel for electricity generation.  The existing power station will be replaced with the latest technology option to take advantage of all the biomass fuel available and converting it as efficiently as possible to steam and electricity.', '5179', '20', '2160', 'Not Applicable', 'Full Indexation of all parts of the tariff based on appropriate indices', 'yes', '', 'fastQ3-2013-36Month', 'The current project schedule indicates a 39-month period from signature of PPA to COD.  There is a real expectation that it will be possible to reduce this schedule.', '6', '36', 'Tongaat Hulett Limited', 'Actom John Thompson (Power Station boilers); Siemens AG (Power Station turbines); Tongaat Hulett (sugar mill efficiency)', 'Not Applicable', 'Not Applicable', 'Project Developer (Tongaat Hulett Limited)\r\nFor a complete company profile visit www.tongaat.com.\r\nCogeneration is standard operation at sugar mills.  Tongaat Hulett has the experience through many years of operating and maintaining biomass power stations at their 4 South African sugar mills and their sugar mills in Mozambique and Zimbabwe.\r\nTongaat Hulett Limited also has been designing sugar mill processes and equipment for almost 3 decades and markets their technology internationally.\r\n\r\nTechnology Providers\r\nActom John Thomson and Siemens AG are reputable suppliers power generation equipment for many years in South Africa and internationally.\r\n', '14373000000', '12081000000', '9681000000', 'yes', '', '', '', '', 18, 'Socio-Economic Development within the context of Tongaat Hulett operations forms an integral part of the businesses activities, and is closely linked to the company’s overall objective of contributing to the creation of successful rural communities.\r\nThe business has traditionally focused its SED spend on improving the quality of life of communities that surround company operations and its employees. Tongaat Hulett is now in the process of shifting this focus, to its private farmers. This shift, which is ongoing, will ensure that private farmers receive the support required for them to be sustainable into the future, and includes actions related to unlocking land for sugarcane development and grant funding from Government.\r\nA number of small scale growers derive their livelihood from delivering sugarcane to the sugar mill operating close to their agricultural operations.  Tongaat Hulett has many years of experience in developing successful indigenous private farmers.\r\nRefer to the supporting document (section 6, section 8 and Appendix II) for more detail on community involvement in the ownership structure as well as enterprise development and socio-economic aspects.', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'no', '4', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', '01/03/2018', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'yes', '', 'no', 'The sugar mill is currently able to supply 90% of the planned bagasse fuel. The sugar mill portion of the project will ensure the supply of the balance. Feasibility studies on the supply of cane leaves and woody biomass indicated no significant concerns. Section 5 and App V has detail on biomass supply.', '1 March 2018', 'Refer to Sugarcane Development in Section 5 & Appendix V', 'Refer to Sugarcane Development in Section 5 & Appendix V', '6', 'project', '', 'no', 'yes', 'yes', 'no', 'yes', '', '6', 'yes', 'finalised', 'yes', 'Experienced Legal and Financial Advisors has been involved for a considerable amount of time.  Studies that would typically be required by Lenders, have either been completed or are at an advanced stage.  Section 4 and Appendix I of supporting documents has the relevant detail.', 'Amatikulu, District of Umlalazi, KZN', '31', '31', '33.85', '29', '02', '43.62', 'yes', 'The site is owned by Tongaat Hulett Limited:\r\n1.  The remainder of farm Lot 54 Amatikulu, No. 13916\r\n2.  The remainder of farm Lot 55 Amatikulu, No. 13917\r\n3.  Sub 1 of the farm Lot 55 Amatikulu, No. 13917\r\nA Rental and Services agreement will be utilized to arrange for the use of the site by the (to be formed) SPV company wholly-owned by Tongaat Hulett.\r\n', 'yes', 'yes', '', 'yes', '01/05/2013', '01/11/2013', 'no', '', '', '*The Department : Rural Development and Land Reform have verified that there are no claims for restitution lodged in respect of the properties.\r\n* The Record of Decision (ROD - EIA) for the Amatikulu Mill Site (Biomass Renewable energy Facility) has been granted by and received from the National Environmental Affairs Department.\r\n* The Act 70 of 70 application for the off channel Dam Area has been granted by and received from the National Department of Agriculture Forestry and Fisheries.\r\n* The Act 70 of 70 application for the Mill Area has been submitted to the National Department of Agriculture Forestry and Fisheries\r\n* The KZN Planning and Development Application has been submitted to the Umlalazi District Municipality and will result in the zoning of the site. \r\n*Permitted Water Use Verification - application has been submitted to DWA (at their request) to verify the existing water use in respect of abstraction (DWA Register No. 21069175) and re-use of effluent for irrigation of sugarcane (DWA Register No. 21188894).\r\n*The minerals application to Department of Minerals is being finalized.', '0.1', '31', '31', '28.18', '29', '02', '49.57', 'Upgraded Amatikulu 88/6.6 kV S/S', 'yes', '15/08/2011', 'yes', 'Cost Estimate Letter Amatikulu 20120921 as Appendix VII in hard copy document.', '2011: Regular engagements with Eskom Eastern Distribution (EED) regarding the conceptual proposal\r\n2011/08/15 - Application for Cost estimate letter submitted\r\n2011/09/15 - Meeting with EED Master Network Planner and others\r\n2011/11/18 - Cost Estimate Letter received\r\n\r\n2012: Regular interaction regarding timing of project\r\n2012/06/25 - Meeting with EED to discuss commencement of Budget Quotation\r\n2012/09/21 - Revised Cost Estimate Letter received from Eskom\r\n2012/12/06 - Payment made of R1 406 551.86 for Budget Quotation to be provided\r\n\r\n2013: Regular interaction to commence work for provision of Budget Quotation and commence EIA for connection\r\n2013/05/14 - Meeting with Eskom Eastern Distribution to discuss progress\r\n2013/05/30 - Eskom appointed Environmental Consult to commence EIA process\r\nOngoing interaction with Eskom Eastern Distribution (EED) and Grid Access Unit (GAU)\r\n\r\nThe estimated grid connection time is 30 months (as per Cost Estimate Letter).  The Budget Quotation process commenced early to reduce this in order to accommodate the project timing.', 'No transmission upgrade required for project.\r\nEskom is upgrading the distribution line from 88/132 kV as part of their planned refurbishment project.\r\nThe existing 88kV line feeding Amatikulu Sugar Mill will be rebuilt to 132 kV Double Circuit (6 km) by Eskom as part of their planned refurbishment.\r\n', 'Eskom', '30', 'Not Applicable', '75-85', '3185', '61.50', 'Most civil and mechanical construction will be done locally.  Turbo-alternators will be the most significant imported component.  Boilers will be manufactured locally.  The percentage local spend stated in the submission, is the minimum expected with definite upside potential.  It should be noted that the most significant portion of the job creation relates to the agricultural supply of sugarcane to be processed to bagasse fuel (for every 3.5 additional hectares planted, 1 job is created.  The supporting document (Section 6 & App II) has detail on the Economic Development aspects of the project.', '5649', 'A significant portion of equipment will be manufactured locally.  It will support and build on existing manufacturing skills in South Africa.', '2013-06-21', '2013-07-11', 'true'),
(13, 63, 'Koch Engineering & Construction', '+351210456370', 'Christian Somborn', 'Torre Oriente, Piso / ', '37', 'Av. do Colégio Militar', 'Lisboa', 'Lisboa', '1500', 'c.somborn@kecpro.com', 'IPP', 'IPP', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '2013-06-21', '0000-00-00', ''),
(14, 64, 'Pieter Colyn', '0825538844', '0825538844', 'Green Environmental', '28', 'Marula Street', 'Dowergen Ext 5', 'Edenvale', '1610', 'rpcolyn@telkomsa.net', 'Blue Waste to Energy Mogale City', 'Blue Waste to Energy entered into an agreement (with all required signed contracts in place) with the Mogale City Local Municipality for:\r\na) The right to 550 000 tons of municipal solid waste at the Luipaardsvlei Landfill Site;\r\nb) Land adjacent to the Luipaardsvlei landfill site for the processing of waste and the generation of electricity from the solid waste;\r\nc) An electricity take-off agreement for the Phase 1 / 8 mWh delivery\r\n\r\nThe Phase 2 portion of the project will deliver 64 mWh or electricity. No take-off agreement has been signed with either the municipality or any other institution at this stage. \r\n\r\nEnvironmental Authorisation  / EIA  has been obtained from the Department of Environmental Affairs (Pretoria).\r\n\r\nThe take-off agreement between Blue Waste to Energy and the Mogale City Local Municipality is currently with the Minister of Energy for ratification and final licensing by NERSA. This authorisation is the final authorisation required before the project may officially commence.\r\n\r\nWhat makes the Blue Waste to Energy system unique?\r\nThe Blue Waste to Energy System DOES NOT INCINERATE AT ANY GIVEN TIME and therefore the process being followed does not generate any CO2 or any other harmful emissions into the receiving environment. The system is totally GREEN in its application.\r\n\r\nWhat does the Blue Waste to Energy system use?\r\nThe system utilises any material matter that is carbon based. So if the product has the ability to "burn" then that product may be used. Therefore the system has the ability to utilise all household solid waste; sludges from waste water treatment plants; old tyres; medical waste; industrial waste; paper; cardboard; plastic etc. \r\n\r\nWhat by-products are generated by the system?\r\nThe system utilises a system whereby all waste is gasified to hydrogen and super heated steam The super heated steam and hydrogen is used to turn special turbines that generate electricity.The hydrogen eventually forms water again and as such the process produces a good amount of distilled water. As there is no incineration the process does not generate any bottom ash. However all carbon based products contain natural salts and these salts are collected during the process as a by-product. The salts are harmless and may be used as a fertilizer in the agricultural field. \r\n\r\nWhat about metals and glass?\r\nDuring the waste separation process the separation system removes glass; metal and building rubble into separate waste stream. These waste streams can then be sold off to recycling companies that collect waste metal and waste glass. Building rubble is used as landfill cover at the landfill site or may be utilised as an aggregate in the making of of cement bricks. \r\n\r\nWhat is the power generation capacity of the system?\r\nThe Blue Waste to Energy System is a modular system that may be adapted to the actual size of a landfill site and the tonnage of solid waste being deposited on site. A single unit utilises 4 tonnes of sorted waste and generates 8 mWh of electricity. At the Mogale City Landfill Site will have a total of 9 units installed with a combined generation capacity of 72 mWh.\r\n\r\nWhat is cost / investment requirements of the Blue Waste to Energy System?\r\nThe Phase 1 (i Unit) pilot plant will require an e=investment of ± R 400 million. Finance has been sourced from an international investor. The total cost for the entire 9 unit facility\r\nhas been calculated as ±R 3.4 billion. International finance has been arranged by Blue Waste to Energy (Pty) ltd. \r\n\r\nWhat down time is required on the facility?\r\nA total of five (5) days per year is required to service and maintain a single unit. Therefore on a facility the size of Mogale City the minimum output capacity during maintenance would be 64 mWh at any given time. Maintenance can be arranged in such a way that down time occurs during lower demand periods in a year i.e. summer month.\r\n\r\nBlue Waste to Energy is currently busy with negotiations with the Buffalo City Municipality for the rights to the waste on their Berlin Landfill Site. The site has the potential for another 9 unit / 72 mWh facility.\r\n\r\nOther potential sites have been identified at Port Elizabeth; Pretoria; Cape Town and Bloemfontein. All of these cites have the potential to support at least a 72 mWh facility. As waste deposits increase so can the generation potential of a facility be increased..\r\n\r\nAny further questions or information may be obtained from:\r\nPieter Colyn\r\nrpcolyn@telkomsa.net\r\n082 553 8844\r\n\r\n\r\n', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '2013-06-22', '0000-00-00', ''),
(15, 69, 'E.ON Masdar Integrated Carbon', '+97126537138', 'Kurt Reuman', ' Masdar City, Block 6', '135067', 'PO Box 135067', 'Khalifa A City, Opposite Presidential Flight', 'Abu Dhabi', '00001', 'kurt.reuman@integratedcarbon.com', 'Generic Industrial Cogeneration Plant', 'E.ON Masdar Integrated Carbon (EMIC) is a joint venture between E.ON, the European utilitiy, and Masdar, the Abu Dhabi government''s clean energy initiative.  EMIC is a developer, owner, investor and operator of industrial energy efficiency projects, specifically waste heat recovery, conversion of simple cycle gas turbines to combined cycle and dedicated cogeneration/trigeneration projects.\r\n\r\nEMIC is not an equipment supplier - rather it provides all of the skills, experience and FINANCING and industrial company may require to successfully develop an energy efficiency project at its manufacturing facility.  In essence, EMIC provides a service to the industrial company, allowing it to outsource the work and risk associated with the utility supply allowing it to focus on its core business and not utilized its limited capital for non-core investments.\r\n\r\nEMIC has approached several of the large energy users in South America regarding its serivces and is working with them to assess the feasibility of such projects.  Although none of these project have yet passed the advanced feasibility study, EMIC believes that it is imporantant to convey its services to the South African government as a mechanism to assist industrial players develop the cogeneration projecsts that it would otherwise not be able to develop on their own.', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', ''