(22, 61, 'Distributed Energy Generation', '0729547116', 'Charles Liebenberg', 'Charles', '36', 'Arklow Road', 'Bryanston', 'Sandton', '2191', 'charles@degpl.com', 'DEG Cogen 1', 'Phase 2 of a cogen project\r\nPhase 1 currently being completed\r\nDeveloper Distributed Energy Generation\r\nProject host Karbochem\r\n15MW electricity and 35t/h steam\r\nAlmost exact replication of phase 1', 'Cogeneration', 'CogenerationBack', 'other32', '', '', '', 'Discard coal', '', '', '', '', '', '6', '5', '5', '85', '0.75', 'CPI', '', '90%', '', '', 'Quater4', '2013', 'Project in construction. COD in December 2013', '2', 'baseload', '', '', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', '192', '10', '990', '', 'CPI', 'yes', '', 'fastQ2-2013-12Months', '', '3', '3', 'Distributed Energy Generation', 'Thermax Ltd and Triveni Turbines Ltd', 'none', 'none', 'Currently completing construction and implementation ', '0', '1000000', '1200000', 'yes', '', '', '', '', 40, 'TBA', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', '1', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', '02/12/2013', 'yes', '15/05/2013', 'yes', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '1', 'project', '', 'no', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', '', '1', '', 'finalised', 'yes', 'Project 70% complete and fully financed', 'Newcastle', '29', '58', '16', '27', '46', '55', 'yes', 'Long term lease extension', 'yes', 'yes', '', 'no', '', '', 'no', '', '', 'none', '1', '29', '58', '16', '27', '46', '55', 'Karbochem', 'no', '', '', '', 'NA', 'None', 'Eskom', '3', 'NA', '75-85', '140', '63.64', 'Local contractors and manufacturers to be used', '175', 'Local contractors and manufacturers to be used', '2013-06-24', '2013-07-06', 'true'),
(23, 98, 'iGas SOC Ltd, The South African Gas Development Company SOC Ltd (herein after the “Respondent”)', '010 201 4750', 'Dr. Mike de Pontes', 'CEF House, Block C, Upper Grayston Office Park', '152', 'Ann Crescent', 'Strathavon, Sandton', 'Johannesburg', '2146', 'mikedep@cefgroup.co.za', 'Coega Power Project (“the Power Project”) and the LNG Import and Terminal Project (“the Gas Project”).', 'The project is conceived as a Liquefied Natural Gas (LNG) to Power Project located within the Coega Industrial Development Zone (IDZ), the core elements of the project being (i) the importation of 1.677 million tons per annum of LNG; (ii) a land-based LNG Re-gasification Terminal (LNGT) for offloading, storage and regasification of LNG; (iii) a 2400 MW (installed generation capacity) Combined Cycle Gas Turbine (CCGT) Power Station; and (iv) the production of 10,512 GWh of electricity to supply to Eskom / Systems Operator, based on a mid-merit operation\r\n\r\nThe LNGT has the current vaporisation design capacity to serve up to 2400 MW at Mid Merit Operation or Base Load Operation in the LNGT design case (i.e the case on which Basic Engineering has already been completed), whereas the berth offloading capacity of the LNGT would allow for a modified Basic Engineering package for the LNGT to provide annual capacity of approximately 6 million tonnes per annum or 312 million gigajoules per annum of LNG, which is enough capacity to roughly serve 4,700 MW at Base Load or 8,600 MW at Mid Merit.\r\n\r\nThe LNGT will be developed, owned and operated by the Respondent with owners that are selected through an appropriate selection process.  The LNGT is on the critical path for CCGT implementation, with a commercial operation date (COD) premised to be approximately 60 months after an investment decision and financial close.  The latter requires clear and explicit Government support and undertakings to ensure an effect LNG and LNGT competition linked to the Power Project.\r\n\r\nThe CCGT Power Plant is premised to be the anchor client for the LNGT.   Technical integration with the power plant includes common sea water intake and outfall facilities and is therefore best developed in a single phase, for co-completion and co-commissioning together with the LNGT.  A Conceptual Design and Works Information Package has also been completed by Eskom for a 2,400 MW sea-water cooled plant operating at Mid-Merit.\r\n\r\nAn iGas SOC Ltd Special Purpose Vehicle, a state-owned Gas Infrastructure Company with provision for private sector and BEE participation therein, and which private sector participation will be based on one or a combination of access to LNG production or LNG Regasification Terminal (LNGT) development and/or operational skills, will be applying for a gas licence in terms of S 15(1) of the Gas Act for an LNGT, and which LNGT gas infrastructure ought to be included in a gazetted Integrated Energy Plan as required in terms of S 6(1) of the National Energy Act, and which LNGT gas infrastructure also meets the requirements of S 6(6) of the National Energy Act, and also satisfies the procurement requirements of S 56(1) of the National Ports Act. It is expected that any LNG-to-Power project should be structured in such a way that the LNGT will be a common user facility for access by multiple LNG sellers and buyers alike over time, with a sufficiently sized combined cycle gas turbine (CCGT) power plant providing the initial and contractual basis for the development of the LNGT gas infrastructure in a manner which prevents the unintended creation of an LNG supply monopoly for LNG demand growth based on additional CCGT opportunities or subsequent industrial users.\r\n\r\nThe cost of generation and electricity will be based on final negotiated price for the primary fuel (LNG).  It is therefore not possible to provide these prices at this time and they are subsequently indicated as ZAR0.\r\n\r\nThe Capacity Factor is indicated as 1% but is To Be Confirmed.\r\nThe Electrical is indicated as 0 but is To Be Confirmed.\r\n\r\nThe Expected Total Project Capital Costs of ZAR 28,000 millions is for BOTH the LNG Terminal AND the CCGT Power Plant. \r\n\r\nIt will take 12 months to make a binding offer from being presented with a bankable PPA.  However, this assumes that other development activities occur in parallel, including but not limited to negotiation of LNG SPA, negotiations with lenders, submission of EIA, conclusion of land rights and FEED. \r\n \r\nIt will take 12 months to settle all relevant details related to the EPC Contractor and Primary Equipment Suppliers and enter into the relevant contract/s after being provided with a bankable PPA.  However, this assumes that other development activities occur in parallel, including but not limited to negotiation of LNG SPA, negotiations with lenders, submission of EIA, conclusion of land rights and FEED.  This applies to other areas where durations are requested but comments cannot be made.\r\n\r\nThe construction of the LNGT will provide an average of 450 jobs/12 months during the 42 month construction, while the power plant will provide approximately 900 - 1200 jobs/12 months during the 24 month construction period.  Permanent employment created amount to approximately 50 for LNGT and 70 for the power plant.  The combined number of permanent jobs have been captured in the template.\r\n', 'GasPlant', 'CCGT', 'LNG', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '2400', '400', '2400', '1', '0', 'To be confirmed/Not applicable', '0', '', '', '', 'Quater2', '2020', 'Actual COD year is 2022 but the options above do not include 2022.  PPA Negotiations still to be initiated.  Critical path item is LNGT construction period of 42 months (51 months including site prep).  COD for power plant has to be aligned with LNGT COD.', '60', 'mid-merit', '12', '260', '16.8', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', '28000', '25', '0', '', '0', 'no', 'Primary Fuel Price (LNG) will have $US and Brent indexation', 'commitQ2-2016-Phased', '12 months after receipt of a PPA. (However, that assumes that other development activities occur in parallel, including but not limited to negotiation of LNG SPA, negotiations with lenders, submission of EIA, conclusion of land rights and FEED)', '12', '60', 'iGas SOC Ltd, The South African Gas Development Company SOC Ltd', 'Siemens (To Be Confirmed)', 'None as yet', 'None. iGas has a JPDA with a multi-national gas & power company. Due to IRP2010 & NewGen Regs it has not committed to any IPP, LNGT developer or LNG seller assuming that a competitive bidding process will be required to procure participants in the Project', 'None', '89000000', '103000000', '106000000', 'no', '', '', '', '', 10, 'Still to be determined', 'no', 'no', 'no', 'no', 'no', '', 'no', '12', 'no', '', '', '', '', '', 'no', 'LNG would likely be purchased by way of a long term supply contract with an international LNG supplier (preferably with an LNG supply portfolio).  The supply of LNG still has to be negotiated but security of supply is contractually achieved, linked to an upstream LNG development, underpinned by P90 gas reserves.', 'no', 'LNG would likely be purchased by way of a long term supply contract with an international LNG supplier (preferably with an LNG supply portfolio).  The supply of LNG still has to be negotiated but security of supply is contractually achieved, linked to an upstream LNG development, underpinned by P90 gas reserves.', 'no', 'LNG would likely be purchased by way of a long term supply contract with an international LNG supplier (preferably with an LNG supply portfolio).  The supply of LNG still has to be negotiated but security of supply is contractually achieved, linked to an upstream LNG development, underpinned by P90 gas reserves.', 'LNG would likely be purchased by way of a long term supply contract with an international LNG supplier (preferably with an LNG supply portfolio).  The supply of LNG still has to be negotiated but security of supply is contractually achieved, linked to an upstream LNG development, underpinned by P90 gas reserves.', 'Front End Development:  Q3 2013 – Q2 2017\r\nFID: Q3 2017\r\nSite prep:  Q4 2017 – Q2 2018\r\nConstruction:  Q3 2018 – Q4 2022\r\nCommissioning:  Q1 2022\r\nCOD:  Q2 2022\r\nHard copy reference is attached as Annexure C - Schedule.\r\n', 'See project timetable', '12', 'project', '', 'yes', 'no', 'no', '', '', '', '12', 'no', 'finalised', 'no', 'LNG would likely be purchased by way of a long-term supply contract with an international LNG supplier (preferably with an LNG supply portfolio).  The supply of LNG still has to be negotiated but security of supply is contractually achieved, linked to an upstream LNG development, underpinned by P90 gas reserves.  The technical feasibility study has been completed.', 'Coega Industrial Development Zone (20kms from PE),  subject to technical & commercial agreement with Transnet Ports Authority (and possibly the Coega Development Corporation), a sufficiently sized site for the CCGT and Power Plant has been earmarked.', '25', '41', '55.4', '33', '47', '27.1', 'no', '', 'no', 'no', '', 'no', '', '', 'no', '', '', 'A joint Power Project and Gas Project EIA was initiated in 2006.  The Draft Scoping Report and Draft Specialist studies were completed (i.e. 70% of the work).  However, the application has since lapsed and will have to be remade.  Approximately 12 months are required to re-initiate and update the application before submission of the Final Environmental Impact Report (EIR).  We estimate an additional 3-6 months before the ROD is granted.  NERSA Licence Applications will also be required for the LNG Terminal and CCGT Power Plant.  These applications should take about 6-9 months in parallel.', '5', '25', '40', '31', '33', '44', '35', 'Dedisa Substation', 'no', '', '', '', 'Eskom has been aware of this project since its inception and has catered for grid connection and capacity in the following ways:\r\n\r\n1.	Undertaken an EIA for the Installation of Electrical Infrastructure in the Coega Industrial Development Zone (IDZ).  Together with the Coega Development Corporation (CDC), Eskom Transmission proposed the installation of electrical infrastructure within the Coega IDZ near Port Elizabeth, Eastern Cape.  The power transmission infrastructure upgrade includes the installation of 400kV and 132kV powerlines, substations for stepping down the power for end users, radio towers for communications, and the upgrade of the existing Grassridge substation.  The proposed Open Cycle Gas Turbine (OCGT) for peaking hours, and Combined Cycle Gas Turbine (CCGT) for mid-merit supply were external to this EIA.  However, the powerlines covered by this EIA need to feed into the CCGT and OCGT, and have thus has been considered in this project.  The proposed power line route from the 2,400 MW CCGT to the Dedisa and Grassridge substations have been mapped and prepared graphically. \r\n\r\n2.	Servitudes are in place for the transmission lines.\r\n\r\n3.	The Transmission Ten-Year Development Plan 2012-2021 (http://www.eskom.co.za/c/22/transmission-development-plan/) includes extensive upgrade of both the Grassridge and Dedisa substations located in the IDZ.\r\n', 'See above', 'Connecting to the Eskom grid via the Dedisa and Grassridge sub-stations as described above.', '24', 'Not Applicable', '100+', '7000', '25.00', 'Civil works for both LNG Terminal and power plant', '120', 'Not applicable at this stage.  The intention is to start the operation of the LNGT with international staff who would then train local staff and transfer knowledge.  In addition, maintenance facilities may be required, but at this stage it is not yet clear what the opportunities will be.', '2013-06-24', '2013-07-11', 'true'),
(24, 106, 'MPC Africa (Ferrostaal GmbH / Atlantis Projects Development (Pty) Ltd.)', '+49201 8182953', 'Stefan Kratz / Brian Blackbeard', 'Building 1, Level 3', '24', 'Hohenzollernstraße', 'Sued', 'Essen', '45128', 'stefan.kratz@ferrostaal.com', 'CCGT IPP Saldanha', 'MPC Africa, consisting of Ferrostaal GmbH and Atlantis Projects Development (Pty) Ltd. and Royal Bafokeng Holdings, are intending the development, financing, building and operation of a Combined Cycle Gas Turbine (CCGT) Thermal Power Plant complex at Saldanha Bay, Western Cape, Republic of South Africa. This combination of leading international and South African companies, teamed up with local BBBEE contractors and suppliers, offer a sustainable Build, Own and Operate (BOO) IPP model.\r\n\r\nThe IPP envisaged provides for a baseload power plant to supply 574 MWe net power output using the configuration of two gas turbines, two heat recovery steam generators and one steam turbine operating of Liquified Natural Gas (LNG) and/or Piped Natural Gas.\r\n\r\nAfter Gauteng and the Durban area, the Western Cape is the third-largest industrial complex in South Africa. Baseload power in the Western Cape is currently supplied by the coal fired-power plants located in Mpumalanga area and the Koeberg Nuclear Power Station near Cape Town. Due to the great distances to transmit the coal fired power, with associated transmission-line losses, and the limited amount of power available from the Koeberg Power Station, which cannot be 100% available due to maintenance requirements, the alternate power supply in the Western Cape is made up by Ankerlig OCGT Peaking Power Station and Hydro storage stations. These facilities are expensive to operate and not designed as baseload power stations. Current projects to provide renewable energy in this region will assist in the energy supply model but cannot be seen to provide energy security for the industrial growth envisioned under the designated Saldanha Industrial Development Zone (IDZ) and planned Special Economic Zone (SEZ) for the West Coast region.\r\n\r\nIt is thus vital to ensure additional baseload power is provided to the Western Cape by locating additional baseload generation in the region.  The only suitable and sustainable alternate baseload option is gas fired power which leverages the immediate availability and access to LNG and future piped natural gas from the west coast of South Africa. The proposed power plant therefore needs to be located in the vicinity of an established deep-draft harbour where bulk LNG supplies can be disembarked. The harbour at Saldanha is ideal for this purpose as it does not suffer congestion or closure due to adverse weather that is sometimes experienced by the Port of Cape Town. Saldanha is also a designated LNG terminal port operated under Transnet National Ports Authority (TNPA).\r\n\r\nIn order to ensure availability of gas for the power plant it is planned to initially supply the plant with LNG imported into South Africa at Saldanha Bay and to be regasified onboard a Floating Storage Regasification Unit (FSRU) vessel which will berthed at the TNPA Liquid Bulk jetty. In the medium and long term this LNG import will be substituted by Natural Gas delivered via sub-sea pipeline directly from the Sunbird Energy/PetroSA Ibhubezi gas fields. The FSRU regasification option will allow the project to reduce capital cost by not building any onshore LNG storage and re-gasification infrastructure in Saldanha Bay. This infrastructure would also become redundant in the event of switching over gas supply from LNG to piped Natural Gas when the Ibhubesi Gas supply comes online. \r\n\r\nCurrent 2013 LNG prices per MMBtu vary globally between 3,5 USD/MMBtu in the USA, 10 USD/MMBtu in Europe and 15 USD/MMBtu in Asia. For the proposed 590 MWe combined cycle operation power plant in base load operation, it shall consume approximately ~ 100 mmscf of re-gasified gas per day. Negotiations with RWE for a secured LNG supply for the first years of operation have been undertaken and a term sheet is under negotiation (www.rwe.com). In any combined cycle power project the fuel costs is the dominant cost driver. As previously presented to the Department of Energy (DoE) and re-iterated in this proposal in order to take into account the fluctuating LNG USD cost multiplied by the volatility of the ZAR exchange rate, the best method of offering a cost effective and transparent energy price we offer options of a tolling concept in which the gas purchase price gets directly paid by the off-taker or a pass through solution in which the input gas cost is reimbursed on a one to one basis at time of purchase. These commercial concepts will require some further review and trade-off to determine the preference of ESKOM. Other long term solutions along the lines of LNG/Gas trading principles are also possible. Infrastructure cost for the berth of the LNG re-gasification vessel are not considered in the total investment cost as they shall be shared with other off-takers e.g. for a gas supply to Ankerlig power plant.\r\n\r\nNegotiations with Excelerate have also been undertaken to hire the FSRU re-gasification ship for the period it will take to get the Ibhubezi offshore fields into production and to complete the sub-sea gas pipeline to Saldanha.\r\n\r\nEngagement with Sunbird Energy, a developer of the Ibhubezi gas field has confirmed their willingness to supply gas to Saldanha for this power plant. Such a supply agreement would offer them the needed off-take to develop the gas fields and to monetize the South African natural gas reserves instead of importing LNG from abroad. This gas off-take would directly contribute to the development of South Africa’s west coast gas fields and stimulate further industrial growth and additional job creation in the region. It would also create a local feedstock source and add to further energy security for the country.\r\n\r\nOur redundant concept (LNG/Natural gas from local offshore fields) for fuel supply to our proposed power plant will not only lead to a secured operation of the Saldanha power plant but also support the process to convert the Ankerlig Peaking power station (1350 MW) to a secured gas supply infrastructure. This would allow the Ankerlig Peaking Power Station to reduce its operating costs and CO2 emissions drastically. \r\n\r\nIt could also be postulated that with a scalable baseload IPP power plant in Saldanha,  the Ankerlig Power Station could return to its peaking mode as originally designed but with enough back up capacity to take care of any mid merit load demand.\r\n\r\nIn attempting to optimise all these factors, the search for an optimal siting of the plant was a function of\r\n\r\n-	distance to the sea for cooling water\r\n-	availability of a suitable berth for the LNG regasification and replenishment vessel \r\n-	distance to the regasification vessel berth\r\n-	preservation of ecological sensitive areas and environmental compliance\r\n-	proximity to a suitable electrical substation \r\n-	avoidance of Saldanha iron ore dust if drawn into turbines\r\n-	availability of suitable land\r\n-	inclusion in the IDZ and or SEZ areas to be designated\r\n\r\nAs an outcome of these analyses, it is proposed to locate the power plant on land within the industrial corridor of Saldanha. This location provides a trade-off between gas piping distances from the bay and the distances to the Aurora and Blouwaterbaai sub-stations. The final location within this area will be determined by further optimisation and trade-off during the Environmental Impact Assessment (EIA) and engineering processes underway. \r\n\r\nWith the Saldanha Bay area already designated for an Industrial Development Zone (IDZ) to be promulgated this year and the further inclusion of Saldanha as a Special Economic Zone (SEZ) planned for approval by cabinet later this year, the generation of efficient baseload electrical power ‘on the doorstep’ of these national industrial growth plans will greatly support the development of these two zones.\r\n\r\nThe advantages of the IDZ and SEZ status have been duly recognized in our financial model.\r\n\r\nDiscussions with the Provincial Authorities (Western Cape Provincial Government) and National Authorities (DTI) have been progressed and both parties are in full support to have a gas fired power plant located in the region. The Port Authorities have received detailed insight into our planning and provided their preliminary consent to the berthing and operation of the regasification vessel.\r\n\r\nOur financial model is based on a regime of capacity and energy fees. As the fuel is to be imported on USD basis the PPA should have an USD or a ZAR/USD hedge element as well. Also some of the capital cost will have to be USD/€ denominated and the tariff elements should consider this.\r\n\r\nAs investors we have identified Royal Bafokeng Holdings, the MPC Group of Companies and ContourGlobal (to be verified within the PPA negotiations. The lending banks considered are known to the investors from other projects and financing planned based on known contractual structures.\r\n\r\nThe long term operation of the plant will be undertaken by ContourGlobal.\r\n\r\nBlack Empowerment participation and support is provided for at all the levels of this IPP project, including;\r\n\r\n-	the investment and equity structure\r\n-	the construction of the plant \r\n-	the supply of components\r\n-	the training of operational personnel\r\n-	the maintenance of the plant\r\n-	the contracting of local industry\r\n\r\nThe EPC contractor for the IPP project will be Koch Engineering & Construction (KEC), an affiliate company of Ferrostaal, Germany and Proman of Switzerland. As KEC will be involved from the early planning to the commissioning of the plant we will have a seamless and fast track solution process for the realization of the plant. The EPC contract will be a consortium type together with the supplier of the key technological components (turbines). This consortium will also undertake the training and the long term guarantee/maintenance support and spare part supply. \r\n\r\nThe schedule of the project development and construction of the plant is based on:\r\n\r\n-	early commitment on a negotiated and bankable PPA by ESKOM/DoE within Q4 2013\r\n-	parallel start of engineering and environmental scoping work\r\n-	18 months project development period and EIA approval to arrive at financial close end of 2014\r\n-	24 months construction time to arrive at open cycle operation end of 2016 (393 MWe gross)\r\n-	Additional 7 months period to complete the combined cycle (588 MWe gross) by mid 2017\r\n', 'GasPlant', 'CCGT', 'other31', '', '', '', '', 'Fuel Feedstock: LNG to start with as interim feedstock solution and after development of the Ibhubesi offshore gas field natural gas will be used.', '', '', '', '', '588', '195', '574', '85.6', '0.307', 'Henry Hub for LNG price, USD/ZAR currency exchange rate, South African Inflation Index for Operations and Maintenance for some cost elements, details to be finalized during PPA negotiations', '54.49% at site conditions in Saldanha', '', '', '', 'Quater4', '2016', 'Offered timeline is based on a commitment from DoE/Eskom for PPA and  Saldanha exclusivity not later than Q4 13 and a COD for the single cycle of 393 MWe gross by end of 16 and the remainder of 195 MWe gross provided by the comb. cycle compl. by mid 2017.', '36', 'baseload', '', '', '', 'yes', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', '7250', '20', '307', 'Number of start-ups exceeding the quantity defined.', 'A USD/EUR/ZAR element for the currency fluctuations to cover the pay back of the investment and part of the O&M such as spare parts to be imported.  Henry Hub will be the reference for LNG imports and an important factor for the overall tariff incl. LNG', 'no', 'Up to 70 % of the total investment cost will require USD/EUR payments, thus part of the capacity payment shall be effected in USD/EUR.', 'fastQ3-2013-36Month', 'Not applicable', '6', '36', 'MPC Africa (Ferrostaal GmbH/Atlantis Projects Development (Pty) Ltd.)', 'Koch Engineering & Construction Lda.', 'Royal Bafokeng Holdings, Atlantis Projects Development (Pty) Ltd., MPC Africa', 'Ferrostaal', 'Some 10.000 MW have been built by Ferrostaal as per reference list attached. Furthermore many other industrial plants have been built as EPC but also as project financed deals with participations of FS in equity. Those projects include major investments with more than 1 bn EUR investment. Attached are references on some of our projects we developed and invested in.', '31000000000', '24000000000', '22000000000', 'yes', '', '', '', '', 20, 'The Saldanha and West Coast region which is historically a fishing community has a very high unemployment rate and low skills levels. Industrial development which has taken place to date has not fully engaged the local community due to their skills shortages. The growth of the industrial base which will offer more employment opportunities is limited by the availability of electricity for major industry.\r\n\r\nAt present all available power is allocated and the future IDZ and planned SEZ cannot be established without more power in the region.\r\n\r\nThis CCGT power plant will not only give the required electrical supply to grow the local industry but will also give the required security of supply to attract major industrial growth to Saldanha and optimise the planned IDZ and SEZ.\r\n\r\nThe establishment of the power plant will in itself also create direct local work opportunities and support the local community by using local contractors and suppliers for materials, equipment and services required during the construction and operation of the plant. Preference to engage with local companies with BBBEE accreditation will be applied.\r\n\r\nAs part of local community involvement, Ferrostaal and Atlantis have already installed a complete computer centre with 30 PCs, server, LAN network and audio visual equipment in the St Andrew’s Primary School in Saldanha under its previous Oil and Gas Fabrication Yard project in Saldanha. This project  also regularly supports local initiatives in conjunction with the Saldanha Municipality to uplift the local community.\r\n\r\nThis Power Plant project will endeavour to maintain such community involvement as already demonstrated by its current shareholders.', 'no', 'no', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'no', '3', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', '01/07/2016', 'no', '', 'yes', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '3', 'project', '', 'yes', 'no', 'no', '', '', '', '18', '', 'draft', 'yes', 'Not applicable', 'Saldanha Bay, Western Cape, South Africa', '18', '03', '55.24', '32', '58', '12.72', 'yes', 'Currently one location has been pre-selected and secured by an option, final site location will be determined by trade-off study optimizing distances between gas input and electricity delivery points.', 'no', 'no', '', 'no', '', '', 'no', '', '', 'Gas Pipeline (NERSA) – 12 months\r\nLNG Terminal Operating License (TNPA) – 12 months\r\nBuilding Plan approvals (Saldanha Municipality) – 6 months\r\nPower Distribution Agreement (Eskom) – 6 months\r\nPower Direct Connection Agreement (Eskom) – 6 months\r\nConnection location & costs (Eskom) – 3 months', '23', '18', '14', '00.00', '33', '00', '29.00', 'Aurora Sub-station – this is the designated Sub-station with adequate connection capacity at this point in time. Blouwaterbaai Sub-station cannot currently accept the 588MW and would need to be upgraded.', 'no', '', '', '', 'Eskom has been contacted via Consulting Electrical engineer (QDP Electrical).\r\nPersons contacted at Eskom:\r\n\r\n-	Leslie Naidoo – Infrastructure Planning Manager       Leslie.naidoo@eskom.co.za\r\n-	Nish Rathalall – Planning Support Manager              RathanN@eskom.co.za\r\n-	Gabrial Kgabo – Head of Grid Access                      Gabriel.kgabo@eskom.co.za\r\n-	Nonhlala Miya – Regional Manager                          MiyaNP@eskom.co.za\r\n-	Are van Zyl – Grid Access 				            VanZylAW@eskom.co.za\r\n', 'A 132kV transmission line will be built connecting IPP power plant to Aurora Sub-station. Provision for transmission lines and Sub-station connection is included in IPP capital cost.', 'Direct connection to Eskom at Aurora Sub-station.', '30', 'Not applicable', '100+', '2000', '27.59', '-	Pipework fabrication\r\n-	Pressure vessel manufacture\r\n-	Pumps and valves\r\n-	Construction steel work\r\n-	Structural steel\r\n-	Construction supplies\r\n-	Construction goods\r\n-	Transformers\r\n-	Transmission lines and components\r\n-	HV Switchgear\r\n-	Instrumentation \r\n-	Control gear\r\n-	Auxiliary plant\r\n-	Fire fighting systems\r\n-	Safety and security systems\r\n-	HVAC systems\r\n', '1980', '-	Technology transfer to maintain and operate the plant\r\n-	Technology transfer to manufacture replacement parts\r\n-	Local spares supply\r\n-	Local operating stores supply\r\n-	Support services – specialised technical support \r\n-	Security services\r\n\r\nConsidering the large numbers of local personnel required for the construction of the power plant and supporting infrastructure, coupled to the unavailability of skilled labour in the Saldanha Bay region, the IPP developer have in view to establish a training centre to develop and train the required local labour required.\r\n\r\nIn addition the EPC is developing a heavy industrial erection company in the Southern African region with own heavy erection and lifting equipment designed for the industrial market that can be used in the present project.\r\n\r\nFor the power plant operational personnel, the EPC together with the selected OEM will provide training to the operational personnel including technical (class room) theoretical training and “on job” practical training during commissioning.', '2013-06-24', '2013-07-10', 'true');
