(25, 94, 'Prana Energy and Basil Read Energy', '011 463 9718', 'Johan Posthumus', 'Coral House', '20', 'Peter Place', 'Bryanston', 'JHB', '2021', 'johan@pranaenergy.co.za', 'SCR Middelburg Cogen Project', 'Samancor Chrome is in the business of producing (amongst other products) ferrochrome. The company owns and operates a charge chrome production facility just outside Middelburg in Mpumalanga. This site is known as the Middelburg Ferrochrome site (“MFC”).  Charge chrome is produced at MFC from two semi-closed AC submerged arc furnaces and two closed direct current plasma furnaces (M3 and M4, 50 MW and 60MW respectively). \r\n\r\nThe two closed DC furnaces (M3 and M4) produce a combustible, CO-rich off-gas as a waste product. This off-gas is currently flared to atmosphere. The off-gas is energy-rich and contains between 60% to 70% CO and 20% to 30% H2 on average. This off-gas is currently being flared to atmosphere.\r\n\r\nPrana Energy and Samancor Chrome initially decided to develop an electricity generation plant at the MFC site when the Eskom Pilot National Co-generation Programme (“PNCP”) was launched in 2007. The intention was to use the furnace off-gas as fuel for the electricity generation plant. This project was put on ice when the PNCP failed but was resurrected subsequently. The project development effort is almost complete at present. \r\n\r\nThe project was successfully registered with the United Nations Framework Convention for Climate Change (“UNFCCC”) in order to qualify for carbon credits. \r\n\r\nAs a result of the significant historical effort, the project will be able to come on line and deliver power very quickly relative to other similar projects. \r\n\r\nThe electricity-generation technology to be used will be Jenbacher gas engines supplied by General Electric. The gas engines will be fuelled by the energy-rich off-gas from furnaces M3 and M4 as the only fuel source. \r\n\r\nAll electricity generated by the power plant will be fed back into furnaces M3 and M4 and as such none of the power generated will be exported back into the Eskom grid. The amount of power imported from the Eskom grid will be reduced by the same amount as the power generated on site. \r\n\r\nThe power plant will have a nameplate capacity of 34MW.\r\n', 'Reciprocating', 'Gas', 'other33', '', '', '', '', '', 'Furnace off-gas', '', '', '', '34', '1.7', '32', '77', '1.20', 'PPI', '36.6%', '', '', '', 'Quater4', '2015', 'Conservative estimate. It may be possible to generate power earlier depending on lead times from Jenbacher GE', '18', 'none', '12', '360', '24', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', '705', '9', '1200', '', 'PPI but a portion could be escallated according to a ZAR / EUR exchange rate index', 'yes', '', 'fastQ3-2013-36Month', 'We are ready now. Please note that the commercial terms in the final PPA (unknown to us at this point in time) will have an impact on COD date, cost of power and various other key parameters.', '6', '18', 'Prana Energy', 'Jenbacher', 'Basil Read Energy (Pty) Ltd', 'NA', 'Prana Energy has been a developer of co-generation projects since 2007 when we (as the project developer for Exxaro On-Site at the time) submitted 930MW of co-generation projects into the Eskom Pilot National Co-generation Programme (“PNCP).\r\n\r\nWe have subsequently developed projects or done advisory work in the co-generation space for a large number of customers in the ferro-alloy, steel, cement and related industries.  \r\n\r\nPrana Energy was the developer of the Namakwa Sands project near Saldanha Bay in the Western Cape. The Namakwa Sands project is currently being implemented on balance sheet with an expected COD date of August 2013.\r\n\r\nOur development approach is to retain a highly qualified and experienced core development team at Prana Energy but to outsource specialist work to a well-established network of partners in the legal, technical, environmental and related spaces. We work closely with two well-established EPC contractors (Basil Read Matomo and Group 5) for the implementation of our projects.\r\n\r\nOur South Africa development partner and eventual project owner, Basil Read Energy is a significant player in the emerging South African energy landscape. A corporate brochure for Basil Read Energy is attached to the hardcopy as a separate Annexure\r\n', '5800000', '9200000', '6100000', 'yes', '', '', '', '', 53, 'TBD', 'no', 'no', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'no', '4', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', '01/01/2014', 'no', '', 'yes', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '4', 'project', '', 'yes', 'no', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', '', '6', '', 'draft', 'no', 'The project uses furnace off-gas as fuel. We have been monitoring the furnace off-gas data since 2007 when we started the development of the project. As such, there is a very good baseline of historical “fuel” data on which the design of the power plant was based. The quality of this data is considered to be adequate for the engineering design phase (which has substantially been completed).\r\n\r\nFuel data is monitored on an on-going basis as it provides additional comfort in the data. This is currently being done by an expert third party in order to provide comfort to Lenders. Monitoring of the “fuel” resource by the third party will continue throughout the development phase and right up to the end of the implementation phase.  \r\n\r\nThe future of the “fuel” resource, however, cannot be predicted with any great accuracy as it is subject to variations in the commodity market for ferrochrome which underlies the production process. \r\n\r\nIt is highly unlikely that a Lender will require additional resource studies if the PPA agreed to, includes a capacity charge as proposed in this document as the capacity charge will remove the need to take a (conservative) view on the future behaviour of the commodity markets.  \r\n\r\n\r\n', 'Middelburg, Mpumalanga, South Africa', '29', '29', '40.38', '25', '48', '16.26', 'yes', 'The site selected for the power generation project is within the boundaries of the bigger Samancor Chrome operation and the specific location for the power generation project has already been agreed to with Samancor Chrome management.\r\n\r\nThis site will be leased from Samancor Chrome for a nominal amount and the lease as well as access servitudes will be registered in the Deeds office as is customary for arrangements of this nature. \r\n\r\nPlease refer to the hardcopy for the site plan.\r\n', 'no', 'yes', '08/04/2010', 'no', '', '', 'no', '', '', 'Generation license. Timeline as per the existing NERSA process.', '0.2', '29', '29', '42.3', '25', '48', '16.2', 'Middelburg Ferrochrome substation', 'yes', '12/01/2009', 'yes', 'Provided in hardcopy as required.', 'The project is well known to Eskom (we initially engaged Eskom at the time of the PNCP programme).  Eskom have stated on many occasions that they would like the project to proceed to implementation as it will have a highly beneficial impact on virtually all aspects of Eskom’s operations (transmission, reduced load at peak times, etc.)\r\n\r\nThe most recent engagements were with the IDM team (Andrew Etzinger) regarding a possible IDM subsidy as was provided to other similar projects and which application was put on hold subsequent to NERSA''s MYPD3 ruling.\r\n', 'No upgrades required to transmission or distribution infrastructure as the cogeneration plant will connect into the existing Samancor Chrome 33kV substation.\r\n\r\nA Point Of Utility Connection is required however (a minor exercise).\r\n', 'Eskom (via the existing Samancor Chrome network)', '12', 'NA', '75-85', '450', '63.83', 'Balance Of Plant equipment such as fans, pumps, valves, chillers, structural steel and piping, electrical equipment, C&I equipment and other Balance of Plant items ', '15', 'A local maintenance capability will be established', '2013-06-25', '2013-07-11', 'true'),
(26, 94, 'Prana Energy', '011 463 9718', 'Johan Posthumus', 'Coral House ', '20', 'Peter Place', 'Bryanston', 'Jhb', '2021', 'johan@pranaenergy.co.za', 'SCR Witbank Cogen Project', 'Samancor Chrome is in the business of producing (amongst other products) ferrochrome. The company owns and operates a charge chrome production facility in Witbank in Mpumalanga. This site is known as the Ferrometals site (“FMT”).  Charge chrome is produced at FMT from two closed direct current plasma furnaces (F4 and F5). \r\n\r\nThe two closed DC furnaces produce a combustible, CO-rich off-gas as a waste product. This off-gas is currently flared to atmosphere. The off-gas is energy-rich and contains between 60% to 70% CO and 20% to 30% H2 on average. This off-gas is currently being flared to atmosphere.\r\n\r\nPrana Energy and Samancor Chrome initially decided to develop an electricity generation plant at the MFC site when the Eskom Pilot National Co-generation Programme (“PNCP”) was launched in 2007. The intention was to use the furnace off-gas as fuel for the electricity generation plant. This project was put on ice when the PNCP failed but was resurrected subsequently. The project development effort is almost complete at present. \r\n\r\nThe project was successfully registered with the United Nations Framework Convention for Climate Change (“UNFCCC”) in order to qualify for carbon credits. \r\n\r\nAs a result of the significant historical effort, the project will be able to come on line and deliver power very quickly relative to other similar projects. \r\n\r\nThe electricity-generation technology to be used will be Jenbacher gas engines supplied by General Electric. The gas engines will be fuelled by the energy-rich off-gas from furnaces F4 and F5 as the only fuel source. \r\n\r\nAll electricity generated by the power plant will be fed back into furnaces F4 and F5 and as such none of the power generated will be exported back into the Eskom grid. The amount of power imported from the Eskom grid will be reduced by the same amount as the power generated on site. \r\n\r\nThe power plant will have a nameplate capacity of 24MW.\r\n', 'Reciprocating', 'Gas', 'other33', '', '', '', '', '', 'Furnace off-gas', '', '', '', '24', '1.7', '22', '77', '1.2', 'PPI', '36.6', '', '', '', 'Quater4', '2015', 'Conservative estimate. It may be possible to generate power earlier depending on lead times from Jenbacher', '18', 'none', '12', '360', '24', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', '565', '9', '1250', '', 'PPI', 'yes', '', 'fastQ3-2013-36Month', 'We are ready now. Please note that the commercial terms in the final PPA (unknown to us at this point in time) will have an impact on COD date, cost of power and various other key parameters', '6', '18', 'Prana Energy', 'GE Jenbacher', 'Basil Read Energy (Pty) Ltd', 'NA', 'Prana Energy has been a developer of co-generation projects since 2007 when we (as the project developer for Exxaro On-Site at the time) submitted 930MW of co-generation projects into the Eskom Pilot National Co-generation Programme (“PNCP).\r\n\r\nWe have subsequently developed projects or done advisory work in the co-generation space for a large number of customers in the ferro-alloy, steel, cement and related industries.  \r\n\r\nPrana Energy was the developer of the Namakwa Sands project near Saldanha Bay in the Western Cape. The Namakwa Sands project is currently being implemented on balance sheet with an expected COD date of August 2013.\r\n\r\nOur development approach is to retain a highly qualified and experienced core development team at Prana Energy but to outsource specialist work to a well-established network of partners in the legal, technical, environmental and related spaces. We work closely with two well-established EPC contractors (Basil Read Matomo and Group 5) for the implementation of our projects.\r\n\r\nOur South Africa development partner and eventual project owner, Basil Read Energy is a significant player in the emerging South African energy landscape. A corporate brochure for Basil Read Energy is attached to the hardcopy as a separate Annexure\r\n', '5800000', '9200000', '6100000', 'yes', '', '', '', '', 53, 'TBD', 'no', 'no', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'no', '4', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', '01/01/2014', 'no', '', 'yes', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '4', 'project', '', 'yes', 'no', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', '', '6', '', 'draft', 'no', 'The project uses furnace off-gas as fuel. We have been monitoring the furnace off-gas data since 2007 when we started the development of the project. As such, there is a very good baseline of historical “fuel” data on which the design of the power plant was based. The quality of this data is considered to be adequate for the engineering design phase (which has substantially been completed).\r\n\r\nFuel data is monitored on an on-going basis as it provides additional comfort in the data. This is currently being done by an expert third party in order to provide comfort to Lenders. Monitoring of the “fuel” resource by the third party will continue throughout the development phase and right up to the end of the implementation phase.  \r\n\r\nThe future of the “fuel” resource, however, cannot be predicted with any great accuracy as it is subject to variations in the commodity market for ferrochrome which underlies the production process. \r\n\r\nIt is highly unlikely that a Lender will require additional resource studies if the PPA agreed to, includes a capacity charge as proposed in this document as the capacity charge will remove the need to take a (conservative) view on the future behaviour of the commodity markets.  ', 'Witbank, Mpumalanga, South Africa', '29', '10', '0', '25', '51', '0', 'yes', 'The site selected for the power generation project is within the boundaries of the bigger Samancor Chrome operation and the specific location for the power generation project has already been agreed to with Samancor Chrome management.\r\n\r\nThis site will be leased from Samancor Chrome for a nominal amount and the lease as well as access servitudes will be registered in the Deeds office as is customary for arrangements of this nature. \r\n\r\nPlease refer to the hardcopy for the site plan.\r\n', 'no', 'yes', '08/04/2010', 'no', '', '', 'no', '', '', 'Generation license. Timeline as per the existing NERSA process.', '0.3', '29', '10', '24.1', '25', '51', '24.1', 'Ferrometals substation', 'yes', '12/01/2009', 'yes', 'Provided in hardcopy as requested', 'The project is well known to Eskom (we initially engaged Eskom at the time of the PNCP programme).  Eskom have stated on many occasions that they would like the project to proceed to implementation as it will have a highly beneficial impact on virtually all aspects of Eskom’s operations (transmission, reduced load at peak times, etc.)\r\n\r\nThe most recent engagements were with the IDM team (Andrew Etzinger) regarding a possible IDM subsidy as was provided to other similar projects and which application was put on hold subsequent to NERSA''s MYPD3 ruling.\r\n\r\n', 'No upgrades required to transmission or distribution infrastructure as the cogeneration plant will connect into the existing Samancor Chrome 33kV substation.\r\n\r\nA Point Of Utility Connection is required however (a minor exercise).\r\n\r\n', 'Eskom', '12', 'NA', '75-85', '400', '70.80', 'Balance of Plant equipment such as fans, pumps, valves, chillers, structural steel and piping, electrical equipment, C&I equipment, and other Balance of Plant equipment', '15', 'A local maintenance capability will be created', '2013-06-25', '2013-07-11', 'true'),
(27, 103, 'Orion Engineered Carbons (PTY) Ltd', '0027827995413', 'Kay Schmidt', 'Administration Building', '1', 'John Tallant Road', 'Deal Party', 'Port Elizabeth', '6000', 'Kay.Schmidt@orioncarbons.com', 'Co-Gen Plant OEC PLZ', 'CURRENT PROCESS\r\nIn order to produce Carbon Black heavy oils with high aromatic content, of which Heavy Fuel Oil (HFO) is a good example, are preheated and fed into a refractory lined reactor with a limited amount of preheated combustion air at high temperatures. The combustion is prematurely stopped with a water quench forming the resulting carbon black and off-gas product. The carbon black is filtered out of the off gas stream, pelleted and dried. The resulting low calorific value, CO (carbon monoxide) rich, wet tail gas stream (carbon black free) is utilised as a fuel gas for the dryers (25 – 30% of the combustible gas) with the balance being used to raise process steam. This balance ‘tail gas stream’ is subject of this project.\r\nIn the industry worldwide this tail gas is typically used to raise steam for process use or drive turbines for electricity generation, or both. At present this tail gas is burnt in a combustion chamber and is passed through a water tube boiler and air pre-heater before being discharged into the atmosphere through a vent stack. Some of the steam produced is used on site and up until recently the balance was sold to third parties.\r\n\r\nPROPOSED PROCESS\r\nOrion Engineered Carbons (Pty) Ltd (OEC) intends to fall in line with the international industry by making efficient use of this ‘tail gas’ energy source to raise steam for process use and to drive turbines for electricity generation. However, the steam produced in the current boiler is saturated and at a relatively low pressure and is used only for process heating.\r\nTherefore OEC intends to invest in a co-generation power plant with the key components of this facility being:\r\n- a water treatment plant for boiler feedwater (± 10 t/h);\r\n- a boiler to generate superheated steam (65 bar and 480ºC);\r\n- a turbine and generator (16 MW at normal, 19.5 MW at ‘max’ tail gas flow); and\r\n- a condenser cooling facility.\r\nThe excess electrical power generated – after fulfilling the plants power requirements – shall be made available to be fed into the electrical distribution grid.\r\n\r\nIt is the intention of OEC to install two inline Waste Heat Boilers (WHB) on two of the three production lines – this will affect the quality of the tail gas resulting in a higher calorific value of the tail gas and reduce the quench water consumption for cooling purposes. It is planned to use all discharge water of the power generation plant in the carbon black process, and thereby not produce any additional quantities of effluent discharge to the municipality. This would mean that these discharge quantities would replace equal quantities of the current water supply for the carbon black production process.\r\n\r\nPOWER GENERATION\r\nTo get a higher efficiency usage out of the gas a prefeasibility study was undertaken, which resulted in a project for a co-generation based power plant with a maximum gross output of 19.5 MW.\r\nThe co-generation plant will be expected to run in two modes:\r\n- Normal Mode: The co-generation plant supplies power to the co-generation plant auxiliaries, Carbon Black Plant and the surplus power is exported to the electrical distribution grid;\r\n- Island Mode: The co-generation plant supplies the co-generation plant and the Carbon Black Plant only – no export of power to the grid.\r\nTable 1: Proposed power output\r\nGross and Net Power Output for the Flow Range of Tail Gas\r\n                                    Design (73k Nm3/h)    Normal (60k Nm3/h)\r\n                                               MW                          MW\r\nGross Power Output                19.5                          16.0\r\nCogeneration Plant Usage          1.5                           1.5\r\nCarbon Black Plant Usage          3.5                           3.5\r\nExport power                            14.7                         11.0\r\n\r\nFrom the gross MW generated approximately 3.5 MW is required by the Carbon Black Plant. It is estimated that the electrical consumption of the co-generation plant will be approximately 1.5 MW. This results in a maximum of 14.7 MW potentially being available to be fed into the grid. The normal operating conditions would generate a maximum of 16 MW which will result in an excess of approximately 11.0 MW to feed into the grid.\r\n\r\nECONOMIC ASPECT\r\nThe total capital investment of the development is estimated to be R 400-500 million which would be the main cost driver. Since the company is part of an international global carbon black manufacturer ', 'Cogeneration', 'Integrated', 'other32', '', '', '', 'furnace off-gas', '', '', '', '', '', '19.5', '19.5', '11', '85', '1.46', 'ZAR', '', '33%', '', '', 'Quater1', '2016', '', '24', 'baseload', '12', '365', '24', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', '550', '10', '1600', '', 'ZAR', 'yes', '', 'fastQ3-2013-36Month', '', '3', '24', 'Orion Engineered Carbons (Pty) Ltd', 'Hitachi Power Africa', 'Hitachi Power Africa', 'Hitachi Power Europe', 'Orion has already Co-Generation plants in the following sister plants:Italy, ', '593517000', '727806000', '727000000', 'no', '', '', '', '', 30, 'tbd', 'no', 'no', 'yes', 'yes', 'no', '', 'no', '6', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', '26/06/2013', 'yes', '26/06/2013', 'yes', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '0', 'project', '', 'no', 'no', 'no', '', '', '', '4', '', 'finalised', 'no', 'Feasibility Study is completed. Value Engineering is currently happening.', 'Port Elizabeth, Deal Party, Eastern Cape, South Africa', '25', '37', '152', '33', '53', '003', 'yes', 'Site is in possession of the developer.', 'yes', 'yes', '', 'no', '', '', 'no', '', '', 'AEL is currently conducted - finalization will is expected in the next month.', '0.5', '25', '37', '829', '33', '53', '776', 'Dunkeld Substation 