(29, 148, 'Illovo Sugar (South Africa) Limited', '0315084550', 'Warren Wessels', 'Building 3C, Gleneagles Park', '10', 'Flanders Drive', 'Mount Edgecombe', 'Durban', '4300', 'Wwessels@illovo.co.za', 'Eston Mill Power Island', 'The Eston Mill currently generates its own power requirements by burning bagasse in low pressure boilers. The operation does not maximise electricity production potential as there has been no economic incentive to do so. A study has been undertaken of the feasibility of  upgrading the electricity generation process and improving factory efficiency  in order to create a surplus of electricity for export to the grid.\r\nThe improvemnet in the electricity generation will be achieved by creating a Special Purpose Vehicle (SPV) with BEE participation to establish a power island with a new high pressure 180t/h 110barg 540C boiler and 40MW extraction condensing turbine. This part of the investment will be project financed \r\nThe second element of the project is the reduction in power consumption of the mill (improved thermal efficiency) by the investment in a number of efficiency measures. This investment will be undertaken and financed by Illovo South Africa. \r\nThe supply of bagasse is a function of cane supplies and to secure these supplies for the duration of the PPA it is necessary to remunerate the farmers for their long term commitment to supply. The improved viability to the farming and milling enterprise as a result of the additional source of revenue will be of great value in supporting the creation of viable black freehold ownership of land. In this regard it should be noted that once the outstanding claims have been dealt with over 50% of cane delivered to Illovo''s mills will be by black growers.\r\n. \r\n', 'Cogeneration', 'Integrated', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '40', '40', '25', '69', '1.81', 'CPI', '', '68', '', '', 'Quater2', '2017', 'Because of seasonality of cane production the generation must commence in March/April.To achieve April 2017 taking into account all the processes and approvals, we require a bankable PPA by 1-Sept-13.  \r\n', '28', 'mid-merit', '8', '252', '24', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'yes', 'It will replace the existing generating capacity of the mill, but it will create an additional exportable surplus supply of electricity. Power generated net of parasitic load 35MW, and net export power 25MW.', '1316', '20', '1810', 'The price of R1810/MWh (R1.81kWh) is in 1 April 2011 terms and  is based on net exportable power to the grid. The1 April 2013 equivalent rate would be R2020/MWh.', 'CPI', 'no', '', 'commitQ2-2014-Phased', 'This is dependant on receiving the bankable PPA by 1- Sept-13 at the latest.', '7', '28', 'Illovo Sugar (South Africa) Limited', 'Illovo Sugar Limited', 'Not applicable', 'Not applicable', 'Respondent operates 4 electricity and steam generating plants at four existing sugar mills with a total installed capacity of 56 MW in South Africa. Illovo Sugar Limited (the parent company and technology provider) has 120 MW of installed capacity in Africa including a recently installation of a 25 MW plant in Swaziland which sells power to the grid. ', '4078700000', '3030200000', '3115000000 ', 'no', '', '', '', '', 20, 'Small scale grower, existing black freehold growers, land reform growers and the communities adjacent to the mill and cane growing areas will benefit from targeted support programs.', 'no', 'no', 'no', 'no', 'no', '', '', '15', 'yes', 'no', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'yes', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '12', 'project', '', 'no', 'no', 'no', '', '', '', '15', '', 'finalised', 'yes', 'The lenders have a long standing relationship with Illovo and and a good understanding of the Industry and the project and so no studies are required in addition to those that will be carried out as part of the bidding process.', 'Eston KZN', '29', '52', '9', '30', '31', '38', 'yes', 'The site on which the mill operates is owned by Illovo South Africa Limited. The SPV will lease an area within this site to establish the Power Island.', 'no', 'yes', '16/01/2013', 'no', '', '', 'no', '', '', 'The Department of Environmental Affairs has evaluated the Final Scoping Report (FSR) and the Plan of Study for Environmental Impact Assessment dated January 2013 and is satisfied that the documents comply with the minimum requirements of the EIA Regulations 2010.The FSR has been accepted by the Department in terms of regulation   30(1)(a).Illovo has been granted permission to proceed with the Environmental Impact Assessment as required in terms of the EIA Regulations, 2010.', '3', '29', '52 ', '7', '30 ', '32', '3', 'Eston', 'yes', '20/03/2013', 'no', '', 'Eston Mill has engaged with Eskom on the need to upgrade the transformer at the Eston sub-station in the event of the project proceeding and has received a budget cost.', 'The incomer transformer is currently a 2.5MVA transformer which will need to be upgraded to accomodate the electicity generated by this project..', 'Connecting to Eskom Grid', '24', 'Not applicable.', '55-65', '850', '64.59', 'Boiler manufacture and provision of the ancillary equipment other than the turbine alternator which will be imported', '15', 'Expansion of boiler making capacity and new technology for high pressure boiler', '2013-06-26', '2013-07-11', 'true'),
(31, 116, 'Wartsila', '+33685082005', 'Arnaud Gouet', 'Runsor', '2 ', 'Tarhajaantie ', 'Vaasa', 'Vaasa', '65101', 'arnaud.gouet@wartsila.com', 'iBhubesi Gas Engine Power Plant', 'Wärtsilä Corporation is a global leader in complete lifecycle power solutions, specialised in manufacturing reciprocating engines, engineering and installation of Turnkey Gas engine power plants as well as operation and maintenance of thermal power plants. \r\nWith the support ofSunbird Energy, a group specialised in gas exploration,Wärtsilä seeking to develop a 474 MW flexible Independent Smart Power Generation project with a minimum project life of 12 years that shall be extended in terms of size and/ or duration depending on the availability of new gas reserves. \r\nFor the purposes of aligning the plant output with the new generation determination published by the Minister of Energy, the developers have decided to adjust the plant size to fit within the current gas based generation allocation of 474MW with a COD intended for last quarter 2017\r\nThe Revised Balanced Scenario of the IRP 2010 has considered following criteria as a base of the balance: \r\na) Reducing carbon emissions;\r\nb) New technology uncertainties such as costs, operability, lead time to build etc;\r\nc) Water usage;\r\nd) Localisation and job creation;\r\ne) Southern African regional development and integration and;\r\nf) Security of supply.\r\nThe aim of this project is to develop a power generation project that answers positively to all those specific points based on the premise of combining an indigenous gas resource, with the concept of a Smart Power Generation solution. \r\n\r\na/ Reducing Carbon emission :\r\nWith the highest simple cycle efficiency of thermal power plant, reciprocating gas engines allows for the lowest possible Carbon footprint to be realised. Once built, this plant will have the highest efficiency in South Africa.\r\nThis technology was chosen by Sasol for the exact same reason, Henri Loubser, Managing director at SNE said : “On average, the carbon foot print of Eskom’s electricity is almost 1000 kg/MWh. Using gas-engine technology will allow us to reduce that figure by more than 40%.”\r\n\r\nb/ New technology, uncertainties such as cost, operability, lead time to build etc.\r\nWärtsilä Corporation will ensure that the power plant shall be delivered on time and within budget thanks to its expertise in design and construction of base load power plant. Wärtsilä has an installed base of 54 GW worldwide which includes over 5000MW in African countries. Within the Southern African Power Pool, Wärtsilä recently completed a 180 MW gas fired power plant at Sasolburg, another 80 MW power plant in Zambia and is currently building a 180 MW gas power plant in Mozambique. All projects being delivered on time and within budget.\r\nWärtsilä, as an experienced O&M contractor, will also function as the operator of the plant to ensure the availability and the reliability guarantees of the power plant are met. \r\n\r\nc) Water usage\r\nOne of the defining characteristics of Wärtsilä Gas engines power plant is to use radiators as the primary method of cooling. The use of dry cooling methods means that the water consumption is negligible which is important in  the Western Cape where water resources are scarce and fragile. \r\n\r\nd/ Localisation and Job creation\r\nDuring Construction, the site will require the employment of more than 1000 people  for civil works, mechanical installation, and electrical installation. During operation and maintenance, more than 100 People will be permanently required for the life of the plant. In the projects realised by Wärtsilä, more than 80% of those resources are employed from the local communities surrounding the power plant who will be afforded the necessary training and development by Wartsila. The power plant will have its own workshop where 100% of the maintenance can be done locally and local manufacturing and supply of spares and services will be encouraged where possible. It is to be noted as well that this area intends to become a hub for the development of Oil& Gas services from which, this project will be an anchor for such a skills creation. \r\n\r\ne) Southern African regional development and integration\r\nAs mentioned, same technology is used in neighbouring countries and will allow development and skill transfers on a regional level. \r\nIn addition, power generated from this project will alleviate the pressure experienced by the local utility (Eskom) to suppress the supply South Africa’s neighbouring countries thus aiding in the future development of both South Africa and the SADC region. \r\n\r\nf/ security of supply\r\nWe define Smart Power generation (SPG), as a resource capacity having high operational flexibility coupled with high energy efficiency. Operational flexibility requires generation to have multiple dynamic operation modes, from ultra fast grid reserve to efficient base load generation. SPG has fast start up, shut down and load ramps with agile dispatch and is able to supply MW’s onto the grid within 1 minute and reach maximum power in 5 minutes. SPG is suitable for base load generation, peaking and balancing requirements. In addition, with the ability to operate each generating unit independently, maximum plant availability can be achieved (99.6% with (n+2)) and the plants high efficiencies remain constant throughout the power range. \r\n\r\nIn addition, this technology is reknowned to be the ‘Renewable Energy’ enabler with its unique abilities to provide grid stability with the introduction of renewable onto the system. This is particularly important considering the fact that by 2018, estimates are that there will be over 4GW of wind based generation of which almost half will be located in the Western Cape area. Without this technology, managing the grid load fluctuations will be problematic for the grid operator.\r\nThe fact that both the gas field developer and the Power plant developer are joining their forces will ensure a secured supply through the entire chain from the GSA to the PPA.\r\n\r\nDetails of the project:\r\n1/ The gas field ( to be filled by Sunbird energy)\r\nGas Field and Gas Processing Plant \r\nOffshore Petroleum Block 2A, the Ibhubesi Gas Field, will be the fuel source for the IPP. Block 2A lies approximately 105km offshore of the West Coast of the RSA. The gas will be piped from the Gas Field to shore through a sub-sea pipeline. \r\nOnce onshore, the condensate will be separated from the dry gas, then the dry gas will be superheated and pressurised to meet the specifications of the relevant turbine manufacturers. All relevant approvals for the gas treatment were obtained as part of the Production Right application process for Block 2A. Interfaces at the gas connection between the IPP plant and the gas processing plant will be clearly identified and the GSA drafted accordingly.\r\n\r\n2/ The power plant\r\nThe location: Saldhana area. \r\nThis location has been chosen for the ease of access to the grid and for its proximity to the end users to limit transport losses. Furthermore, would further gas reserve be proven it can benefit either the expansion of the plant or possible distribution of the gas to other industrial users. \r\n \r\nAn application has been lodged with ESKOM for the connection at Aurora Substation (an MTS substation) as it currently presents the following connection capacity for generation:\r\nLEVEL 1: \r\n•	 Voltage level : 132 KV\r\n•	 Available line Bays : 5\r\n•	 Connection capacity : 660 MW	LEVEL 2: \r\n•	 Voltage level : 400 KV\r\n•	 Available line Bays : 3\r\n•	 Connection capacity : 1620 MW\r\n \r\nIt is to be noted that this location allows to directly feed into an existing network without any requirement for any new line.\r\nThe plant shall be equipped with 28x W18V50SG reciprocating gas engines. More details are given in the application. \r\n \r\n', 'Reciprocating', 'Gas', 'other33', '', '', '', '', '', 'iBhubesi offshore gas field', '', '', '', '512', '18', '474', '48', '1.275', 'Fuel escalation fixed 2.5% p.a., other variable costs with inflation', '47%', '', '', '', 'Quater4', '2017', '12 months for financial close from PPA signature. + 26 months construction period', '38', 'mid-merit', '12', '5', '16', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', '5500', '12 ', '1700', 'This expected tarif has been calculated using a gas price of 18USD/MMBTU which is the price offered officially by SUnbird energy. This variable shall of course be discussed and depends on many factors, including the length of the PPA. It is based on a mid merit mode.', 'Capacity tariff to be indexed according to relevant inflation index (CPI). Fuel cost at fixed rate 2.5% pa. Other variable costs with relevant inflation index (CPI).', 'yes', 'Gas portion shall be be denominated in USD', 'commitQ3-2013-Phased', 'COD date will depend on the Financial close of the project', '4', '38', 'Wärtsilä ', 'Wärtsilä', 'To be defined', 'Wartsila', 'Sasolburg 180MW gas power plant (South Africa). Mozambique CTRG 180MW gas power plant. Mauritania 120MW gas power plant. Cameroon 216MW gas power plant. Jordan IPP 3 DUAL 630MW. USA 570MW gas&dual last 24months. Dominican Republic Quisqueya I-II DUAL combine cylce 431MW. Azerbaijan Boyuk Shor GAS 371MW. Azerbaijan Sangachal DUAL 307MW. Jordan IPP 4 DUAL 273MW.\r\n \r\n Wartsila installed capacity is over 55 GW.  Wartsila experience in IPP''s is over 10 GW.', '47000000000', '42000000000', '46000000000', 'no', '', '', '', '', 27, 'During construction, there will be more than 1,000 job creation that will benefit directly the Western Cape region. During operation there will be more than 100 permanent direct employment. Furthermore this will generate skills development.', 'no', 'no', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'no', '4', 'yes', 'no', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'yes', '', 'no', 'Not available at time of RFRI submission', 'Second quarter 2017', 'Still to