(50, 177, 'Sappi Southern Africa Limited', '011 407 8472', 'Tyrone Hawkes', 'Sappi', '48 ', 'Ameshoff Street', 'Braamfontein', 'Johannesburg', '2001', 'tyrone.hawkes@sappi.com', 'Usutu - Recovery Boiler Retrofit to Biomass', 'Sappi has a strategic intent to develop renewable energy generation facilities produced from biomass sources within the group''s control. This project on a key production site is one of five being submitted in this RFRI. It is Sappi''s intent to develop a portfolio of these projects.\r\n\r\nThe DOE has indicated their interest in supporting projects that can be brought online quickly. Although the preparation for this project in not well advanced,  the boiler exists and we believe that we can commission the project quickly. Should the DOE be interested we can accellerate our work on the project.\r\n\r\nThe project proposes converting an exiting recovery boiler at Sappi''s Usutu mill in Swaziland into a biomass boiler to produce 100 tph of steam and installing a 25MW condensing turbine.\r\n\r\nThe project is green, utilises an existing boiler that would require retrofitting and therefore reduces the time till COD.\r\nThe location of the project in Swaziland will reduce line-losses and wheeling charges due to Eskom''s current obligations.\r\nAuthorisation required would entail re-licencing of de-commissioned  equipment. The project can connect to an existing grid in Swaziland and will displace Eskom purchased power in Swaziland.\r\n\r\nFuel Supply:- The biomass for the project will be supplied from a 3rd party sawmill, own forest waste and bark initially, and could include own sawmill waste in the future as a sawmill is proposed in 2020. In the long therm the biomass cost should reduce as market mechanisms develop.\r\n\r\nMain Cost Drivers:- Significant rehabilitation of existing equipment and biomass costs.\r\n\r\nDecision Points:-  Sappi requires certainty on the IPP termination clauses and tariff escalation provisions within the PPA before progressing to financial close. \r\n \r\nThe recently accounced sale of Sappi''s Usutu forests and assets to Montigny is contingent to their successful application for funding.  This has been discussed with Montigny and they have indicated their interest in the project and agreed to the submission of this RFRI. The biomass is currently owned by Sappi/Montigny and a formalised biomass supply agreement would need to be drawn up with the boiler SPV. \r\n\r\nPlease note, all financial analyses done at ZAR 9 to USD. Cresco Project Finance Consulting were used in the development of the financial model supporting the inputs to the submission.\r\n\r\n\r\n', 'Thermal', 'NewBiomass', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '25', '25', '22', '81', '0.787', 'Basket of CPI wages and transport.', '', '', '', '', 'Quater1', '2015', 'Expectation that environmental and other authorisations will not delay the process.', '12', 'baseload', '', '', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', '539.75', '20', '1390', '', 'Basket of CPI, wages and transport.', 'yes', '', 'fastQ2-2013-12Months', '', '6', '12', 'Sappi Southern Africa Limited', 'Proven technology to be used. Final equipment supplier to be confirmed - currently short listed.', 'None', 'Intended international partners cannot be disclosed at this stage due to the sales process.', 'Sappi has an installed capacity of 803MW of power globally. (Sappi Turbines - 5 Hydros, 2 Gas, 31 Steam, on 14 sites in 7 countries).', '12114000000', '12071000000', '11276000000', 'no', '', '', '', '', 1, 'Both through the development of biomass sources, as well as, getting the community involved in supplying biomass.', 'no', 'no', 'no', 'yes', 'no', 'no', 'no', '6', 'yes', 'no', 'no', '02/12/2013', 'no', '02/12/2013', 'yes', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '3', 'project', '', 'yes', 'no', 'no', '', '', '', '3', '', 'finalised', 'yes', 'A  bid-compliant financial model has been developed and current assumptions relating to CAPEX and OPEX to be confirmed through signing of legal agreements.  The project should be able to meet the minimum basic compliance requirements of a bid procurement project assuming the REIPP process is used.  No additional resource studies are anticipated as the project involves the installation of new generation capacity at an existing generation site. The biomass study has been completed - independent audit outstanding.', 'Bhunya, Swaziland', '31', '0', '24.76', '26', '31', '57.98', 'yes', 'Sappi owned site.', 'no', 'no', '', 'no', '', '', 'yes', '30/08/2013', '31/01/2014', 'Waste management and water use license - should receive authorisation within the same time period as environmental authorisation.', '0.280', '31', '0', '24.76', '26', '31', '57.98', 'Usutu/SEC substation', 'no', '', '', '', 'No meetings have taken place with Eskom regarding this project.  Permission is required from Swaziland Electricity Company for the project to take place.  They have confirmed that they would be happy with this arrangement.', 'None.', 'SEC', '4', 'This will be a planned-offset opportunity between SEC and Eskom.', '100+', '339', '62.81', 'It is expected that a significant portion of the construction and erection would come from South Africa, with a significant portion coming from within Swaziland. The local content portion indicated above will come from Southern Africa.', '40', 'Boiler and electrical components.', '2013-06-28', '2013-07-12', 'true'),
(53, 184, 'KiPower (Pty) Limited', '+27136563659', 'Ayanda Bam', 'Private Bag X 7250', '2', 'Neven Street', '-', 'Witbank', '1035', 'hearlgm@bv.com', 'Kuyasa Power Plant Project', 'The Kuyasa Power Plant Project (Project) is envisaged to form part of Eskom’s base load Independent Power Producer (IPP) Programme, where the resulting electricity generated from the facility will be sold to Eskom and other potential customers.  This Project will be a 600 MW (gross) mine-mouth coal-fired power plant to be built, owned and operated by KiPower (Pty) Limited (KiPower), which is a subsidiary of Kuyasa Mining (Pty) Limited (Kuyasa).  The power plant will be located on a site owned by Kuyasa, about 80 km east of Johannesburg and about 20 km southeast of Delmas in the Victor Khanye Municipality, within the Nkangala District Municipality of the Mpumalanga Province.  Kuyasa owns the Delmas Coal and Ikhwezi Colliery.\r\n\r\nThis RFRI response provides updated information for the Kuyasa Power Plant Project in relation to the RFI information submitted by KiPower (Pty) Limited to DOE on 20 March 2012.\r\n\r\nThe power plant will be fuelled by coal produced from Kuyasa’s Delmas Coal mine.  Potable water will either be produced at the power plant or will be provided from a Rand Water line that runs between Springs and Devon to the south of the mine.  Rand Water could also provide all the raw water required for the power plant, but other potential sources of water are also being investigated to reduce and/or supplement this source of water in the long term.  The raw water will be piped to the site and stored in a raw water storage tank.\r\n\r\nThe 600 MW (gross) power plant configuration will consist of four units each capable of producing 150 MW (gross) electrical power.  Each unit will consist of one circulating fluidized bed (CFB) boiler supplying steam to a 150 MW (gross) steam turbine generator.  The power plant will include all associated material handling systems for coal, sorbent and ash, all other auxiliary systems, and plant administrative building and structures.  \r\n\r\nEmissions resulting from the combustion of coal will be controlled to within South African emissions limits.  Sulphur dioxides (SO2) emissions will be controlled through combustion processes by directly injecting sorbent into the CFB boiler combustion chamber. Nitrogen oxides (NOx) emissions will be controlled through regulating combustion temperature by varying combustion air supplied by one full capacity primary air fan and one full capacity secondary air fan.  A pulse jet fabric filter system will control particulate emissions.  The facility will also use air-cooled condensers (or dry cooling towers), fin fan coolers for the auxiliary cooling water systems, and a zero liquid effluent discharge system to minimise water usage and avoid any discharge of waste-water.  Ash generated by the power plant will be delivered via overland conveyor to an ash disposal facility to be located within proximity of the power plant site.  Electricity generated from the facility will be connected to Eskom’s 400 kV transmission network.  \r\n', 'Thermal', 'Coal', '', '', 'Plant Features Air-Cooled Condenser', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '600', '150', '525', '85', '0.85', '1', '35%', '', '', '', 'Quater1', '2018', 'The project schedule covers an overall duration of 51 months from signature of PPA to Commercial Operation Date (COD) of the first unit (or Unit 1). The\r\nimplementation plan is based on 45 month construction and commissioning period for each unit.\r\n', '51', 'baseload', '12', '310', '24', 'yes', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', '16000', '30', '1020', 'Expected Price Per MWh indicated is Average First Year Power Sales Rate', 'Not applicable', 'yes', '', 'commitQ2-2014-Phased', 'KiPower (Pty) Limited will be ready to negotiate to a set of commitment guarantees by 2Q 2014. COD for Phase 1 (Unit 1) planned for Q1 of 2018.', '6', '51', 'KiPower (Pty) Limited', 'Technology provided has not yet been identified.', 'South Africa partner (if any) has not been identified.', 'International partner (if any) has not been identified.', 'KiPower (Pty) Limited plans to partner with qualified and experienced local contractors, and local equipment and material suppliers for this Project. Local partners have not been identified at this time. Experienced power industry consultants are involved in developing the Project and will also be involved in the Project execution. Black & Veatch as an Owner''s Engineer has extensive international experience in power plant project development, design, and construction.', '0', '0', '0', 'no', '', '', '', '', 100, 'To be determined.', 'no', 'no', 'no', 'yes', 'no', 'no', 'no', '9', 'yes', 'no', 'no', '07/01/2017', 'no', '', 'yes', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '3', 'project', '', 'no', 'no', 'no', '', '', '', '12', '', 'finalised', 'yes', 'The Kuyasa Power Plant Project Feasibility Study Final Report prepared by Black & Veatch Corporation (Kansas City, USA) was completed in March 2010. The Feasibility Study Final Report concluded a 4x150 MW power plant using circulating fluidized bed boiler technology can be built near the site owned by Kuyasa Mines (Pty) Limited. A Final Scoping Report (FSR) was submitted to the National Department of Environmental Affairs (DEA) and was approved on 7 November 2012. The Draft EIA and EMPr reports are being finalized and are anticipated to be issued for public comment no later than 4Q 2013.', 'Delmas, Mpumalanga, South Africa', '28', '50', '43.824', '26', '14', '43.278', 'yes', 'The proposed 600 MW (gross) Kuyasa Power Plant Project will be constructed\r\non a site already owned by BHP Billiton approximately 80 km east of Johannesburg and approximately 20 km southeast of Delmas. Land purchase of the site by KiPower (Pty) Limited is underway. The power plant will be a mine – mouth coal-fired power generation facility and it will be located within 5km of the mines North Shaft.  The ash disposal facility site is owned by Ikhwezi Colliery (Pty) Limited (part of Kuyasa Mining).', 'no', 'no', '', 'yes', '03/10/2013', '01/03/2014', 'no', '', '', 'A Final Scoping Report (FSR) was submitted to the National Department of Environmental Affairs (DEA) and was approved on 7 November 2012. The Draft EIA and EMPr reports are being finalized and are anticipated to be issued for public comment no later than 4Q 2013. Specialist studies required to be performed to obtain other government approvals such as the National Environmental Management Act (Act 107 of 1998), National Environmental Management: Waste Act (Act 59 of 2008), National Water Act (1998), National Environmental Management: Air Quality Act (Act 39 of 2004), National Heritage Resources Act (1999), Occupational Health and Safety Act, Act 85 (1993), Land Zoning, Development Facilitation Act (1995), Town Planning and Townships Ordinance (1986) are being finalized.', '5', '28', '50', '52.321', '26', '14', '16.949', 'Eskom 400 kV Near Farm Haverglen 269 IR in the Mpumalanga area', 'yes', '12/07/2012', 'yes', '"Cost Estimate Letter for the Construction of Works to Connect a Generator to the Transmission System for 600 MW Thermal Power Plant for Ki Power (Pty) Limited" issued by Eskom 19 December 2012.', 'Meeting to review the "Cost Estimate Letter for the Construction of Works to Connect a Generator to the Transmission System for 600 MW Thermal Power Plant for Ki Power (Pty) Limited" conducted at Eskom''s Menlyn Park (Pretoria) office on 12 April 2013.', 'The Kuyasa Power Project will tie into the planned Kusile-Zeus Eskom 400 kV transmission line. A new switchyard will be constructed at the Kuysas Project''s point of supply.', 'Project will be connected to the existing Eskom grid.', '36', 'Not applicable as the Project is located within South Africa near town of Delmas in Mpumalanga, South Africa.', '0-30', '2400', '15.00', 'Selected plant equipment and construction commodity materials.', '2500', 'During operations, some 160 to 200 permanent operations and maintenance (O&M) positions will be created. These will range from unskilled to highly specialised positions. ', '2013-06-28', '2013-07-12', 'true'),
(54, 185, 'Dave Long', '+27832352964', 'Dave Long', 'House', '7', 'St Andrews Road', 'Glenadrienne', 'Sandton', '2196', 'dlong.ies@gmail.com', 'PAMSA Cogen and Biomass', 'This is a dummy project for education and understanding of the RFRI process, all in support of PAMSA''s role in engaging DOE and National Treasury on the IPP procurement processes. ', 'Cogeneration', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '27', '27', '25', '80', '1.40', '6%', '', '60%', '', '', 'Quater2', '2014', '', '6', 'mid-merit', '12', '350', '24', 'yes', '', 'yes', 'MTPPP ends in December 2013.', 'yes', 'TA 1 on 32b system will be decommissioned.', '800', '15', ' 1400', '', '6', 'yes', '', 'fastQ2-2013-24Month', '', '3', '12', 'PAMSA Crew', 'Widgets Pty Ltd', 'Self', 'Widgets International', 'What a question!', '10000000 ', '12000000', '13000000', '', '', '', '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '2013-06-30', '2013-07-10', ''),
(55, 45, 'Farmsecure Energy / Basil Read Energy', '0826730514', 'Werner van Wyk', 'Avanti South Block', '1', 'Carl Cronje Drive', 'Tygervalley', 'Cape Town', '8001', 'werner.vanwyk@farmsecure.co.za', 'Busby Renewables', 'The Busby Renewables 10MW Biomass Project is a co-generation project which will integrate with the existing sawmill activity.  The project will utilize waste wood chips, sawdust as well as off-cuts from the sawmill, currently burnt in low pressure steam boilers for the drying kilns.  Additionally, waste wood from existing plantations will be collected and utilized to generate electricity to be sold under the short term risk mitigation program as issued by the Department of Energy.\r\n\r\nThe J&J Timber Mill is located approximately 45 kilometers North-West of Piet Retief, which is in the South African province of Mpumalanga. Piet Retief is approximately 330km North of Durban. The site is located at S 26.812, E 30.441; the elevation is 1250m.\r\n\r\nFinancial models were developed based on a steam Rankine cycle in order to evaluate the feasibility and the most suitable technology on a project specific basis\r\nThe fuel specifications are:\r\n•	Biomass Price (Rand/ton): 300 \r\n•	Biomass Feed (wet ton/day): 270\r\n•	Moisture Content: 30%\r\n•	Higher Heating value (MJ/kg on a dry basis): 20.50\r\n\r\nThe design output/objective of the plant is:\r\n•	8.8 MWe net/salable power into existing grid ~10 MW generated power\r\n•	8 ton/h of steam at 6 Bar(g) saturated supply to drying kilns\r\n\r\nThe total electricity that will be available for sale is 70 650 602 kW/h per annum. The plant will start in the first quarter of 2015. The income, in 2015, from the electricity generated will be approximately R102 million at a selling price of R1.15/kWh (2013 price) and steam selling at R189. From 2015 onward the electricity price will grow with a projected annual increase of 5% per year. The all inclusive total capex will amount to R242 million for this waste to energy project and the annual operating expenses and cost of sales will be R47.2 million (2015, 6% annual growth).\r\n\r\nThe following direct agreements and approvals are in place:\r\n•	Long term Lease agreement\r\n•	Long term Biomass Supply agreement for 100 000 ton/annum based on a Lower \r\n        Heat Value of 12.83 MJ/kg      \r\n•	Pre-Engineering Procurement, Construction and Commissioning agreement with KC Cottrell for the power island (off-shore)             \r\n•	Heads of Terms agreement for the Engineering, Procurement and Construction (on \r\n        shore) with Basil Read Matomo   \r\n•	Heads of Terms agreement for the Operation and Maintenance of the energy    \r\n        generation facility\r\n•	Environmental compliance based on a confirmation letter from the Department of Environmental affairs\r\n•	Eskom approved grid connection point\r\n•	Signed Termsheet with Basil Read Energy for the equity investment into four\r\n        biomass to energy projects \r\n•	Debt Termsheet from Investec based on 70% gearing\r\n', 'Cogeneration', 'Integrated', 'BiomassCurrent', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '10', '10', '8.83', '80.1', '1.21', 'CPI Inflation (5%)', '', '37.6%', '', '', 'Quater1', '2015', 'EPC commited to 16 months from date of signature to commissioning. Additional 2 months required to reach financial close.', '18', 'baseload', '', '', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', '242', '20', '1210', '', 'CPI Inflation (5%)', 'yes', '', 'fastQ2-2013-24Month', '', '2', '18', 'Farmsecure Energy/Basil Read Energy JV', 'KC Cottrell', 'Basil Read Matomo', 'KC Cottrell', 'Basil Read Energy develops, funds, owns, operates and maintains utility scale power generation and energy storage assets in Africa.  As an integrated energy company Basil Read Energy believes that the key to electrical power generation in Africa is through utilising the renewable and other primary energy resources available in the region to create truly sustainable, efficient and cost effective power plants to provide electrical power to the African continent (company profile attached).\r\nBasil Read Energy flagship projects in the energy projects in Africa are:\r\n• Metrowind Van Stadens Wind Farm (27 MW) – under construction, COD February 2014\r\n• Beaufort West Photovoltaic Solar Plant (75 MW) – under development, COD Q1 2015\r\n• EOS Furnace Off Gas Power Plants (2 x 30 MW) – under development, COD Q3 2015\r\n• Biomass fuelled cogeneration plant (20 MW) – under development, COD 2015\r\n• Hydro 1 (4 MW) – under development, COD 2015\r\n• Hydro 2-4 (3 x 10 MW) – prefeasibility, COD 2016\r\n\r\nBasil Read Matomo is a leading design, project engineering, procurement and construction (EPC) company servicing the minerals processing, chemical and renewable energy sectors. We offer the full range of turn-key solutions for project implementation, ranging from concept development and feasibility studies through to final project execution. BRM has extensive experience in the practical implementation of projects including multi-disciplinary engineering, design, procurement, construction, project management and commissioning. We also offer post-implementation operating services (company profile attached)\r\n\r\nKC Cottrell is a global leader in Green technologies and flue gas cleaning as well as state of the art environmental technologies and engineering capability (company profile attached).\r\n', '400000', '7000000', '16000000', 'yes', '', '', '', '', 30, 'All un-skilled labour for the power plant will be sourced from the surrounding historically disadvantaged communities.  The project will further increase job opportunities for un-skilled labour as it is required for the harvesting and transportation of biomass to the power plant.  Job opportunities will be created at two levels: permanent jobs and through community involvement.  Permanent jobs will consist of truck drivers and biomass collectors, around forty jobs will be created at this level.  In addition it is envisaged that around sixty opportunities for self employment will be created in the surrounding informal sectors, where the community may collect biomass to be weighed and earn an income.\r\n\r\nFurthermore, any enhancement of the sustainability of the forestry industry has a positive socio-economic effect on the region.  Additional economic activity generated by greater utilization of the biomass will contribute to the rural economy through increased income levels and greater employment.  Personnel reside in the rural communities in which the power plant is located.  This means that dividends, profits, higher-paid salaries, business skills, technical skills and entrepreneurial skills are retained in the local rural economy and contribute directly to further economic activity in the otherwise impoverished rural economy. \r\n\r\nIt is also the shareholders prerogative for 5% of the project equity to be placed in a community trust for spending on community upliftment and education.', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', '3', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', '01/12/2014', 'yes', '01/12/2014', 'yes', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '3', 'project', '', 'no', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'no', '', '3', '', 'finalised', 'yes', 'Yes. Busby Renewables will utilize plantation residues from forestry operations and sawmill residues from sawmill operations as feedstock for the power plant.  To evaluate the biomass availability for the plant, Farmsecure Energy has compiled the following biomass assessment report: “Assessment of the plantation residues available for the Busby Renewables project”. The report shows that there is more than sufficient biomass available for the project.\r\n\r\nBusby Renewables applied for a Section 21 (a) Water Use for the abstraction of ground water from existing boreholes.  A Groundwater Potential Study was conducted by WSM Leshika Consulting which concluded that the existing boreholes can sustain the plant’s water demand and that the proposed abstraction volume is within the recommended sustainable volume.  \r\n\r\nNo additional studies are likely to be required by any lenders.  \r\n', 'Panbult, Mpumalanga, South Africa', '30', '26', '26', '26', '48', '51', 'yes', 'Long term lease agreement has been signed and attached. Site map included and attached. No additional rights for land use and site location is required.', 'yes', 'yes', '', 'no', '', '', 'no', '', '', 'Farmsecure Energy’s Environmental Consultant send a letter to the Department of Environmental Affairs requesting confirmation that the Busby Renewables project does not require an environmental authorisation.  This letter contained all the possible listed activities associated with the project and the reasons why these activities are not triggered. The Department concurred with the findings of the letter and approved that the establishment of the Busby Renewables plant does not trigger any listed activities and therefore, the project does not require Environmental Authorisation, a Waste Management License nor an Atmospheric Emission License for the commencement of the project.\r\n\r\nBusby Renewables applied for a Section 21 (a) Water Use for the abstraction of ground water from existing boreholes.  The application was submitted to the Department of Water Affairs on the 7th of May 2013.  For this application a Groundwater Potential Study was conducted by WSM Leshika Consulting which concluded that the existing boreholes can sustain the plant’s water demand and that the proposed abstraction volume is within the recommended sustainable volume.  The Department of Water Affairs has indicated that the application is currently with their Geohydrological department.  \r\n\r\nFarmsecure Energy has engaged with Nersa and has reached a stage where the Power Purchase Agreement (PPA) needs to be submitted to Nersa by Farmsecure Energy in order to start the 120 day generation license finalisation and award period.', '1', '30', '26', '24.68', '26', '48', '46.30', 'Panbult Substation', 'yes', '15/06/2012', 'yes', 'Hard copy attached', 'Site visits and meetings held with Eskom''s Grid Access Unit.', '1km overhead line required to connect to Panbult substation. Extension of the bus bar at the sub station required. Establishment of feeder bay and metering equipment at Panbult sub station. The other option available is to connect on the sawmill''s site and build own substation. The quickest option however will be taken.', 'Eskom grid connection.', '4', 'Project within the borders of South Africa.', '75-85', '97', '40.08', 'The project will create opportunities for local South African manufacture companies that can supply the project with fuel handling systems, water treatment plant, air cooled condenser set, HV electrical system, LV electrical, MCC''s instrumentation and controls, piping, valves and on-site reticulation.  Local South African companies also have the opportunity to do all civil works, shipments, local transport and the grid connection for the project.', '65', 'The project will create opportunities for local South African companies to be contracted to do maintenance on imported and local equipment.  All un-skilled labour will be sourced from the surrounding rural communities.  Employees will be trained over a period of two years under the supervision of O&M manager to eventually run the plant together with the O&M manager.  ', '2013-07-01', '2013-07-11', 'true');
