(56, 45, 'Farmsecure Energy/Basil Read Energy', '+27826730514', 'Werner van Wyk', 'Avanti South Block', '1', 'Carl Cronje Drive', 'Tygervalley', 'Cape Town', '8001', 'werner.vanwyk@farmsecure.co.za', 'Kubusi Energy', 'The Kubusi Energy 9.2 MWe Biomass Project is a co-generation project which will feed into the Eskom grid.  The project will utilize waste wood chips, sawdust as well as off-cuts from the sawmill.  Additionally, waste wood from existing plantations will be collected and utilized to generate electricity to be sold under the medium term risk mitigation program as issued by the Department of Energy.\r\n\r\nThe Rance Timber Kubusi Mill is located outside Stutterheim, 60km North-West of East-London, which is in the South African province of the Eastern Cape.  The site is located at S 32.586, E 27.288; the elevation is 982m.\r\n\r\nThe fuel specifications are: \r\n•	Biomass Price (Rand/ton): 250\r\n•	Biomass Feed (wet ton/day): 300\r\n•	Moisture Content: 40%\r\n•	Lower Heating value (MJ/kg as received): 10.70\r\n\r\nThe design output/objective of the plant is:\r\n•	8.07 MWe net/salable power into existing grid ~9.23 MW generated power\r\n\r\nThe total electricity that will be available for sale is 64 556 475 kWh per annum. The plant will commission in the first quarter of 2015. The income, in 2015, from the electricity generated and steam produced will be approximately R106 million at a selling price of R1.33/kWh (2013) and R196 per ton steam. The escalation for the electricity price is linked to the consumer price index (CPI) of 5% per year. The all inclusive total capex will amount to R273 million for this co-generation project and the annual operating expenses and cost of sales will be R46 million (2015, 5% annual growth).\r\n\r\nThe following direct agreements and approvals are in place:\r\n•	Long term Lease agreement on the Kubusi Sawmill\r\n•	Long term Biomass Supply agreement for 100 000 ton/annum based on a Lower \r\n        Heat Value of 10.70 MJ/kg      \r\n•	Pre-Engineering Procurement, Construction and Commissioning agreement with\r\n        KC Cottrell for the power island (off-shore)             \r\n•	Heads of Terms agreement for the Engineering, Procurement and Construction (on \r\n        shore) with Basil Read Matomo   \r\n•	Heads of Terms agreement for the Operation and Maintenance of the energy    \r\n        generation facility\r\n•	Environmental compliance based on screening report\r\n•	Eskom approved grid connection point\r\n•	Signed Termsheet with Basil Read Energy for the equity investment into four\r\n        biomass to energy projects \r\n•	Debt Termsheet from Investec based on 70% gearing', 'Cogeneration', 'Integrated', 'BiomassCurrent', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '10', '10', '8.07', '73.6', '1.41', 'CPI Inflation (5%)', '', '37%', '', '', 'Quater1', '2015', 'EPC committed to 16 months from date of signature to commissioning. Additional 2 months required to reach financial close.', '18', 'baseload', '', '', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', '273', '20', '1410', '', 'CPI inflation (5%)', 'yes', '', 'fastQ2-2013-24Month', '', '2', '18', 'Farmsecure Energy / Basil Read Energy JV', 'KC Cottrell', 'Basil Read Matomo', 'KC Cottrell', 'Basil Read Energy develops, funds, owns, operates and maintains utility scale power generation and energy storage assets in Africa.  As an integrated energy company Basil Read Energy believes that the key to electrical power generation in Africa is through utilising the renewable and other primary energy resources available in the region to create truly sustainable, efficient and cost effective power plants to provide electrical power to the African continent (company profile attached).\r\nBasil Read Energy flagship projects in the energy projects in Africa are:\r\n• Metrowind Van Stadens Wind Farm (27 MW) – under construction, COD February 2014        \r\n• Beaufort West Photovoltaic Solar Plant (75 MW) – under development, COD Q1 2015\r\n• EOS Furnace Off Gas Power Plants (2 x 30 MW) – under development, COD Q3 2015\r\n• Biomass fuelled cogeneration plant (20 MW) – under development, COD 2015\r\n• Hydro 1 (4 MW) – under development, COD 2015\r\n• Hydro 2-4 (3 x 10 MW) – prefeasibility, COD 2016\r\n\r\nBasil Read Matomo is a leading design, project engineering, procurement and construction (EPC) company servicing the minerals processing, chemical and renewable energy sectors. We offer the full range of turn-key solutions for project implementation, ranging from concept development and feasibility studies through to final project execution. BRM has extensive experience in the practical implementation of projects including multi-disciplinary engineering, design, procurement, construction, project management and commissioning. We also offer post-implementation operating services (company profile attached)\r\n\r\nKC Cottrell is a global leader in Green technologies and flue gas cleaning as well as state of the art environmental technologies and engineering capability (company profile attached).\r\n', '400000', '7000000', '16000000', 'yes', '', '', '', '', 30, 'All un-skilled labour for the power plant will be sourced from the surrounding historically disadvantaged communities.  The biomass project will further increase job opportunities for un-skilled labour as it is required for the harvesting and transportation of biomass to the power plant.  Job opportunities will be created at two levels: permanent jobs and through community involvement.  Permanent jobs will consist of truck drivers and biomass collectors, around forty jobs will be created at this level.  In addition it is envisaged that around 400 opportunities for self employment will be created in the surrounding informal sectors, where the community may collect biomass and earn an income.\r\n\r\nFurthermore, any enhancement of the sustainability of the forestry industry has a positive socio-economic effect on the region.  Additional economic activity generated by greater utilization of the biomass will contribute to the rural economy through increased income levels and greater employment.  Personnel reside in the rural communities in which the power plant is located.  This means that dividends, profits, higher-paid salaries, business skills, technical skills and entrepreneurial skills are retained in the local rural economy and contribute directly to further economic activity in the otherwise impoverished rural economy.\r\n\r\n It is also the shareholders prerogative for 5% of the project equity to be placed in a community trust for spending on community upliftment and education.\r\n', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', '3', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', '01/12/2014', 'yes', '01/12/2014', 'yes', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '3', 'project', '', 'no', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'no', '', '3', '', 'finalised', 'yes', 'Yes. Kubusi Energy will utilize plantation residues from forestry operations and sawmill residues from sawmill operations as feed-stock for the power plant.  To evaluate the biomass availability for the plant, Fractal Forest has compiled the following biomass assessment report: “Assessment of the biomass of the timber plantations of the Amathole Forestry Company”.  The report shows that there is more than sufficient biomass available for a biomass to energy project.\r\n\r\nRance Timber Trust is already in possession of a Water Use Certificate for 500 000m3 per year for irrigation purposes.  Kubusi Energy will apply for an article 25(2) transfer of 40000m3 per year of the existing water use.\r\n                                                                                                                                 No additional studies are likely to be required by any lenders.\r\n', 'Stutterheim, Eastern Cape, South Africa', '27', '17', '12', '32', '35', '19', 'yes', 'Long term lease agreement has been signed and attached. Site map included and attached. No additional rights for land use and site location is required.', 'yes', 'yes', '', 'no', '', '', 'no', '', '', 'In 2010 Imithi Services compiled a screening report on the Kubusi Energy project and concluded that the project does not require environmental authorization.  This report was send to the Department of Economic Development, Environment and Tourism (DEDET), however no letter of confirmation on the findings was received from DEDET.  Therefore, Farmsecure Energy’s Environmental Consultant also sent a letter of enquiry to the Department of Environmental Affairs requesting confirmation that the Kubusi Energy project does not require environmental authorisation.  This letter contained all the possible listed activities associated with the project and the reasons why these activities are not triggered.  The letter of enquiry was send on the 3de of July 2013 and a decision is expected by the middle of August 2013.  We trust that the outcome of their findings will be similar to the Busby Renewables project and that the Department will confirm that the establishment of the Kubusi Energy project does require Environmental Authorization, a Waste Management License nor an Atmospheric Emission License as was approved for the Busby Renewables project.\r\n\r\nRance Timber Trust is already in possession of a Water Use Certificate for 500 000m3 per year for irrigation purposes.  Kubusi Energy will apply for an article 25(2) transfer of 40 000m3 per year of the existing water use. This application will be submitted to the Department of Water Affairs before the end of July. \r\n\r\nFarmsecure Energy has engaged with Nersa and has reached a stage where the Power Purchase Agreement (PPA) needs to be submitted to Nersa by Farmsecure Energy in order to start the 120 day generation licence finalisation and award period.', '26.2', '27', '28', '43.21', '32', '35', '54.97', 'Kubusi substation', 'no', '', '', '', 'Phase 1 application submitted. Receival of Phase 1 Eskom grid connection application confirmed by Grid Access Unit of Eskom.', 'Transmission line required. Possible extension of busbar at Kubusi substation.', 'Eskom grid. Please see map of grid connection point and path of transmission line.', '8', 'Not applicable. Project within the boundaries of South Africa.', '75-85', '127', '46.52', 'The project will create opportunities for local South African manufacture companies that can supply the project with fuel handling systems, water treatment plant, air cooled condenser set, HV electrical system, LV electrical, MCC''s instrumentation and controls, piping, valves and on-site reticulation.  Local South African companies also have the opportunity to do all civil works, shipments, local transport and the grid connection for the project.', '65', 'The project will create opportunities for local South African companies to be contracted to do maintenance on imported and local equipment.  All un-skilled labour will be sourced from the surrounding rural communities.  Employees will be trained over a period of two years under the supervision of O&M manager to eventually run the plant together with the O&M manager.  ', '2013-07-01', '2013-07-11', 'true'),
