er Plants (2 x 30 MW) – under development, COD Q3 2015\r\n• Biomass fuelled cogeneration plant (20 MW) – under development, COD 2015\r\n• Hydro 1 (4 MW) – under development, COD 2015\r\n• Hydro 2-4 (3 x 10 MW) – prefeasibility, COD 2016\r\n\r\nBasil Read Matomo is a leading design, project engineering, procurement and construction (EPC) company servicing the minerals processing, chemical and renewable energy sectors. We offer the full range of turn-key solutions for project implementation, ranging from concept development and feasibility studies through to final project execution. BRM has extensive experience in the practical implementation of projects including multi-disciplinary engineering, design, procurement, construction, project management and commissioning. We also offer post-implementation operating services (company profile attached)\r\n\r\nKC Cottrell is a global leader in Green technologies and flue gas cleaning as well as state of the art environmental technologies and engineering capability (company profile attached).', '400000', '7000000', '16000000', 'yes', '', '', '', '', 30, 'All un-skilled labour for the power plant will be sourced from the surrounding historically disadvantaged communities.  The project will further increase job opportunities for un-skilled labour as it is required for the harvesting and transportation of biomass to the power plant.  Job opportunities will be created at two levels: permanent jobs and through community involvement.  Permanent jobs will consist of truck drivers and biomass collectors, around forty jobs will be created at this level.  In addition it is envisaged that around sixty opportunities for self employment will be created in the surrounding informal sectors, where the community may collect biomass and earn an income.  \r\n\r\nFurthermore, any enhancement of the sustainability of the forestry industry has a positive socio-economic effect on the region.  Additional economic activity generated by greater utilization of the biomass will contribute to the rural economy through increased income levels and greater employment.  Personnel reside in the rural communities in which the power plant is located.  This means that dividends, profits, higher-paid salaries, business skills, technical skills and entrepreneurial skills are retained in the local rural economy and contribute directly to further economic activity in the otherwise impoverished rural economy. \r\n\r\nIt is also the shareholders prerogative for 5% of the project equity to be placed in a community trust for spending on community upliftment and education.', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', '3', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', '01/12/2014', 'yes', '01/12/2014', 'yes', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '3', 'project', '', 'no', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'no', '', '3', '', 'finalised', 'yes', 'Lazybend Renewables will utilize plantation residues from forestry operations and sawmill residues from sawmill operations as feedstock for the power plant.  The Institute for Commercial Forestry Research (ICFR) has committed to supply Farmsecure Energy by the end of July 2013 with the necessary information to compile a biomass assessment report similar to “Assessment of the plantation residues available for the Busby Renewables project”.  \r\n\r\nLazybend Renewables applied for a Section 21 (a) Water Use for the abstraction of ground water from existing boreholes.  A Groundwater Potential Study was conducted by WSM Leshika Consulting which concluded that Borehole BH2 can sustain the plant’s water demand and that the proposed abstraction is within the General Authorization limits in terms of R399 and therefore this water use only needs to be registered.  \r\n', 'Amsterdam, Mpumalanga, South Africa', '30', '37', '50', '26', '30', '55', 'yes', 'Long term Lease agreement has been signed and attached, site map included and attached. No additional rights for land use and site location is required.', 'yes', 'yes', '', 'no', '', '', 'no', '', '', 'Farmsecure Energy’s Environmental Consultant sent a letter to the Department of Environmental Affairs requesting confirmation that the Lazybend Renewables project does not require environmental authorization.  This letter contained all the possible listed activities associated with the project and the reasons why these activities are not triggered.  The letter of enquiry was sent on the 13th of July 2013 and and a decision is expected by the middle of August 2013.  We trust that the outcome of their findings will be similar to the Busby Renewables project and that the Department will confirm that the establishment of the Lazybend Renewables project does not require Environmental Authorization, a Waste Management License nor an Atmospheric Emission License as was approved for the Busby Renewables project.\r\n\r\nLazybend Renewables applied for a Section 21 (a) Water Use for the abstraction of ground water from existing boreholes.  The application was submitted to the Department of Water Affairs on the 20th of June 2013.  For this application a Groundwater Potential Study was conducted by WSM Leshika Consulting which concluded that Borehole BH2 can sustain the plant’s water demand and that the proposed abstraction is within the General Authorization limits in terms of R399 and therefore this water use only needs to be registered.  \r\n\r\nFarmsecure Energy has engaged with Nersa and has reached a stage where the Power Purchase Agreement (PPA) needs to be submitted to Nersa by Farmsecure Energy in order to start the 120 day generation license finalization and award period.', '32.5', '30', '29', '1.93', '26', '39', '27.56', 'Jericho substation', 'yes', '01/06/2012', 'yes', 'Copy attached', 'Site visits and meetings held with Eskom''s Grid Access Unit.', '33 km 22kV line required to connect to Jericho substation. Add feeder bay at sub station. Establish Lazybend sub station. Install VT units for islanding protection. Install bidirectional metering at the point of connection.', 'Eskom grid connection', '8', 'Project within the borders of South Africa.', '75-85', '137', '48.41', 'The project will create opportunities for local South African manufacture companies that can supply the project with fuel handling systems, water treatment plant, air cooled condenser set, HV electrical system, LV electrical, MCC''s instrumentation and controls, piping, valves and on-site reticulation.  Local South African companies also have the opportunity to do all civil works, shipments, local transport and the grid connection for the project.', '65', 'The project will create opportunities for local South African companies to be contracted to do maintenance on imported and local equipment.  All un-skilled labour will be sourced from the surrounding rural communities.  Employees will be trained over a period of two years under the supervision of O&M manager to eventually run the plant together with the O&M manager.  ', '2013-07-01', '2013-07-11', 'true'),
(58, 31, 'Tsb Sugar RSA (Pty) Ltd', '0315087326', 'Luke Brouckaert', 'Admin Building', '1', 'Malalane Mill Complex Off R570', 'Malalane', 'Malalane', '1320', 'brouckaertl@tsb.co.za', 'Komati T/A 3', 'This RFI response covers the proposed installation of a new Turbo-alternator to utilize an existing let-down steam opportunity at Komati Mill. Information provided here is as accurate as possible with regards to the current state of the project.  Some changes are expected as the project development progresses.  The pre-feasibility study was done in 2011 and this needs to be developed into a full feasibility study with an update on the capital, lending arrangements, SPV structure and confirmed power export capacity.  \r\n\r\nKomati Mill has existing sugar cane bagasse boilers and currently some steam is passed through a let-down station.  With some modification to the existing infrastructure the opportunity exists to install a new turbo-alternator to take advantage of this let-down steam to generate more electricity.  All this additional co-generated electricity would be available to the grid as the Mill is already electricity self sufficient.  \r\n\r\nThe fuel for this opportunity comes from the fibre delivered with the sugar cane to the Mill.  \r\n\r\nThe Environmental Impact Assessment Report has been received by the Department and approval is expected by end of July 2013.  The project may be EPC/EPCM, a decision still to be taken. The project execution structure would be shaped to best benefit the project and lenders.The final execution of the project will be subject to approval by the Tsb Sugar Board of Directors.\r\n\r\nThis opportunity is a quick to market solution to assist in supplying electricity.  In the RFI submitted in 2012 it was indicated that the Mill can achieve 81 MW in an optimzed scenario with a full power potential of 94 MW.  The other mills in the group namely Pongola and Malalane can achieve 41MW/51MW and 39MW/50MW respectively in the Optimized and full power output.  To achieve these scenarios would require amonst others successful development of "brown leaf" separation technology from hand-cut cane and the installation of high pressure boilers at the Mills. Significant engineering still needs to be done to achieve accurate estimates for these options and they are therefore not considered in the detail submission presented in this RFRI.\r\n', 'Cogeneration', 'CogenerationBack', 'BiomassCurrent', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '35', '15', '11', '58.8', '0.36', 'Basket', '', '', '', '', 'Quater2', '2016', 'COD depends on delivery of turbine.  It is possible to adjust the COD if some integration work can be executed while the Mill is in operation.  This is subject to detail study and information is not available yet.', '22', 'mid-merit', '9', '260', '21.6', 'no', '', 'yes', 'Komati Mill currently has an ESKOM agreement in place to supply at maximum 6MW. (Normal supply 4MW)', 'no', 'The project will not replace but will supplement the existing power co-generation by allowing additional power to be co-generated.  ', '356', '20', '0.90', '', 'Basket', 'yes', '', 'fastQ3-2013-36Month', 'Subject to Tsb Sugar Board approval', '9', '22', 'Tsb Sugar RSA (Pty) Ltd (a subsidiary of Remgro)', 'Tsb Sugar RSA (Pty) Ltd ', 'Tsb Sugar RSA (Pty) Ltd ', 'N/A', 'The promoter, Tsb Sugar RSA (Pty) Ltd, has been generating electricity at the various sites since 1967 when its first Mill was commissioned in Malalane. \r\nThe technology and link into current operations is proven and well established.  Komati Mill has been exporting power since it''s commissioning in 1994.  \r\nTsb Sugar Technical Support Services was assigned the role of Project Manager for the recent installation of a new 30MW turbine at RSSC Swaziland.\r\n', '4427136000', '4717922000', '3422175000', 'no', '', '', '', '', 6, 'Potential partnership with our Growers is in process. In this submission it is assumed to have 2.5% free carry + 3.75% of Growers buy-in.  \r\nTsb Sugar is proud to receive more than half of its cane from black owned cane farms.  As suppliers of the biomass, small scale growers form part of the supply chain and will ultimately benefit from this opportunity.', 'no', 'no', 'no', 'yes', 'no', 'no', 'no', '6', 'yes', 'no', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'yes', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '6', 'project', '', 'no', 'no', 'no', '', '', '', '6', '', 'draft', 'no', 'A bid compliant financial model has been developed and current assumptions relating to capex and opex need to be confirmed through the final legal agreements. The Project should be able to meet the minimum bid compliant requirements of a Procurement program (assuming REIPPP used as a basis).   No additional resource studies anticipated as the project only involves expansion of an existing co-generation facility.', 'Komatipoort, Nkomazi, Mpumalanga, South Africa', '31', '52', '08.5', '25', '36', '35.3', 'yes', 'The project will be located on the existing premises of the Tsb Sugar Komati Mill. The turbine will be housed in an expansion to the existing turbine building.  ', 'no', 'yes', '17/05/2013', 'no', '', '', 'no', '', '', 'The addition of the turbine does not impact the current air emission licence of the Mill. Except for the EIA and NERSA approval no further approvals are required.  The Environmental Authorisation is expected by end of July 2013.', '0', '31', '52', '15.88', '25', '36', '47.17', 'Lomati', 'no', '', '', '', 'Komati Mill is currently connected to the Eskom grid with a 22KV line. Discussions with the Grid Access Unit on 27 May 2013 indicated the opportunity exsists for a self build line of 132KV to upgrade the current line. This proposed 132KV line is part of the current project scope.', 'The 132 KV line proposed will allow the project to export more power.  This upgrade is included in the capital estimate provided.  The line EIA still needs to be conducted. A period of 9-12 months is anticipated to complete the EIA for the powerline. The project can proceed without the upgrade on the line albeit at lower power export in the interim if the project needs to be accelerated. ', 'Connection will be to Eskom.  Current existing connection is a 22KV line with Eskom. A period of 20 months is anticipated to connect the 132KV line to the substation.', '20', 'N/A', '45-55', '213.6', '60.00', 'The construction of the building and infrastructure will be done by local companies.', '3', 'High speed rotating equipment is a specialist area and opportunities will be created throughout the power generation indusrty.  This would require skills and skills development.  ', '2013-07-01', '2013-07-10', 'true'),
(59, 108, 'Sidala Energy Solutions', '+27828224792', 'Christiaan Bode', 'Not applicable', '14', 'Carlow Rd', 'Parkview', 'Johannesburg', '2193', 'cbode@sidala.com', 'Kgubetswana Hydro', 'Kgubetswana Hydro is the name of the project company that will be established to own two, Run-of-River small hydro power plants generating in total 4.1 MW between Bethlehem and Clarens in the Eastern Free State, South Africa. The hydro projects are located on the Kruisvallei 190 farm which is owned by Mayborn Investments (Pty) Ltd. ', 'Hydro', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '4.4', '2.1', '4', '71', '1.15', 'Full indexation with CPI', '', '', '0', '', 'Quater4', '2015', 'Construction time is 18 months. The financial close period will be dependent on the DOE programme. We aim to complete detailed design during the financial close period (3-6 months) so that at financial closure, construction will commence', '18', 'baseload', '12', '30', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', '240', '20', '1150', '', 'CPI 100% of tariff', 'yes', '', 'fastQ2-2013-24Month', '', '1', '18', 'Sidala Energy Solutions', 'Gugler', 'Basil Read Matomo', 'Not applicable', 'Sidala Energy Solutions was established as a renewable energy developer in 2009 with the aim to develop small hydro plants in Southern Africa. Sidala has developed and spent R10mil bringing Kruisvallei Hydro (development company) to bankability. Sidala is working closely with Basil Read Matomo who will be a shareholder in the project company Kgubetswana Hydro. Basil Read Matomo will also provide the fixed price EPC contract to build Kruisvallei. Although they have not built a hydro plant before, they have got considerable civil infrastructure experience and their hydromechanical subcontractor, Gugler turbines will provide the required expertise on the plant side. Please find attached both of their profiles. ', '120000', '500000', '120000', 'yes', '', '', '', '', 30, 'Kgubetswana Hydro, through the situational needs analysis, has identified and ring fenced the Kgubetswana community outside Clarens in the Eastern Free State as the beneficiary to the Socio-Economic development contributions from the Kgubetswana Hydro Power plant. The community is situated within 15km of the Kgubetswana Hydro power plant. This area falls within the Dihlabeng local Municipality and is part of the larger Thabo Mofutsanyane region.  It has identified that education, youth-focused community welfare, and vocational skills-development as priority sectors for investment.  The needs analysis goes into detail on the current situation faced at the Kgubetswana community.\r\n\r\nKgubetswana Hydro sees meaningful social investment as being essential to the long-term success of the Kgubetswana Hydro power plant. The project should create not only facilities and jobs, but knowledge, skills, and a strategic opportunity to create and develop a community that is uniquely poised to benefit from the growth of an increasingly environmentally-aware economy. It is the hope of Kgubetswana Hydro that the facility comes to be viewed as a community asset, and that its presence may help to leverage broader developmental dividends.\r\n\r\nKgubetswana Hydro has assisted the Kgubetswana community to set up and register a community trust called the Kgubetswana Community Trust. The Kgubetswana Community Trust (KCT) will own 25% of the Kgubetswana Hydro project company with financal support from the DBSA.\r\n', 'no', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'no', '1', 'no', '', '', '', '', '', 'yes', '', 'yes', '', 'yes', 'NotApplicable for Hydro Power', 'Not applicable', 'Not applicable', 'Not applicable', '0', 'project', '', 'no', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'no', '', '3', 'yes', 'finalised', 'yes', 'All resource studies have been completed. The hydrological study is complete as well as the energy yield analysis. A technical due diligence has been completed by ARUP and no further studies are required. Because the resource is bound by a guaranteed purchase of between the Lesotho Highlands Water Project and South Africa, the resource is well known and does not carry seasonal variability. ', 'Kruisvallei No 190, Bethlehem district, Eastern Free State, South Africa', '28', '21', '49.66', '28', '24', '14.69', 'yes', 'An option to lease the land is in place. Kgubetswana will be built entirely on the Kruisvallei farm. The farm is owned by the shareholders of the project. The land owner will lease the land to the project. The option will be exercised and the Lease will be executed prior to financial close.', 'yes', 'yes', '', 'yes', '02/05/2011', '09/07/2013', 'no', '', '', 'The rights to the site are secure through a long term lease. Minister''s Consent in terms of Subdivision of Agricultural Land Act 1970 has been granted through Consent No. 46626. All key land use and environmental authorisations have been acquired.', '12', '28', '26', '37.78', '28', '27', '23.61', 'Node Rural', 'yes', '10/09/2010', 'yes', 'Please find the cost estimate letter attached as a hard copy. ', 'Met with Charl Jooste and Yusuf Ally on the 7 October 2010 in their Bloemfontein office. This meeting was to discuss the proposed grid connection of the project. Subsequent to that a cost estimate letter was applied for and granted to Kruisvallei Hydro. The first Indicative cost estimate letter was granted to us on the 17 march 2011. The latest cost estimate letter that has been received was granted to us on the 29 January 2013', 'The project will connect to Eskom Distribution and will require the installation of a 22kV distribution line to the project. No deep connection upgrades or transmission upgrades will be required.', 'Eskom Distribution', '18', 'NotApplicable', '55-65', '200', '83.33', 'The majority of the project will be civil infrastructure related which is local content in nature. The turbine itself will be imported from overseas but there is local manufacturing opportunities for the draft tube, and other mechanical components linked to the power house.', '200', 'The maintenance of the plant will be 100% local. South Africa has the required experience to perform the maintenance of the plant. There may be opportunies to create training centres but that would mainly be support for development into Africa because the Hydro industry in South Africa is small.', '2013-07-01', '2013-07-10', 'true'),
(60, 194, 'Gabriele Maraschin', '+32 59 569 700', 'Peter Calcoen', 'Cape Quater, The Paizza', '72', 'Waterkant Street', 'Green Point', 'Cape Town', '8051', 'peter.calcoen@electrawinds.be', 'Building Energy', 'A Base Load Stand Alone Power Plant ', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '2013-07-01', '0000-00-00', ''),
(61, 115, 'Exxaro Resources Limited', '0123074243', 'Jan Oberholzer', 'Exxaro HQ', '1', 'Roger Dyason Road', 'Pretoria West', 'Pretoria', '0183', 'jan.oberholzer@exxaro.com', 'Waterberg UCG Power Station', 'An Underground Coal Gasification (UCG) Project is being proposed for the Lephalale, Waterberg District, Limpopo Province area. The power station will have a capacity of 400-MW, with a first phase of 200-MW and a second phase of 200-MW, with syngas being burned in gas turbines to produce electricity. The syngas will be sourced from an adjacent undergound coal gasification facility under the aegis of an SPV formed between Exxaro Coal and Linc Energy.\r\n\r\nAn Australian publicly listed company, Linc Energy is a global leader in Underground Coal Gasification (UCG), which delivers a synthesis gas feedstock to supply commercially viable energy solutions – such as electricity, transport fuels and oil production – through gas turbine combined cycle power generation, Gas-to-Liquids (GTL) Fischer-Tropsch processing and Enhanced Oil Recovery.\r\n\r\nLinc Energy has constructed and commissioned the world’s first UCG to GTL demonstration facility located in Queensland, Australia. This facility produces GTL synthetic diesel fuel. Linc Energy also owns the world’s only commercial UCG operation, Yerostigaz, located in Uzbekistan. Yerostigaz has produced commercial UCG synthesis for power generation for over 50 years.\r\n\r\nExxaro Coal is the second largest coal producer in South Africa and aims to be an innovative coal and reductants division. Eight fully managed coal mines and one 50:50 joint venture operation produce about 50 million tons per annum of power station, steam and coking coal. All of the power station coal is supplied to the national power utility, Eskom, and municipal power stations. Exxaro has links to the energy-industry through Cennergi (a joint venture between Exxaro and Tata Power) and has engaged in Project Development of Co-generation and Coal-fired Power Stations in South Africa.', 'GasPlant', 'OCGT', 'CoalOther', '', '', 'Syngas sourced from underground coal gasification facility', '', '', '', '', '', 'Syngas sourced from underground coal gasification facility', '400', '100', '360', '85', '1.05', 'NERSA MYPD', '40%', '', '', '', 'Quater4', '2017', '', '24', 'baseload', '', '', '', 'yes', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', '8000', '30', '1050', 'Base cost July 2013, and does not allow for carbon-taxes, etc..', 'NERSA MYPD', 'yes', '', 'commitQ2-2015-Phased', '', '3', '24', 'Exxaro Resources Limited & Linc Energy Limited SPV', 'Linc Energy Limited (for UCG)', 'Exxaro Resources Limited', 'Linc Energy Limited (Australia)', 'Linc Energy has constructed and commissioned the world’s first UCG to GTL demonstration facility located in Queensland, Australia. This facility produces GTL synthetic diesel fuel. Linc Energy also owns the world’s only commercial UCG operation, Yerostigaz, located in Uzbekistan. Yerostigaz has produced commercial UCG synthesis for power generation for over 50 years. Exxaro Resources is the second largest coal producer in South Africa and largest supplier to ESKOM. Eight fully managed coal mines and one 50:50 joint venture operation produce about 50 million tons per annum of power station, steam and coking coal. All of the power station coal is supplied to the national power utility, Eskom, and municipal power stations. Exxaro Resources has also completed and commissioned 13.6MW Co-gen project at Exxaro’s Namakwa Sands operations in the Northern Cape which Co-gen facility is currently under construction and scheduled to produce 100GWh by 2014. Exxaro Resources is also a 50/50 shareholder in Cennergi (together with Tata Power) which was successful in achieving Financial Close in two wind projects totalling 239-MW under the DOE''s rolling renewable energy independent power producer procurement programme (REIPPPP).', '17040000000', '20961000000', '16121000000', 'no', '', '', '', '', 51, 'The main shareholders in Exxaro are Exxaro’s empowerment partners (54.1%) through a black economic empowerment holding company, the broad based employee share option plan, Anglo American and a minority shareholder free float on the JSE (as at 31 December 2012).\r\n\r\nThrough several steps the empowerment partners consisting of Eyesizwe shareholders, members of the empowerment consortia (Tiso, Eyabantu and Basadi ba Kopane) and the IDC became shareholders in the holding company of Exxaro (BEE Holdco) – making Exxaro one of the largest black-owned, controlled and managed companies in South Africa. \r\n', 'no', 'no', 'no', 'no', 'no', 'no', 'no', '3', 'yes', 'no', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', 'Resource Appraisal to conclude Q4 2013, with drilling taking place on site and Pre-Feasibility Study being completed by Q2 2014. Pilot gasification to commence in 2015.', 'no', 'Environmental impact assessment to commence in Q4 2013, with EA expected by Q3 2015.', 'no', '', 'Q4 2017', 'As per attached (ANNEXURE A)', 'As per attached (ANNEXURE A)', '3', 'corporate', '', 'yes', 'no', 'no', '', '', '', '3', 'no', 'none', 'no', 'Drilling to be completed on site by Q4 2013, with resource/reserve studies being finalised by Q1 2014.', 'Lephalale, Waterberg District Municipality, Limpopo Province', '27', '30', '00', '23', '40', '00', 'no', '', 'no', 'no', '', 'yes', '30/11/2014', '30/06/2015', 'no', '', '', 'Waste License (Q2 2015), Air Emissions License (Q2 2015), Water Use License (Q3 2015)', '5', '27', '36', '00', '23', '40', '12', 'Matimba', 'yes', '21/05/2012', 'yes', 'ESKOM Cost Estimate Letter (Ref IPP 70033036) in ANNEXURE-B', 'Submitted Grid Application Form to ESKOM and communication with Grid Access Unit by e-mail. ESKOM have submitted Cost Estimate in July 2013.', 'HV-Yard will need to be constructed at proposed Power Station, with transmission lines running from Power Station to Matimba HV-Yard.', 'ESKOM', '24', 'Inside South Africa', '65-75', '2400', '30.00', 'Preference to be given to local Lephalale suppliers, then Limpopo based suppliers, then national suppliers and thereafter after other suppliers. To the extent possible a target of 50% local SA content will be pursued.', '1200', 'The new technologies (syngas-fired turbines) presents opportunities for local manufacture and Operations & Maintenance activities. ', '2013-07-01', '2013-07-12', 'true'),
