(64, 149, 'Gledhow Sugar Company', '+27836493866', 'Paul de Robillard', 'Gledhow Sugar Company', '1', 'Gledhow Mill Road', 'Gledhow', 'Kwa-Dukuza', '4450', 'pderobillard@gledhow.co.za', 'The Gledhow Sugar Company Greenfield Energy Generation Project', 'For many years Gledhow Sugar Company (GSC) has been generating only the power it needs to operate its Factory by burning the fibrous residue of processed sugar cane, called bagasse, in boilers to produce the steam to drive the turbine driven generators. GSC''s thermal efficiency of the Factory, and the efficiency of its boilers and turbine driven generators is typical for the industry but could be significanlty improved to produce surplus bagsse to be used for the generation of electricity surplus to GSC''s requirements for export to the grid.\r\n\r\nGSC is unique in the sugar industry in that it is the first BBBEE sugar company in South Africa and that 72% of the cane supply area falls under the umbrella of Land Reform. Currently there are 30 000 hectares of land under plantation and the intention is to grow this by 5 500 hectares during the next 5 years which will make a significant contribution to GSC''s objective of 1 500 000 tons cane per annum. A crop of this size will have a material effect on GSC''s and its cane growers'' profitability. However, in order to achieve this GSC must be in a position to offer incentives to growers of sugar cane in exchange for their commitment to supply their cane to GSC for the duration of the Power Purchase Agreement.\r\n\r\nThe project to improve the thermal efficiency of GSC''s factory to produce the surplus bagasse will be undertaken and financed by GSC. A Special Purpose Vehicle (SPV) will be formed to build a power island which will buy surplus bagasse from GSC. This bagsse will generate 75t/h of steam at 65barg in a new high efficiency boiler. The steam will be supplied to a new Extraction/Condensing turbo-alternator with an installed capacity of 17MWe producing 12MWe on average.    ', 'Cogeneration', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '17', '17', '12', '71', '1.25', 'CPI', '', '68', '', '', 'Quater1', '2016', 'GSC''s crushing season normally commences in March/April each year. This will dictate the scheduled COD provided a bankable PPA is received by mid-September 2013.', '30', 'mid-merit', '8.31', '244', '23.28', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', '640', '20', '1.61', '', 'CPI', 'yes', '', 'commitQ2-2014-Phased', '', '8', '30', 'Gledhow Sugar Company', 'Gledhow Sugar Company and Illovo (South Africa) Limited', 'n/a', 'n/a', 'Illovo (South Africa) Limited has a 30% shareholding in GSC and is contracted to manage GSC. Illovo has recently commissioned a 25MWE plant in Swaziland and this plant sells the electricity to the Swaziland grid. The South African Sugar Industry, including GSC, has been operating in-house bagasse fired boilers and turno-alternators for generations.', '1000000000', '1000000000', '1000000000', 'no', '', '', '', '', 34, 'Gledhow Cane Growers Association is a 25.1% shareholder in GSC and as such qualifies for any annual dividends paid. The Association comprises commercial farmers and 1 550 medium and small size growers, the majority of whom are black growers who directly or indirectly support an estimated 7 000 people living in the rural environment adjacent to GSC. The planned development of an additional 5 500 hectares under the National Land Reform Programme will significantly increase the number of black growers of the Association.', 'yes', 'no', 'yes', 'yes', 'no', '', 'no', '7', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', '01/03/2017', 'no', '', 'yes', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '12', 'project', '', 'no', 'no', 'no', 'no', '', '', '12', '', 'draft', 'yes', 'The Feasibility Study has been completed . The Draft Scoping Repost in compliance with South Africa''s environmental legal framework has been submitted and the EIA will be submitted at the end of October 2013.Discussions with potential lenders have been taking place for a number of months.', 'Kwa-Dukuza', '29', '47', '14.7', '28', '32', '36.51', 'yes', 'The site on which GSC operates is owned by GSC. The area required for the Power Island will be leased from GSC.', 'no', 'yes', '08/08/2012', 'no', '', '', 'no', '', '', 'The Draft Scoping Report has been completed and submitted. The EIA will be submitted for approval in October 2013.', '0.3', '31', '17', '7.11', '29', '21', '52', 'Kwa-Dukuza Municipality Gledhow Sub-station', 'no', '', '', '', 'Discussions have taken place with the Kwa-Dukuza Municipality Electricity Head of Department and their consultants AURECON. The point of connection was identified. Minutes of the meeting are avaialble on request.', 'Existing Kwa-Dukuza Municipality''s Gledhow Sub-station 33kV busbar will be extended to accept the installed capaity of the Power Island''s 17MWe.', 'To the Kwa-Dukuza Municipality''s Electricity System', '6', 'n/a', '65-75', '565', '88.28', 'Manufacture of the boiler (except perhaps the steam drum) and all ancillary plant and equipment', '6500', 'New technology for high pressure boilers and potentially turbo-generator manufacture', '2013-07-02', '2013-07-09', 'true'),
(65, 201, 'Ki Power (Pty) Limited', '0824570197', 'Ayanda Bam', 'Kuyasa Mining', '2 ', 'Neven Street', 'Fransville', 'Witbank', '1035', 'kimin@global.co.za', 'Ki Power ', 'Ki Power (Pty) Limited intends building a mine mouth base load power station next to its sister company Delmas Coal (Pty) Limited located in Delmas magisterial district. The station', 'Thermal', 'Coal', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '600', '150', '540', '85', '70', '2', '70', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'baseload', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '2013-07-02', '2013-07-02', ''),
(66, 170, 'Jindal Botswana (Pty) Ltd', '+267-3911982', 'Bharat Rohra', '1st Floor, Victoria House, Plot ', '132', 'Independence Avenue', 'Gaborone', 'Gaborone', '0001', 'bharat.rohra@jindalafrica.com', 'Jindal Mmamabula Energy Project', 'Project Overview\r\n\r\nJindal BVI Ltd. (Jindal) a subsidiary of Jindal Steel & Power (Mauritius) Ltd. that is wholly owned by Jindal Steel & Power (India) Ltd., in September 2012 merged with CIC Energy Corp and acquired rights to develop Mmamabula Coal Fields which were earlier held by CIC Energy Corp.\r\n\r\nThe project is situated in the Mmamabula East Coalfield within the Mahalapye Sub-District within the Central District of Botswana. Mmamabula is the name of an existing railway siding on the country’s main railway line which runs parallel to the A1 national highway between Ramatlabama and Ramokgwabwe. \r\n\r\nJindal proposes to continue with the development of its mineral license areas in Mmamabula and this development will now be referred to as the Jindal Mmamabula Energy Project (JMEP) and which consists of the development of the JMEP and its various components in phases over time. The project is planned to be developed in 3 distinct phases, as depicted below. The timeframes for Phase 2 and 3 will be determined by the economic feasibility and demand for power and coal both regionally and internationally. Phase I of the project partly envisages supply of power to Botswana Power Corporation and the balance to neighboring countries. Hence the timeframes of these phases are therefore subject to change depending on the demand for power and based on the outcome of this enquiry issued by Department of Energy, Republic of South Africa.\r\n\r\nThe following table details out the project phasing as presently envisaged by us:\r\n\r\nPhase	Project Description	Construction Timeframe	Operations Timeframe\r\nJMEP - I	4 x 175MW power plant	May 2013	                2015/2016\r\nJMEP - II	4 x 175MW power plant	2016	2019\r\nJMEP - III	3 x 800MW power plant	2018	2024\r\n\r\nFuel Supply Arrangements\r\n\r\nThe coal for all the three phases will be sourced from the Mmamabula coal fields rights to which are now with Jindal post merger with CIC Energy Corp. Jindal has two retention licences RL 2009 / 1R and RL 2012 / 1R. We have submitted our application for a mining license to be awarded for concessional areas under RL 2012 / 1R and expect to get the same by the end of July 2013. \r\nThe total estimated coal reserves in the concession areas under RL 2012 / 1R are sufficient to meet the coal requirements for all the phases of the JMEP. As and when export of coal picks up, Jindal shall also apply for a mining license for the other concession area under RL 2009 / 1R.\r\n\r\nWater Supply Arrangements\r\n\r\nThrough the merger, Jindal acquired rights to utilize water for construction and power plant operation from two wellfields located near to the site - Bonwapitse and Maiphafela. Through these water rights, Jindal can withdraw 6.4Mm3/yr of water from the Bonwapitse wellfied and 5.6Mm³/yr from the Maiphafela wellfield.\r\n\r\nProgress on JMEP – I : 4 x 175 MW\r\n\r\nSince Jindal’s merger with CIC Energy Corp in September 2012, the following works have been completed and or initiated at the site that will enable us to meet the proposed deadline of project commissioning and offer power to the market.\r\n•	The EIA approval from the Department of Environment Affairs, Botswana for all the components is in an advanced stage and likely to be issued by the end of July 2013.\r\n•	Government of Botswana has indicated its preparedness to issue an IPP license irrespective of whether Botswana Power Corporation buys power from JMEP.\r\n•	Finalization of the mining plan under RL 2012 / 1R.\r\n•	Finalization of main plant equipment vendors i.e. boiler and turbine to Siemens (Germany) and BHEL (India). The Letters of Intent have also been issued to these vendors for phase 1.\r\n•	Finalization of construction water and construction power scheme. Work to begin on this as soon as EIA approval for the project has been received.\r\n•	Survey works of site approach road, power plant boundary and internal roads within the power plant boundary completed.\r\n•	A camp to house employees and contractor is already present at the site. Vendors have been identified who will be involved in expansion and operation of the same once project construction starts.\r\n•	Transmission integration solution with Botswana’s network and Masa sub station in South Africa is under finalization with the help of our transmission consultants.\r\n•	M/s. Mott MacDonald have been appointed as Engineering consultant in place to support us in project development activities.\r\n', 'Thermal', 'Coal', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '3800', '800', '3000', '85', '0.989', '6%', '96%', '', '', '', 'Quater2', '2016', 'Phase I - 2015/16; Phase II - 2019; Phase III - 2024. Since we are already going ahead with the construction of the project, assuming ESKOM enters into a PPA with us by January 2014, we propose 30 months from PPA signing as a reference timeframe.', '30', 'baseload', '', '', '', 'yes', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', '85000', '25', '1020', 'Tariff break up, indexation and other tariff terms - Withholding Tax on Interest; Withholding Tax on Interest on Working Capital', 'Capacity Charge - 6% fixed annual escalation + Annual movement between USD / BWP + Botswana CPI + Botswana overall Labor & Mining Index; Variable Charge - Botswana CPI + Botswana Diesel Index', 'yes', 'Due to import of equipments the price will be linked with movemen', 'fastQ3-2013-36Month', 'Not Applicable', '1', '30', 'Jindal Botswana (Pty) Ltd.', 'Siemens, BHEL', 'None', 'None', 'The ultimate parent company of Jindal Botswana (Pty) Ltd. is Jindal Steel & Power (India) Ltd. or JSPL. JSPL is a major player in the Indian core sector and has set up a number of large sized projects in the same category. It operates a 3 MTPA steel plant at Raigarh in Chhattisgarh and is setting up a 1.6 MTPA steel plant in the state of Odisha, India and 3 MTPA steel plants in the state of Jharkhand, India and 2 MTPA Steel plant in Oman. \r\n\r\nWith an annual turnover of over US$ 3.5 billion, JSPL is a part of the \r\nUS$ 18 billion diversified O. P. Jindal Group and is consistently tapping new opportunities by increasing production capacity, diversifying investments, and leveraging its core capabilities to venture into new businesses. The company has committed investments exceeding US$ 30 billion in the future and has several business initiatives running simultaneously across continents.\r\n\r\nJSPL has achieved excellent backward integration for its steel and power plant operations by tying up key raw materials for its plant operations – coal and iron ore – through captive mines. JSPL and Jindal Power Ltd. (JPL) together mine about 12 million tonnes of coal every year from captive coal mines located in Chhattisgarh state in India. In addition, captive coal blocks have been allotted for upcoming projects in Angul, Odisha and Jharkhand state, where project activities are expected to start shortly. Apart from coal, JSPL’s mining expertise also extends to iron ore, with mining being carried out in district Sundergarh, Odisha from which around 3 million tonnes of iron ore is being mined. JSPL in 2010 acquired Shadeed Iron & Steel Co. LLC (SISCO) a company incorporated under the laws of the Sultanate of Oman. The project commenced commercial operations in Jan 2011 which was four months ahead of schedule. SISCO is also implementing the steel melting shop of 2 MTPA with an investment of US $ 300 mn (approx.)\r\n\r\nJSPL is one of the pioneers of the Indian Power Sector. Its involvement in Power Sector started with use of waste gases to generate power for captive use. Presently, JSPL has 1433 MW of captive power plants. It also has 270MW of captive power projects under execution after completion of which the total captive capacity of JSPL shall be about 1703 MW.It has setup 24 MW wind farm comprising 16 number of wind mills of capacity 1.5 MW each in Satara district in Maharashtra, India. Taking the next steps forward, Jindal Power Ltd. has built upon the tradition set by its Parent Company in the Indian power sector. JSPL, through its subsidiary JPL also own and operate 1000 MW Independent power plant in Chattisgarh.\r\n\r\nJindal Power Ltd. (JPL) is a subsidiary of JSPL involved in setting up of Independent Power Plants (IPPs) in India and Global markets. Incorporated in 1995, JPL is an established Power Generation Company that has the distinction of developing and operating India’s first largest private thermal power project of 1000 MW (4 x 250 MW set up in two phases of 500 MW each) at Raigarh in the state of Chhattisgarh, India. JPL’s 1000 MW O.P Jindal Super Thermal Power Plant is the first mega IPP power project in the private sector in India, fully operational since September, 2008. The plant has been setup in 2 phases of 500 MW each, with a total investment of about US $ 1 Billion. Punjab National Bank, India acted as the lead lender for the project. Fuel is supplied to the 1000 MW Plant from JPL’s captive coal mines, which are located at a distance of around 8 km from the plant through a cross country conveyer belt. The mines started operation in June 2007 and a production of about 6 million tonnes of coal was achieved during FY2009-10. JPL is in the process of developing phase 3 and 4 of the same project that entails construction of additional 2400 MW thermal power plant in 4x600 MW configurations. Along with its 3 hydroelectric projects in India and other proposed power plants that are under various stages of implementation. JPL in the coming years will add an aggregate generation capacity of more than 10,000 MW to its power generation portfolio in India. \r\nJSPL’s Presence in Africa\r\nJSPL has established a significant footprint on the continent through operations in South Africa, Mozambique, Madagascar, Tanzania, and Zambia. Africa has also facilitated JSPL’s entry into base metals copper exploration being performed in Zambia and Tanzania. JSPL’s intent is to pass on the inherent knowledge and experience to the continent by enriching lives, creating job opportunities and adding value\r\nJSPL’s African headquarters are based in Johannesburg from where it oversees the regional operations and expansion plans. Its operational activities in the country include the Kiepersol Colliery, outside the town of Piet Retief in Mpumalanga province. The coal mine is producing about 1.2 million tonnes per annum of high quality Anthracite which is sold both domestically and internationally. There are plans to ramp up the capacity to 2 million tonnes per annum, after which JSPL will become the largest producer of Anthracite in South Africa. JSPL has also acquired a number of coal and iron ore concessions in which exploration and development work are in progress.\r\n\r\nOur group companies are producing and have under development coal mines in South Africa, Botswana, and Mozambique with coal reserves of about 2.7 Billion tonnes in Botswana and 1 Billion tonne in Mozambique. With a global outlook, JSPL has always been on the lookout for power and mining opportunities in global markets.  In many respects, the JSPL development plan and vision for exploration and development of the Mmamabula coal concessions will follow a proven and successful approach used in Mozambique since 2008. It is JSPL’s intention to utilise the experience and expertise of their Mozambique team to fast-track the exploration and projects in Botswana. In Mozambique, JSPL has been involved in all aspects of the development from exploration, mining, washing, rail infrastructure and port developments.  JSPL has also entered into a framework agreement with the Ministry of Energy to set up a 2640 MW thermal power plant in the Tete region in Mozambique. \r\n', '37612000000', '37992000000', '29218000000', 'yes', '', '', '', '', 1, 'We have a well defined community development program that has been implemented partially at the project site and covers 5 villages that immediately are getting affected by our proposed developments. The community development program envisages development of educational facilities, upgradation of existing and development of new medical facilities, skill upgradation of local people around so that they can be offered suitable employment in our project as and when required. In addition, the entire region of influence will benefit from upgradation and addition of roads, railway line, sewerage, water supply and electrification because of our project.', 'no', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'no', '2', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', '01/08/2015', 'yes', '01/08/2015', 'no', '', 'no', 'All relevant  licences are expected to be issued in second half of 2013. ', 'no', 'The mining plan is ready, however work at the site awaits formal grant of EIA and the mining license.', '01/08/2015', 'Not Applicable', 'Not Applicable', '2', 'corporate', '', 'no', 'no', 'no', '', '', '', '3', 'yes', 'finalised', 'yes', 'We have a technical and financial bankable feasibility study ready for the project that can be shared with the interested lenders as and when we initiate the process of arranging debt with them. These studies have been done by independent consultants appointed by Jindal Botswana (Pty) Ltd. and complemented by numerous other resource level studies with respect to fuel quality and quantity, water quality and quantity, environment assessment, infrastructure works that can be shared with the interested lenders.', 'Jindal Capricorn camp, near Mmapashalala village, Botswana', '26', '46', '28.65', '23', '36', '43.80', 'no', 'The mining concession rights as defined in Botswana give', 'no', 'yes', '05/02/2013', 'no', '', '', 'no', '', '', 'EIA Approval - July 2013, IPP License - August 2013, Mining License - August 2013', '17', '26', '42', '34.9765', '23', '32', '25.3510', 'Loop in loop out in existing Botswana Power Corporation Network''s Isang- MorupuleB line, a new line to Phokoje sub station in Botswana and Masa sub station in South Africa. The common coupling point mentioned at 17 km is to BPC network for stage I', 'no', '', '', '', 'Interaction between Eskom and erstwhile CIC Energy Corp with regards to the Mmamabula Energy project dates back to 2006 and the signing of a Memorandum of Understanding. Since that time, interaction between the two parties has been extensive, including the submission & negotiation of a PPA in 2009. Since that time Eskom and DEA has been continually appraised of the status of the project and its preparedness to supply power to South Africa. At the highest levels, Eskom was also kept informed of the merger process between Jindal and CIC Energy Corp.A dual 400 KV line has been designed between the project site and Eskom''s substation. Environmental approvals for such lines were approved in 2007 by Botswana Environmental affairs.', 'We are in the process of finalizing transmission integration study with the help of our consultant. The objective of the study is to suggest multiple options and network upgrade if required for suggested options for transmitting power to Botswana Power Corporation''s network and to South Africa.', 'We are in the process of finalizing transmission integration study with the help of our consultant. The objective of the study is to suggest multiple options and network upgrade if required for suggested options for transmitting power to Botswana Power Corporation''s network and to South Africa.', '12', 'We will need to enter into transmission agreements with Botswana Power Corporation in case the power is transmitted through their network to South Africa. In case of a direct connection with South Africa, we will have to get into a transmission agreement with Eskom. We await our consultant''s report for finalizing on the feasible option.', '0-30', '8500', '10.00', 'A large project that involves mining and power plant construction & operations will generate opportunities for South African contractors, material providers, ancillary services providers like camp management, vehicular services etc.', '1500', 'A power plant involves usage of heavy machinery across its value chain that requires trained manpower to install and operate. The machinery also requires daily maintenance and scheduled maintenance. Since we are sourcing the power plant components from vendors of international repute, we expect their South Africa offices to provide us with maintenance and training support.', '2013-07-02', '2013-07-11', 'true'),
(67, 148, 'Illovo Sugar (South Africa) Limited', '0315084550', 'Warren Wessels', 'Building 3C, Gleneagles Park', '10', 'Flanders Drive', 'Mount Edgecombe', 'Durban', '4', 'wwessels@illovo.co.za', 'Eston Small Project (optimisation)', 'The Eston mill currently genarates its own power requirements by burning bagasse in its low pressure boilers. Illovo has undertaken a study of the feasibility of optimising back-pressure power generation from existing steam generation capacity and fuel supply.\r\nThe current factory operates with a let down margin and has inefficient steam turbine drives which would be replaced by electric motors. The factory would be modified to use a new efficient back-pressure turbine (10MW). Marginal steam economy improvements will be made to achieve a bagasse only fuel balance.\r\n\r\nTo secure the cane supply for the duration of the PPA it will be necessary to secure long term cane supply agreements. The farmers will require remuneration for this commitment. \r\n\r\nAs this is an optimisation process within the existing business there will be no change to Illovo South Africa''s BBBEE flowing directly from it. It should be noted that once the outstanding Land Claims have been resolved, black growers will supply over 50% of Illovo''s cane and the additional revenue will be important in supporting the viability of the farming community.\r\n\r\nIf required the project could be phased to make available some power a year earlier. This would mean 1.5MWh from 1 April 2015 and then 6MWh from 1 April 2016.', 'Cogeneration', 'CogenerationBack', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '18.5', '10', '6', '69', '1.27', 'CPI', '', '71', '', '', 'Quater2', '2016', 'To achieve the planned timetable requires the signature of the PPA by 1 June 2014, which in turn requires the receipt of a bankable PPA by 1 September 2013', '22', 'mid-merit', '8', '252', '24', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', 'It will replace the current generation of power for the factory, and produce a surplus for export of 8MW.', '156', '10', '1270', 'Tariff of R1270 is based on net exportable power after parasitic load in 1 April 2011 terms. If the tariff is escalated to 1 April 2013 terms it is R1420.  .', 'CPI', 'yes', '', 'fastQ3-2013-36Month', 'The internal approval process of the bid submission approval will require until end March 2014. In order to meet the planned COD of 1 April 2016 it will be necessary to have financial close by 1 June 2014. This is only 2 months after bid submission, but as this is Corporate financed and a relatively simple project this should be possible.', '7', '22', 'Illovo Sugar (South Africa) Limited', 'Illovo Sugar Limited', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'Respondent operates 4 electricity and steam generating operations in South Africa with an installed capacity od 56 MW. Illovo Sugar Limited the parent company and the technology supplier, operates a further 120MW of installed capacity in the rest of Africa. This includes a recently installed 25MW plant in Swaziland which delivers power to the grid.', '4078700000', '3030200000', '3115000000', 'yes', '', '', '', '', 14, 'As this project falls within the scope of our existing business, no new  community involvement is planned beyond the various development initiatives already in existence. Small scale and black freehold farmers will benefit.\r\n\r\nNote that the 14% BEE participation in the block above is the BEE participation reflected in Illovo Sugar Limited''s BBBEE Contributor scorecard.', 'no', 'no', 'no', 'no', '', '', '', '9', 'yes', 'no', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'yes', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '6', 'corporate', '', 'no', 'no', 'no', '', '', '', '6', '', 'finalised', 'yes', 'This will be a corporate financed project, and as it is a modification of an existing factory within the normal scope of business, it does not require any studies.', 'Eston KZN', '29', '52', '9', '30', '3', '38', 'yes', 'Ownership', 'no', 'no', '', 'no', '', '', 'no', '', '', 'Optimisation project that can be undertaken within the bounds of existing authorisations.', '3', '29', '52 ', '7', '30 ', '32', '3', 'Eston', 'yes', '20/07/2012', 'no', '', 'Discussions have been held on the need to upgrade the transformer at the Eston sub-station with Mr Ravi Moonsamy of Eskom. Received a budget cost for the upgrade.', 'The incomer transformer is currently a 2.5MVA transformer which will need upgrading.', 'Eskom grid.', '24', 'N/A', '55-65', '85', '65.38', 'Turbine will be imported, but piping and fitments will be sourced locally', '5', 'N/A', '2013-07-02', '2013-07-11', 'true'),
(68, 30, 'South African Clean Energy Solutions (SACE)', '+27115309523', 'Willem Johannes Van der Merwe', 'Antrust', '101', 'Oxford Road', 'Saxonwold', 'Johannesburg', '2132', 'willem@saces.co.za', 'SACE01-Gasifier', 'Herewith the description of the power generation project:\r\n-	The plant to be built will be tied into the ESKOM grid and generate electric power through five modular gasifier and generator units; the feedstock for the generator will be forestry residue from the surrounding area, supplied by a local forestry company under a long term feedstock agreement.\r\n\r\nPower generated by the plant:\r\n-	The plant will consist of 5 units with an electrical power generation capacity of 250 kW each.\r\n-	Each power generation unit consists of a gasifier producing between 685 and 750 kW of thermal energy through the conversion of forest residue (woody biomass) to low calorific value wood gas, and an engine/generator set with a rated efficiency of 34%, producing between 233 and 255 kW of electrical power from the gasifier’s wood gas.\r\n-	The total maximum electrical power generated by the plant will be 1 275 kW and the total maximum thermal power generated will be 3 750 kW.\r\n-	The typical uptime of the plant is 8 040 hours per year, producing between 9 367 and 10 251 MWh of electrical energy per year.\r\n\r\nLocation and footprint of plant:\r\n-	The plant will be installed in Mpumalanga on one of the feedstock supplier’s sawmills at the following coordinates: -25.255584, 31.019773; the sawmill is situated 8 km north of White River, on the side of the R40.\r\n-	Footprint of the plant with a 1 month buffer area for feedstock (i.e. additional stacking area for feedstock outside):  0.56 hectare (5 600 m2).\r\n\r\nTie-in Point:\r\n-	Pole number PNG127 is given as the closest tie-in location situated at the mill.\r\n-	The voltage for the existing power line in question is 22kV.\r\n\r\nFeedstock:\r\n-	The plant requires up to 12 000 tonnes of Eucalyptus forest residue from the surrounding area, with the residue having a maximum moisture content (using a dry base convention) of 37% and a minimum bone-dry calorific value of 17.5 MJ/kg\r\n-	Feedstock dimensions: minimum allowable length is 55 mm and minimal cross-sectional area is 20 cm2, with larger pieces being cut to size as required.\r\n-	Feedstock is supplied by a local forestry company situated in the area, with a long term supply agreement and is made up of forest residue that does not currently qualify as a value-adding commodity.\r\n\r\nThe attachments to the physical copy of this submission also contains a similar description as given above, but with additional information and a satellite image of the site. Also included as attachment is a snapshot from the techno-financial model, showing some of the main technical and financial variables covered in the model.\r\n\r\nA full feasibility with financial model has been completed in conjunction with the forestry company. The feasibility is available on request, with certain conditions.\r\n', 'Reciprocating', 'Gas', 'other33', '', '', '', '', '', 'Low calorific wood gas from gasification of forest residue, 5.9 MJ/Nm3 (Nm3 = Norm cubic meter)', '', '', '', '1.275', '1.25', '1.25', '92', '0.76', '?', '25%', '', '', '', 'Quater1', '2014', '', '4', 'mid-merit', '11', '335', '22', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', '24.4', '17', '90', '7 % increase first 3 years, followed by 8% annually thereafter. All energy produced must be bought. No capacity tariff, only energy tariff, yearly flat-rate, increasing as indicated.', '?', 'yes', '', 'fastQ2-2013-12Months', '', '2', '8', 'South African Clean Energy Solutions Limited', 'Carbo Consult Engineering', 'Industrial Development Corporation', 'none', 'Carbo Consult: rights sold to Kawasaki Heavy Industries, 3 plant built in Japan, 175 kW output each. 120 kW plant built in Melani village, South Africa.', '1800000', '1200000', '0', 'yes', '', '', '', '', 26, 'At least 27 full time jobs (unschooled labour from surrounding communities) for operation of plant. Additionally, 1 full time position for managing plant and 1 part time position for administration.', 'no', 'no', 'yes', 'no', 'yes', 'yes', 'no', '4', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', '31/01/2014', 'no', '', 'yes', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '2', 'corporate', '', 'no', 'no', 'no', '', '', '', '3', '', 'finalised', 'yes', 'Technical and financial parameters have all been researched, measured and quantified, including: feedstock availability, quantities, energy quantities, logistics, labour and transport costs of feedstock, leasing cost, maintenance cost, additional running costs and all other variables with significant influence on the return calculated in the techno-financial model. Environmental legislative requirements have been met, covering Waste Management, Water Licensing, Environmental Impact Assessment and Air Emissions.  ', 'White River, Mpumulanga, 8 km North of White River on the R 40', '31', '1', '13.46', '25', '15', '24.01', 'no', '', 'no', 'yes', '11/07/2013', 'no', '', '', 'no', '', '', 'NERSA generation license: 4-5 months (mid Nov/Dec 2013) and ESKOM grid tie-in: 4-6 months (mid Nov 2013/ Jan 2014).', '0.5', '31', '1', '13.462', '25', '15', '24.008', 'Paardekop (31° 1'' 14.4978" E, 25° 17'' 53.5986" S )', 'yes', '07/06/2013', 'no', '', 'Grid Access Unit, Modikoe Makhene, received cost estimation request and gave reference number, 96603158. From Network Planning (Mpumalanga), Faans Van Zyl assisted with identifying sub-stations near proposed installation site and in general area. Multiple correspondences with Faans for coordination meeting with Network Planner assigned to project.', 'No. It has been indicated (informally) that there is enough capacity for a 1.25 MW tie-in to the nearby line. As part of cost estimation, flow analysis still needs to confirm suitability of tie-in location (pole number PNG127).', 'Eskom.', '4', 'Not applicable.', '65-75', '16.82', '68.93', '5 gasifier units (main technology component), including scrubbers, coolers, piping and particle filter drums. All civil works and infrastructure.', '37', 'Core technology maintenance using local content/components, as well as engine maintenance using local expertise. ', '2013-07-02', '2013-07-11', 'true'),
(70, 164, 'Synergy World Energy LLC', '0835005375', 'Justin Duvenhage', 'Unison House', '190', 'Smit Street', 'Fairland', 'Johannesburg', '2195', 'justin@maningi.com', 'Clean Water Energy - Africa', 'Synergy World Energy, a technology company, has developed a system that allows processing of water from any source into potable drinking water and energy. Each system is scalable purifying from 950 000 to 37 000 000 litres of water per day, generating from 3Mw to 280Mw of energy per day respectively. \r\nThe system requires minimal space to operate - the largest needs approximately 180 square metres of space and if necessary, holding reservoirs for the clean water produced.\r\n\r\nSystems are operational today and water from the units are currently sold throughout the Western United States as drinkable water. In addition to providing high quality water at municipal levels of output, each system is self powered and capable of generating excess power which can power a user''s facility or be sold directly to a utility company under a Power Purchase Agreement. \r\n\r\nThe filtration process starts by connecting to a water supply, be it waste, salt or contaminated, so that the system harnesses the power within the contaminates along with the hydrogen and methane in the water. This power packed water is then pressurized and the purification process separates out the toxins and pollutants which are transformed into fuel for power generation. Through gasification the process converts the water contaminates into a form of "Syngas" (gasification of the contaminates in water at a molecular level) which powers a turbine engine and generator completing a perfect energy circle. The power and water service does not consume carbon fuels - coal, oil or natural gas, but converts pollutants during the water refining process into energy ensuring carbon credit, not carbon footprint. \r\n\r\nSystems are constructed using the highest quality materials and are warranted for the life of the contract for services or the term of the Power Purchase Agreement. The equipment is maintained for the lifetime of the contract at no extra charge to the client and each system is remotely monitored by factory personnel to ensure optimum performance and timely service. The system is self powered and needs no external power source to run and is self maintained. \r\n\r\nSystems are scalable. A 3MwE system can purify 950 000 litres of water per day and generate up to 3Mw of electricity per day. A 280MwE system purifies 37 000 000 litres of water generating up to 280 megawatts of electricity per day. Systems are available in different sizes subject to availability of water and other requirements. Systems from 3Mw to 40Mw can be built as portable units and used in disaster relief. \r\n\r\nFunding of any project is contingent on the strength of a Power Purchase Agreement, a Water Cleaning Agreement and/or the overall Client''s credit rating. With an appropriate Power Purchase Agreement the company has the ability to provide an AAA financial performance bond and financing is in place to fund an entire project.  ', 'Other', '', '', '', 'A pressurized system is used to purify water to separate the hydrogen, methane, toxins and pollutants in the water which are transformed into fuel for power generation.', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '280', '280', '280', '100', '1.20', '5% p.a', '98.7', '', '24', '', 'Quater2', '2014', 'A client has not yet been identified, but it is expected that subject to meeting regulatory requirements, it would take 12 to 18 months from signature of a PPA to build, install and commission a system. ', '9', 'baseload', '', '', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'yes', 'The system will replace existing power generation dependent of the size of the unit that is installed. Initially systems will be built in 20Mw increments.', '2800', '20', '1200', 'Unknown at this stage', 'This will be linked to the annual inflation rate in South Africa', 'no', 'Price will denominated in USD', 'commitQ3-2013-Phased', '', '3', '9', 'Synergy World Energy LLC', 'na', 'na', 'Still to be negotiated', 'Negotiations to install systems in the USA and some South American countries are in progress.', '0', '0', '0', 'no', '', '', '', '', 20, 'To be negotiated with location specific authorities in terms of supplying communities with potable drinking water and energy.', 'no', 'yes', 'no', 'yes', 'no', 'no', 'no', '3', 'no', '', '', '', '', '', 'no', 'No carbon fuel supplier will be required. A water source will need to be secured to produce potable water and energy. Water usage to produce energy will be approximately 5 percent of throughput.', 'no', 'No, we still need to apply for a water use licence, an electricity producer licence and clearance from the DEA. These authorisations will be location specific.', 'no', 'A turnkey solution will be developed on signing of a PPA', 'Immediately once a water source has been secured and the system has been installed.', 'Minimum build time will be incurred due to no major infrastructure development needed.', 'Milestones will be: Obtaining a PPA, Finalising regulatory authorisations, Completion of site preparation, system installation, grid connection, water reticulation and system commissioning.', '3', 'corporate', '', 'no', 'no', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', '', '3', 'no', 'draft', 'yes', 'Feasibility studies have been conducted for numerous overseas installations that are awaiting finalisation pending regulatory approvals and authorisations. It will be necessary to use these inputs and learnings to conduct studies locally once a client and location has been identified.', 'Any appropriate site with a reliable water source. See comments on Additional Information sheet.', 'na', 'na', 'na', 'na', 'na', 'na', 'no', '', 'no', 'no', '', 'no', '', '', 'no', '', '', 'We are in the process of applying for the necessary key authorisations and approvals. No timeline has been done.', '1', 'na', 'na', 'na', 'na', 'na', 'na', 'Not known at this stage', 'no', '', '', '', 'No engagement has been entered into with Eskom as yet', 'Uknown at this stage. These issues will only be determined once a location and site has been identified.', 'Preferably to Eskom. However this will be dependent on the client''s requirements which could result in a direct supply to the user.', '12', 'At this stage it is not known whether any projects will be located in neighbouring states or other countries in Southern Africa. ', '0-30', '10', '0.36', 'All connections, water and power, to and from the system will be manufactured locally i.e. piping, cabling and transformers.', '15', 'Until a client has been identified and local feasibility studies completed it will not be possible to comment on this section', '2013-07-02', '2013-07-11', 'true');
