(77, 205, 'Black Lite Solar', '+27 11 4477651', 'Sanjay Soni', 'The Workshop', '70 ', '7th Avenue ', 'Parktown North', 'Johannesburg', '2196', 'sanjay@blacklite.co.za', 'City of uMhlathuze', 'We are bidding to supply the uMhlathuze Municipality with 10MW of solar energy on a 20 year PPA model.  We will use Copper Indium Gallium Selenide (CIGS) thin film solar modules in our proposed power plant.  \r\n\r\nThe main cost drivers include the following:\r\nAccess to land\r\nFlatness of Land\r\nProximity to transformer\r\nLength of PPA\r\nTerms of adjustment to Tariff (inflation linked etc.)\r\nGuarantees from National Government on the PPA\r\nFacilitation of funding from the Development Finance Institutions like the IDC, DBSA etc\r\n\r\nKey decision points:  We are awaiting the decision of the Municipality on shortlisting of potential service providers.  Another key decision point is on the proposed tariffs  and acceptance of the PPA tariff by the Muncipality.\r\n\r\nThis is the first municipal IPP and could form the basis of other similar projects.  Municipalities receive a large portion of their revenue from the sale of electricity.  Therefore, if they produce their own electricity they could make greater margins.  \r\n\r\n', 'Other', '', '', '', 'photovoltaic', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '10', '1', '9', '20', '1.9', '2%', '11%', '', '', '', 'Quater2', '2014', '', '12', 'peaking', '12', '365', '9', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', '180', '20', '1900', '', '2%', 'yes', '', 'fastQ3-2013-36Month', '', '3', '12', 'Black Lite Solar', 'Manz', 'Black Lite Solar (Pty) Ltd', 'Manz AG', 'None', '0', '0', '0', 'no', '', '', '', '', 70, 'We intend to use local contractors from the Richards Bay area to assist or conduct the Civil, electrical engineering and implementation.  We have asked the municipality to provide a list of approved suppliers for the scope of works required.\r\n\r\nWe will also upskill local community members with solar installation skills and assist with developing the local community based on their needs like providing solar systems to schools in the area.\r\n\r\nWe are also working with the University of Zululand to conduct various studies into Solar.', 'no', 'no', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'no', 'no', '3', 'no', '', '', '', '', '', 'yes', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '4', 'project', '', 'yes', 'no', 'no', '', '', '', '6', 'yes', 'draft', 'no', 'We are still at the RFI stage and once we have been shortlisted we will complete any studies required by Lenders and other authorities.', 'uMhlathuze', '28', '48', '00', '32', '06', '00', 'no', '', 'no', 'no', '', 'no', '', '', 'no', '', '', 'We are in the process of bidding to the Richards Bay Municipality to have the first Municipal IPP.  This will require the assistance of the municipality to ensure that all the environmental and other authorisations are in place.  We will work with the municipality to ensure that all legal requirements are met and fulfilled.  ', '5', '28', '48', '00', '32', '06', '00', 'uMhlathuze Minicipality ', 'no', '', '', '', 'We are still at the RFI phase, and will engage Eskom on the basis we get to a preferred bidder stage. We understand the Municipality has had an engagement with Eskom - at this stage, we are not aware of the nature of this engagement. ', 'This cannot be assessed at this stage. ', 'We will be connecting directly into the uMhlathuze Minucipality grid connection. ', '12', 'Not applicable', '100+', '54', '30.00', 'Black Lite Solar is in the process of establishing a CIGS Thin Film Solar Manufacturing plant in East London using Manz technology.  The local content of our solar panels have been calculated at 84% based on a cost of production.', '290', 'This project will be the catalyst for establishing a local production facility for a 150MW pa CIGS thin film solar plant.', '2013-07-03', '2013-07-11', 'true'),
(78, 116, 'Wartsila', '+33685082005', 'Arnaud Gouet', 'Runsor', '2', 'Tarhajaantie', 'Vaasa', 'Vaasa', '65101', 'arnaud.gouet@wartsila.com', 'COEGA LNG Gas engines', 'Wärtsilä Corporation is a global leader in complete lifecycle power solutions specialised in manufacturing reciprocating engines, engineering and installation of Turnkey Gas engine power plants as well as operation and maintenance of thermal power plants. \r\nWärtsilä is as well highly experience in terms of LNG transportation and transformation as the majority of actual LNG Carriers are equiped with Wartsila engines. Furthermore through the aquisition of Hamworthy, Wärtsilä is one of the leader in the manufacturing of Regasification units for FRSU. \r\n\r\nTherefore Wärtsilä proposes to combine its strength in both world of Shipping and Power Plant, to offer a complete LNG To Power  Solution as a single EPC Contractor. \r\n\r\nWe are therefore seeking to develop  a  flexible Independent Smart Power Generation project with a minimum project life of 20 years, that includes the delivery of a FRSU to be anchored in Coega to feed not only a new 474 MW gas power plant, but would be capable of supplying extra fuel capacity to be used in the new Dedisa Power Plant, as well as other potential users either immediately or in the future.\r\n \r\nFor the purposes of aligning the plant output with the new generation determination published by the Minister of Energy, the developers have decided to adjust the plant size to fit within the current gas based generation allocation of 474MW with a COD intended for last quarter 2017, and offer the DOE an opportunity to reduce its generation cost at the Dedisa peaker power plant by off-setting the consumption of expensive diesel.\r\n\r\nThe Revised Balanced Scenario of the IRP 2010 has considered following criteria as a base of the balance: \r\na) Reducing carbon emissions;\r\nb) New technology uncertainties such as costs, operability, lead time to build etc;\r\nc) Water usage;\r\nd) Localisation and job creation;\r\ne) Southern African regional development and integration and;\r\nf) Security of supply.\r\nThe aim of this project is to develop a power generation project that answers positively to all those specific points based on the premise of combining an indigenous gas resource with the concept of a Smart Power Generation solution. \r\n\r\na/ Reducing Carbon emission :\r\nWith the highest simple cycle efficiency of thermal power plant, reciprocating gas engines allows for the lowest possible Carbon footprint to be realised. Once built, this plant will have the highest efficiency in South Africa.\r\nThis technology was chosen by Sasol for the exact same reason, Henri Loubser, Managing director at SNE said : “On average, the carbon foot print of Eskom’s electricity is almost 1000 kg/MWh. Using gas-engine technology will allow us to reduce that figure by more than 40%.”\r\n\r\nb/ New technology, uncertainties such as cost, operability, lead time to build etc.\r\nWärtsilä Corporation will ensure that the power plant shall be delivered on time and within budget thanks to its expertise in design and construction of base load power plant. Wärtsilä has an installed base of 54 GW worldwide which includes over 5000MW in African countries. Within the Southern African Power Pool, Wärtsilä recently completed a 180 MW gas fired power plant at Sasolburg, another 80 MW power plant in Zambia and is currently building a 180 MW gas power plant in Mozambique. All projects being delivered on time and within budget. Wärtsilä, as an experienced O&M contractor, will also function as the operator of the plant to ensure the availability and the reliability guarantees of the power plant are met. \r\n\r\nc) Water usage\r\nOne of the defining characteristics of Wärtsilä Gas Engines Power Plant is to use radiators as the primary method of cooling. The use of dry cooling methods means that the water consumption is negligible which is important in South Africa where water resources are scarce and fragile. \r\n\r\nd/ Localisation and Job creation\r\nDuring Construction, the site will require the employment of more than 1000 people  for civil works, mechanical installation, and electrical installation. During operation and maintenance, more than 100 People will be permanently required, for the life of the plant. In the projects realised by Wärtsilä, more than 80% of those resources are employed from the local communities surrounding the power plant who will be afforded the necessary training and development by Wartsila. The power plant will have its own workshop where 100% of the maintenance can be done locally and local manufacturing and supply of spares and services will be encouraged where possible. It is to be noted as well that this area intends to become a hub for the development of Oil& Gas services from which, this project will be an anchor for such a skills creation. \r\n\r\ne) Southern African regional development and integration\r\nAs mentioned, same technology is used in neighbouring countries and will allow development and skill transfers on a regional level. In addition, power generated from this project will alleviate the pressure experienced by the local utility (Eskom) to suppress the supply South Africa’s neighbouring countries thus aiding in the future development of both South Africa and the SADC region. Finally the extra capacity of gas can easily supply the Dedisa power plant and allow other project to be developped at a marginal cost.\r\n\r\nf/ security of supply\r\nWe define Smart Power generation (SPG), as a resource capacity having high operational flexibility coupled with high energy efficiency. Operational flexibility requires generation to have multiple dynamic operation modes, from ultra fast grid reserve to efficient base load generation. SPG has fast start up, shut down and load ramps with agile dispatch and is able to supply MW’s onto the grid within 1 minute and reach maximum power in 5 minutes. SPG is suitable for base load generation, peaking and balancing requirements. In addition, with the ability to operate each generating unit independently, maximum plant availability can be achieved (99.6% with (n+2)) and the plants high efficiencies remain constant throughout the power range. \r\n\r\nIn addition, this technology is reknowned to be the ‘Renewable Energy’ enabler with its unique abilities to provide grid stability with the introduction of renewable onto the system. This is particularly important considering the fact that by 2018, estimates are that there will be over 4GW of wind based generation of which almost half will be located in the Western Cape area. Without this technology, managing the grid load fluctuations will be problematic for the grid operator.\r\n\r\nThe fact that both the gas field developer and the Power Plant developer are joining their forces will ensure a secured supply through the entire chain from the GSA to the PPA.\r\n\r\nDetails of the project:\r\n1/ The LNG\r\nWärtsilä will be able to provide the entire infrastrucure necessary to import LNG within South Africa under a complete tunkey contract. Ideally the Government of South Africa can source the LNG from the market at preferential conditions.\r\n2/ The power plant\r\nThe location: Coega IDZ\r\nThis location has been chosen as the best place for mooring a FRSU in proper condition. Furthermore it is close to a proper grid connection and allows the feed of extra gas to an existing peaker power plant that can be converted.\r\n \r\nThe plant shall be equipped with 28x W18V50SG reciprocating gas engines, that can be instaleld either as an open cycle or a combined cycle immediately or at a later stage. More details are given in the application. \r\n', 'Reciprocating', 'Gas', 'other33', '', '', '', '', '', 'We shall supply as an EPC a complete solution that include a FRSU. GSA can be facilitated or DOE to purchase gas from the maket.', '', '', '', '512', '18', '474', '48', '0'