(81, 183, 'RVM 1 Hydro Electric Power (Pty) Ltd.', '+27 21 934 5503', 'Niel Theron', 'Level 3 Terminal Building Execujet Business Centre', '999', 'Tower Road', 'Cape Town International Airport', 'Cape Town', '7525', 'niel@hydro-sa.com', 'RVM Hydro Electric Power Project', 'The proposed RVM hydropower station would be located on the farm Riemvasmaak (Remainder of Farm no. 497 and Portion 1 of Farm no. 498) located approximately 40 km north west of Kakamas in the Northern Cape. The location of the proposed hydropower station is within the AFNP, but the area on which the hydropower station would be located (i.e. Remainder of Farm no. 497 and Portion 1 of Farm no. 498) is private land. This land was returned to the Riemvasmaak Community Trust as part of the first land claim in South Africa . While previously within the AFNP Riemvasmaak was deproclaimed on 19 February 2004 and has been managed by the park since then.  \r\nThe facility would be a run-of-river hydropower scheme capable of producing a maximum of 40 MW of electricity. \r\nA run-of-river hydropower station, like the proposed, consists of the following main components:\r\n      •	Intake infrastructure (i.e. weir and off-take structure);\r\n      •	Water conveyance infrastructure (i.e. canal or pipeline);\r\n      •	Head pond/ forebay;\r\n      •	Power station intake structure/ penstock;\r\n      •	Powerhouse; and \r\n      •	Outlet works/ tailrace.\r\nAncillary infrastructure includes access roads for use during construction and for maintenance purposes during operation, a transmission line for evacuating the energy produced by the hydropower station, a switchroom and transformer yard.\r\n\r\nThe hydrology of the Orange River is well understood and considered to pose little risk to the project given only a small portion of the river flow is require and will be used for power generation.\r\n\r\nHydro electric projects are heavily reliant on civil infrastructure, and civil works make up a considerable proportion of the cost of hydro electric projects. Electrical and Mechanical equipment, which generates the electricity, will be sourced from an international supplier. \r\n\r\nKey authorisations required for the project to proceed include the Environmental Authorisation and the Water Use Licence. Without these authorisations it will be impossible to construct the project. The Environmental Impact Assessment of the project is already underway and should address all the environmental concerns about the project. The environmental assessment process will be allowed to run its course before a decision is made on whether to proceed with the project.\r\n\r\nIt is propsed to bid the RiemvasmaakHydro Electric Project in Round 4 of REIPP.', 'Hydro', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '40', '10', '40', '80', '1.06', '5.7%', '', '', '0', '', 'Quater1', '2018', '', '36', 'baseload', '', '', '', 'no', '', 'yes', 'Neusberg Hydro Electric Project', 'no', '', '930', '20', '1060', '', '5.7%', 'yes', '', 'commitQ2-2014-Phased', '', '6', '36', 'Hydro SA', '', 'Hydro Tasmania South Africa', 'N/A', 'Hydro SA and Hydro Tasmania South Africa are the developers of South Africa''s first run-of-river hydro electric project to be constructed under the REIPP programme. The 10MW Neusberg Hydro Electric Project is currently under construction and is due for completeion in early 2015.Hydro Tasmania is Australia’s leading renewable energy business and the largest manager of water in the country.Hydro Tasmania''s 2,270MW installed capacity is provided by 29 power stations ranging in size from 700 kW to 600MW using water storages in six major catchments. The first of Hydro Tasmania''s major hydro electric projects was constructed in 1914, while the last was completed in 1990. Several small hydros have been iimplemented over the past 15 years. Hydro Tasmania also owns and operates three large scale wind farms with a total installed capacity of over 300 MW.', '0', '0', '0', 'no', '', '', '', '', 10, 'T