(94, 284, 'Sese Power (Pty) Ltd', '+61864655560', 'Thomas Scott-Morey', 'Unit', '9', 'Kgale Mews', 'Gabs International Finance Park', 'Gaborone', '0001', 'info@mitochondria.co.za', 'Sese Integrated Power Project (MQ.13.07.002E)', 'African Energy Resources Limited (AFR or the Company) owns 100% of Prospecting Licences No. 96/2005 and PL197/2007 which encompass areas of 287km2 and 229km2, respectively. AFR has a Board of Directors and senior management team with wide experience of exploring and developing mineral opportunities in southern Africa. Members of the executive team also have extensive experience in the development of coal mines and power generation facilities. AFR has established Sese Power (Pty) Ltd (Sese Power) in Botswana as the Special Purpose Vehicle for the 300MW Sese Integrated Power Project (the Project). It is intended that Sese Power will sell the entire electrical power output from the Project to Eskom.\r\n\r\nThe overall Sese Coal and Power opportunity was first discovered in mid-2010 after a drilling programme designed to test uranium targets intersected a near surface, thick coal seam. Subsequent drilling programmes over the ensuing 12 months resulted in an initial JORC inferred resource of 2.7 billion tonnes of bituminous thermal coal. This has since been upgraded to a Measured, Indicated and Inferred Resource of over 2.5 billion tonnes.\r\nSese Power’s short-term goal is to develop the Project. The initial mine development (1.0 to 1.5 Mtpa) will be sufficient to supply coal to the power station for the economic life of the Project and the coal reserves to be allocated to Sese Power will include a strategic reserve over this amount.\r\n\r\nThe near term goals for the Project are as follows:\r\n•	Negotiation of Power Purchase Agreement with Eskom\r\n•	Completion of Environment Impact Studies and gaining of requisite approvals\r\n•	Negotiation of EPC contract for the construction of the Project.\r\n•	Completion of a final bankable feasibility study.\r\n•	Mining Licence for a 1.5 Mtpa coal mine to provide fuel for the power station.\r\n•	Generation Licence for 300MW power plant.\r\n•	Arrangement of equity/debt financing for the project financing\r\n\r\nIn the past 12 months, activities have focused on the preparation of the feasibility study and environmental impact assessment for a coal mine and 300MW power station. Sese Power has completed its initial Measured Resource calculation in accordance with JORC requirements.. This resource will form the basis of the mine plan to be prepared for the first phase of mining.  The Mining Licence for this resource will be applied for once the Environmental Impact Study and Bankable Feasibility Study has been completed later this year. In parallel with these studies, Sese Power is progressing the negotiation of a power off-take agreement with a state-owned power utility. These negotiations are expected to be substantially completed by the end of this year.\r\n\r\nIn the two years since the deposit was discovered, Sese Power has rapidly progressed the Project and has clearly defined the options for development of the vast coal resources that it has discovered. ', 'Thermal', 'Coal', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '300', '150', '265', '85', '0.35', 'CPI', '33% thermal efficiency (LHV)', '', '', '', 'Quater2', '2017', '6 months from PPA to Project Financial Close and then 30 and 33 months for COD for units 1 and 2, respectively.', '36', 'baseload', '', '', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', '7500', '20', '850', 'Price quotes are in January 2013 Rand with CPI from this point in time.', 'Rand CPI assigned to all tariff except debt interest costs.', 'yes', '', 'commitQ2-2014-Phased', '', '6', '36', 'Sese Power (Pty) Ltd', '', 'Terracotta Resources (Pty) Ltd', 'Name withheld at this point in time.', 'Project development staff have completed project financing of over 4,000 MW of coal and gas fired power generation projects in India, Philippines and Australia. Further details can be provided. Terracotta experience.', '0', '0', '0', 'yes', '', '', '', '', 30, 'Local Botswana BEE Partner\r\n\r\nTerracotta Resources (Pty) Ltd is the local SA Partner and is 100% BEE.', 'yes', 'no', 'no', 'no', 'yes', '', '', '6', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', '02/01/2017', 'yes', '02/01/2017', 'no', '', 'no', 'Mining Licence required. Generation Licence required.', 'no', 'Mining and generation plant will be constructed under EPC contract.', 'June 2017', 'See Project attachment.', 'See Project attachment.', '6', 'project', '', 'yes', 'no', 'no', '', '', '', '6', 'yes', 'draft', 'no', 'Yes, and the details of this are included in the Project description attachment.', 'Sese, near Tonota, Eastern District, Botswana', '27', '13', '00', '21', '35', '00', 'no', '', 'no', 'no', '', 'no', '', '', 'yes', '31/12/2013', '30/06/2014', 'Mining Licence 31/12/2013 Generation Licence 31/12/2013', '76', '27', '50', '00', '22', '00', '00', 'border with Botswana', 'no', '', '', '', '2 meetings with Eskom', 'No, it is expected that any transmission upgrades will be in Botswana and that the existing transmission line from Botswana into South Africa will have sufficient capacity to accommodate the net output of the Project.', 'The Project will connect to the Botswana high voltage transmission network and a transmission agreement will be signed with BPC to transmit the net power from the Project to the South African border.', '36', 'Transmission Agreement with BPC', '30-40', '1000', '13.33', 'This will be mostly construction material and balance of plant.', '100', 'Limited as the power plant will be provided under a turn-key Engineering, Procurement and Construction contract with most major equipment being manufactured outside of Africa.', '2013-07-08', '2013-07-12', 'true'),
(95, 75, 'Gerald Chiwashira', '27820673518', 'Gerald Chiwashira', 'Regus Business Centre, West Tower                                	 2nd Floor, Nelson Mandela Square', '001', 'Maude Street', 'Sandton', 'Sandton', '2146', 'gerald@ageinvestments.com', 'AGE', 'The project is bio-energy utilizing waste to be collected from Pikitup sites in Johannesburg that will be converted to energy. The key dependencies will be the ability to collect 5000 tonnes of waste on a daily basis which will form the source heat. The heat will be incinerated and converted to energy.\r\nThe technology to be utilized will be supplied by Satarem of France.', 'Other', '', '', '', 'Waste to heat', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '100', '50', '100', '98', '0.60', '10', '95', '', '', '', 'Quater4', '2015', '', '11', 'baseload', '', '', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', '700', '20', '1', '', '0.1', 'yes', '', 'fastQ3-2013-36Month', '', '3', '11', 'Gerald Chiwashira', 'Satarem', 'n/a', 'Satarem', '1.Likeng WTE, Guangzhou\r\nScope?2x450t/d  QLHV=7500kJ/kg\r\nSteam Parameters?64bar,450?\r\nCapacity?22MW\r\nAnnual Operating Hours?8000h\r\nAnnual Power Production?16.5x104 MWh\r\nOwner?Guangzhou Environmental-Sanitation Bureau, China\r\nOperator: Veolia Environnement\r\n2. Scope?4x750t/d (3000tpd)  QLHV=7118kJ/kg\r\nSteam Parameters?40bar,400?\r\nCapacity?2x30MW\r\nAnnual Operating Hours?8000h\r\nAnnual Power Production?43.05x104 MWh\r\nOwner?Shenzhen Energy Corp.\r\n', '430000000 ', '430000000 ', '430000000 ', 'yes', '', '', '', '', 65, 'Magalies Community Trust', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', '2', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', '05/01/2015', 'no', '', 'no', 'The EIA is under way, RoD expected in November 2013.', 'no', 'The EIA is under way, RoD expected in November 2013.', 'no', 'Follows RoD', '', '', '', '2', 'project', '', 'no', 'no', 'no', '', '', '', '3', 'no', 'draft', 'no', 'To commence in August 2013', 'Johannesburg, Gauteng', '27', '958', '038', '26', '024', '921', 'no', '', 'yes', 'yes', '', 'no', '', '', 'no', '', '', 'Local Authority, Water Use, Zoning all take 12 months', '1', '27', '958', '038', '26', '024', '921', 'Kya Sand', 'no', '', '', '', 'None', 'Not yet ', 'Eskom', '14', 'n/a', '65-75', '300', '42.86', 'Fabrication and casting of moving parts to be sourced locally.', '55', 'to work with ESETA in sourcing technical skills', '2013-07-08', '2013-07-11', 'true'),
(96, 21, 'GDF SUEZ Southern Africa', '0828744660', 'Sanjith Mungroo', 'Lincolnwood Office Park', '6', 'Woodlands Drive', 'Woodmead', 'Sandton', '2191', 'sanjith.mungroo@gdfsuez.com', 'Thabametsi Power Plant', 'Thabametsi Power Plant\r\nIntroduction:\r\nGDF SUEZ Energy Southern Africa (Pty) Ltd and Exxaro Resources Limited concluded a Project Development Agreement and a Coal Supply Term Sheet. Exxaro has started the development of the greenfield Thabametsi Mine with the intention to secure the supply and off-take of coal to the 600MW coal fired power plant being developed by GDF SUEZ. With past experience in South Africa on both the Peaker Project and West Coast 1 Wind Project, GDF SUEZ is well acquainted with the requirements to develop projects successfully in this region. The project structure will be finalised after the issue of the procurement and project documentation to ensure our ability to comply with procurement rules. It may also be necessary for the introduction of another international developer to ensure the best resources are available to ensure the success of this project. \r\nThabametsi Mine - Status:\r\nThe proposed mine mouth power plant will have a total capacity of up to 1 200 MW (to be developed in two phases of 600 MW each). The Thabametsi mine is a prospective greenfields mine adjacent to Grootegeluk mine in the Waterberg, Limpopo province. Grootegeluk is currently the only operating mine in the Waterberg, and supplies both of Eskom’s Matimba and Medupi (still in construction) power stations respectively.\r\n•	The prefeasibility study for the Thabametsi mine has commenced.  The prefeasibility study is anticipated to be completed by the end of 2013.\r\n•	The bankable feasibility study will then commence beginning 2014 and should be complete by the end of 2014.\r\n•	A Mining Right Application (MRA) for the proposed project was submitted to the Limpopo Regional Office of the Department of Mineral Resources (DMR) on 24 April 2012. The MRA was accepted by the DMR as per signed acceptance letter dated 03 August 2012 [DMR Ref: LP30/5/1/2/2/10013MR]. In fulfilment of the requirements stipulated under Section 39 of the MPRDA, an Environmental Impact Assessment (EIA) process was initiated for the proposed project. The Scoping Report was completed and submitted to the DMR on 13 November 2012. Subsequent to the undertaking of certain social and environmental specialist studies, this EIA and Environmental Management Program (EMPr) Report was compiled. The Final EIA and EMPR was completed and submitted to the DMR on 31 January 2013.\r\n•	Environmental Authorisation from the Limpopo Department of Economic Development, Environment and Tourism (LDEDET) in terms of the National Environmental Management Act, 1998 (Act No 107 of 1998) (NEMA) and Associated Environmental Impact Assessment (EIA) Regulations (GNR. 543 of 18 June 2010) has been applied for and the process has started.\r\n•	Waste Management Licence from the Department of Environmental Affairs (DEA) in terms of the National Environmental Management: Waste Act, 2008 (No. 59 of 2008) (NEM: WA) has been applied for and the process has started.\r\n•	An application for an Integrated Water Use Licence (IWUL) in accordance with the National Water Act, 1998 (Act No. 36 of 1998) (NWA) will be submitted to the Department of Water Affairs (DWA) will be applied for by October 2013.\r\n\r\nCoal Supply Agreement:\r\nA coal supply term sheet was concluded with Exxaro that sets out the key commercial principles relating to the supply and off-take of all of the IPP Developer’s coal requirements to be supplied from the Thabametsi Mine for use by the Facility for the generation of electricity. This term sheet is now being developed into a Coal Supply Agreement.\r\nEnvironmental Impact Assessment & Permitting:\r\nSavannah Environmental has been appointed as independent environmental consultants to undertake the EIA.\r\nTechnology:\r\nThe quality of the coal requires the use of Circulating Fluidised Bed technology utilising. Dry cooling and in-furnace with lime stone injection is proposed for environmental reasons. It is also envisaged that the plant will be configured with 2 X 300 MW (sub-critical) generating units. It is proposed that the power will be evacuated via a 400kV transmission line approximately 43km long and connecting to the Eskom Masa Substation.\r\nLand and Water Resources:\r\nExxaro presently owns and has pre-selected five separate properties for the Project. The IPP Developer may select the most appropriate Site for the construction of the Facility. Subject to the successful outcome of the feasibility study and environmental process over the Site, Exxaro shall, upon selection of the Site by the IPP Developer, procure that Exxaro Coal will negotiate in good faith to enter into an option agreement with the Project Company for the sale of land to the Project Company, which option will be exercisable on/or before Financial Close. IPP Developer will ensure only the necessary amount of land will be utilised and in this way we ensure environmental compliance and maximum protection of the natural landscape.\r\nIt is well known that South Africa is a water stressed country and care is being taken in choosing appropriate technologies in the configuration of the power complex. Best efforts are being made to minimise the combined water consumption of both the mining and power complex. The design of the power plant assumes the utilisation of un-beneficiated (or run of mine) coal.\r\nExxaro will supply water (up to 650 000 kilo litres per annum) to the power station, for the interim period, for construction and operation purposes until the Mokolo and Crocodile River (West) Water Augmentation Project Phase 2 is commissioned. \r\nThe water supply is a portion of the total volume of water currently allocated to Exxaro Coal Proprietary Limited in terms of the Mokolo and Crocodile River (West) Water Augmentation Project Phase 1.\r\nThe above mentioned water supply is conditional upon the parties obtaining all the required approvals and consents from the competent authorities to enable Exxaro to either supply the water to the power station or to transfer the 650 000 kilo litres per annum water allocation in terms of the Mokolo and Crocodile River (West) Water Augmentation Project Phase 1 to GDF SUEZ.\r\nProposed EPC Contractor:\r\nThe EPC contractor for the project has not yet been selected.  The EPC request for proposals document is far progressed and will only be ready for issue once the procurement and project documents are available.\r\nIPP Developer expects that the EPC contractor, will most likely be South Korean or Chinese, but this remains to be determined. GDF SUEZ has strong links into these countries, and is confident that an acceptable technical and commercial arrangement can be obtained. We are also mindful to select parties that are likely to be bankable.\r\nProposed O&M Contractor:\r\nThe operation and maintenance of the power station will be undertaken by GDF SUEZ as they have extensive experience in the operation and maintenance of thermal generating plant located globally. \r\nEconomic Development Obligations:\r\nThe IPP Developer is aware of Economic Development Obligations under the procurement program and best efforts will be made to comply or exceed expectations. We bring to your attention that this project will be bid under a Project Company yet to be incorporated therefore our response for the BBBEE Contributor is incorrect. This field was completed to enable us to complete the submission of the RFRI.\r\n\r\nFinancing and Tariff:\r\nGDF SUEZ has extensive experience in financing power projects with non-recourse project finance basis and we will draw on our experience and leverage within the global market to get the most competitive terms for this project. Once the lenders are appointed they will require a complete independent due diligence to be conducted including the availability and quality of the resource. Thus far Sponsor has started this process and no fatal flaws have been identified. The partnership with Exxaro provides an immense amount of comfort in understanding the resource and being able to exploit this resource in an economical way.\r\nWe would like to draw to your attention that the tariff and percentage subject to indexation indicated is incorrect. This was inserted merely to enable us to complete the RFRI. Whilst we are confident that we are able to come up with the most competitive tariff, at this stage it is premature to state something meaningful in the absence of the RFP and supporting project documents.\r\nGiven the size of the project, allowing a portion of the tariff to be indexed to foreign currency will allow to attract international lending capacity,  which will increase the competitiveness of the financing, and the capacity of the developers to raise financing for the projects.\r\nThe alternative would be to include cross-currency swaps hedging break costs in termination provisions. Whilst this would also attract international lending capacity, this would come with additional costs for the project, impacting the tariff.\r\nWe anticipate the total project cost to be approximately 1.620 MUSD and this will be confirmed at a later stage. It will take approximately 42 months to reach COD after Financial Close.\r\n', 'Thermal', 'Coal', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '600', '300', '535', '81', '1', '40', '35', '', '', '', 'Quater2', '2018', 'Assumption made that PPA will be signed Q4 2014', '42', 'baseload', '', '', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', '16200', '30', '1000', 'Given the size of the project, allowing a portion of the tariff to be indexed to foreign currency will allow to attract international lending capacity,  which will increase the competitiveness of the financing, and the capacity of the developers to raise financing for the projects.\r\nThe alternative would be to include cross-currency swaps hedging break costs in termination provisions. Whilst this would also attract international lending capacity, this would come at an additional costs for the project, impacting the tariff.\r\n', '40', 'no', 'preference for portion of the tariff to be in USD/EUR', 'commitQ2-2014-Phased', 'We will be able to commence with a procurement process in Q4/2013 as there is much work to be done once we receive the PPA. Six months of bid preparation time will be reasonable to provide a binding offer and this will also allow us sufficient time to best optimise the tariff offered considering  all elements of the PPA. Therefore it will be possible to make a binding offer to the DOE by Q2/2014.', '6', '42', 'GDF SUEZ Energy Southern Africa', 'TBC', 'Exxaro Resouces Limited', 'GDF SUEZ', 'GDF SUEZ has extensive interests in power and gas transportation with more than 8,200 MW of coal generation alone. The coal generation experience includes sub-bituminous and brown coal in various combustion topologies ranging from pulverised fuel to circulating fluidised bed.\r\nThe lead developer for the generating station will be GDF SUEZ.  GDF SUEZ will apply its resources and experience to the generating station to ensure that the end product is reliable, technically and environmentally acceptable, and commercially viable. \r\nPlease refer to the Project Reference list for the South Asia, Middle East and Africa.', '97000000000000', '90673000000000', '84478000000000', 'no', '', '', '', '', 15, 'The Project will ensure compliance with all bid requirements. Provisions have been made to accommodate local partners and foreign partners to ensure the most competitive offer.', 'no', 'no', 'no', 'yes', 'no', 'no', 'no', '6', 'yes', 'yes', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', 'The Thabametsi Mine is not in production at the moment.', 'The development of the mining complex is in progress and will be ready to supply the power plant with the necessary coal as per the timeframe indicated. With the present planning site preparations and pre-stripping can commence in H2 2015.', 'Activity                                                             	Completion Date\r\nFinal EIA Report submission to DEA	                  18 November 2013\r\nEnvironmental Authorisation Decision from DEA	 21 February 2014\r\nCoal Supply Agreement – dependant on PPA	 March 2014\r\nEPC Term Sheet                                              	January 2014\r\nEPC Contract – dependant on PPA	                  TBC\r\nDMR Approval Application	                                    August 2013\r\nGeneration License – dependant on PPA	                  TBC\r\nFinancing Book Build	                                                      November 2013\r\nGrid Integration Studies                                                   November 2013\r\nThabametsi Mine Prefeasibility Study	                  December 2013\r\nThabametsi Mine Bankable Feasibility Study	                  December 2014\r\nFinancial Close - dependant on RFP                               TBC\r\nCOD	                                                                       July 2018\r\n', '', '6', 'project', '', 'no', 'no', 'no', '', '', '', '6', 'yes', 'draft', 'no', 'Once the lenders are appointed they will require a complete independent due diligence to be conducted including the availability and quality of the resource. Thus far Sponsor has started this process and no fatal flaws have been identified. The partnership with Exxaro provides an immense amount of comfort in understanding the resource and being able to exploit this resource in an economical way. The development of the project includes further geotechnical assessments, updated resource statements, grid interconnection studies etc. The timelines provided to the DOE makes sufficient time available to conclude all such work as required for this project.', 'Lephalale', '27', '28', '39', '23', '35', '51', 'yes', 'Exxaro presently owns and has pre-selected five separate properties for the Project. The IPP Developer may select the most appropriate Site for the construction of the Facility. Subject to the successful outcome of the feasibility study and environmental process over the Site, Exxaro shall, upon selection of the Site by the IPP Developer, procure that Exxaro Coal will negotiate in good faith to enter into an option agreement with the Project Company for the sale of land to the Project Company, which option will be exercisable on/or before Financial Close. IPP Developer will ensure only the necessary amount of land will be utilised and in this way we ensure environmental compliance and maximum protection of the natural landscape.', 'no', 'yes', '20/12/2012', 'yes', '04/10/2013', '06/12/2013', 'no', '', '', 'Environmental Authorisation is required and this is expected to be achieved in the first quarter of 2014. We will make best efforts to get most of the permitting in place prior to bid however there is still considerable time after bid and before financial close to complete outstanding authorisations. Below is a list of approvals in progress:\r\n•	Compilation of EIA according to NEMA,\r\n•	Including Environmental Impact Assessments and Management Plans;\r\n•	Facilitation and conducting of Public Participation Process;\r\n•	Appointment of and management of Specialist Studies Consultation;\r\n•	Development of an Integrated Water & Waste Management Plan (IWWMP);\r\n•	Development of an Air Quality Management Plan (AQMP);\r\n•	Development of a Biodiversity Management Action Plan (BMAP);\r\n•	Generation License\r\n•	Department of Minerals and Resources Approval\r\n', '43', '27', '23', '00', '23', '46', '00', 'Masa Substation', 'yes', '24/02/2012', 'yes', 'Cost Estimate Letter attached for your convenience ', 'All communication was directed via the Grid Access Unit at Eskom Megawatt Park, Maxwell Drive. Eskom did estimate that the grid connection will take approximately 72 months however this is unreasonable and we will continue to understand the breakdown of this timeframe. There is sufficient amount of work that can be done by the developer that will certainly reduce the time needed for Eskom.', 'The cost estimate letter indicates this is necessary and we will continue to work together with Eskom to reduce costs to the greatest extent possible. We have also appointed independent Advisors to assist with grid integration.', 'Thabametsi Power Plant will connect to the Eskom 400 kV Masa Substation and negotiations are in progress with Eskom.', '36', 'N/A', '100+', '3240', '20.00', 'we will encourage all contractors to maximise on both job creation and local content', '200', 'Coal fired power plants is nothing new to South Africa however as part of the project we will ensure that we contribute to the technology transfer and skills transfer to South Africans. The mechanism used to achieve this will be decided closer to the time and after evaluating the project in much more detail.', '2013-07-08', '2013-07-11', 'true'),
(97, 279, 'Sunbird Energy Ltd', '011 4845005', 'Carla Mackay', 'The Isle of Houghton, 3rd floor, Old Trafford 4', '4', 'Boundary Road', 'Houghton', 'Johannesburg', '2198', 'cmackay@sunbirdenergy.com.au', 'Ibhubesi Gas Project', 'Subsequent to DoE''s earlier call for Expressions of Interest ("EOI") for baseload power generation capacity in March 2012, Sunbird executed an agreement to acquire a 76% stake in the Block 2A Production Right,  ("Ibhubesi Gas Project") offshore of the west coast of South Africa in December 2012. The transaction, which is subject to approval of a transfer of title from the South African Department of Mineral Resources, will give Sunbird the right to operate and develop the Ibhubesi Gas Project, South Africa’s largest undeveloped gas field. \r\n\r\nThe Ibubhesi Gas Project ("IGP") is South Africa’s largest undeveloped gas field with independently certified 1P reserves of 210 Bcf and 2P reserves of 540 Bcf. The IGP is located in the 5,000km2 Production Right, Block 2A, offshore west coast South Africa. The partners in the IGP are Sunbird Energy Ltd (76%) and PetroSA (24%).\r\n\r\nSince Sunbird executed the acquisition agreement and assumed operatorship, it has reshaped the development plans based on the proven reserves and taken a development approach to match the current reserves with the existing gas-to-power ("GTP") market opportunities.\r\n\r\nSunbird is currently obtaining independent BEE certification based on its South African presence and its association with Umbono Capital (a Level One BEE Contributor). Additional participants, including BEE, still need to be confirmed across the GTP value chain (and hence some of the responses in this RFRI). Sunbird is in ongoing discussions with IPP developers (including Wartsila) in respect of the IGP, and a number of responses contained within this RFRI are based on gas engine power generation technology with input variables provided by Wartsila (which need to be confirmed in due course for the selected gas engine technology but also for open cycle and combined cycle gas turbines). \r\n\r\nA recent and independent verification of reserves has certified 1P reserves of 210 Bcf and 2P reserves of 540 Bcf and confirmed that the 2P reserves can support a mid merit  474 MW plant for in excess of 20 years or base load operation in excess of 15 years. \r\n\r\nDevelopment of the IGP as a gas to power project would provide critical load-following capacity at an economically competitive tariff utilising largely Rand-based energy pricing. There are few other projects that can provide mid merit or peaking power at comparable size, cost and time to market.  \r\n\r\nThe location of the IGP on the Western Cape coast also provides significant operational benefits to the power grid and line-loss reductions.  Alternative fuel supply for independent power producers ("IPPs") is through the importation of LNG or diesel – both are oil price indexed and US$ denominated, whilst the Ibubhesi Gas Project could present an alternative pricing basis and set a pricing level that enables the economic development of integrated GTP developments in the Western Cape.\r\n\r\nDevelopment of the IGP would provide South Africa with critical gas fired power generation capacity at an economically competitive tariff and offset current high cost diesel imports with subsequent relief on the country''s stressed balance of payments. \r\n\r\nDevelopment of a known domestic energy resource would create a new industry in South Africa and provide local energy supply to South Africa’s west coast, increasing mid-merit and peaking power capacity and alleviating power shortages. Additionally, development would provide significant infrastructure and government revenues throughout the life of the IGP through royalties, corporate taxes and state participation.\r\n\r\nSunbird estimates that another 6 months (from July 2013) will be required before an integrated GTP project can make a detailed power tariff proposal. However, this RFRI has been completed based on current studies, together with certain inputs provided by Wartsila (as potential IPP partner) and Standard Bank (as Financial Advisor), and are subject to change and finalisation on completion of ongoing studies. \r\n\r\n  ', 'Reciprocating', 'Gas', 'other33', '', '', '', '', '', 'Ibhubesi Gas Project (IGP), which can supply either or combination of Gas Engines, Open Cycle Gas Turbines or Combined Cycle Gas Turbines ', '', '', '', '512', '18', '474', '95', '0', 'n/a', '47', '', '', '', 'Quater2', '2018', 'Financial Close and Final Investment Decision: 3 months\r\nMobilisation and Site Prep (upstream development): 6 months\r\nConstruction (upstream development): 33 months\r\nCommissioning (upstream development): 3 months', '39', 'mid-merit', '12', '260', '16.8', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', '18000 ', '12', '1500', 'This expected tarif has been calculated using a gas price of 12USD/MMBTU. This variable shall of course be discussed and depends on many factors, including the length of the PPA. It is based on a mid merit mode.', '0', 'no', 'Upstream costs will be predominantly USD denominated, although this may be priced in ZAR.', 'commitQ3-2013-Phased', 'Sunbird estimates that another 6 months (from July 2013) will be required before an integrated GTP project can make a detailed power tariff proposal, i.e. 1Q2014. However, this RFRI has been completed based on current studies, together with certain inputs provided by Wartsila (as potential IPP partner) and Standard Bank (as Financial Advisor), and are subject to change and finalisation on completion of ongoing studies.', '3', '39', 'Sunbird Energy', 'To be confirmed. Ongoing discussions with IPP developers.', 'Umbono Capital (Level One BEE Contributor)', 'To be decided', 'Sunbird Energy Ltd is an ASX-listed (ASX:SNY) gas explorer and developer focused on southern Africa. The management team of Sunbird has extensive experience in the development of energy projects internationally.  The team includes experts in the fields of exploration geology, geophysics, reservoir engineering, drilling engineering, project management and project financing. Sunbird also works with a number of specialist consultants and service companies that provide expertise to review, plan and manage the efficient execution of the company’s work programs. Additionally, Sunbird is working with IPP developers to complement Sunbird’s capabilities and provide specific gas-fired power generation skills.\r\n', '0', '0', '0', 'no', '', '', '', '', 20, 'To be developed', 'no', 'no', 'no', 'no', 'no', '', '', '3', 'yes', 'no', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'yes', '', 'no', 'Plant to be constructed as part of the integrated IGP gas to power development ', '2Q2018', 'Refer to Concept Schedule Diagram in the Covering Letter.', 'IGP FID 2015 (assuming PPA developed in tandem with GSPA)', '3', 'project', '', 'no', 'no', 'no', '', '', '', '3', 'yes', 'draft', 'no', '•	Independent studies confirm viability of development of the Ibhubesi Gas Project\r\n\r\n•	Existing discovered 1P Reserves of 210 Bcf at Ibhubesi Gas Project support viable Phase 1 development\r\n\r\n•	2P reserves of 540 Bcf represent the most likely recoverable volume and indicates significant expansion potential for Phase 2 development\r\n\r\n•	Ibhubesi  gas  marketing  discussions  progressing  –  proven  reserves  base  provides opportunity to contract and commit gas volumes under a Gas Sales Agreement\r\n', 'Saldanha, Western Cape, in proximity to either the Blouwater or Aurora Substations ', '18', '04', '43', '32', '58', '23', 'no', '', 'no', 'no', '09/07/2013', 'yes', '31/03/2014', '28/02/2015', 'no', '', '', '1) Re-affirmation of EIA Approval for Upstream based on potential FDP revision 2) EIA for gathering and/or transmission pipelines 3) Approval from DMR of Sunbird''s acquisition of 76% stake in Ibhubesi 4 ) Re-zoning of land for gas processing plant and/or power plant in Saldanha  ', '5', '18', '03', '02', '32', '58', '54', 'Blouwater ', 'no', '', '', '', 'Not applicable.', 'Needs to be evaluated as part of a Grid Connection Study', 'Eskom Grid', '39', 'Not applicable', '100+', '0', '0.00', 'To be evaluated', '0', 'To be evaluated. Local content estimated at 20% of the integrated project (ZAR 3600 Million). The template above was faulty and wouldn''t allow this to be inserted as such.', '2013-07-08', '2013-07-12', 'true'),
(98, 141, 'Ansaldo Energia SpA', '+393355787021', 'Masè Gianluigi', 'Ansaldo Energia SpA', '8', ' Via N. Lorenzi', 'Campi', 'Genova', '16152', 'gianluigi.mase@aen.ansaldo.it', 'Medium Term Risk Mitigation Energy 474 MW CCGT', 'Ansaldo Energia (herein after AEN) is a global supplier of turn-key power plants and offers the full set of the most reliable and best performing solutions available today, supplying whole plants as well as power blocks in both open and combined cycles (see Attachment 1 “Company Presentation”).\r\nAEN is one of the few companies in the world able to offer a broad range of products as manufacturer of the main power plant components, with a total shop capacity of about 60 units/year.\r\n \r\nAEN is fully acknowledged as EPC for turnkey projects, and therefore as a global plant engineering contractor as well as LTSA provider. \r\n \r\nAEN enjoys an outstanding reliability and has references on all five continents especially accrued on CCGT plant, an established preferred solution on Power Generation market (See Attachment 2 – “AEN Reference List”).\r\n \r\nActually, a general worldwide trend on IPP market highlights that the investment costs of gas fired plants are lower than coal fired and nuclear power plants. \r\nGas fired power plants are built rapidly and, in most cases, expenditures are spread over two to three years. \r\nFurthermore, generally the O&M costs of gas fired power plants are significantly lower than those of coal fired or nuclear power plants in all countries,.\r\n \r\nBased on the above considerations and leveraging on proprietary knowledge and capabilities, AEN proposes a solution for the “Medium Term Risk Mitigation Energy  -  474 MW CCGT” project consisting of a CCPP in Multishaft configuration adopting 2 x GT (model type AE94.2, ISO rating 170 MW) +1 x ST (model type MT20, ISO rating 170 MW) +2 x Turbogenerators (model type WY21Z, air cooled). \r\n\r\nYou can find in Attachment 3 - zip folder “500MW2+1MS”:\r\n\r\n-	Detailed description (file name “STD AE94 2_2+1”)\r\n-	Standard Layout (file name “2+1A0VVFP004_1_0”) and \r\n-	Single Line Diagram (file name “STD_A0VVCU141_00”). \r\n \r\nAEN proposed solution is tuned to accomplish the main goals and value drivers for the typical IPP needs on cycling loads:\r\n \r\n•         Low CAPEX;\r\n•         Short lead time (from greenfield to Power Generation in about 28 – 30 months) ;\r\n•         High flexibility in Operation;\r\n•         Dual Fuel capability (optional);\r\n•         Extended maintenance schedule;\r\n•         Lower O&M costs\r\n•         Low CO2/NOx emissions.\r\n \r\nImportante toolgates/decision points for the project are:\r\n \r\n•         Authorizations by all official empowering bodies;\r\n•         Enforcement of a related Purchase Power Agreement;\r\n•         Enforcement of a related Fuel Supply Agreement;\r\n•         Project Financing structure.\r\n', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '2013-07-08', '0000-00-00', ''),
(99, 234, 'BergWind Energy PTY Ltd', '+27287541526', 'Dawid Roux Pretorius', 'Southern Cape Renewables', '67', 'Erica Drive', 'Stilbaai Hoogte', 'Stilbaai', '6674', 'jacques@sascr.co.za', 'Lunsklip Wind Farm', 'Lunsklip Wind farm is situated 8km North East of Stilbaai. BergWind Energy has been busy with the development of the project since 2011. Land leases have been secured and site surveys done for the construction of 6-8 Wind turbines. Environmental Impact Study was completed in June 2013. FBAR submitted to DOE in December 2012 and amendments together with Final Bird and Bat reports, Transport Study, Eskom Cost Estimate will be submitted by August 2013 for ROD.\r\n\r\nProcess for lease of property from Hessequa Municipality for the construction of a 22kv overhead power line to be connected to a new substation built adjacent to the excisting substation is ongoing and will be finalized within the next two months.', 'Other', '', '', '', 'Wind', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '50', '3.3', '20 ', '42', '1.05', 'Co-related to inflation', '95', '', '', '', 'Quater1', '2014', '', '9', 'none', '12', '365', '24', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', '350', '15', '1.15', '', '0 Not Applicable', 'yes', '', 'commitQ2-2014-Phased', '', '2', '3', 'BergWind Energy PTY Ltd', 'Vestas - Not Confirmed', 'Southern Cape Renewables PTY Ltd', 'BlueBear Advisory Africa (Dutch), Adcofin (Belgium)', 'Involved in the development and construction of the Couga Wind Turbine in Port Elizabeth constructed in 2010.', '0', '0', '0', 'no', '', '', '', '', 24, 'Local Economic development. Community Projects have been identified.', 'yes', 'no', 'no', 'no', '', '', '', '9', 'no', '', '', '', '', '', 'no', '', 'yes', '', 'no', '', '', '', '', '6', 'project', '', 'yes', 'no', 'no', '', '', '', '9', 'yes', 'finalised', 'yes', 'FBAR submitted to DOE for ROD. Agricultural, Bird, Bat, Botanical, Archeological, Heritage, Visual, etc studies are complete. See Attched FBAR', 'Stilbaai, Western Cape, South Africa', '34', '18', '243', '21', '28', '023', 'yes', 'Land lease for construction of turbines secured and in process with LUPO', 'no', 'yes', '07/12/2012', 'yes', '11/09/2013', '11/12/2013', 'no', '', '', 'CAA - Approval received, DWA - Approval received', '5', '34', '19', '640', '21', '24', '411', 'Stilbaai Substation', 'yes', '09/05/2012', 'yes', 'Cost Estimate Attached', 'Several discussions with Eskom Network Planning office. See attachments', 'No transmission, only Distribution. See Attachments', 'Eskom. See attachment', '9', 'No', '0-30', '100', '28.57', 'Electrical, Civil, Maintenance, Tower construction, Roads, financial services', '150', 'Maintenance facilities', '2013-07-08', '2013-07-11', 'true'),
(100, 294, 'MOOI HYDRO', '0828089865', 'JOHAN VAN ZYL', 'PROFOUND ENGINEERING', '87', 'RAVEL STREET', 'MANTEVREDE', 'VANDERBIJLPARK', '1911', 'johan.vanzyl@prof-eng.co.za', 'CAMRO', 'The project is a Brownfield’s Hydro Power Generation Plant located close to Port Shepstone in the Kwazulu Natal Province of South Africa, 200 kilometres South of Durban.  The project entails the construction of a 750kW power plant required for the supply of electricity to the existing Eskom network in KZN.\r\nThe proposed power plant will be situated on the farm Camro Estates. There is an existing transfer tunnel, that transfers water from the one side of the farm to the opposite side of the farm and it was used for power generation and driving irrigation pumps.\r\nFrom our surveyor data, a total of 7m head are available for the generation of power.\r\nThe decision was made to base the study on utilising 2 off 400kVA or 350kW  S-shape Kaplan turbines totalling an installed capacity of 700kW at leading or lagging power factor or a single 700kW Kaplan turbine.\r\nThis feasibility study is only concerned with the generation of the power using the water resource available at the proposed site in Port Shepstone. Although the river has substantial higher volumes available, the existing tunnel has a limited capacity.\r\nThis study includes economical evaluations and any commercial processes that could be to the advantage of this project. \r\nThe electrical energy generated is envisaged to be fed back into the 11kV Grid network supplying all the various farms in the area. This plant will be interconnected into the national grid. Mooi Hydro (Pty) Ltd has entered into a contract with Camro Estates busy forming a new Special Purpose Vehicle entity for this project. \r\nThe cost of inter connecting to the grid is included in the total cost estimate. We included the Eskom proposed cost due to the fairness of the costs. \r\nThis document assumed that the funding will be done on a typical recourse funding methodology with a NewCo being the sole investor / shareholder. \r\nIn order to finalise financing for the project NewCo will need to enter into a Power Purchase Agreement. The IDC has already expressed a willingness to fund the project provided that a PPA can be securred. \r\nThe project must apply for an IPP Generation License from the National Energy Regulator of South Africa (NERSA) and will need to enter into an interconnection agreement with Eskom. Eskom has provided a quote for this and Eskom has entered into a similar agreement with Mooi Hydro for their Harlestone Hydro Power Project, which forms a seperate application to this one.\r\n\r\n1.2	    WATER RESOURCE EVALUATION\r\nAccording to the Umgeni Water Resource Master Plan 2012 Volume 1 (Table 4.53 page 172) the Umzimkulu river has a total capacity/yield of 1,373 million cubic meters per annum of water. This equates to an average of 156,735 m3 / hour or 43 m3 / second.\r\n\r\n\r\n \r\nFrom the tunnel calculations the maximum flow through a tunnel of this specific size is 10.4 m3/s. \r\n\r\nFlow in rectangular channel (Manning)\r\n 	 	 \r\nChannel width (mm):	b	2500\r\nWater height in channel (mm):	y	2000\r\nChannel slope: (mm/m)*	S	0.5\r\nChannel area (m²):	A	5\r\nWetted perimeter (m²):	P	6.5\r\nManning''s "n" value:	n	0.009\r\nFlow volume (liters/hour) =	Q	   37 545 056.56 \r\nFlow volume (m3/s) =	 	10.42918238\r\nVelocity (m/s)	V	2.09\r\n*Use figure of 0.1 if there is no slope to the "channel"\r\n\r\nThis volume of water constitutes approximately 25% of the total amount of water available on a continuous basis.\r\n\r\nThe power plant output should thus not be subject to any rainfall variations. \r\n\r\nThe power plant also has a zero influence of the water availability to any third parties as the water that is taken out of the river is reinstated still on the same owner’s property. The owner of the farm is part of the development team for this project.\r\n', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '2013-07-08', '0000-00-00', '');
