(112, 210, 'Prometheus Energy', '+27118024036', 'Edwin Kikonyogo', '1st Floor, Building 16, The Woodlands Office Park', '20 ', 'Woodlands Drive (Cnr. Kelvin Drive)', 'Woodmead', 'Johannesburg', '2191', 'edwin@destinycorporation.co.za', 'Mooinooi Waste Heat Recovery', 'Prometheus Energy (Proprietary) Limited is advanced in its acquisition of a 17MW smelter off-gas fuelled power plant, located in Mooinooi, North-West. The plant consists of a bank of ten 1.7MW each GE Jenbacher engines, capable of generating up to 17 MW per hour. \r\n\r\nAs part of its expansion of the capacity of the plant, Prometheus proposes to recover the waste heat generated by the engines, using a heat exchanger, and then convert this into electricity through an organic rankine cycle ("ORC") platform. This will generate an additional 2 MW of electricity, and could be increased to as much as 4MW', 'Reciprocating', 'Gas', 'other33', '', '', '', '', '', 'Organic Rankine Cycle to recover waste heat off existing electricity producing engines', '', '', '', '17', '1.7', '2', '94', '0.76', 'CPI', '50%', '', '', '', 'Quater1', '2015', 'PPA with Department of Energy for additional would facilitate financial close and development work beginning', '12', 'mid-merit', '12', '31', '24', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', '150', '20', '95', '', 'CPI', 'yes', '', 'fastQ2-2013-24Month', '', '2', '12', 'Destiny Corporation Energy (Pty) Ltd', 'Ormat Technologies Inc.', 'Destiny Corporation Energy', 'Destiny Corporation Energy', 'The existing Waste Gas to Power Plant is the first of its kind in South Africa - AAP Power and Vuselela Energy has developed a unique waste gas fuelled power plant, using modified & de-rated GE Jenbacher engines. Waste smelter off-gas (consisting primarily of CO2, CO, and H2) is collected off a chrome smelter furnace, cooled down and piped into a gas scrubber, before being injected into ten gas engines. The Industrial Development Corporation SOC Limited recently invested into a very similar plant, SA Calcium Carbide (Pty) Ltd''s plant, which is now South Africa''s second waste off-gas to power plant. Working with international Organic Rankine Cycle technology providers (e.g. NYSE-listed ORMAT technologies, Destiny Corporation Energy has been mandated to develop this expansion for Prometheus'' plant.', '0', '0', '0', 'yes', '', '', '', '', 69, '. Economic: Does the project contribute to national economic development?\r\nYes, the project activity has a robust economic dimension addressing the following in terms of national economic development:\r\n• The project will generate employment both during construction (estimated 130 temporary positions) and operation (estimated 7 permanent positions). The majority of these positions will be filled from the local community of the Majakaneng and Mooinooi districts.\r\n• All of the shares in the project are directly owned by South African entities and therefore will provide financial returns to these parties.\r\n• There are no existing projects using the envisaged technology in South Africa and the project will provide an opportunity for technological interaction and knowledge transfer to local citizens. That Destiny has identified a further 400 MW in this regard bodes well for the country as well the Mooinooi municipal district.\r\n2. Social: Does the project contribute to social development in South Africa?\r\nYes, the project will contribute significantly to the social upliftment and development of the people of South Africa and particularly in the project area, through the following:\r\n• Through the creation of jobs both temporary and permanent, most of which will be from the local communities, the project activity will contribute to alleviation of poverty in the project area.\r\n• Because there are no similar technology installations in the area, the local people will require education and training in the operation and maintenance of the plant. This will enhance information sharing and skills transfer from foreign parties to the local community.\r\n• The creation of jobs, together with the wider impact of poverty alleviation will create a distribution of wealth within the local communities, with a direct and measurable improvement of health and quality of life for citizens of the local community\r\n3. Environmental: Does the project conform to the National Environmental Management Act principles of sustainable development?\r\nThe project activity will take place on an existing industrial site, on unused open land within the greater plant operation covered by the original EIA. Therefore:\r\ni) That the disturbance of ecosystems and loss of biological diversity are avoided, or where they cannot be avoided, are minimised and remedied\r\nThere will be no disturbance of any ecosystem or loss of biodiversity through the project activity. The selected site is on the existing industrial property between existing operational units with no active ecosystem or biodiversity constraints.\r\nii) That pollution and degradation of the environment are avoided, or where they cannot be altogether avoided, are minimised and remedied\r\nBy harvesting waste heat emitted, and replacing fossil fuel based electricity from the national grid, the project activity will have a positive impact on pollution by lowering national and local CO2 emission levels. Therefore, there will be no pollution or degradation of the environment through the project activity; in fact, there will be an improvement.\r\niii) That the disturbance of landscapes and sites that constitute the nation’s cultural heritage is avoided, or where it cannot be altogether avoided, is minimised and remedied.\r\nThere will be no disturbance of landscapes and sites that constitute the nation’s cultural heritage through the project activity as the selected site is within the boundary of the existing IFM industrial complex.\r\niv) That waste is avoided, or where it cannot be altogether avoided, minimised and reused or recycled where possible and otherwise disposed of in a responsible manner\r\nThe project activity will not generate any operating waste. Not even the usual inert building rubble will typical of construction projects will be generated during construction. \r\nv) That the use and exploitation of non-renewable resources is responsible and equitable, and takes into account the consequences of the depletion of the resource\r\nThe project activity will not consume or exploit non-renewable resources. By generating waste-heat based electricity, the project will have a positive impact on the use of non-renewable resources by extending the existing plant''s objective of replacing fossil fuel based generation capacity.\r\nvi) That the development, use and exploitation of renewable resources is responsible and equitable, and takes into account the consequences of the depletion of the resource.\r\nThe electricity generated by the project is based on a waste heat stream, from engines that themselves are fuelled by waste gas from the furnaces at IFM. Therefore the project activity by\r\ndefinition will not consume or exploit renewable resources but rather a waste source.\r\nvii) That a risk averse and cautious approach is applied, which takes into account the limits of current knowledge about the consequences of decisions and actions\r\nPrior to construction the project activity will be scrutinized and monitored by the EIA consultants used by IFM for the overall plant development. In addition, a monitoring methodology forming part of the UNFCCC criteria for CDM registration has already been implemented and adhered to during operation. This same methodology will be extended to the proposed project\r\nvii) That negative impacts on the environment and on people’s environmental rights be  anticipated and prevented, and where they cannot be altogether prevented, are minimised and remedied.There will be no negative impacts on the environment and on people’s environmental rights through the project activity.', 'no', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'no', 'no', 'no', '3', 'yes', 'no', 'yes', '12/01/2015', 'no', '12/01/2015', 'yes', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '3', 'corporate', '', 'no', 'yes', 'no', '', '', '', '3', '', 'finalised', 'yes', 'Everything has been completed - the plant from which the waste heat will be recovered and converted into electricity is already operational. As it operates to generate the current 17 MW it delivers, it produces waste heat and exhaust gas, which is released / vented into atmosphere. The proposed project will capture these emissions and recycle them, using the ORC platform, into electricity. As the existing plant will be 100% owned by Prometheus, and the proposed waste heat recovery project, which is an extension of the existing plant, is also to be owned by Prometheus, the fuel supply and integration issues that may be typical of such projects do not exist here. ', 'Buffelsfontein JQ465, Mooinooi, North-West Province', '27', '36', '41.93', '25', '43', '29.74', 'yes', 'The ORC waste heat recovery platform will be built adjacent to the existing 17MW gas to power plant owned and operated by Prometheus Energy. Prometheus is signing a long-term access-and-usage-of-land-in-return-for-rental agreement with IFM SA - this same agreement''s terms include access for the proposed expansion.                         ', 'yes', 'no', '', 'no', '', '', 'no', '', '', 'All authorisations and approvals secured. Only outstanding is transfer of NERSA Generating license from IFM SA (the current owner) into the name of Prometheus Energy (the acquiring / incoming owner of the existing plant), and the approval of the proposed increase, from waste heat recovery, in generating capacity from 17MWe gross', '0.8', '27', '36', '41.93', '25', '43', '29.74', 'IFMSA has an Eskom substation ("Mooinooi") on site', 'no', '', '', '', 'When the 17 MW waste gas to Power plant was commissioned, Eskom confirmed that there was existing capacity for excess power to be transmitted back into the grid using existing infrastructure', 'There will be no Eskom infrastructure upgrades required for the transmission of power generated through this project', 'Eskom - Mooinooi substation, Mooinooi, North-West Province', '3', 'Host country is South Africa', '75-85', '70', '46.67', 'There is significant construction work (civils, structural), welding, bending & related steelwork, as well as the long-term maintenance of this infrastructure. In addition, Destiny Corporation Energy and Prometheus have identified a further 400 MW of waste heat recovery projects that they have prioritised for development. This would allow for economies of scale, which would lead to sustainable local manufacturing in this industry niche', '120', 'Destiny intends to develop a South-Africa based waste heat recovery & harvesting offering, which will be targeted at utilities, mining & industrial companies, and other energy intensive consumers across the African continent. Together with our international technology partners, ORMAT Technologies, we intend setting up training centres, operations monitoring & response centres, as well as plant & equipment maintenance centres that will support both Prometheus'' own projects as well as 3rd-party projects utilising similar technology', '2013-07-09', '2013-07-12', 'true'),
(113, 115, 'Exxaro Resources Limited', '0123074243', 'Jan Oberholzer', 'Exxaro Corporate Centre', '1', 'Roger Dyason Road', 'Pretoria West', 'Pretoria', '0183', 'Jan.Oberholzer@Exxaro.com', 'Waterberg IPP Phase 2 & 3', 'Exxaro has partnered with GDF-Suez for the first phase (600-MW) of the project, having signed a Project Development Agreement (PDA) and Coal Supply Termsheet. GDF-Suez has several decades experience in the ownership and operation of independent power plants internationally, totalling over 116,000MW worldwide. Exxaro intends expanding production in a further two phases, with a Phase-2 and a Phase-3 of 600-MW each, to bring total capacity up to 1800-MW at the site.\r\n\r\nThese plants will burn low-CV coal in Fluidised-Bed Combustion (FBC) boilers, which will minimise water usage as no beneficiation will be necessary due to Run-of-Mine (RoM) coal being utilised. These boilers utilise in-bed sorbent desuphurisation with no water-intensive Flue-Gas Desulphurisation (FGD) being required. Furthermore these power plants will make use of dry-cooling and dry-ashing technologies, which will make these units the most water-efficient in the country as well the most environmentally-friendly as it also reduces mining processing and waste disposal.\r\n\r\nThe fuel for Phase-2 & 3 will be supplied via conveyor from Exxaro''s open-cast Thabametsi Mine adjacent to the power-plant.  The main decision points for the expansion will be availability of water from the Mokolo Crocodile River (West) Water Augmentation Project Phase-2 (MCWAP-2) and the HV-grid access in the area.', 'Thermal', 'Coal', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '1200', '300', '1065', '85', '1.10', 'Mechanism: Combination of actual cost increase year-on-year and PPI', '37', '', '', '', 'Quater1', '2020', 'First 300MW Unit will be COD Q1, 2020 with next 300MW Q3, 2020 for Phase-2. Phase-3 in turn first 300MW Unit will be COD Q1, 2022 with next 300MW Q3, 2022.', '42', 'baseload', '', '', '', 'yes', ''