(115, 178, 'jonny moosa', '27765423839', 'jonny moosa', 'Zwelihle', '149', 'Ingwe Street', 'Kwa Guqa Ext 2', 'eMalahleni', '1039', 'bonview14@gmail.com', 'Malelane Power Station', 'Malelane Power Station\r\n\r\nBon View Trading 14 (PTY) LTD trading as Bon View Energy(kj) intends developing a natural gas fired power station situated in Malelani (Mpumalanga) South Africa.  Natural gas is planned to be secured from ENI, a company that is currently exploring for gas in Mozambique in the mamba complex.  Our organisation has already began the process of engaging ENI for natural gas allocation for the proposed project and a suitable site for the proposed construction of the power plant.  \r\n\r\nA huge natural gas discovery within the Mamba Complex in Area 4, at the Coral 3 delineation well, offshore Mozambique was announced by Eni. This is a significant new exploration discovery that highlights Eni commitment to maximise the potential of this massive gas reserve base.\r\n\r\nThe drilling operations took place about 65 kilometres off the Cabo Delgabo coast and reached a total depth of 5,270 meters by drilling into 2,035 of water. The discovery has added 6 trillion cubic feet (tcf) of gas, taking the full potential of the Mamba Complex to 75 tcf of gas in place.\r\n\r\nAfter this discovery, the existence of hydraulic communications with the reservoir Coral 1, Coral 2 and Coral 3 is proved. Therefore, it is now believed that each well will provide higher production rate in the upcoming exploration operations. Eni plans to drill at least two further wells to maximise the full potential of the complex.\r\n\r\nNatural gas is an extremely important source of energy for reducing pollution and maintaining a clean and healthy environment. In addition to being a domestically abundant and secure source of energy, the use of natural gas also offers a number of environmental benefits over other sources of energy, particularly other fossil fuels.\r\n\r\nThis discovery, has paved the way for a new power plant in the Mpumalnaga area that will be fed by pipeline from Mozambique and promote the "intra -Africa trade", which is widely considered to be insignificant among African countries.  \r\n\r\nSouth Africa have good political relations with the government of Mozambique and doing business between the nations has been going on for centuries.  This project will both benefit South Africa and Mozambique on creating permanent jobs and energy security in the continent.\r\n\r\nThe main cost drivers of this project will be the proposed pipeline to transport the gas  (Natural gas) from Mozambique.  This pipeline has the potential of being one of the longest pipeline in the world. It is not envisaged that tapping into the grid will be extremely expensive as the 300 000 kilometers of Eskom power-lines runs threw the Malelane area. \r\n\r\nUnstable labour and  weak productivity in the construction phase also has the potential of driving costs to levels that are unexpected, however all  these risks can be mitigated.\r\n\r\nThe proposed project can only come into being if the natural gas allocation is granted and the South African government via Nersa grants a license to supply power to power utility eskom.  \r\n', 'GasPlant', 'CCGT', 'NaturalGas', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '4800', '800', '3000', '60', '9000', 'fundamental indexation', 'BTU', '', '', '', 'Quater2', '2017', 'Operation date can be shifted based on labour and contractor performance problems.', '36', 'baseload', '', '', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', '8000', '3', '9000', 'none', 'Fundamental indexation', 'yes', '', 'commitQ2-2014-Phased', 'none', '6', '36', 'Bon View Energy(kj)', 'GE ENERGY', 'None', 'Siemans', 'Site address of GE Energy (http://www.ge-energy.com/about/power_water.jsp) and Siemans (http://www.siemens.com/innovation/apps/pof_microsite/_pof-spring-2013/_html_en/gas-turbines.html)', '1500000', '1500000', '1800000', 'no', '', '', '', '', 51, 'Local supplier development projects in the region', 'no', 'no', 'no', 'no', '', '', '', '6 ', 'no', '', '', '', '', '', 'yes', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '6', 'corporate', '', 'yes', 'no', 'no', '', '', '', '6', '', 'none', 'no', 'No other studies have been conducted.  All relevant studies can be concluded in six months once the Department of Energy intends to issue a license to develop the station.', 'Malelane (Mpumalanga Province) South Africa', '25', '02', '217', '25', '29', '601', 'no', '', 'no', 'no', '', 'no', '', '', 'no', '', '09/07/2013', 'Local Chief and Municipality authorization', '20', '25', '29', '601', '25', '02', '217', 'Main Transmission Substation  ..... Khanyazwe (Malelane) 275kV loop-in (Marathon - Komatipoort 1st 275kV line', 'no', '', '', '', 'No meetings and proposals have been made to Eskom to date.', 'Eskom is currently building a new sub station in Malelane under their new built program. Please note that not the precise co-ordinates of the newly built substation are known to our organisation, but it is confirmed Eskom is investing in a new sub-station in Malelane.', 'We will be connecting to Eskom', '24', 'Only the natural gas is outside South Africa and a gas allocation proposal has been forwarded to ENI.', '100+', '3500', '43.75', 'Estimated 300 companies will benefit from this construction.', '12000', 'Component manufacturing will receive a boost from the project and these companies will be those that have been brought online by Transnet multi billion project.  Our organisation plans to encourage our international partners to invest in centers for training and component manufacturing.', '2013-07-09', '2013-07-09', 'true'),
(116, 326, 'Ncondezi Coal', '+442071835402', 'Hanno Pengilly', '3rd Floor Albemarle House', '1', 'Albemarle Street', 'London', 'London', '0169', 'francois@crescopf.co.za', 'Ncondezi Coal Fired Power Plant', 'Ncondezi plans to develop Mozambique’s first coal fired power plant on the Ncondezi Project area in the Tete Province. This follows the conclusion of both a Mine and Power DFS which confirmed that a large scale, long life, open pit thermal coal mine and integrated power plant is technically and economically viable.\r\n\r\nThis large scale project will be developed in phases, starting with a 300MW integrated mine and power plant (“300MW Project”), expanding ultimately to an 1800MW power plant. The Power DFS was conducted by Parsons Brinckerhoff and independently reviewed by STEAG, one of Germany’s largest electricity producers, from an operator’s perspective.\r\n\r\nThe 300MW Project, the first phase of Ncondezi Project, will see the development of an open pit mining producing 1.2 million tonnes per annum of coal for consumption by a 300MW base load thermal coal fired power plant, which will be adjacent to the mine. The power plant will use a modern and proven Circulating Fluidised Bed (“CFB”) technology, which has low emissions and will comply with the Government of Mozambique’s requirements for air quality.\r\n\r\nThe power plant will be located about 90kms away from the local transmission network. The cost of the project is estimated between US$500 – US$600 million. Construction is planned for 2014, with the power plant generating electricity in 2017.\r\n\r\nNcondezi’s power project has a unique advantage over other potential power projects in the region because it is entirely focused on supplying Mozambique’s growing energy demands over the short to medium term, it can be delivered in a reasonably short time frame and the power plant can be scaled up in 300MW units.\r\n\r\nThe 300MW Project is closely aligned to the Mozambican Government’s stated objective of accelerating the electrification of the country and expanding access to electricity. Mozambique is the largest exporter of power to South Africa and yet only 20% of the country is currently electrified. The power plant will help Mozambique maximise the potential of its resources in country and will be an important contributor to Mozambique’s future development.\r\n\r\nNcondezi has submitted its application for a Mining Concession to the Ministry of Mineral Resources of the Republic of Mozambique (“MIREM”).\r\n\r\nPower Framework Agreement\r\nNcondezi has signed a Power Framework Agreement ("PFA") with the Government of Mozambique. The PFA governs the relationship between Ncondezi and the Government during the Development Phase of the Ncondezi Power Project and sets out the agreed pathway and requisite Government and Developer Milestones that need to be reached prior to Project Financial Close for Ncondezi to become eligible for the award of a formal Power Concession.\r\n\r\nThe PFA is, amongst others, a legal pre-requisite to the initiation of exclusive power off-take discussions with potential off-takers, including Electricidade de Mozambique (“EdM”), the state owned power utility company, for the conclusion of a power purchase agreement (“PPA”). Mozambique is one of the largest generators and exporters of electricity in sub-Saharan Africa and is strategically well positioned, with existing transmission infrastructure, to meet the shortfalls in energy supply domestically and in the broader Southern African Power Pool, especially South Africa, Zimbabwe, Botswana, Malawi and Namibia.  The Ncondezi Power Project is targeting power generation in 2017 and through the conclusion of the PFA, the Government has formally undertaken to support Ncondezi as a potential integral contributor to power production in Mozambique and the broader region.\r\n\r\nThe PFA covers the first two phases of the Ncondezi project up to 600MW and stipulates that Ncondezi and the Government shall negotiate in good faith terms and conditions that are mutually acceptable to both parties for any subsequent phases of the Ncondezi Power Project from 600MW up to 1800MW.\r\n\r\nThe PFA will become effective upon the fulfilment, or waiver by Ncondezi in its discretion, of a number of conditions precedent (“CPs”) within 365 days of the PFA’s signature. The CPs include: (i) the conclusion of heads of terms with credible off-takers for all or part the Project’s power generation; (ii) the conclusion of heads of terms with the GoM and applicable government bodies on the local and foreign strategic shareholding in the project; (iii) a commercially bankable tax incentive structure and (iv) transmission arrangements. Ncondezi anticipates meeting all these conditions precedent within the agreed timeframe.  \r\n\r\nRoadmap to Implementation\r\nNcondezi is now proceeding with the implementation of its roadmap to construction and ultimately production in 2017. All work streams are being accelerated with a view to signing a power purchase agreement and commencing project financing in 2014.', 'Thermal', 'Coal', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '600', '150', '540', '85', '120', 'USCPI and Local currency', '34%', '', '', '', 'Quater2', '2017', '', '36', 'baseload', '', '', '', 'yes', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', '12000', '25', '1200', 'Price dependent on terms of PPA and risk allocation, including escalation formulas', 'Combination of USCPI and Local Moz', 'no', 'Predominantly US$ denominated pricing as funding in US$', 'fastQ3-2013-36Month', '', '6', '36', 'Ncondezi Coal Company', 'To be finalised. Currently receiving EPC proposals', 'N/A', 'Under negotiation', 'Partner and EPC & O&M arrangements are currently being negotiated. Project will be structured with credible power partners and service providers. Will be bankability requirement.', '0', '0', '0', 'no', '', '', '', '', 5, 'Local Mozambique investment and shareholding will be accommodated according to Mozambican legislation.', 'no', 'no', 'yes', 'yes', 'no', '', 'no', '6', 'yes', 'yes', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', 'Mining concession being finalized with Mozambican authorities.', 'no', 'Mine development is dependent of Power Project development. Mine development plan is included in overall power plant development plan.', '', '', '', '6', 'project', '', 'yes', 'no', 'no', '', '', '', '6', 'yes', 'finalised', 'yes', 'A number of studies and commercial arrangements are being finalized. The target date for completion is end 2013.', 'Tete, Mozambique', '33', '54', '34', '15', '52', '0', 'yes', 'Owner of Mining concessions 804L and 805L', 'no', 'yes', '', 'yes', '', '31/12/2013', 'yes', '', '31/12/2013', 'All applications will be made as per Mozambican  legislation and International best practice.', '85', '34', '25', '35.42', '16', '25', '58.45', 'Matambo', 'no', '', 'yes', '', 'EdM well aware of project and in agreement with proposed grid integration solution. Ncondezi will fund and build the connection.', 'No transmission works required except for connection to the EdM network. In discussion with EdM to finalize arrangements.', 'Will connect to EdM 220kV network', '24', 'Will be able to wheel up to 225MW through Zimbabwe. Need to adapt transmission solution to enable this arrangement, but can be done.', '0-30', '600', '5.00', 'Real opportunity to provide engineering, and construction services. Extend to be determined once procurement finalized.', '1000', 'TBA', '2013-07-09', '2013-07-12', 'true'),
(117, 313, 'Africary Holdings (Pty) Ltd', '+27824971995', 'Johan Brand', 'Suite 2B Grand Palace', '1', 'Heunis Street', '0', 'Secunda', '2430', 'Johan.Brand@Africary.com', 'Theunissen UCG Project (Phase I)', 'Africary is planning to build a 50-60 MW power generation facility situated between Welkom and Theunissen in the Free State.\r\n\r\nAfricary has acquired the coal rights to the Theunissen coal field (approx 300 sq km) and is proposing to develop underground coal gasification (UCG) as a means of exploiting these coal reserves. AgriCary has acquired the surface rights to the farms strategically located above these reserves. AgriCary will continue with agricultural activities on these farms while providing access to Africary to exploit the coal and process the raw gas from the UCG wells. The syngas will be used to generate electricity using a high efficiency gas turbine (GT).\r\n\r\nThe GT will be small and could fit inside a container, with the ancillary infrastructure consisting of water and power reticulation, a security kiosk, offices and a workshop occupying more space with the steam generator and stack being the most visible items. \r\n\r\nThe personnel complement is estimated at about ten people. The proposed development will include:\r\n -- Underground coal gasification of a roughly 100 ha coal footprint (5 million tons of coal);\r\n -- Infrastructure footprint of about 2 – 3 ha;\r\n -- Infrastructure to include gas cleaning, power generation, waste handling (but not on-site disposal), administration and maintenance; and \r\n -- Approximately thirteen kilometre Eskom distribution line (132 kV) connecting to a substation adjacent to Beatrix Gold Mines; including a water supply line from Sedibeng Water connecting to the supply line close to Beatrix Gold Mines.\r\n\r\nThe coal seams in the project area occur at depths ranging from 320 to 500 metres (m) below the surface and have an average thickness of 3.2 m.  \r\n\r\nUCG is an in-situ gasification process that converts coal deep underground into combustible gas, which is extracted for beneficial use via boreholes. Two boreholes (also referred to as wells) are drilled into the coal seam fairly close to one another. \r\n\r\nAir enriched with oxygen is delivered into the coal seam via one borehole (the injection well) and the coal is ignited in order to start the chemical mining process. The burning front results in high temperatures that cause the coal ahead of the front effectively to release gas. Groundwater, augmented by water added to the air injection borehole if necessary, reacts with the carbon in the coal to form a combustible gas mixture of mainly carbon monoxide (CO), hydrogen (H2) and methane (CH4). \r\n\r\nThe gas mixture is extracted via the second borehole (the production well). UCG can be applied to coal resources that are otherwise unprofitable or technically difficult to extract by traditional mining methods. The gas produced by this method can be used as a chemical feedstock or as fuel for power generation. \r\n\r\nAsh and other remnants of the coal remain underground and gets burried.\r\n\r\nUCG has much lower environmental and safety impacts than traditional coal mining and power generation. This technology eliminates mine safety issues, surface damage, stockpiles of overburden and discard coal, and solid waste discharge like ash dumps, and reduces sulfur dioxide (SO2) nitrogen oxide (NOx) and particulate (PM10) emissions.', 'GasPlant', 'CCGT', 'CoalOther', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Underground coal gasification', '57', '57', '43', '86', '1.28', 'CPI of 6%', '48%', '', '', '', 'Quater2', '2016', '', '30', 'baseload', '', '', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', '1400', '25', '1280', 'The price of R1280 is quoted in 2013 prices and is set to escalate at 6% pa.  \r\n', 'Electricity & water component in PPI as published by Stats SA', 'yes', '', 'fastQ3-2013-36Month', '', '6', '30', 'Africary Holdings (Pty) Ltd', 'Johan Brand (Ex-Sasol UCG Business De