onsultant has been commissioned to advise on transmission capacity requirements for exports.', 'Connection will be through SAPP', '39', 'Connection will be through SAPP', '45-55', '1772', '20.00', 'Some regional sourced materials, e.g. RSA steels and cables', '1000', 'Fabrication works for penstocks and steel structures, inspections and non-destructive testing and laboratory testing', '2013-07-09', '2013-07-12', 'true'),
(122, 255, 'Vukani Empowerment Consultants', '+27815267510', 'Rajko Damjanac', 'IPTV', '24', 'Rotterdam', 'Monte Vista', 'Cape Town', '7460', 'rajko@vect.co.za', 'Tabase ', 'Vukani is the business trust established by the Dywili Community Trust of Tabase Rural Area, and run by the team of proven professional developers engaged on the local, national, and multinational levels. Vukani fights poverty by empowering people to enable them to improve their living conditions on their own, to enhance their influence on institutions and decisions, to make use of their rights, and to bring about changes in structures, and framework conditions.\r\n\r\nVukani has undertaken the task to create extensive development program in order to eradicate poverty within the Tabase rural area creating self-sustainable economy within the boundaries of their traditional land.\r\n\r\nTabase is situated in the service area of King Sabata Dalinyebo Local Municipality, which forms part of the O.R. Tambo District Municipality. There are 18 rural settlements in Tabase, which about 100 000 Xhosa-speaking people call their permanent home. The traditional leader of Tabase is Chaiftainess, Nokhaka Jumba, a Thembu of the Madiba clan. \r\nOn behalf of Tabase rural community, Vukani has prepared long term development plan which will be executed by community members themselves with the help of South African Government Institutions in the line of current Department of Rural Development and Land Reform   (DRDLR) 2011-2014 Strategic Plan, specifically focusing on Comprehensive Rural Development programme (CRDP).\r\n\r\nThe current economic situation within the Tabase is seriously hampered with the lack of infrastructure, as well as necessary knowledge, capacity and capital.\r\nHowever, Tabase Rural Community does live on excess of 40,000 hectares of prime land with moderate climate and abundance of water. The community has made the decision to find the way to utilize and cultivate their land and appointed Vukani Empowerment Consultants to research all available options and opportunities which will initiate sustainable social and economic development and eradicate poverty.\r\nIn the past two years, Vukani has made extensive global research looking for fruitful experience and various marketing opportunities that would initiate investment and productive economic activity in the area.\r\nSo far, with the very limited resources and vast international and local partnerships and connections, Vukani has identified several opportunities that could be implemented within the Tabase Rural Area:\r\nThe immediate opportunity available to Tabase Community is renewable energy production on communal land and sale to Treasury via INEP programme developed by Department of Energy. The current 18 village settlements in Tabase area suffer electricity shortage on a daily basis due to the low current supply from the sparse Eskom network. \r\nThis project is planned with major international consulting agency Mott McDonald PDNA, which brings necessary credentials, as well as project expertize. The outcome would be dual benefit, improved local power supply, as well as, necessary income to Tabase Community, for further development funding.\r\nThe preferable choice for renewable energy production is hybrid wind / solar power generation applicable to local conditions. We have sourced suitable equipment in China that consist number of 5-30 kW medium sized wind turbines that will be positioned around the area and feed power into the existing Eskom distribution network. Apart from wind power generation, photovoltaic solar panels could be installed through village settlements where community members can provide maintenance and safe keeping.\r\nTabase area has moderate wind capacity (according to the closest measuring station No. 10 at Butterworth) of approximately 6.32 m/s @ 60m height. Tabase area is surrounded by hills that are around 900-1000m altitude compared to 600m at Butterworth, so the mean annual wind speed is expected to be higher.\r\n\r\nThe optimum capacity in Tabase area that could feed into Eskom’s distribution network without the major network upgrade is estimated to be 5-10 MW capacity. District city of Umtata is 30km away with requirements for much higher capacity, so the successful outcome of initial Tabase project could be replicated and with some network upgrade feed the city with much higher requirements.\r\n\r\nThe costing and investment return example is set in the following example based on 20 kW wind turbine that could produce 24,300 kWh (worth USD 3,040) annually. The equipment and installation cost of USD 2.00 per watt means that with the current price of USD 0.125 per kWh, repayment for 50% investment (USD 1.00 per watt) would be around 5.5 years. Considering that price of the electricity in South Africa is announced to grow at 65% rate annually over the next 5 years, this period could be shortened to just 4 years.\r\n In order to secure highest bid ranking and government investment portion we have devised further community development plan that could benefit potential investors from China by stimulating trade and export.\r\n \r\nThe agricultural development is the prime long term opportunity for the Community, as there is an excellent opportunity to adopt fully organic production methods and offer produce to the market at the premium price.\r\n\r\nThe proceedings from the intended renewable power project will be directly invested into further local economic development, specifically into organic agricultural  production and marketing.\r\nThis development is planned in several phases, improving current cultivated land and methods by introducing low cost agricultural machinery, such as walk-behind tractors, tillers, planters, lawn movers, compost makers, etc… We have sourced suitable machinery from China, where single family could be equipped with tractor and attachments for the sum of ZAR 50-60K. \r\n\r\nIn conclusion, we believe that combining energy generating equipment from China, subsidized with export incentives of Chinese government would make significant cost performance difference and create in the trade offset real economic empowerment opportunity for Tabase rural community.\r\n ', 'Other', '', '', '', 'Wind Generated Power', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '10', '1', '10', '98', '0.72', '1', '', '', '', '', 'Quater4', '2015', '', '18', 'mid-merit', '12', '365', '24', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', '220', '20', '1250', '', '100', 'yes', '', 'fastQ2-2013-24Month', '', '2', '18', 'Vukani Empowerment Consultants PDNA JV ', 'Qingdao Anhua Eew Energy Company', 'Mott McDonald PDNA', 'Vina International', 'Community involved project in Brazil with 200 MW installed hybrid power and 600 MW ordered for 2014. More details will be provided separately.', '0', '0', '0', 'no', '', '', '', '', 75, 'Vukani is the business trust established by the Dywili Community Trust of Tabase Rural Area, and run by the team of proven professional developers engaged on the local, national, and multinational levels. Vukani fights poverty by empowering people to enable them to improve their living conditions on their own, to enhance their influence on institutions and decisions, to make use of their rights, and to bring about changes in structures, and framework conditions.\r\nVukani has undertaken the task to create extensive development program in order to eradicate poverty within the Tabase rural area creating self-sustainable economy within the boundaries of their traditional land.\r\nTabase is situated in the service area of King Sabata Dalinyebo Local Municipality, which forms part of the O.R. Tambo District Municipality. There are 18 rural settlements in Tabase, which about 100 000 Xhosa-speaking people call their permanent home. The traditional leader of Tabase is Chaiftainess, Nokhaka Jumba, a Thembu of the Madiba clan. \r\n', 'yes', 'no', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', '2', 'yes', 'no', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'yes', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '1', 'project', '', 'no', 'no', 'no', '', '', '', '2', '', 'draft', 'no', 'YES', 'Tabase Mission, KSD District Municiplaity, Eastern Cape', '28', '34', '41', '31', '34', '68', 'yes', 'Dywili Community Property Trust', 'no', 'no', '', 'no', '', '', 'no', '', '', 'Department of Rural Development and Land Reform', '4', '28', '36', '41', '31', '33', '29', 'Kukani', 'no', '', '', '', 'Eskom - to be announced', 'Minor network upgrade expected as the wind farm will be made of large number of small to medium generating units spread along existing power lines covering 42000 hectares and approximately 100,000 population.', 'Existing Eskom Network', '18', 'RSA', '85-100', '220', '100.00', 'Support structure and installation', '450', 'Wind turbine poles and concrete bases will be manufactured locally. Approximately 300 local jobs will be created during installation time and another 40 for maintenance purpose.', '2013-07-09', '2013-07-11', 'true'),
(123, 312, 'Mark Grenning', ' +617 3625 3990', 'Mark Grenning', 'Rio Tinto Coal Mozambique', '24', ' Edificio 24 Avenida 24 de Julho nº 1123-3º, ', 'Maputo', 'Maputo', '3610', 'mark.grenning@riotinto.com', 'Benga Power Project', 'Rio Tinto Coal Mozambique (RTCM) is currently in the project development stage for a coal fired power plant, the Benga Power Plant (BPP), on the Benga Mining Concession in the Tete province in Mozambique.\r\nThe BPP will primarily provide power for export to the SAPP, along with supply to EdM, the Mozambique Government owned energy utility and to Rio Tinto Coal Mozambique’s operations in the Tete region. The BPP will export power into the SAPP via transmission capacity (through Mutambo substation via Songo in northern Mozambique). \r\nThe BPP plan is to be online to produce first commercial production in 2018. It is the potential export power to the SAPP that is relevant to the possible procurement sought under this RFI.\r\n\r\nA brief overview of key project elements are contained below:\r\n1. Fuel supply: The BPP will be located at the mine mouth. RTCM operations will supply the BBP with fuel under a long term supply arrangement.\r\n\r\n2. Land Ownership: The BPP will be situated on the Benga Mining concession.\r\n\r\n3. Grid connection: The BPP will export power into the SAPP via transmission capacity (through Mutambo substation via Songo in northern Mozambique).\r\n\r\n4. Strategic Equity Partner (SEP): A shortlist of two SEPs have been selected. It is expected that a preferred SEP will be selected by the end of 2013\r\n\r\nPlease note that due to the stage of development there are a range of decisions that are yet to be made. These include final configuartion, fuel pricing and project economics including cost of production. As such BPP is unable to fully provide the information called for under this process. Please note that in these cases, ( in order to satisy the electronic submission) a "0" has been entered. This information will not likely be fully available until financial close. Additionally the project is to be developed outside of South Africa so some of the questions relating to development within South Africa are not relevant.\r\n\r\n\r\n', 'Thermal', 'Coal', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '540', '135', '480', '90', '0', '0', '36', '', '', '', 'Quater2', '2018', 'Subject to financial closure', '0', 'baseload', '', '', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', '15000', '25', '0', '', '0', 'yes', '', 'commitQ3-2013-Phased', '', '0', '36', 'RTCM', 'TBD', 'N/A', 'World class strategic equity partners selected but subject to confidentiality at this stage', 'We cannot provide experience relating to international partners at this stage due to confidentiality provisions. Some relevant Rio Tinto experience is outlined below;                                                Rio Tinto has over 4,000MW of generation capacity that it owns and operates wholly or partly covering coal, hydro, gas and diesel plant. The primary purpose of this plant is to supply power to its mining, refining and smelting operations. In some cases it supplies additional power to the local grid or other customers. Some specific examples are set out below;                                                            \r\n                      \r\nRio Tinto Iron Ore – currently implementing a major project to expand its existing power\r\ngeneration network in the Pilbara region of Western Australia. Rio Tinto currently builds, ownsand operates its power system with 285MW generating capacity and will invest capital in powerand fuel supply projects to expand its generating capacity as part of its drive to substantially increase iron ore production capacity. When the expansion is completed, Rio Tinto''s integrated Pilbara power and gas network will be upgraded to approximately 500MW generating system consisting of open and combined cycle gas plant configurations.                                                                                                        \r\nRio Tinto Alcan – in 2010 it commissioned a 160 megawatt gas fired co-generation plant at its Yarwun alumina refinery in Gladstone, Queensland, Australia. The co-generation unit supplies the refinery’s steam and power requirements and also delivers surplus power to the Queensland grid. This power station was a build, own and operate structure.                                                                                                                              \r\n', '220000000000', '260000000000', '160000000000', 'no', '', '', '', '', 1, 'N/A as project to be developed outside of South Africa. There are obligations under Mozambique agreements and legisation on offering equity to Mozambique participants. ', 'no', 'no', 'no', 'no', 'no', '', '', '0', 'yes', 'no', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'yes', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '0', 'project', '', 'yes', 'no', 'no', '', '', '', '0', '', 'draft', 'no', 'Some additional studies will be required but the base supply of fuel will be from an operational mine.', 'Benga , Tete Province', '16', '10', '0', '33', '36', '0', 'yes', 'Provisional registration of a notarial leasehold over the site is secured.Site is part of an existing mine lease which is under mining operation.', 'yes', 'yes', '', 'no', '', '', 'no', '', '', 'Record of decision granted by MICOA (2011) for 2000 MW coal fired plant', '28', '16', '17', '45', '33', '30', '16', 'Matambo Substation (Part of EDM transmission network) near Tete Mozambique', 'no', '', '', '', 'None related to electrical connection for Eskom potential offtake as the power would be supplied at the Zimbawe border. Arrangements with EDM to facilitate such supply are well advanced.', 'No upgrade for  Eskom network as power will be supplied at the Zimbawe border', 'Connecting to EDM grid in Mozambique for onward supply to Eskom at the Mozambique Zimbabwe border under SAPP rules.', '0', 'Formal allocation of transmission capacity for export purposes made by Ministry of Energy (Mozambique) to the Project.', '0-30', '0', '0.00', 'Project to be developed in Mozambique- subject to further consultation - but likely that there will be sourcing of various goods and services from South Africa. ', '0', 'Project to be developed in Mozambique - subject to further consultation', '2013-07-10', '2013-07-12', 'true'),
(124, 340, 'DBSA', '0829014256', 'MIKE MARLER', 'DBSA ', '1258', 'LEVER ROAD', 'HEADWAY HILL', 'MIDRAND', '1685', 'mikem@dbsa.org', 'DBSA PROGRAMME EVALUATION', 'Assisting DoE with evaluation of RFRI submissions', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '2013-07-10', '0000-00-00', ''),
(125, 71, 'XEnOPTA Holdings (Pty) Ltd', '+27 11 678 7188', 'Seth Olivier', 'Building 1', '21', 'Ethel Ave.', 'Northcliff', 'Johannesburg', '2195', 'setho@enopta.net', 'Dedisanova Power station', 'EnOPTA has developed an IPP (Independent Power Producer) solution that consists of a 2 000 MW, Combined cycle base load, Natural Gas fired power plant. The plan is to erect the plant at Coega Port Elizabeth IDZ, giving access to existing grid networks and will alleviate supply pressures in the Eastern Cape.\r\n\r\nEver rising cost of Electricity and Carbon materials are driving Industry beyond their economical tipping point.  The prime objective of this project is to ensure security of supply to current intensive electricity users in the IDZ area and to elevate the ever mounting pressure on ESKOM to produce electricity in the Eastern Cape.\r\n\r\nThe Power plant will go a long way to stabilize the Eastern Cape Grid and afford ESKOM the window to address the current supply shortage. The location of the IPP will reduce electricity supply losses due to long inland transmission lines. Additional base load will enable connection of new Industries in the planned IDZ (Industrial Development Zone). New load connections are currently unavailable, holding up direct investment opportunities into the IDZ. \r\n\r\n. \r\nPROJECT DESCRIPTION \r\n\r\nThe project will supply the inland steel plant  electricity needs of ArcelorMittal South Africa (600MW) (i.e. excluding Saladnha Steel) and the excess electricity (+/-1 421MW) will be made available to industries within the IDZ or sold to Eskom, and/or Municipalities within the Eastern Cape Province, at competitive rates. An MOU has been signed with ArcelorMittal.\r\n\r\n \r\nFUEL SUPPLY \r\n\r\nNatural gas in the form of Compressed Natural Gas (CNG) will be supplied by ship to the port of Saldanha, where it will be offloaded via a submersible pipeline either from a mooring area located off shore or a birthing location in the harbor in Coega. The Natural Gas is compressed on site at the well head, from African supply countries (Angola, Tanzania and Nigeria), and stored in specially designed containers on dedicated ships. The CNG ship will act as the storage facility in port. All technology has successfully undergone full due-diligence by independent third party specialists and demonstrated in practice.\r\n \r\n\r\nPOWER PLANT EQUIPMENT /OPERATIONS / MAINTENANCE\r\n\r\nThe plant will consist of 2 436MW installed capacity, with 2 000MW available on a 24 hour basis. \r\n\r\nThe equipment chosen for the project consists of the following: \r\n\r\n	18 X 115MW brand new GE FRAME 9 PG171-E’s (AT PORT READY FOR SHIPMENT)\r\n\r\n	2 X 183MW completely refurbished with GE Guarantees GE FRAME 9171’s                                                   (at port ready for shipment)\r\n	\r\n\r\nEnOPTA, through its International partnerships brings the expertise to deliver, install, operate and maintain the power plant for the life of the power plant.  The power plant will be fully installed within 18 to 24 months from completion  of the EIA’s and financial closing. (Approximately 36 months from start)', 'GasPlant', 'CCGT', 'other31', '', '', '', '', 'Tri-fuel: LNG, CNG, Fuel oil/diesel', '', '', '', '', '2436', '183', '2020', '85', '0.69', 'Linked to NERSA approved tariff increases to Eskom and a component linked to international gas price (negotiable)', '52.7%', '', '', '', 'Quater2', '2016', 'Assuming 12 months for an EIA. ', '24', 'baseload', '', '', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', '17500', '20', '73', 'Our price is a flat rate per MWh and does not include any wheeling fees. The price per MWh is based off the full off take of plant', 'Linked to NERSA approved tariff increases to Eskom and a component linked to international gas price (negotiable)', 'no', '60% is linked to the USA dollar price of Natural Gas', 'fastQ3-2013-36Month', '', '3', '36', 'International Power Consortium South Africa', 'General Electric via PCS Africa and PCS USA (see below)', 'XEnOPTA Holdings (Pty) Ltd. Trading as EnOPTA', 'Power & Combustion Services Africa Inc.', 'The International Power Consortium South Africa team involved in completing this project have been involved in power plant construction and operations and maintenance for over 60 years. Power & Combustion Services USA division comprises of several international contractors and subcontractors that have design engineered and installed power plants of this size and capacity world wide:(for example):\r\n     •	Millmeran Power project 800MW (Brisbane, Australia)\r\n     •	Redhills Power Generation Facility 440MW (Mississippi, USA)\r\n     •	Baijo Power Project 1 950MW Combined cycle (Mexico)\r\nIncluded in the overall services that Power & Combustion Services provide, comes over 60 years of Operations and Maintenance (O&M) experience where PCS USA division performs O&M for over 60 IPP''s world wide including India, Trinidad, Tobago and the USA:\r\n     •	PEPCO Energy Services 275MW simple cycle HFO (Arlington, Virginia USA)\r\n     •	North American Energy Service 550MW (Washington, DC USA)\r\n     •	National Institute of Health 23MW Cogeneration Facility (Bethesda, MD USA)\r\n     •	GE energy Birchwood power facility 250MW coal (King George, VA USA\r\n     •	International experience includes O&M contracts in Chile, Trinidad, Tobago with facilitating training facilities for O&M contractors in the Philippines. \r\n     •	Experience also includes boiler making for ArcelorMittal USA, Baltimore USA\r\n\r\nThe members of EnOPTA have been involved in large scale energy, IT and maintenance projects in Africa for over 30 years, with combined experience in the following:\r\n     •	Electrical transmission and distribution – AC and DC generation inter-connectors for:\r\n            o	Eskom\r\n            o	Mozambique\r\n            o	Zimbabwe\r\n            o	Zambia\r\n            o	Namibia\r\n            o	Botswana\r\n     •	Electrical generation power systems protection control automation with turn-key design engineering for balance of plant with Siemans:\r\n            o	Majuba\r\n            o	Kendall\r\n            o	Matla\r\n            o	Kariba\r\n            o	Ketse dam distribution substation\r\n     •	Operational management experience in large scale maintenance scheduling and facilities for Pratt & Whitney and Garret turbines.\r\n     •	Management of large IT and on-line banking system implementation projects: e.g.\r\n            o	Natal Building Society – 1974 - 1977\r\n            o	Anglo American Technical Services – 1985 - 1987\r\n     •	Management of large consulting and organisational change projects: e.g.\r\n            o	ISCOR – 1996 - 1998\r\n            o	Transnet – 2006 - 2008\r\n            o	Rand Refinery – 2008 - 2009\r\n     •	Director of Companies\r\n     •	MSc. MBA \r\n     •	Environmental protection services with Government agencies', '1500000000', '1800000000', '1900000000', 'yes', '', '', '', '', 26, 'A fundamental aspect of the project, and part of the agreement with the primary electricity off-taker, is that the project directly provides benefits to the local community of Port Elizabeth.  This will manifest in the following way:\r\n1.	The primary off-taker for the electricity will be the ArcelorMittal South Africa (600MW to be wheeled).   This will immediately reduce the load on ESKOM.\r\n2.	The excess electricity will be available to support economic development of the Coega IDZ, which is currently turning prospective investors away (e.g. smelters) because ESKOM cannot supply the electricity needed.  The 2 000MW plant will have 1 400MW of power available to off-takers in the IDZ at prices equal to or less than Megaflex.\r\n3.	The plant can provide the local municipality with all its needs, also at economic rates.\r\n4.	Local direct job creation during construction, for on-going operation and maintenance, local training.\r\n5.	The SPV that will be established will create an employee share trust through which local employees of the plant and their dependents will benefit directly from the plant profits. This share trust will hold a material share in the SPV.\r\n6.	The investors will be developing a service center that will also provide jobs, training and provide service support on turbines and engines to local industry.\r\n7.     The Community Trust will support training through the provision of bursaries to further technical training and to support the education of children of employees at the plant and of the children of technical training bursary winners.', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', '3', 'yes', 'no', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'yes', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '2', 'project', '', 'no', 'no', 'no', '', '', '', '4', '', 'draft', 'yes', 'Preliminary feasibility studies have been completed, but the following detailed work is outstanding:\r\n1.	Environmental impact assessment \r\n2.	Some geological testing of the site\r\n3.	Confirmation of utilities at site.\r\n4.	Co-operative study with ESKOM of the grid interface and network stabilisation requirements\r\n5.	Studies with the Coega Port Authority regarding gas off-loading both off-shore and at quay.  Location of undersea pipeline from off-shore storage to on-shore storage.\r\n6.	Confirmation of land zoning.\r\n7.	Confirmation of usage of the existing servitude from the plant to the harbour.\r\n8.	Port arrangements for the delivery and off-loading of turbines and heavy equipment\r\n9.	Finalisation of roadway  load capabilities\r\n10.	Gas supply source: finalisation of off-take agreement based on final demand requirements at Saldanha.\r\n11.	Gas shipping: finalisation of shipping contract based on PPA \r\n12.	Gas storage: finalisation of site requirements, regulatory approval.\r\n', 'Coega IDZ, Port Elizabeth (Nelson Mandela Bay), Eastern Cape, South Africa', '25', '41', '29', '33', '47', '17', 'no', '', 'no', 'no', '', 'no', '', '', 'no', '', '', '1.	IPP licence (NERSA) - 3 months\r\n2.	Gas import licence - 3 months\r\n3.	Gas storage approval - 3 months\r\n4.	IDZ registration (investment etc) - 1 month\r\n5.	Agreements with Port Authority - 1 month\r\n6.	Local business trading licences - 1 month\r\n7.     Examine possible amendments to existing ESKOM EIA at Coega (already discussed with ESKOM) to see if this can be used for the plant', '6', '25', '40', '34', '33', '44', '34', 'Dedisa Substation', 'no', '', '', '', 'In January 2013 we met with Divisional Executive (Office of the Chief Executive) Kannan Lakmeeharan and presented the opportunity of providing the country with 2 GW base load power generated from Natural Gas. We were then asked to submit a proposal, which was submitted in February 2013. From there we met again with the Divisional Executives office and were requested to present to Senior Executives on the 8th of April 2013. On the 8th of April 2013 we presented to Senior Executives including Dan Marokane (Group Executive Technology & Commercial). Since then we have had meetings with the Senior Manager Project Development Department in regards to the project development. Discussion included possible use of existing Eskom  EIA at Coega.', 'Not required', 'Eskom', '18', 'N/A', '65-75', '3087', '17.64', 'A service center, consequential industrialization of the Coega IDZ. Example: Manganese smelter can be built.', '3000', 'Opportunities fall into two categories:\r\n1.	Directly associated with the power plant.\r\na.	Local content will be: \r\ni.	civil engineering and construction of site, buildings, roads, utilities\r\nii.	plant infrastructure including piping, wiring, switchgear, transformer rewiring\r\niii.	training centre - to be established as part of the plant (during construction) and then for ongoing training in technical and administrative skills as well as plant management.\r\niv.	increased use of the Port at Coega\r\n2.	Indirect benefits and job creation:\r\na.	Supply of power to IDZ that is not currently available will stimulate local economy and attract local manufacture and beneficiation \r\nb.	Increase use of Port\r\nc.	Broader economic stimulus for the Eastern Cape Economic Development initiative.                                                                                                                                          d.     Community Trust will support training of local people as part of the job creation initiative by proving bursaries for technical training and supporting education of the children of the plant employees and of the bursary winners.           ', '2013-07-10', '2013-07-11', 'true'),
