(127, 294, 'Mooi Hydro (Pty) Ltd', '0828089865', 'Johan van Zyl', 'Profound', '87', 'Ravel Street', 'Mantevrede', 'Vanderbijlpark', '1911', 'johan.vanzyl@prof-eng.co.za', 'Teebus Hydro', '1.	GENERAL\r\nThe Gariep dam in the Eastern Cape supplies water to the Teebus Spruit via a 82km long tunnel exiting between Middelburg and Steynburg. This tunnel is known as the Orange – Fish Tunnel. About 5 km before the tunnel fall out the tunnel control station is situated and is accessible via a small road tunnel to the control valves and the existing small turbine generator set.\r\n\r\nThere are currently a 600kVA small turbine generator set installed in the tunnel. The equipment was however damaged during commissioning and was never made operational.\r\n\r\nCurrently the water flow rate in the tunnel is controlled via a set of control valves and DWAF has permanent employees at the site looking after the valves and the maintenance of these valves. This operation requires 24 hours shift workers to be present as water is continuously released via the tunnel at a rate of up to a maximum of 54m3/s.\r\n\r\n From the flow measurements taken in the tunnel the average water stream flow is 15 cubic metres per second of water with a drop of approximately 90 metres. This equates to a possible average power generation capacity of between 8-10MW. \r\n\r\n2.	CONCEPT PROPOSAL\r\n\r\nThe entire structure was originally designed to allow for the installation of two large hydro powered turbine generator sets. The valves and civil work was done in such a format that the installation of two new turbine generator sets should be fairly easy and not as costly as a new hydro power plant. Normally the bulk of the costs for hydro power plants are vested in the civil works, which has been completed already.\r\nThe Consortium proposes the following Public Private Partnership principles, whereby the Consortium will be responsible for the following:\r\n?	Design, supply, install and commission two 5MW (or sized for the water volume) turbine generators in the tunnel.\r\n?	Finance the above.\r\n?	Operate and maintain the power plant for a period of 20 years \r\n?	Operate and maintain the valve station for a period of 20 years \r\n?	The power so generated is sold either to the Department of Minerals and Energy or Eskom\r\n?	The buyer of the electricity pays the Consortium a unit rate of x cents per kWh generated. The Consortium uses this payment to repay the financing of the project and for the operations and maintenance of the entire facility. Where x cents per kWh will be the selling rate in Rand cent per kWh. Typically at the moment x would be 65 cents / kWh.\r\n?	The Consortium pays DWAF / Eskom (water rights belong to Eskom /  infrastructure belong to DWAF) a Royalty fee of say 1 cent/kWh for the use of the water energy as well as for the use of the tunnel infrastructure.\r\n?	Once the 20 year period expires DWAF may enter into a new contract with the Consortium or with any other party and no monies are due to the Consortium.\r\n?	DWAF guarantees that all water flowing through the Orange Fish Tunnel will be made available to the Teebus Hydro Power JV for power generation.\r\n?	DME guarantees that all electricity so generated will be purchased by either DME or Eskom at the prescribed rate as per the Power Purchase Agreement. \r\n3.	TURBINE / GENERATOR \r\n\r\nHere we propose the use of two Francis Turbines. If you consider the standard efficiency charts it is evident that we should be able to generate approximately 10MW with the available average flow and the head as a result of the intake weir to this point.\r\n\r\nThe existing gate valves installed at the penstock exit points will be tied into the turbine via a short piece of reducing pipe. Part of the scope of work will also be the repair and restoration of the gate valves.\r\n \r\n4.	HIGH VOLTAGE YARD AND SUBSTATION\r\n4.1	Objective\r\nThis section serves to outline the High Voltage electrical requirements including the required electrical reticulation and generation systems.\r\nThis system will be interfaced to and monitored by the main plant control system via an industrial Ethernet communications network.\r\n4.2	Scope\r\nThe HT yard will be situated at ground level just outside the tunnel exit. Two 10MVA two pole synchronous generators will generate at 11kV which will be stepped-up to 66kV at this HT yard.\r\nThe generator will be directly connected to the Low Voltage (L.V.) side of two 10MVA 11/66kV OFAF cooled generator transformers.\r\nThis HT yard will consist of 2 x 11kV Circuit Breakers equipped with the required generator and transformer protection relays. The generator protection will include amongst others current differential, overload, sensitive earth fault, instantaneous over current, over- under-voltage, synchronising check protection and under frequency, the transformer protection will include current differential, over current, earth fault, restricted earth fault, Buchholz and winding temperature monitoring.\r\nTwo out of two voting will be employed in the synchronisation of the generator units to the grid.\r\n5.	TRANSMISSION LINE\r\nA 66kV transmission line of 18km needs to be constructed next to the existing 22kV transmission line. The existing 22kV transmission line does not have the capacity to transfer the full generated power of the power plant to the substation. \r\n6.	INSTRUMENTATION – EQUIPMENT\r\n6.1	Operating & Control Philosophy \r\nMonitoring and operator control of the plant would be from a central control point, with local control stations located at the Turbine-Generators.  Depending on the final selection of equipment, full automatic control of all plant sections will be by means of  PLC’s with possible minor exceptions.\r\n6.2	PLC/SCADA System\r\nThe PLC system selected to provide overall control of the plant is the Siemens S7 PLC or similar utilising two S7-400 processors. One processor will be used for control of the Turbine circuits and the other will be used for the control of the Water circuit and all other plant services. The PLC CPU(s) and engineering station will be located at the main control building instrument equipment room which will be situated on ground level outside the tunnel. \r\n6.3	Turbine-Generator\r\nControl of both the turbine and the generator will be by means of the integrated vendor supplied control systems.  Primary operating and control of the system will be from the vendor supplied operator interface.  The level of monitoring and control that will be provided on the DCS/PLC will depend on the final selection of the turbine-generator.\r\nAll instruments associated with the system will be supplied as part of the vendor package.\r\n', 'Hydro', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '16', '8', '10', '95', '0.64', 'CPI', '', '', 'N/A', '', 'Quater3', '2015', '', '18', 'baseload', '', '', '', 'no', '', 'yes', 'Mooi Hydro has a 1 year PPA with Eskom for a 340kW Hydro Power Plant in Kwazulu Natal. This is NOT at the same site.', 'no', '', '237', '15', '650', '', 'CPI', 'yes', '', 'fastQ2-2013-24Month', '', '2', '18', 'Mooi Hydro (Pty) Ltd', 'Profound Engineering (Pty) Ltd', 'Profound Engineering (Pty) Ltd', 'VA TEC HYDRO (NOT FINAL)', 'Mooi Hydro - Harlestone Project 340kW 2013 (Also refer to Profound Engineering company profile)', '4500000', '0', '0', 'yes', '', '', '', '', 50, 'The consortium believes in the rectification of the injustices of the past. Due to this belief, we will develop local skills from previously disadvantaged communities to operate and maintain the power plant.\r\nWe will also endeavour to procure as much as possible from black enterprises. We do however belief in fair market practices and all tenderers will tender on an equal footing, with preference given to a BEE entity if more than one tender is commercially compatible. One of the key drivers here is also that the sub contractor or supplier must have the necessary skills and quality of products.\r\nDue to the fact that there are no local manufacturers of hydro turbine generator sets, which accounts for approximately 50% of the total project costs, we will not be able to procure the bulk of the equipment from black enterprises.\r\n', 'no', 'no', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'no', '1', 'yes', 'no', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'yes', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '1', 'project', '', 'yes', 'no', 'no', '', '', '', '3', '', 'finalised', 'yes', 'None additional required', 'Middelburg in Eastern Cape', '25', '38', '00', '31', '23', '60', 'no', '', 'no', 'no', '', 'no', '', '', 'no', '', '', 'The issues are as follows: The facility is the property of DWAF and we have had a number of meetings with DWAF who said that they are keen to develop the project. The water rights however belong to Eskom. We have also had a number of meetings and interaction with Eskom, who seems to believe that they will develop the project themselves. We have been trying since 2006 to develop this project without any success. Only government intervention will be able to resove the deadlock between DWAF and Eskom.', '16', '25', '40', '38', '31', '15', '1.9', 'Bulhoek 22kV Substation', 'no', '10/07/2013', '', '', 'Extremely long list of emails and correspondence available.The project was also submitted to the MTPPP in 2008', 'New 66kV line required of 18km. This is priced in.', 'Eskom', '6', 'N/A', '100+', '100', '42.19', 'TRANSMISSION LINE', '40', 'NONE', '2013-07-10', '2013-07-11', 'true'),
(128, 199, 'York Timbers (Pty) Ltd', '0828000099', 'Reinhard Mulder', 'Corporate Office', '3', 'Main Road', 'Sabie', 'Sabie', '1260', 'rmulder@york.co.za', 'York Timbers Cogen Sabie', 'York Timbers (Pty) Ltd (York) is currently in the process of finalising detailed studies, as well as obtaining the necessary approvals, regarding the planned construction of a Cogeneration Plant (Cogen) at its Sabie processing site.  A basic feasibility study, done by externally appointed consultants, has already been completed.  As part of the feasibility study the available fuel from the York processing facilities as well as the plantations surrounding Sabie were determined.\r\n\r\nThe study simulation indicates that the proposed Cogen plant could potentially generate between 20 and 30MW of electricity (depending on final supply agreements) while supplying sufficient thermal energy to all the envisaged processing facilities on site.\r\n\r\nThe existing York Timbers Sabie processing site comprises both the largest sawmill and largest plywood plant in South Africa.  A fundamental part of the York growth strategy, as presented in the York 2012 annual report, will focus around the expansion and development of York Timbers’ Sabie site.\r\n\r\nThe planned upgrade and expansion of the York Sabie site will incorporate three main projects:\r\n•	Upgrade and expansion of the sawmill and plywood plants;\r\n•	A Co-generation plant; and\r\n•	A Value Adding Plant.\r\n\r\nIn order to facilitate the expansion and developments on the York Sabie site work on the project, including the required approvals and licences, started more than two years ago.  In parallel with initial feasibility studies pertaining to the planned expansion and value adding plants, application was made under the Development Facilitation Act (DFA) for the establishment of a land development area to obtain land use rights for the existing industrial activities and proposed expansions.  The DFA process has been completed and approval received for a development area totalling 172.7 ha at the York Sabie site.\r\n\r\nThe required environmental approvals for the Sabie site development, including the construction of the Cogen plant, is under way with final approval of the EIA expected by end October 2013 for the sawmill development and by end April 2014 for the Cogen plant.\r\n\r\nThe site layout is currently being finalised by the appointed Civil engineering contractors.  Planning for the site development is at an advanced stage and breaking of the first ground is expected during the first half of 2014.\r\n\r\nBy integrating the various processing facilities at the Sabie processing site the residues from York’s substantial pine plantations around Sabie, as well as other sources in the Sabie area, can be combined with available Sabie production plant by-products in order to feed the proposed Cogen plant at the Sabie site.\r\n\r\nThe integrated site will also ensure that the energy efficiency of the combined facility will be significantly improved.  Since various functions can be integrated the production costs for the individual processing facilities, including the Cogen plant, will be reduced considerably.\r\n\r\nThe Cogen plant will produce thermal energy which will be utilised by the on-site customers being the sawmill, plywood and value add plants.  Long term off-take agreements will be concluded between the individual plants and the Cogen facility.  Excess energy will be used to produce electrical energy of between 20 and 30 MW (depending on supply agreements in the process of being finalised) with the intention of feeding electricity into the national grid.\r\n\r\nLong term agreements on fuel supply as well as off-take agreements, both for electricity as well as for on-site thermal energy, will ensure project sustainability.\r\n', 'Cogeneration', 'CogenerationBack', 'BiomassExpanded', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '20', '20', '18', '95.8', '1.06', 'CPI', '', '75%', '', '', 'Quater3', '2016', '', '30', 'baseload', '', '', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', '800', '20', '1400', '', '7%', 'yes', '', 'commitQ3-2013-Phased', '', '6', '24', 'York Timbers', 'Bosch Projects/Dieffenbacher/Vyncke/Urbas/Bono Sistemi', 'SAFCOL', 'None', 'Bosch Projects: (1) Umkomaas, South Africa,  (2) Mtibwa, Tanzania                                                      Dieffenbacher: (1) Swedspan, Poland                                                                                                          Vyncke: (1) Batang Berjuntai, Malaysia, (2) Teluk Intan, Malaysia, (3) Angers, France                                                                                                                     Urbas: (1) Bardejov, Slovakia, (2) Klagenfurt, Austria, (3) Klagenfurt, Austria                                                                                                            Bono Sistemi: (1) La Thuile municipality, Italy                                                                    ', '909361000', '959143000', '1112843000', 'no', '', '', '', '', 10, 'Local community will be involved in terms of gathering and delivering plantation biomass to the plant.', 'no', 'no', 'no', 'yes', '', '', '', '6', 'yes', 'no', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'yes', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '6', 'project', '', 'no', 'no', 'no', '', '', '', '6', '', 'draft', 'no', 'Resource studies have been completed by York Timbers as well as SAFCOL. The resource studies indicated that a total of 473 000 ton/year of biomass will sustainable be available for the cogeneration plant. This will consist of on-site processing plant by-product biomass of 298 000 ton/year and plantation biomass of 175 000 ton/year.', 'Sabie, Mpumalanga, South Africa', '30', '45', '01.81', '25', '06', '32.49', 'yes', 'Secured ownership as well as zoning finalised. EIA approval in process - expected final approval by May 2013. Proposed site layout plan attached.', 'no', 'yes', '13/02/2013', 'no', '', '', 'no', '', '', 'Eskom Point of Utility Connection: Preliminary approval September 2013', '0.2', '30', '44', '56.43', '25', '06', '28.58', 'Sabie Substation', 'yes', '15/04/2013', 'no', '', 'Eskom reference number is 91096161                                                                               Meeting with Eskom was held at York Timbers on the 27th of May 2013. The Nelspruit and Central Planning division from Megawatt Park was present.  Attendance register as well as info provided to Eskom by York Timbers attached.       ', 'Existing transmission line will be used', 'Will be connecting to Eskom', '18', 'Project is within South Africa', '65-75', '400', '50.00', 'All civil construction will be performed locally (Civil Engineers have already been appointed: PDNA). Most structural steel will be manufactured locally. A South African contractor will be used for the electrical connection design and installation.', '1000', 'Electrical, structural steel and conveying components will most likely be sourced locally. The substation for the plant will be provided by a South African engineering company.', '2013-07-10', '2013-07-12', 'true'),
(129, 79, 'Cennergi', '0027126756655', 'Wendy Green', 'Block A, Lakefield Office Park', '272', 'West Avenue', 'Centurion', 'Centurion', '0157', 'wendy.green@cennergi.com', 'Maputo Pessoas Energia', 'Maputo Gas Project\r\n1.	Background\r\nIn response to the well- publicised power requirements within the Southern African region, Cennergi has been evaluating various power generation options. As part of this process, key stakeholders have been engaged to understand their requirements and drivers so as to ensure that these form the basis of the design principles of any project. Stakeholders engaged include local utilities, regulators, end users, suppliers, financiers, fuel suppliers, government authorities, industry experts and strategic partners. In broad terms the main requirements and drivers identified with regards to energy supply were:\r\n1.	Timelines to supply;\r\n2.	Cost of supply;\r\n3.	Security of supply;\r\n4.	Flexibility of supply; and\r\n5.	Financibility of supply\r\nBased on these principles a number of projects are at various stages of development within Cennergi. The Project discussed in this submission is considered to be one of the three most advanced projects in the portfolio. All three of these projects are being submitted under separate RFRI responses.\r\n\r\n2.	The Project\r\nThe site for the Project is located within the Beluluane Industrial Park (BIP) in Maputo, Mozambique and was proposed to Cennergi by the government of Mozambique. BIP is a Strategic Economic Zone (SEZ) developed by the Mozambique government with the aim of attracting foreign direct investment (FDI). The Mozal smelter forms part of this complex. The project will be developed as an initial phase of 500MWe comprising five General Electric (GE) LMS100 Aero-derivative turbines in open cycle utilising imported liquefied natural gas (LNG) as fuel source. This will be increased in a number of subsequent ring-fenced phases utilising LMS100’s and GE Frame 9E’s to a total of 3GWe in a combination of open and closed cycle. The LNG will be supplied via a Floating Storage and Regasification Unit (FSRU) provided by Excelerate that will be moored within the Maputo harbour complex in close proximity to the project site. The grid connection point,  the Maputo Substation, is within 1km of the site. This Substation is capable of evacuating approximately 2500MW and connects to South Africa via two 400kV lines. The Project provides a unique solution, whereby a large scale base load capable power station holds significant load following capability without losing efficiency and holding an unparalleled response time of less than 10 minutes to reach full capacity of the mid-merit generation capacity.\r\n\r\n3.	Strategic rationale\r\n•	The site has been selected due to the following:\r\no	Proximity to fuel supply;\r\no	Proximity to grid evacuation point;\r\no	Fast tracked regulatory authorisations;\r\no	Tax and financing benefits to the project that can be passed on to the buyer of the power;\r\no	Existing unmet power demand within the complex; and\r\no	The lack of available power in Mozambique has discouraged FDI. Availability of power within BIP will ensure significant investment.\r\n•	The technology option was selected as a result of:\r\no	High fuel and thermal efficiency;\r\no	Load following capabilities;\r\no	Reliability;\r\no	Speed of deployment; and\r\no	Bankability of technology and supplier.\r\n•	LNG as fuel source:\r\no	Cost of generation;\r\no	Environmental impact;\r\no	Availability; and\r\no	Bankability\r\n•	FSRU as supply option:\r\no	Speed of deployment;\r\no	Impact on tariff price;\r\no	Security of supply; and\r\no	Bankability of supplier.\r\n•	Project size:\r\no	The ultimate size of 3GW is based on current market demand as well as available grid infrastructure to evacuate this power from the site.\r\no	The initial phase of 500MW is based on availability of equipment, project development time lines, bankability of the project as well as fuel supply.\r\no	Subsequent phases are based on availability of equipment, project development timelines, bankability, available fuel supply as well as upgrades to infrastructure.\r\no	The foreseen market for the 3GW:\r\n?	1000MW to Eskom to displace existing supply to Mozal;\r\n?	1000MW to Eskom via existing Motraco system;\r\n?	500MW to Eskom to displace existing supply to Mozambique; and\r\n?	500MW to EdM to meet current unmet demand.\r\n\r\n4.	Key success factors:\r\n•	Short development timelines due to site selection and strategic local partnerships;\r\n•	General Electric as joint development partner leveraging technology, finance and access to fuel supply;\r\n•	The FSRU supplier, Excelerate Energy LLP, currently has 80% of the international market share and is able to provide a turnkey solution on the FSRU, mooring facility as well as gas pipeline to site in the required project timelines;\r\n•	Existing grid infrastructure with the ability to evacuate at least 2.5GW;\r\n•	Strong parent companies and development partners with proven track records in their respective fields;\r\n•	Credible equity through the shareholders of Cennergi;\r\n•	Strong relationships with international gas suppliers;\r\n•	Strong relationships with local and international financiers;\r\n•	Flexibility with regards to:\r\no	Availability and dispatchability of power – can be either peaking, base load or mid-merit with the latter being the preferred option;\r\no	Tariff structures – can either be a blended rate or any combination of capacity charge, energy charge and fuel charge;\r\no	PPA term and structure – options include:\r\n?	10 year fixed tariff (with option to extend);\r\n?	10 year fixed tariff plus 10 years energy and fuel charge (with capital costs amortised over 10 or 20 years);\r\n?	10 – 20 year capacity, energy and fuel charge (with capital costs amortised over 10-20 years)\r\n?	Years 11 – 20 can also be structured as reserve margin charge.\r\no	Gas pricing.\r\n\r\n5.	Gas pricing\r\nGas costs make up the largest component of any gas-fired power station tariff. It is therefore cardinal to ensure that these costs are as predictable and reasonable as possible. A cost estimate has been received from JP Morgan on a 10 year, fixed escalation, Rand based basis using Brent Crude as indexation. This cost is high due to underlying assumptions that have been employed, but will be decreased significantly closer to financial close by addressing the following:\r\n•	Direct engagement with gas owners such as Gazprom and Qatar Petroleum;\r\n•	Using a different indexation;\r\n•	Enhancing the creditworthiness of the project SPV;\r\n•	Government guarantees underpinning the PPA; \r\n•	Inclusion of instruments such as MIGA to underwrite Mozambique risk; and\r\n•	Availability of local gas in the medium to long term.\r\nCennergi is in direct contact with Gazprom, Qatar Petroleum, Sonangol and other LNG owners and will use instruments such as those provided by JP Morgan and others to provide longer term, fixed escalation, Rand based pricing. Dollar based pricing can also be provided to enable the DoE to review various options regarding gas pricing.\r\n\r\nThe tariff quoted in this RFRI assumes a fully hedged ZAR capacity charge and a fully hedged fixed price 10 year LNG supply. Therefore, there exists a significant opportunity to positively impact the tariff through a more aggressive hedging strategy at financial close.\r\n\r\n6.	Project schedule and timelines\r\nCennergi’s planning with regards to the Project is based on the following assumptions:\r\n•	Commence formal engagement with DOE: Q4 2013\r\n•	Signature of PPA and financial close: Q2 2014\r\n•	COD for Phase 1: Q2 2015\r\n\r\nThe first 500MW phase of the project has been designed and scheduled to reach commercial operation date (COD) within 12 months of signature of the PPA and financial close.\r\nThe second phase is based on the same design and will increase the OCGT generation capacity to 1,000MW. This will then provide the main load following capability of the project.\r\nThe subsequent two phases can be constructed as a base load plant in CCGT configuration or as a mid-merit plant with a base load capability. The subsequent two phases are 1,000MW each that will bring the total generation capacity of Pessoas Energia to 3,000MW.\r\nIn summary, the Project is broken down into the following ring fenced phases:\r\n•	Phase 1: OCGT (500MW), Mid-merit\r\no	 Assuming PPA signature and FC  - Q2 2014, \r\no	COD - Q2 2015\r\n•	Phase 2: OCGT (500MW), Mid-merit\r\no	Assuming PPA signature and FC Q3 2014\r\no	COD (Q3 2015, 200MW) & COD 2 (Q4 2015 300MW)\r\n•	Phase 3:\r\no	Base Load (PPA Signature Q3 2014), CCGT (1,080MW), COD Q1 2017; OR\r\no	Mid-merit (PPA Signature Q3 2014), OCGT (1,000MW), COD 1 (Q2 2016, 500MW) & COD 2 (Q3 2016, 500MW)\r\n•	Phase 4:\r\no	Base Load (PPA Signature Q4 2014), CCGT (1,080MW), COD Q4 2017; OR\r\no	Mid-merit (PPA Signature Q4 2014), OCGT (1,000MW), COD 1 (Q4 2016, 500MW) & COD 2 (Q1 2017, 500MW)\r\nCennergi has worked closely with our partners, General Electric and Excelerate Energy LLP to be able to meet these timelines.\r\nGeneral Electric has earmarked five gas turbines in late stages of manufacturing for this project that will enable us to meet the short deadline to commission the generation site. In addition, Excelerate Energy has earmarked an FSRU for this project that is ready to sail. Both GE and Excelerate Energy will commit these items upon signature of the PPA by Q2 2014.\r\n7.	Process going forward\r\nThe various project components have been developed to an advanced stage in anticipation of entering into negotiations with potential buyers. The process now awaits sight of the draft PPA and IA to ensure that the requirements of these two documents are incorporated into the various project agreements. Current planning shows that the necessary agreements will be concluded in 3 months of receipt of the PPA and IA. These agreements include:\r\n•	Fuel supply agreements;\r\n•	EPC contract;\r\n•	O&M agreement;\r\n•	Lease agreement;\r\n•	Finance agreements;\r\n•	Project SPV agreement;\r\n•	Transmission agreement;\r\n•	Generation licence;\r\n•	Grid connection agreement; and\r\n•	Project insurance.\r\n\r\nIn addition the shareholders of Cennergi have already given their in-principle support to the project.\r\n\r\nWe believe that this project has all the ingredients required to deliver credible and reliable power to the buyer at very good value for money. We look forward to your favourable consideration and welcome any queries you may have.', 'GasPlant', 'OCGT', 'LNG', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '515', '103', '500', '52', '0.76', 'SA CPI', '98%', '', '', '', 'Quater2', '2015', 'For this Project, we have worked with our development partners on their manufacturing schedule to ensure delivery of turbines within sufficient time to commission the first 500MW in Q2 2015. This is dependent on signing the PPA by Q2 2014.', '12', 'mid-merit', '12', '6', '15', 'yes', '', 'yes', '135MW Amakhala Emoyeni Wind Farm\r\n95MW Tsitsikama Community Wind Farm', 'no', '', '4809.995', '20', '2430', 'Will need to cover the different options:\r\n1. Energy charge, with contracted hours of operation and a fixed fuel price for 10 years, with a 5 year fixed priced price for the remaining period and tariff adjusted accordingly. 2. Calculations are made based on OCGT configuration and did not take into account later conversion to CCGT.', 'Indexation of fuel will be based upon Brent Crude, however, this will be readjusted once a PPA is provided for negotiations and other sources of LNG can be found.', 'no', 'ZAR and USD', 'fastQ2-2013-12Months', 'This COD is contingent upon signature of the PPA by Q2 2014. ', '2.5', '12', 'Cennergi (Pty) Ltd', 'General Electric, Excelerate Energy LLP and Hyundai Heavy Industries', 'Cennergi (Pty) Ltd', 'General Electric, Excelerate Energy LLP, Grupo Videre', '1. Cennergi (Pty) Ltd: In construction on 234MW of Wind Projects in South Africa.              2. Tata Power 8,527 MW installed capacity (coal, gas, hydro wind and solar).                     3. GE hold 75% of global turbine market for both frame mounted and aeroderivative turbines.                                                                                                                                 4. Excelerate Energy LLP own and operate 11 of the global 14 floating, storage and regasification units in operation globally and operate on four continents.                              5. Grupo Videre are partners and shareholders in the Kuvaninga 40MW gas project.', '0', '0', '0', 'no', '', '', '', '', 19, 'Cennergi is a Joint Venture between Exxaro Resources Limited and The Tata Power Company with a South African BBBEE percentage of 19%. Furthermore, the project will hold a strong percentage of local Mozambican ownership in the project of up to 15% bringing the total local an equivalent local and South African BBBEE percentage up to 34%. Therefore the above proposed BEE percentage above is based upon the South African participation.\r\n\r\n1	Cennergi’s Approach to Economic Development\r\n\r\nCennergi’s vision is to become the leading cleaner energy Independent Power Producer in Southern Africa. Sustainability is a guiding principle at our Company and the goal of value creation remains a key element of our strategy. This strategy advances the needs of the community, employees and customers by creating opportunities within our value chain.\r\n\r\nOur approach is tailored to the needs and economic development policy of each country to meet socio-economic goals. Like South Africa, the procurement policy of Mozambique does permit price preferences to reach certain socio-economic goals. The preferencing system allows for local content while the other elements are similar to the pillars in South Africa’s Broad Based Black Economic Empowerment (B-BBEE) Act:\r\n•	Local content: goods assembled, manufactured and maintained in Mozambique\r\n•	Ownership: persons domiciled or companies incorporated in Mozambique, Mozambiquan manufacturing countries\r\n•	Preferential procurement/Enterprise development: SMME development for small scale industries\r\n•	Socio-economic development: poverty alleviation and employment creation in communal or underdeveloped areas\r\nTo achieve these objectives in South Africa and Mozambique we will use an approach that combines:\r\n•	Targeted Procurement\r\n•	Supplier Development\r\n•	Capacity Building \r\n \r\nThis approach is used to ensure sustainability is built into initiatives to develop community self-reliance by creating local employment and business opportunities. Based on preliminary market analysis the following opportunities will be created for local manufacture in SA with the potential to create 350 jobs:\r\n•	Cables\r\n•	Switchgear/Transformers\r\n•	Pumps (fuel pumps, water, fire etc.)\r\n•	Pipework\r\n•	Labour\r\n•	Large Cranes\r\n•	Logistics from port to site\r\n•	SA engineers\r\n•	Structural Steel Work /Air Intakes/Exhausts.\r\n•	Civil Works excluding the main station\r\nWithin Mozambique opportunities are mainly in civil works. This will focus primarily on the main station build and terracing earth works for the HV substation. This balanced approached by Cennergi to economic development will result in economic progress for both countries. \r\n', 'no', 'no', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'no', '3', 'yes', 'no', 'no', '10/09/2014', 'no', '', 'yes', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '4', 'project', '', 'no', 'no', 'yes', 'no', '', '', '3', '', 'draft', 'yes', 'The resource is sourced from proven production reservoirs within the global LNG market backed by credible and strong suppliers as well as operational LNG train operators. Security of supply is not of a concern to the project and more attention will be paid to price predictability, volume and frequency of deliveries to minimize stock holding costs and transport costs. Cennergi have identified and already initiated this procurement process, however the structure and pricing of the LNG supply agreement is highly dependent upon the structure of the proposed PPA for which the project will be banked on.', 'Beluluane, Maputo, Mozambique', '25', '53', '35.84', '32', '23', '21.06', 'yes', 'The rights to the land have been secured on a 50+50 year lease basis for which Cennergi will hold the full rights of the land. The final terms of the agreement are in advanced stages of negotiation and a draft lease agreement will be submitted to the DOE.', 'no', 'no', '', 'no', '', '', 'no', '09/08/2013', '12/12/2013', '1.	Land: Law 19/97 of October 1st - a DUAT (the Right of Use and Utilization of Land) must be obtained from the Mayor of the Municipal Council or by the District Administrator where there is a Public Services of Land Registration. The applicant of the DUAT must present a plan for use of the land to the Public Services of Land Registration. The right to the entitlement under the DUAT is issued by this office. \r\n2.	Environmental: Law 20/97 of October 7th  - an environmental permit must be obtained in relation to the nature, location and dimension of activities from the Ministry of the Environment (MICOA) through the National Directorate of Environmental Impact Assessment. provided that all legal requirements are met, the permit is issued in a period of 8 days.\r\n3.	PPA Concessions: Decree 42/2005 of November 29th - a contract for the supply of electricity must be submitted to the Council of Ministers for approval provided that the National Council for Electricity (CNELEC) has been heard on the matter. Approval or rejection is given within a period of 30 days. The applicant is required to enter into an agreement of exchange of electricity with the Manager of the National Network of Electricity (EDM) for quantities that exceed any purchase in the contract.\r\n4.	Petroleum: Law 3/2001 of February 21st - a permit is required for petroleum and gas operations whereby such a request must be submitted to the Minister in charge of Petroleum at the National Institute of Petroleum.\r\n5.	Petroleum permit: Minister''s Credential 272/2009 of December 30th - Regulation for Permits of Facilities and Petroleum Activities - An installation permit is required for the construction of petroleum facilities which must be submitted to the Chairperson of the National Institute of Petroleum. The Institute will issue the permit in a period of 10 days. An operations permit must also be obtained which must be addressed to the Chairperson of the National Institute of Petroleum. The Institute will issue the permit in a period of 20 working days.\r\n6.	Electricity: Law 2/97 of October 1st - electrical installations require permits of establishment and use of the facility which are issued by the Ministry of Energy.\r\nIndicative timelines:\r\n1.	Concessions:\r\n    a.	Generation - End of September 2013\r\n    b.	Fuel supply – End of October 2013\r\n2.	Environmental approvals – March 2014\r\n3.	Permitting, licences and authorisations – End of March 2014\r\n    a.	Generation\r\n    b.	Grid connection\r\n    c.	Transmission\r\n    d.	Fuel pipeline\r\n    e.	Mooring facility\r\n    f.	Fuel importation\r\n    g.	Berthing\r\n', '1', '32', '22', '51.57', '25', '53', '41.7', 'Maputo Sub-station', 'no', '10/07/2013', '', '', 'Our team and representatives have engaged with the local utility EdM, as well as the Ministry of Energy whom are in support of the project and connection to the Maputo sub-station. A detailed grid-connection study will commence by the end of Q3 2013 that will finalise all grid-connection requirements with EdM and will form the basis of the grid-connection request. A highlight of some of our meetings, include:•	Mark Sims (22/10/2012) – Discussion introducing the Cennergi Project Portfolio and prioritising of projects with Eskom\r\n•	Mark Sims & Willem Theron (28/11/2012) – Short-lead time and crossborder projects\r\n•	Mark Sims, Willem Theron, Mziyanda Mbuseli & Tino Espinheria – Short-lead time and crossborder projects\r\n•	Mark Sims (07/01/2013) – Short lead time and cross border meeting with a focus on Pessoas Energia and Oryx projects\r\n•	Mark Sims & Willem Theron (11/02/2013) – Meeting with EdM and Nampower to discuss cross border projects and interaction with Eskom in addition to identification of local needs and grid connection\r\n•	Mark Sims & Willem Theron (22/2/2013) – Attendance of SAPP meeting with Eskom\r\n•	6,7/03/2013 – Meeting with EdM focussing on Pessoas Energia Project requirements and final siting for evacuation and demand centre supply, including EdM Transmission, Distribution and EdM Commercial\r\n•	Mark Sims, Willem Theron, Callie Fabricius, Tino Espinheria (25/3/2013) – Update on Cennergi projects and inclusion of Eskom requirements with a focus on project generation sizing and evacuation capacity\r\n•	Mark Sims, Willem Theron, Callie Fabricius, Tino Espinheria, Akash Prakash and Daryl Govender (25/3/2013) - Update on Cennergi projects and inclusion of Eskom requirements into project design with a focus on project generation sizing, despatchability and evacuation capacity\r\n•	Mark Sims & Willem Theron (15/4/2013) - - Update on Cennergi projects and inclusion of Eskom requirements into project design with a focus on project generation sizing, despatchability and evacuation capacity. \r\n', 'No deep connection upgrades are foreseen as the EdM Maputo switchyard currently accommodates loads > 1000MW. It is envisioned for Phase 1 to displace 500MW that is currently brought into Mozambique from South Africa via the Motraco 400kV lines. New transmission feeder bays (with total protection, metering, control, civil and electrical infrastructure) will have to be added to the existing Maputo 400kV busbars to accommodate the termination of the new 1km overhead lines from the GT power plant. The possibility of fault limiting equipment will be considered should the rating be exceeded due to the new generation capacity connected to the grid.', 'The physical grid connection will be to EdM infrstructure', '8', 'Through Cennergi''s engagement with Eskom on this project, the main objective of this project will be to displace international obligations of Eskom to the local demand center in Mozambique, namely Mozal and Maputo. ', '75-85', '480.995', '10.00', 'There will be significant opportunity for South African companies to supply the project, especially as the local market does not have the local infrstructure to provide much of the equipment required for this project. Some fo the equipment that would likely be procured from South Africa, would be: Cables\r\nSwitchgear/Transformers\r\nPumps (fuel pumps, water, fire etc.)\r\nPipework\r\nLabour\r\nLarge Cranes\r\nLogistics from port to site\r\nSA engineers\r\nStructural Steel Work /Air Intakes/Exhausts.\r\nCivil Works\r\n', '500', 'A South African EPC has been engaged to develop this project with the intention of developing skills within Mozambique as well as South Africa with a specific focus of local procurement and employment.', '2013-07-10', '2013-07-12', 'true');
