(134, 353, 'fernando bustos ', '+258823067013', 'fernando bustos', 'JAT 5.1, 8th floor', '833', 'Rua Dos Desportistas', 'Maputo', 'Maputo', '833', 'fernando.bustos@camargocorrea.co', 'HMNK', 'a) Site name and location: Mphanda Nkuwa Hydro Power Plant, in Zambezi River, approx. 70 km downstream of existing Cahora Bassa HPP and approx 60 km from province capital (Tete) in Mozambique. Coordinates hereto attached\r\nb) Generation capacity: 1, 500 MW (1st phase). A 2nd phase with additional 1,125 MW is planned after Cahora Bassa North Bank HPP expansion\r\nc) Grid capacity and network capability: Energy produced by HMNK will be delivered at Cataxa substation of future Mozambique transmission backbone system (STE), approx 30 km from HMNK HPP. Connection from HPP to Cataxa substation will be implemented by HMNK, whereas STE system will be installed by a future SPV to be created by Electricidade de Moçambique (hereinafter EDM) and other shareholders. 1st phase of STE grid planned to have 2, 225 MW capability, sufficient to evacuate HMNK HPP 1, 500 MW 1st phase capacity.\r\n\r\nDescription of Project: A run-of-river HPP to be constructed in Zambezi River, 70 km downstream of the large existing Cahora Bassa HPP. The Project will use water flows released by the operation of turbines and flood spillway at Cahora Bassa HPP. The Project will be developed in two stages: (i) A 1st phase installation comprising Dam, Spillway and Powerhouse to constructed in the dam foot at left bank of river, equipped with 4 units of 375 MW each (1,500 MW installed capacity) designed to use flows released by existing Cahora Bassa South bank HPP and (ii) A 2nd phase underground Powerhouse to be constructed in right bank of river, equipped with 3 units of 375 MW each (1,125 MW installed capacity) for mid-merit dispatching, to be implemented after the construction and operation of upstream Cahora Bassa HPP North bank expansion and downstream re-regulating dam in Boroma HPP. \r\n\r\nThe annual energy generation at the 1st phase installed capacity will be 8,600 GWh/yr. After construction of Cahora Bassa HPP North bank extension, additional water flows released by the new turbines there will allow the Project 2nd phase to increase annual generation to 9,540 GWh/yr.\r\n\r\nThe Project 1st phase was studied in the Feasibility report made in 2002 by a Consortium of Lahmeyer International, Electricite de France (EDF) and Knight Piesold. HMNK revised feasibility level design to achieve between FEL 2 and FEL 3 FIDIC’s level and a pre-conceptual reference design was prepared for supporting an EPC proposal, including required additional geological drillings and river bathymetric studies.\r\n\r\nHMNK received Project’s Authorization and special Fiscal Package from Government of Mozambique (GoM) in August 2010 and signed the Project Concession Agreement in December 2010. The Project’s concession term is 35 years counted from Commercial Operation Date (COD) of 1st generating unit of 1st phase. The Concession Agreement includes a provision of possible renewal of concession term for additional 15 years. The Project’s Environmental Impact Assessment (EIA) Study was completed and environmental study was approved by GoM by end December 2011.\r\n\r\nDESCRIPTION	1ST PHASE	2ND PHASE\r\nDAM	 	 \r\nType	CCR	(*)\r\nLength (m)	700	(*)\r\nMaximum height (m)	90	(*)\r\nSPILLWAY	 	 \r\nType	Surface	(*)\r\nNumber of segment gates	13	(*)\r\nDesign flow (cu.m/s)	33,000	(*)\r\nRESERVOIR	 	 \r\nUseful volume (cu.km)	2.5	(*)\r\nNormal WL (m)	207	(*)\r\nArea (sq.km)	100	(*)\r\nWATER INTAKE	 	 \r\nType	 Compact	 Compact\r\nPOWERHOUSE	 	 \r\nType	Sheltered  	Underground\r\nINSTALLED CAPACITY (MW)	1,500	1,125\r\nFinal	 	2,625\r\n375 MW GENERATING UNITS	 	 \r\nType	Francis	Francis\r\nNumber	4	3\r\nFinal	 	7\r\nNET FIRM GENERATION (GWh/year)	7,290	70\r\nFinal	 	7,360\r\nNET AVERAGE GENERATION (GWh/year)	8,592	940\r\nFinal	 	9,532\r\n\r\nExpected project cost: At December 2012 price level, the Project’s CAPEX is USD 3.4MM, without Interest during Construction and Financing costs. ', 'Hydro', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '1500', '375', '849', '60', '0', '0', '', '', 'to be defined ', '', 'Quater4', '2019', 'at the moment definition of COD is dependent on conclusion of PPA and Financial Close, which is expected to be July 2015', '52', 'mid-merit', '12', '30', '24', 'yes', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', '34000', '35', '900', 'transmission tariff ', 'USD CPI plus exchange variation from USD to Rands ', 'no', 'price in USD, or in Rands with indexation in USD CPI', 'commitQ3-2013-Phased', '', '12', '52', 'Hidroelectrica de Mphanda Nkuwa (HMNK)', 'hydro', 'no', 'camargo correa', 'Camargo Correa is one of world’s leading experts in developing and constructing Hydro Power Plants. Since the 1950’s, in Brazil and Latin America, Camargo Correa has been responsible for construction and operation of 7% of world’s total installed capacity of HPP’s. A list of Camargo Correa relevant HPPs in operation is shown in below:\r\nHPP NAME	COUNTRY	CAPACITY MW	YEAR COD\r\nIN OPERATION\r\nLimoeiro	Brazil	80	1955\r\nJupia	Brazil	1344	1967\r\nItauba	Brazil	500	1972\r\nGuri	Venezuela	10000	1978\r\nIlha Solteira	Brazil	3200	1982\r\nSalto Santiago	Brazil	1320	1983\r\nItaipu	Brazil/Paraguai	14000	1984\r\nTucurui	Brazil	8300	1984\r\nPorto Primavera	Brazil	2200	1997\r\nSerra da Mesa	Brazil	1200	1998\r\nMachadinho	Brazil	1140	2002\r\nBarra Grande	Brazil	690	2005\r\nCampos Novos	Brazil	880	2006\r\nSalto Pilao	Brazil	224	2008\r\nPorce III	Colombia	844	2009\r\nFoz do Chapeco	Brazil	855	2010\r\nSerra do Facao	Brazil	220	2011\r\nDEVELOPED AND/OR UNDER CONSTRUCTION\r\nEstreito	Brazil	1087	2012\r\nJirau	Brazil	3450	2012\r\nBelo Monte	Brazil	11333	2015\r\nMphanda Nkuwa	Mozambique	2625	2019\r\nMaraba	Brazil	2300	2018\r\nTapajos Complex	Brazil	12600	2018\r\nAs can be seen from above, Camargo Correa was responsible for the construction of 17 HPPs already in operation, with a total capacity of 47 GW. In a