(140, 210, 'Destiny Corporation Energy', '+27118024036', 'Edwin Kikonyogo', '1st Floor, Building 16, The Woodlands Office Park', '20', 'Woodlands Drive (Cnr. Kelvin Drive)', 'Woodmead', 'Johannesburg', '2191', 'edwin@destinycorporation.co.za', 'Komatipoort Waste Heat Recovery', 'Destiny Corporation Energy ("Destiny") has proposed to ROMPCO, the owner of the natural gas pipeline that pipes natural gas between Mozambique and South Africa, as well as to strategic partners, Sasol Limited and CEF Group SOC Limited, that Destiny develop, own and operate a waste heat recovery facility, located at ROMPCO''s Komatipoort pipeline compressor station. This facility will recover waste heat from the turbines currently operating at there, and utilise this to generate 4MW of electricity for transmission onto the South African grid', 'Other', '', '', '', 'Organic Rankine Cycle technology', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '4', '3.5', '3.5', '91', '0.75', 'CPI', '37', '', '', '', 'Quater1', '2015', 'Only outstanding item is PPA with Department of Energy as sole off-taker', '12', 'mid-merit', '12', '30', '24', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', '120', '20', '95', '', 'CPI-linked tariff escalation', 'yes', '', 'fastQ2-2013-24Month', '', '2 ', '12', 'Destiny Corporation Energy (Pty) Ltd', 'Ormat Technologies Inc', 'Destiny Corporation Energy', 'Destiny Corporation Energy', 'This will be the first pipeline compression waste heat recovery project in South Africa. Ormat Technologies, the international technology partner, that will also deliver the EPC and Operations & Maintenance solutions, has 575 MW of ORC-technology installations. The Destiny-ORMAT team will be working together with Environment & Process Solutions, who have a number of waste heat recovery projects to their credit, as well as with Sasol''s internal engineers. Sasol operates & manages the ROMPCO compressor station in Komatipoort.', '0', '0', '0', 'yes', '', '', '', '', 69, 'Economic: Does the project contribute to national economic development?\r\nYes, the project activity has a robust economic dimension addressing the following in terms of national economic development:\r\n• The project will generate employment both during construction (estimated 200 temporary positions) and operation (estimated 5 permanent positions). The majority of these positions will be filled from the local community of the Komatipoort area.\r\n• All of the shares in the project are directly owned by South African entities and therefore will provide financial returns to these parties.\r\n• There are no existing projects using the envisaged technology in South Africa and the project will provide an opportunity for technological interaction and knowledge transfer to local citizens.\r\n?????2. Social: Does the project contribute to social development in South Africa?\r\nYes, the project will contribute significantly to the social upliftment and development of the people of South Africa and particularly in the project area, through the following:\r\n• Through the creation of jobs both temporary and permanent, most of which will be from the local communities, the project activity will contribute to alleviation of poverty in the project area.\r\n• Because there are no similar technology installations in the area, the local people will require education and training in the operation and maintenance of the plant. This will enhance information sharing and skills transfer from foreign parties to the local community.\r\n• There will be stimulus of local small and medium sized business, as a result of the sub-contracting and procurement requirements of the project \r\n• The creation of jobs, together with the wider impact of poverty alleviation will create a distribution of wealth within the local communities, with a direct and measurable improvement of health and quality of life for citizens of the local community\r\n?????3. Environmental: Does the project conform to the National Environmental Management Act principles of sustainable development?\r\nThe project activity will take place on an existing industrial site, on unused open land within the greater plant operation covered by the original EIA. Therefore:\r\n?????i) That the disturbance of ecosystems and loss of biological diversity are avoided, or where they cannot be avoided, are minimised and remedied\r\n??????There will be no disturbance of any ecosystem or loss of biodiversity through the project activity. The selected site is on the existing industrial property between existing operational units with no active ecosystem or biodiversity constraints.\r\n????ii) That pollution and degradation of the environment are avoided, or where they cannot be altogether avoided, are minimised and remedied\r\n????By reducing fossil fuel based electricity emissions from the turbines operating in the ROMPCO facility, and reducing electricity drawn from or generated by the national grid, the project activity will have a positive impact on pollution by lowering national CO2 emission levels. Therefore, there will be no pollution or degradation of the environment through the project activity.\r\n????iii) That the disturbance of landscapes and sites that constitute the nation’s cultural heritage is avoided, or where it cannot be altogether avoided, is minimised and remedied\r\n????There will be no disturbance of landscapes and sites that constitute the nation’s cultural heritage through the project activity as the selected site is within the boundary of the existing IFM industrial complex.\r\n????iv) That waste is avoided, or where it cannot be altogether avoided, minimised and reused or recycled where possible and otherwise disposed of in a responsible manner\r\n????The project activity will not generate any operating waste. There will not even be inert building rubble will be generated during construction, which is normal for this type of project. From a power generation perspective, the project is fundamentally about the re-use and recycling of existing waste energy streams.\r\n????v) That the use and exploitation of non- renewable resources is responsible and equitable, and takes into account the consequences of the depletion of the resource\r\n?The project activity will not consume or exploit non-renewable resources. By generating waste-heat based electricity, the project will have a positive impact on the use of non-renewable resources by replacing fossil fuel based generation capacity.\r\n?????vi) That the development, use and exploitation of renewable resources is responsible and equitable, and takes into account the consequences of the depletion of the resource.\r\n???The electricity generated by the project is based on a waste heat stream from the turbines at ROMPCO. Therefore the project activity by\r\ndefinition will not consume or exploit renewable resources but rather a waste source.\r\n?????vii) That a risk averse and cautious approach is applied, which takes into account the limits of current knowledge about the consequences of decisions and actions\r\n???Prior to construction the project activity will be scrutinized and monitored by the EIA consultants used by ROMPCO and SASOL for the overall plant development. \r\n?????vii) That negative impacts on the environment and on people’s environmental rights be anticipated and prevented, and where they cannot be altogether prevented, are minimised and remedied. the project activity will have a positive impact on the environment by lowering national CO2 emission levels. Therefore, there will be no negative impacts on the environment and on people’s environmental rights through the project activity.', 'no', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'no', '', 'no', '6', 'yes', 'no', 'yes', '15/01/2015', 'no', '', 'yes', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '4', 'corporate', '', 'yes', 'yes', 'no', '', '', '', '3', '', 'finalised', 'yes', 'Sasol, as operator of the ROMPCO facility, and the Destiny Corporation team have been engaged over the last 8 months in detailed analysis, feasibility, risk assessment & mitigation and modelling. All this work has been completed, and a presentation made to the Board of Directors of ROMPCO. A final yes / no decision is expected by the end of August 2013. If positive, then project development will commence with the goal being to reach financial close within 6 months of that decision. After financial close, Construction and development is expected to commence relatively immediately', 'ROMPCO Compressor Station, Komatipoort, Mpumalanga, South Africa', '31', '56', '09.98', '25', '26', '59.19', 'yes', 'Should the provide receive approval from ROMPCO, the company will enter into a land access and usage agreement for the project', 'no', 'no', '', 'no', '', '', 'no', '', '', 'NERSA Generating Licence for Destiny Corporation Energy on this site - estimated 90 days process', '0.6', '31', '56', '09.08', '25', '27', '02.82', 'Komatipoort substation', 'no', '', '', '', 'None yet', 'None - SASOL / ROMPCO have an existing transformer and other transmission infrastructure that is already connected to the Eskom grid network. This will be able to comfortably the proposed 4MW additional capacity', 'Eskom', '6', 'Host country is South Africa', '75-85', '36', '30.00', 'There will be a relatively significant (30% estimated) amount of local procurement spend, typically on engineering and construction related activities. Bearing in mind Destiny Corporation Energy''s 400MW pipeline of waste heat opportunities, the opportunity for the creation of a technology / supplier hub in South Africa, underpinned by experienced contractors who have worked with Destiny on these projects, is immense. When one considers the potential for project development across Africa, and what this means to South Africa''s exports position, one begins to appreciate the opportunities this project presents for local manufacturers.', '120', 'Destiny has established an energy engineering technical services division, that within the next 5 years, will have secured the transfer of all the necessary intellectual property, skills and relevant experience required for Destiny''s personnel (primarily South Africans) to operate and maintain all its energy facilities. In addition, Destiny will use its purchasing power with original equipment manufacturers, and its relationship, to secure the manufacture in South Africa, of an increasing percentage of components for its facilities. Over time, these could serve as the foundation for a Southern Africa hub of technological excellence in energy plant manufacturing', '2013-07-10', '2013-07-12', 'true'),
(142, 360, 'Sasol', '0761050675', 'Craig', 'sdfgrsag', '453798', 'adjtaryt', 'adhate', 'ajareth', '2005', 'mika.hajjar@gmail.com', 'Sasolburg', 'aetjuaetjarj64udshsa', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '2013-07-10', '0000-00-00', ''),
(144, 79, 'Cennergi (Pty) Ltd', '0027126756655', 'Wendy Green', 'Building A, Lakefield Office Park', '272', 'West Avenue', 'Centurion', 'Centurion', '0157', 'wendy.green@cennergi.com', 'Namibia - Oryx 120', 'NOTE: This is an HFO project and the submission was requested by the DOE in our meeting dated 4 July 2013.\r\n\r\n\r\nOryx120 HFO Project\r\n1.	Background\r\nIn response to the well- publicised power requirements within the Southern African region, Cennergi has been evaluating various power generation options. As part of this process, key stakeholders have been engaged to understand their requirements and drivers so as to ensure that these form the basis of the design principles of any project. Stakeholders engaged include local utilities, regulators, end users, suppliers, financiers, fuel suppliers, government authorities, industry experts and strategic partners. In broad terms the main requirements and drivers identified with regards to energy supply were:\r\n1.	Timelines to supply;\r\n2.	Cost of supply;\r\n3.	Security of supply;\r\n4.	Flexibility of supply; and\r\n5.	Financibility of supply\r\nBased on these principles a number of projects are at various stages of development within Cennergi. The project discussed in this submission is considered to be one of the three most advanced projects in the portfolio. All three of these projects are being submitted under separate RFRI responses.\r\n\r\n2.	The project\r\nThe site for the project is located at Nonidas in Namibia and was proposed to Cennergi by the local Namibian developers. The site is strategically located in close proximity to the national grid as well as other infrastructure and includes a railway siding on site. The project will utilise 120MW Wartsilla and Sulzer diesel generator sets currently available within the Tata Power portfolio utilising heavy fuel oil (HFO) as fuel source. The HFO will be supplied via rail and road from the port of Walvisbay in close proximity to the site. The nearest grid connection point able to evacuate the project is 4km from the site. The project will make use of corporate finance structures to enable early delivery of power at acceptable costs. \r\n\r\n3.	Strategic rationale\r\n•	The site has been selected due to the following:\r\no	Proximity and access to fuel supply;\r\no	Proximity to grid evacuation point; and\r\no	Fast tracked regulatory authorisations.\r\n•	The technology option was selected as a result of:\r\no	High fuel and thermal efficiency;\r\no	Load following capabilities;\r\no	Ability to finance on a corporate finance basis;\r\no	Reliability; and\r\no	Speed of deployment.\r\n•	HFO as fuel source:\r\no	Cost of generation;\r\no	Availability; and\r\no	Bankability\r\n•	Project size:\r\no	The ultimate size of 120MW is based on the current disclosed shortfall in Namibia as shared with Cennergi by Nampower, available grid infrastructure to evacuate this power from the site as well as equipment availability. In addition this is also NamPower’s requirement for reserve margin when Kudu comes online.\r\n\r\n4.	Key success factors:\r\n•	Short development timelines due to site selection, strategic local partnerships, availability of equipment and corporate finance structure;\r\n•	Tata Power as joint development partner leveraging technology, finance and access to fuel supply;\r\n•	Existing grid infrastructure with the ability to evacuate 120MW;\r\n•	Strong parent companies and development partners with proven track records in their respective fields;\r\n•	Credible equity through the shareholders of Cennergi;\r\n•	Strong relationships with international fuel suppliers;\r\n•	Flexibility with regards to:\r\no	Availability and dispatchability of power – can be either peaking, base load or mid-merit with the peaking being the preferred option;\r\no	Tariff structures – can either be a blended rate or any combination of capacity charge, energy charge and fuel charge;\r\no	PPA term and structure – options include:\r\n?	10 year fixed tariff (with option to extend);\r\n?	10 year fixed tariff plus 10 years energy and fuel charge (with capital costs amortised over 10 or 20 years);\r\n?	10 – 20 year capacity, energy and fuel charge (with capital costs amortised over 10-20 years)\r\n?	Years 11 – 20 can also be structured as reserve margin charge.\r\n\r\n5.	HFO pricing\r\nFuel costs make up the largest component of any tariff.  It is therefore critical to ensure that these are as predictable and reasonable as possible. A cost estimate has been received from Engen Namibia. \r\n\r\n6.	Project schedule and timelines\r\nCennergi’s planning with regards to the project is based on the following assumptions:\r\n•	Commence formal engagement with DOE: Q4 2013\r\n•	Signature of PPA: Q4 2013\r\n•	COD: Q3 2014\r\n\r\n7.	Process going forward\r\nThe various project components have been developed to an advanced stage in anticipation of entering into negotiations with potential buyers. The process now awaits sight of the draft PPA and IA to ensure that the requirements of these two documents are incorporated into the various project agreements. Current planning shows that the necessary agreements will be concluded in 3 months of receipt of the PPA and IA. These agreements include:\r\n•	Fuel supply agreements;\r\n•	EPC contract;\r\n•	O&M agreement;\r\n•	Lease agreement;\r\n•	Finance agreements;\r\n•	Project SPV agreement;\r\n•	Transmission agreement;\r\n•	Generation licence;\r\n•	Grid connection agreement; and\r\n•	Project insurance.\r\n\r\nIn addition the shareholders of Cennergi have already given their in-principle support to the project.\r\n\r\nWe believe that this project has all the ingredients required to deliver credible and reliable power to the buyer at very good value for money. We look forward to your favourable consideration and welcome any queries you may have.\r\n', 'Reciprocating', 'Diesel', 'LiquidFuelOther', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'HFO', '', '', '120', '16', '112', '61', '0.60', 'SA CPI', '98%', '', '', '', 'Quater3', '2014', 'This is a configuration we will be delivering to site within the next few months for installation on the back of an executed PPA.', '11', 'mid-merit', '12', '6', '16', 'no', '', 'yes', '135MW Amakhala Emoyeni Wind Farm\r\n95MW Tsitsikama Community Wind Farm', 'no', '', '360', '20', '1800', 'tbd', 'tbd', 'yes', '', 'fastQ2-2013-12Months', '', '4', '11', 'Cennergi (Pty) Ltd', 'Tata Power', 'Cennergi (Pty) Ltd', 'Tata Power and Tata Consulting Engineers', 'This is a current Tata Power plant that will be re-deployed. 1. Cennergi (Pty) Ltd: In construction on 234MW of Wind Projects in South Africa. 2. Tata Power 8,527 MW installed capacity (coal, gas, hydro wind and solar).', '0', '0', '0', 'no', '', '', '', '', 19, 'Cenenrgi is a Joint Venture between Exxaro Resources Limited and The Tata Power Company with a BBBEE percentage of 19%. Furthermore, the project will hold a strong percentage of local ownership in the project of up to 15% bringing the totale local and BBBEE percentage up to 34%. 1	Cennergi’s Approach to Economic Development Cennergi’s vision is to become the leading cleaner energy Independent Power Producer in Southern Africa. Sustainability is a guiding principle at our Company and the goal of value creation remains a key element of our strategy. This strategy advances the needs of the community, employees and customers by creating opportunities within our value chain. Our approach is tailored to the needs and economic development policy of each country to meet socio-economic goals. Like South Africa, the procurement policy of Namibia does permit price preferences to reach certain socio-economic goals. The preferencing system allows for local content while the other elements are similar to the pillars in South Africa’s Broad Based Black Economic Empowerment (B-BBEE) Act: •	Local content: goods assembled, manufactured and maintained in Nambia •	Ownership: persons domiciled or companies incorporated in Namibia, Namibian manufacturing countries •	Preferential procurement/Enterprise development: SMME development for small scale industries •	Socio-economic development: poverty alleviation and employment creation in communal or underdeveloped areas To achieve these objectives in South Africa and Namibia we will use an approach that combines: •	Targeted Procurement •	Supplier Development •	Capacity Building This approach is used to ensure sustainability is built into initiatives to develop community self-reliance by creating local employment and business opportunities. Based on preliminary market analysis the following opportunities will be created for local manufacture in SA with the potential to create 350 jobs: •	Cables •	Switchgear/Transformers •	Pumps (fuel pumps, water, fire etc.) •	Pipework •	Labour •	Large Cranes •	Logistics from port to site •	SA engineers •	Structural Steel Work /Air Intakes/Exhausts. •	Civil Works excluding the main station Within Namibia opportunities are mainly in civil works. This will focus primarily on the main station build and terracing earth works for the HV substation. This balanced approached by Cennergi to economic development will result in economic progress for both countries.', 'no', 'no', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'no', '5', 'yes', 'no', 'yes', '20/06/2014', 'no', '', 'yes', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '4', 'corporate', '', 'no', 'no', 'no', '', '', '', '5', '', 'draft', 'yes', 'HFO is an internationally traded commodity, of which there is sufficient supply for the project from local suppliers. This has been secured through a preliminary procurement process.', 'Nonidas, Swakopmund, Namibia', '14', '43', '26.47', '22', '37', '55.52', 'yes', 'The site is owned by Gecko and is already zoned for industrial activities. Cennergi has included in the supporting documentation a Single Line Diagram, Proposed Site Plan, proposed Grid Connection Single Line Diagram. In addition, we have included a site plan and single line diagram from an independent consultant. ', 'no', 'no', '', 'no', '', '', 'no', '', '', 'Number	Permit and Legislation	Applicable requirements	Relevant Authority\r\n1.	Environmental Clearance \r\n(Environmental Management Act (Act No. 7 of 2007 & the Namibia’s Environmental Assessment Policy of 2007)	•	The erection or construction of facilities for the commercial generation of electricity with an output of more than one megawatt;\r\n•	The erection or construction of facilities for the commercial transmission and supply of electricity with the exception of power supply lines of less than 2 kilometres in length;\r\n•	The erection, construction or upgrading of manufacturing, storage, handling or processing facilities for any hazardous substance, including transportation routes, structures and facilities connected therewith, and for the purpose of this clause “hazardous substance” means any substance declared as hazardous substance in terms of section 3(1) of the hazardous substances ordinance, 1974 (Ordinance no. 14 of 1974), or in terms of any other law relating to the control of hazardous substances;\r\n•	The erection and construction of sewage treatment plants and associated infrastructure;\r\n•	The erection and construction of waste sites, including any facility for the final disposal or treatment of waste;\r\n•	The construction of oil, water, gas and petrochemical and other bulk supply pipelines.\r\n•	The rezoning of land from agricultural use to industrial use;\r\n•	Any activity entailing a scheduled process referred to in the atmospheric pollution prevention ordinance, 1976 (Ordinance no. 11 of 1976).\r\n	Ministry of Environment and Tourism: Directorate Environmental Affairs (MET:DEA)\r\n\r\n2.	Electricity Generation Licence\r\n(Electricity Act (Act No. 2 of 2000)	For the installations for the generation, transformation, transmission and distribution of electrical energy	The Electricity Control Board (ECB)\r\n3.	Traffic Permit	•	Approval for the modifications to the traffic crossing.\r\n•	An application for principal approval of the access road. \r\n\r\n•	Approval for the crossing of any railway line	Roads Authority and TransNamib. \r\n\r\n4.	Heritage Permit	•	Clearance must be obtained from the National Heritage Council for the project construction prior to construction commencing.	National Heritage Council\r\n5.	Water Permit\r\n(Water Resources Management Act (2004) and Regulation for Waste Water (2010)\r\n	•	Permits will be required to construct a waste water treatment works, to abstract water (should this be considered in the future), and to drill boreholes	Water Authority\r\n', '10', '14', '43', '26.47', '22', '9', '26.5', 'Loop-in-out to the local Nampower 220kV line', 'no', '', '', '', 'A meeting with the DOE was held on 4 July 2013 at which a request was made for this project to be submitted in this RFRI process.•	Mark Sims (22/10/2012) – Discussion introducing the Cennergi Project Portfolio and prioritising of projects with Eskom\r\n•	Mark Sims & Willem Theron (28/11/2012) – Short-lead time and crossborder projects\r\n•	Mark Sims, Willem Theron, Mziyanda Mbuseli & Tino Espinheria – Short-lead time and crossborder projects\r\n•	Mark Sims (07/01/2013) – Short lead time and cross border meeting with a focus on Pessoas Energia and Oryx projects\r\n•	Mark Sims & Willem Theron (11/02/2013) – Meeting with EdM and Nampower to discuss cross border projects and interaction with Eskom in addition to identification of local needs and grid connection\r\n•	Mark Sims & Willem Theron (22/2/2013) – Attendance of SAPP meeting with Eskom\r\n•	6,7/03/2013 – Meeting with EdM focussing on Pessoas Energia Project requirements and final siting for evacuation and demand centre supply, including EdM Transmission, Distribution and EdM Commercial\r\n•	Mark Sims, Willem Theron, Callie Fabricius, Tino Espinheria (25/3/2013) – Update on Cennergi projects and inclusion of Eskom requirements with a focus on project generation sizing and evacuation capacity\r\n•	Mark Sims, Willem Theron, Callie Fabricius, Tino Espinheria, Akash Prakash and Daryl Govender (25/3/2013) - Update on Cennergi projects and inclusion of Eskom requirements into project design with a focus on project generation sizing, despatchability and evacuation capacity\r\n•	Mark Sims & Willem Theron (15/4/2013) - - Update on Cennergi projects and inclusion of Eskom requirements into project design with a focus on project generation sizing, despatchability and evacuation capacity. \r\n', 'No deep connection upgrades are foreseen as the indications suggest that the existing Nampower 220kV network can accommodate an additional 120MW as is. A new 220kV transmission line of 10km will be required which will be T’d into the existing Nampower 220kV ring between the Walmund and Rossing switchyards. The switchyard at the power plant will be designed in a loop-in loop-out configuration with two outgoing overhead lines terminating at the T-in point.', 'The physical grid connection will be on Nampower infrastructure.', '11', 'Current discussions are with Nampower to provide power to Nampower and therefore this would offset the existing supply obligation of South Africa/Eskom.', '75-85', '36', '10.00', 'Cenenrgi is a Joint Venture between Exxaro Resources Limited and The Tata Power Company with a BBBEE percentage of 19%. Furthermore, the project will hold a strong percentage of local ownership in the project of up to 15% bringing the totale local and BBBEE percentage up to 34%. 1	Cennergi’s Approach to Economic Development Cennergi’s vision is to become the leading cleaner energy Independent Power Producer in Southern Africa. Sustainability is a guiding principle at our Company and the goal of value creation remains a key element of our strategy. This strategy advances the needs of the community, employees and customers by creating opportunities within our value chain. Our approach is tailored to the needs and economic development policy of each country to meet socio-economic goals. Like South Africa, the procurement policy of Namibia does permit price preferences to reach certain socio-economic goals. The preferencing system allows for local content while the other elements are similar to the pillars in South Africa’s Broad Based Black Economic Empowerment (B-BBEE) Act: •	Local content: goods assembled, manufactured and maintained in Nambia •	Ownership: persons domiciled or companies incorporated in Namibia, Namibian manufacturing countries •	Preferential procurement/Enterprise development: SMME development for small scale industries •	Socio-economic development: poverty alleviation and employment creation in communal or underdeveloped areas To achieve these objectives in South Africa and Namibia we will use an approach that combines: •	Targeted Procurement •	Supplier Development •	Capacity Building This approach is used to ensure sustainability is built into initiatives to develop community self-reliance by creating local employment and business opportunities. Based on preliminary market analysis the following opportunities will be created for local manufacture in SA with the potential to create 350 jobs: •	Cables •	Switchgear/Transformers •	Pumps (fuel pumps, water, fire etc.) •	Pipework •	Labour •	Large Cranes •	Logistics from port to site •	SA engineers •	Structural Steel Work /Air Intakes/Exhausts. •	Civil Works excluding the main station Within Namibia opportunities are mainly in civil works. This will focus primarily on the main station build and terracing earth works for the HV substation. This balanced approached by Cennergi to economic development will result in economic progress for both countries.', '120', 'There will be some requirement for components from South Africa, based on what is not available within Namibia.', '2013-07-10', '2013-07-12', 'true');
