(145, 79, 'Cennergi (Pty) Ltd', '00276756655', 'Wendy Green', 'Building A, Lakefield Office Park', '272', 'West Avenue', 'Centurion', 'Centurion', '0157', 'wendy.green@cennergi.com', 'Namibia - Oryx 600', 'Oryx600 Gas Project\r\n1.	Background\r\nIn response to the well- publicised power requirements within the Southern African region, Cennergi has been evaluating various power generation options. As part of this process, key stakeholders have been engaged to understand their requirements and drivers so as to ensure that these form the basis of the design principles of any project. Stakeholders engaged include local utilities, regulators, end users, suppliers, financiers, fuel suppliers, government authorities, industry experts and strategic partners. In broad terms the main requirements and drivers identified with regards to energy supply were:\r\n1.	Timelines to supply;\r\n2.	Cost of supply;\r\n3.	Security of supply;\r\n4.	Flexibility of supply; and\r\n5.	Financibility of supply\r\nBased on these principles a number of projects are at various stages of development within Cennergi. The project discussed in this submission is considered to be one of the three most advanced projects in the portfolio. All three these projects are being submitted under separate RFRI responses.\r\n\r\n2.	The project\r\nThe site for the project is located within the Vision Industrial Park (VIP) 15km north of Swakopmund, Namibia and was proposed to Cennergi by the local Namibian partners. VIP has received official support from the Namibian parliament for the development of a port and industrial park. This includes the development of a power generation facility. The project will be developed as a 600MWe comprising six General Electric (GE) LMS100 Aero-derivative turbines in open cycle utilising imported liquefied natural gas (LNG) as fuel source. The LNG will be supplied via a floating storage and regasification unit (FSRU) provided by Excelerate Energy LLP that will be moored within the VIP harbour complex in close proximity to the project site. The project will connect into the existing Trejkopje 275kV network. \r\n\r\n3.	Strategic rationale\r\n•	The site has been selected due to the following:\r\no	Proximity to fuel supply;\r\no	Proximity to grid evacuation point;\r\no	Fast tracked regulatory authorisations; and\r\no	Existing unmet power demand within the complex.\r\n•	The technology option was selected as a result of:\r\no	High fuel and thermal efficiency;\r\no	Load following capabilities;\r\no	Reliability;\r\no	Speed of deployment; and\r\no	Bankability of technology and supplier.\r\n•	LNG as fuel source:\r\no	Cost of generation;\r\no	Environmental impact;\r\no	Availability; and\r\no	Bankability\r\n•	FSRU as supply option:\r\no	Speed of deployment;\r\no	Impact on tariff price;\r\no	Security of supply; and\r\no	Bankability of supplier.\r\n•	Project size:\r\no	The 600MW is based on current market demand, available grid infrastructure to evacuate this power from the site, availability of equipment, project development time lines, bankability of the project as well as fuel supply.\r\n\r\n4.	Key success factors:\r\n•	Short development timelines due to site selection and strategic local partnerships;\r\n•	General Electric as joint development partner leveraging technology, finance and access to fuel supply;\r\n•	The FSRU supplier, Excelerate Energy LLP, currently has 80% of the international market share and is able to provide a turnkey solution on the FSRU, mooring facility as well as gas pipeline to site in the required project timelines;\r\n•	Existing grid infrastructure;\r\n•	Strong parent companies and development partners with proven track records in their respective fields;\r\n•	Credible equity through the shareholders of Cennergi;\r\n•	Strong relationships with international gas suppliers;\r\n•	Strong relationships with local and international financiers;\r\n•	Flexibility with regards to:\r\no	Availability and dispatchability of power – can be either peaking, base load or mid-merit with the latter being the preferred option;\r\no	Tariff structures – can either be a blended rate or any combination of capacity charge, energy charge and fuel charge;\r\no	PPA term and structure – options include:\r\n?	10 year fixed tariff (with option to extend);\r\n?	10 year fixed tariff plus 10 years energy and fuel charge (with capital costs amortised over 10 or 20 years);\r\n?	10 – 20 year capacity, energy and fuel charge (with capital costs amortised over 10-20 years)\r\n?	Years 11 – 20 can also be structured as reserve margin charge.\r\no	Gas pricing.\r\n\r\n5.	Gas pricing\r\nGas costs make up the largest component of any tariff. It is therefore cardinal to ensure that these are as predictable and reasonable as possible. A cost estimated has been received from JP Morgan on a 10 year, Rand based, fixed escalation basis using Brent Crude as indexation. This cost is high due to underlying assumptions used, but will decreased significantly closer to financial close through addressing the following:\r\n•	Direct engagement with gas owners such as Gazprom and Qatar Petroleum;\r\n•	Using a different indexation;\r\n•	Enhancing the creditworthiness of the project SPV;\r\n•	Government guarantees underpinning the PPA; and\r\n•	Availability of local gas in the medium to long term.\r\nCennergi is in direct contact with Gazprom, Qatar Petroleum, Sonangol and other LNG owners and will use instruments such as those provided by JP Morgan and others to provide longer term, fixed escalation, Rand based pricing. Dollar based pricing can also be provided to enable the DoE to review various options regarding gas pricing.\r\n\r\n6.	Project schedule and timelines\r\nCennergi’s planning with regards to the project is based on the following assumptions:\r\n•	Commence formal engagement: Q4 2013\r\n•	Signature of PPA and financial close: Q2 2014\r\n•	COD: Q3 2019\r\n\r\nCennergi has worked closely with our partners, General Electric and Excelerate Energy LLP to be able to meet these timelines.\r\n7.	Process going forward\r\nThe various project components have been developed to an advanced stage in anticipation of entering into negotiations with potential buyers. The process now awaits sight of the draft PPA and IA to ensure that the requirements of these two documents are incorporated into the various project agreements. Current planning shows that the necessary agreements will be concluded in 3 months of receipt of the PPA and IA. These agreements include:\r\n•	Fuel supply agreements;\r\n•	EPV contract;\r\n•	O&M agreement;\r\n•	Lease agreement;\r\n•	Finance agreements;\r\n•	Project SPV agreement;\r\n•	Transmission agreement;\r\n•	Generation licence;\r\n•	Grid connection agreement; and\r\n•	Project insurance.\r\n\r\nIn addition the shareholders of Cennergi have already given their in-principle support to the project.\r\n\r\nWe believe that this project has all the ingredients required to deliver credible and reliable power to the buyer at very good value for money. We look forward to your favourable consideration and welcome any queries you may have.\r\n', 'GasPlant', 'OCGT', 'LNG', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '618', '103', '575', '92', '780', 'SA CPI', '98%', '', '', '', 'Quater3', '2019', 'The project will be built with the development of the Vision Industrial Park Port 25 km north of Swakopmund. Supporting documentation for the port, including the parliamentary approval for the development of the port and associated power station approval.', '36', 'baseload', '', '', '', 'no', '', 'yes', '135MW Amakhala Emoyeni Wind Farm\r\n95MW Tsitsikama Wind Farm', 'no', '', '4809.995', '20', '2430', '', 'SA CPI', 'no', 'Price quoted is fully ZAR and assumes exposure is fully hedged. Therefore, the price would need to be broken down into ZAR, NAM$ and USD', 'fastQ3-2013-36Month', '', '6', '30', 'Cennergi (Pty) Ltd and Gecko', 'General Electric, Excelerate Energy (Pty) Ltd', 'Cennergi (Pty) Ltd', 'General Electric, Gecko and the Hangala Group', ' This is a current Tata Power plant that will be re-deployed. 1. Cennergi (Pty) Ltd: In construction on 234MW of Wind Projects in South Africa. 2. Tata Power 8,527 MW installed capacity (coal, gas, hydro wind and solar). 3. GE hold 75% of global turbine market for both frame mounted and aeroderivative turbines. 4. Excelerate Energy LLP own and operate 11 of the global 14 floating, storage and regasification units in operation globally and operate on four continents..', '0', '0', '0', 'no', '', '', '', '', 19, 'Cennergi is a Joint Venture between Exxaro Resources Limited and The Tata Power Company with a South African BBBEE percentage of 19%. Furthermore, the project will hold a strong percentage of local Namibian ownership in the project of up to 15% bringing the total local an equivalent local and South African BBBEE percentage up to 34%. Therefore the above proposed BEE percentage above is based upon the South African participation.\r\n\r\n1	Cennergi’s Approach to Economic Development\r\n\r\nCennergi’s vision is to become the leading cleaner energy Independent Power Producer in Southern Africa. Sustainability is a guiding principle at our Company and the goal of value creation remains a key element of our strategy. This strategy advances the needs of the community, employees and customers by creating opportunities within our value chain.\r\n\r\nOur approach is tailored to the needs and economic development policy of each country to meet socio-economic goals. Like South Africa, the procurement policy of Namibia does permit price preferences to reach certain socio-economic goals. The preferencing system allows for local content while the other elements are similar to the pillars in South Africa’s Broad Based Black Economic Empowerment (B-BBEE) Act:\r\n•	Local content: goods assembled, manufactured and maintained in Namibia\r\n•	Ownership: persons domiciled or companies incorporated in Namibia, Mozambiquan manufacturing countries\r\n•	Preferential procurement/Enterprise development: SMME development for small scale industries\r\n•	Socio-economic development: poverty alleviation and employment creation in communal or underdeveloped areas\r\nTo achieve these objectives in South Africa and Namibia we will use an approach that combines:\r\n•	Targeted Procurement\r\n•	Supplier Development\r\n•	Capacity Building \r\n \r\nThis approach is used to ensure sustainability is built into initiatives to develop community self-reliance by creating local employment and business opportunities. Based on preliminary market analysis the following opportunities will be created for local manufacture in SA with the potential to create 350 jobs:\r\n•	Cables\r\n•	Switchgear/Transformers\r\n•	Pumps (fuel pumps, water, fire etc.)\r\n•	Pipework\r\n•	Labour\r\n•	Large Cranes\r\n•	Logistics from port to site\r\n•	SA engineers\r\n•	Structural Steel Work /Air Intakes/Exhausts.\r\n•	Civil Works excluding the main station\r\nWithin Namibian opportunities are mainly in civil works. This will focus primarily on the main station build and terracing earth works for the HV substation. This balanced approached by Cennergi to economic development will result in economic progress for both countries.', 'no', 'no', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'no', '5', 'yes', 'no', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'yes', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '5', 'project', '', 'no', 'no', 'no', '', '', '', '5', '', 'draft', 'yes', 'The resource is sourced from proven production reservoirs within the global LNG market backed by credible and strong suppliers as well as operational LNG train operators. Security of supply is not of a concern to the project and more attention will be paid to price predictability, volume and frequency of deliveries to minimize stock holding costs and transport costs', 'Swakopmund, Namibia', '14', '48', '35.13', '22', '9', '26.5', 'yes', 'The site is owned by Gecko Namibia, the development partner and forms a part of the Vision Industrial park under the development by Gecko Namibia. Cennergi has included in the supporting documentation a Single Line Diagram, Proposed Site Plan, proposed Grid Connection Single Line Diagram. In addition, we have included a site plan and single line diagram from an independent consultant.', 'no', 'no', '', 'no', '', '', 'no', '', '', 'Number	Permit and Legislation	Applicable requirements	Relevant Authority 1.	Environmental Clearance (Environmental Management Act (Act No. 7 of 2007 & the Namibia’s Environmental Assessment Policy of 2007)	•	The erection or construction of facilities for the commercial generation of electricity with an output of more than one megawatt; •	The erection or construction of facilities for the commercial transmission and supply of electricity with the exception of power supply lines of less than 2 kilometres in length; •	The erection, construction or upgrading of manufacturing, storage, handling or processing facilities for any hazardous substance, including transportation routes, structures and facilities connected therewith, and for the purpose of this clause “hazardous substance” means any substance declared as hazardous substance in terms of section 3(1) of the hazardous substances ordinance, 1974 (Ordinance no. 14 of 1974), or in terms of any other law relating to the control of hazardous substances; • The erection and construction of sewage treatment plants and associated infrastructure; •	The erection and construction of waste sites, including any facility for the final disposal or treatment of waste; •	The construction of oil, water, gas and petrochemical and other bulk supply pipelines. •	The rezoning of land from agricultural use to industrial use; •	Any activity entailing a scheduled process referred to in the atmospheric pollution prevention ordinance, 1976 (Ordinance no. 11 of 1976). Ministry of Environment and Tourism: Directorate Environmental Affairs (MET:DEA) 2.	Electricity Generation Licence (Electricity Act (Act No. 2 of 2000)	For the installations for the generation, transformation, transmission and distribution of electrical energy	The Electricity Control Board (ECB) 3.	Traffic Permit	•	Approval for the modifications to the traffic crossing. •	An application for principal approval of the access road. •	Approval for the crossing of any railway line	Roads Authority and TransNamib. 4.	Heritage Permit	•	Clearance must be obtained from the National Heritage Council for the project construction prior to construction commencing.	National Heritage Council 5.	Water Permit (Water Resources Management Act (2004) and Regulation for Waste Water (2010) •	Permits will be required to construct a waste water treatment works, to abstract water (should this be considered in the future), and to drill boreholes	Water Authority', '50', '14', '43', '35.13', '22', '9', '26.5', 'A loop into a 220KV transmission line to the Trekopje 220kV switchyard', 'no', '', '', '', 'Nampower have been engaged with on this project, of which strong interest has been received. Cennergi have engaged with the Managing Director, CEO, head of trade, head of commercial and head of technical. All of which have provided support to the project. In Eskom, we met with: •	Mark Sims (22/10/2012) – Discussion introducing the Cennergi Project Portfolio and prioritising of projects with Eskom\r\n•	Mark Sims & Willem Theron (28/11/2012) – Short-lead time and crossborder projects\r\n•	Mark Sims, Willem Theron, Mziyanda Mbuseli & Tino Espinheria – Short-lead time and crossborder projects\r\n•	Mark Sims (07/01/2013) – Short lead time and cross border meeting with a focus on Pessoas Energia and Oryx projects\r\n•	Mark Sims & Willem Theron (11/02/2013) – Meeting with EdM and Nampower to discuss cross border projects and interaction with Eskom in addition to identification of local needs and grid connection\r\n•	Mark Sims & Willem Theron (22/2/2013) – Attendance of SAPP meeting with Eskom\r\n•	6,7/03/2013 – Meeting with EdM focussing on Pessoas Energia Project requirements and final siting for evacuation and demand centre supply, including EdM Transmission, Distribution and EdM Commercial\r\n•	Mark Sims, Willem Theron, Callie Fabricius, Tino Espinheria (25/3/2013) – Update on Cennergi projects and inclusion of Eskom requirements with a focus on project generation sizing and evacuation capacity\r\n•	Mark Sims, Willem Theron, Callie Fabricius, Tino Espinheria, Akash Prakash and Daryl Govender (25/3/2013) - Update on Cennergi projects and inclusion of Eskom requirements into project design with a focus on project generation sizing, despatchability and evacuation capacity\r\n•	Mark Sims & Willem Theron (15/4/2013) - - Update on Cennergi projects and inclusion of Eskom requirements into project design with a focus on project generation sizing, despatchability and evacuation capacity. \r\n', 'It is anticipated that a new double circuit transmission overhead line will be required from the power plant site spanning 50km to the most applicable Nampower transmission switchyard i.e. Trekopje 220kV switchyard. It is foreseen that a new 220kV busbar arrangement and all associated auxiliaries will be required to accommodate the power injection at this switchyard. Additionally, new feeder bays will have to be constructed at Trekopje to terminate the overhead lines. Depending on the future loading at the new Vision 500 site and at Trekopje, it may be required to upgrade the transmission infrastructure further upstream of Trekopje. ', 'The physical grid connection will be on Nampower infrastructure.', '24', 'Transmission agreement will be enterred into with Nampower for this project. Cennergi will apply for membership of SAPP with respect to the requirements of a wheeling agreement.', '75-85', '480.9995', '10.00', 'There will be significant opportunity for South African companies to supply the project, especially as the local market does not have the local infrstructure to provide much of the equipment required for this project. Some fo the equipment that would likely be procured from South Africa, would be: Cables\r\nSwitchgear/Transformers\r\nPumps (fuel pumps, water, fire etc.)\r\nPipework\r\nLabour\r\nLarge Cranes\r\nLogistics from port to site\r\nSA engineers\r\nStructural Steel Work /Air Intakes/Exhausts.\r\nCivil Works\r\n', '500', 'A South African EPC has been engaged to develop this project with the intention of developing skills within Namibia as well as South Africa with a specific focus of local procurement and employment.', '2013-07-10', '2013-07-12', 'true'),
(146, 345, 'Hernic Ferrochrome (Pty) Ltd', '+27 12 381 1292', 'Kenichiro Tauchi', 'Hernic', '103', 'R/E of Portion 103', 'Brits', 'Brits', '0250', 'ken@hernic.co.za', 'Hernic Integrated Clean Energy Project', 'Project Background\r\nHernic Ferrochrome (Pty) Ltd (Hernic) is the world’s fourth largest ferrochrome producer in terms of smelting capacity and operates two chrome mines and four furnaces at its Brits works in North-West Province of South Africa. As an energy-intensive business, Hernic consumes approximately 200MW of electrical power.\r\n\r\nIn response to steep and sustained electricity tariff increases and security of electricity supply concerns, Hernic is exploring the development of a power co-generation project (the Hernic Integrated Clean Energy (ICE) Project) that will be fueled by the combustible waste gas from its smelting process.  It is anticipated that the power from this project will either be designated for "own use" and meet approximately 10 to 15 percent of Hernic’s current electrical power requirements, or alternatively be sold to the grid if acceptable off-take terms are obtained.\r\n\r\nIn addition, consideration is being given to carbon emissions reduction by replacing electricity drawn from the national grid, with an anticipated net reduction in CO2 emissions of approximately 180,000 tCO2e/annum.\r\n\r\nPower Plant Description\r\nThe ICE project will utilise the waste gas generated by the furnaces as a fuel for internal combustion engines that will drive generators. The primary combustible gas elements comprise carbon monoxide (CO) and hydrogen (H2), which are currently flared to atmosphere.\r\n\r\nThe ICE project will broadly entail the provision of the following facilities that will be integrated into the existing furnace infrastructure:\r\n•	Gas take-off 	– 	Diverting waste gas destined for flaring\r\n•	Gas conditioning 	– 	Cleaning the diverted waste gas\r\n•	Gas boosting 	– 	Increasing the gas pressure to required levels\r\n•	Power plant 	– 	Using the cleaned waste gas as fuel to generate electricity\r\n•	Reticulation 	– 	Feeding the generated power into the Hernic power grid\r\n\r\nTechnology Selection and Plant Sizing\r\nIn selecting the most appropriate technology various options were considered. This included gas turbines, steam boiler and turbine and internal combustion engines.\r\n\r\nSpark ignited internal combustion gas engines were ultimately selected as the optimum generation technology for the Hernic ICE plant. The key reasons for this include:\r\n•	Higher tolerance for varying gas quality than gas turbines\r\n•	Higher thermal (conversion) efficiency than boiler and steam turbine\r\n•	Modular and “off-the-shelf” components\r\n•	Ability to scale the power plant capacity up and/or down to match gas supply\r\n•	Proven track record in waste gas power generation\r\n\r\nGeneral Electric (GE) Jenbacher was selected as preferred engine technology supplier based on their proven track record with ferro-alloy waste gas application. The GEJ620 GS-E53 engine was selected to match typical gas parameters prevalent in the ferro-alloy industry as well as site specific results for carbon monoxide and hydrogen composition obtained from extensive waste gas analysis and testing undertaken.\r\n\r\nBased on the volumes and composition of the waste gas, a battery of 15 engines (each rated at 1.7MW) was selected as the optimal plant configuration, delivering an overall installed capacity of 25.5MW and projected energy production of approximately 170 GWh per annum. \r\n\r\nKey Cost Drivers\r\nThe primary cost drivers for the power co-generation plant include the capital costs for the internal combustion engines and the operating and maintenance (O&M) costs. Fuel costs are not significant, given that this is waste gas that is presently flared.\r\n\r\nEnvironmental Approvals\r\nHernic and its consultants have undertaken applicable environmental compliance work to cover:\r\n•	Environmental Authorisation(s) (EA)\r\n•	Air emissions licencing (AEL)\r\n\r\nNERSA Licensing\r\nThe application for exemption of a generating licence was submitted to NERSA in January 2012 with a view to registering the ICE project on the NERSA database as well as to request exemption from a generating licence. The motivation for an exemption is based on the fact that Hernic will not export energy to a third party via the Eskom grid, but that all generated power will be consumed by Hernic. A formal response was received from NERSA giving Hernic exemption from requiring a generation licence.  \r\n\r\nNERSA licensing requirements will be reviewed if necessitated by changes in the Electricity Regulation Second Amendment Bill and/or if required in order to sell to the grid under the IPP procurement process. \r\n\r\nProject Status\r\nA full project feasibility study has been completed including engineering design and project capital cost estimate for plant, equipment and construction  - base dated January 2013. \r\n\r\nHernic is exploring alternative ownership and funding options to advance the project.', 'Cogeneration', 'CogenerationReciprocating', 'other32', 'Gas', '', '', 'GE Jenbacher reciprocating gas engines fueled by furnace waste gas (predominantly carbon monoxide and hydrogen)', '', '', '', '', '', '25.5', '1.7 ', '23.2', '84', '0.75', 'To be agreed', '', '37%', '', '', 'Quater2', '2015', '', '15', 'baseload', '', '', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', '600', '15', '750', '', 'To be determined', 'yes', 'EURO for capex and O&M contract', 'fastQ3-2013-36Month', 'Q3/4 2013 Fast Track Process with participant to provide commitment guarantees, and COD in 18 months or less from signature of PPA', '6', '15', 'Hernic Ferrochrome (Pty) Ltd', 'AAP Carbon, GE Jenbacher, Outotech', 'N/A', 'Potential international partnership under consideration', 'GE Jenbacher engines successfully deployed in similar application by AAP Carbon at International Ferro Metals Limited', '2500000000', '2700000000', '2900000000', 'no', '', '', '', '', 15, 'Hernic Ferrochrome  Is in compliant to Mining Carter (MC) as a mining company with 15% BEE partnership and other MC requirements. The company also committed to achieve 26% BEE partnership including ESOPs and community trusts by end of April 2014 in accordance with MC deadline.', 'no', 'no', 'yes', 'yes', 'no', '', 'no', '6', 'yes', 'no', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'yes', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '6', 'corporate', '', 'yes', 'no', 'no', '', '', '', '6', '', 'finalised', 'yes', 'All key studies have been completed', 'Brits, North West Province', '25', '39', '38', '27', '50', '42', 'yes', 'Site presently owned by Developer (Hernic Ferrochrome)', 'yes', 'yes', '01/01/2013', 'no', '', '', 'no', '', '', 'NERSA Licensing\r\nThe application for exemption of a generating licence was submitted to NERSA in January 2012 with a view to registering the ICE project on the NERSA database as well as to request exemption from a generating licence. This motivation for an exemption was based on the fact that Hernic would not export energy to a third party via the Eskom grid, but that all generated power would be consumed by Hernic. A formal response was received from NERSA giving Hernic exemption from requiring a generation licence.  \r\n\r\nNERSA licensing requirements will be reviewed if necessitated by changes in the Electricity Regulation Second Amendment Bill and/or if required in order to sell to the grid under the IPP procurement process. ', '0', '25', '39', '34', '27', '50', '42', 'Dinaledi', 'yes', '11/04/2012', 'yes', 'Letter attached', 'Various meetings held - coordinated by the "Regional Customer Executive, Eskom Northern Region"', 'None anticipated ', 'Eskom', '6', 'N/A', '40-45', '300', '50.00', 'To be determined', '20', 'To be determined', '2013-07-10', '2013-07-12', 'true'),
(147, 361, 'Cape Advanced Engineering (Pty) Ltd', '+27 82 775 1001', 'Andrew Taylor', 'CAE, Atlantis Foundries Business Park', '1', 'corner of Neil Hare Rd. and William Gourlay St.', 'Atlantis', 'Cape Town', '7441', 'andrewtaylor@cae.co.za', 'Bio-Gas Peaking Power Generation', 'In response to the REFIT programme, between 2003 and 2011, Cape Advanced Engineering (Pty) Ltd constructed 5 anaerobic bio-digesters at large scale commercial piggeries and a large scale commercial dairy and animal feeds manufacturer.  These bio-digesters currently currently produce bio-gas at a rate adequate to generate 1.5 MW electric continuously (base load).  Bio-gas is only produced from the animal manure at these intensive farming operations, and this animal waste feed stock supply that generates the bio-gas is sustained throughout the year.  These renewable power generation projects have been developed to sell power under the REFIT programme within Joint Venture agreements with the respective host farms.  Following the disbanding of REFIT only two engines (0.35 MW) were installed and most of the bio-gas is currently being vented or flared instead of being used to generate renewable electricity.  Such vented bio-gas potentially releases 50 000 tons of greenhouse gas emission per year.\r\n\r\nCAE manufactures bio-gas power generation plants in South Africa with locally developed and locally built bio-gas engines - 22 litre, V12 electronically controlled spark-ignition engines.  The technology has been verified from 2009 to 2012 in grid embedded and island mode operation in Limpopo with the knowledge and oversight of Eskom.  If allowed to generate, these bio-gas power generation plants have high local content (>70%) and create numerous sustained local job opportunities (>50).\r\n\r\nFor this RFRI, Cape Advanced Engineering (Pty) Ltd, proposes to supply peak power on demand by installing bio-gas storage and three times as much generation capacity as the average daily bio-gas production capacity, so as to be able to generate peak power for 8 hours per day.  In base load operation, the projects described above - using these locally developed and built engines - are feasible at the indexed REFIT tariff for bio-gas (IRR=15%).  Relative to base load operation, peaking operation requires three times the number of engines to be installed, thus the cost of peak demand power is higher than the REFIT tariff - the engines are operated at times of peak demand, which translates to 8 hours per day.\r\n\r\nGiven the critical shortage of power at peak times, CAE proposes to build and operate these bio-gas power generation plants as peaking plants.  The plants have already been built with the capacity to store gas for at least 24 hours per day, and CAE can install enough generator engines to consume the accumulated gas over whatever portion of the day is appropriate for national peak demand management.  \r\n\r\nThis submission is based on peak generation for 8 hours per day at 300% of the base-load capacity of the bio-digesters for 365 days of the year - this is determined by the constant daily volume of bio-gas production. ', 'Reciprocating', 'Gas', 'other33', '', '', '', '', '', 'Renewable bio-gas is already produced and stored in volumes of at least one day''s production to be adequate to allow peak generation at any time on demand for between 6 and 12 hours per day. Raw gas is scrubbed in the gas line to the multiple engines.', '', '', '', '3', '1', '3', '95', '2.40', '8%', '35%', '', '', '', 'Quater2', '2014', 'Four Bio-Digesters are already operational, only requiring assembly of the containerised engine/generator units in Atlantis. CAE has already acquired the engine blocks required.  The high local content ensures short lead times for procurement.', '8', 'peaking', '12', '365', '8', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', '36', '7', '2500', 'The bio-gas power generation plants built by Cape Advanced Engineering at four large scale commercial piggeries in South Africa are feasible in base load operation with 0.25 MW output at a price of R1.20/kWh. In response to the DoE''s Medium Term Risk Mitigation strategy, we offer peak generation by adding gas storage and 300% installed generator capacity, which requires a higher tariff than REFIT, estimated to be between R2.40 and R3.00/kWh depending on the PPA term.', '8%', 'yes', '', 'fastQ2-2013-12Months', 'The IDC has financed an identical bio-gas power peaking generation project which we are undertaking with the City of Windhoek.  The IDC has thus evaluated our technology and financial feasibility, so similar finance can be secured during PPA negotiation.  Generation can be underway within 6 months of PPA signature and credit approval, which will require 2 months after PPA signature. Manufacture will require 6 months.', '2', '8', 'Cape Advanced Engineering (Pty) Ltd', 'Cape Advanced Engineering (Pty) Ltd', 'Cape Advanced Engineering (Pty) Ltd', 'not applicable - this is a South African local technology, local content and local job creation project.', 'Between 2007 and 2013, Cape Advanced Engineering has developed bio-gas power generation projects in which 5 large anaerobic bio-digesters have been built and commissioned at large scale commercial piggeries and a commercial dairy, each with base load fuel capacity of at least 0.25 MW.  The bio-digesters are already operational at these farms and the bio-gas produced is being flared or vented owing to the absence currently of a means of generating power and supplying onto the national grid. Cape Advanced Engineering has operated its 0.25 MW containerised generator modules throughout 2009, 2010, 2011 and 2012 in both grid embedded and island mode to validate the technology and satisfy Eskom''s requirements.To generate power for this proposed peaking power project, each site will be equipped with up to 4 containerised  generator units operating in tandem under the control of proven generator control systems and Eskom approved switch-gear. Cape Advanced Engineering is also building a new 0.5 MW bio-gas power peaking plant for the City of Windhoek which incorporates the same 0.25 MW generator modules to be used for peak generation at the piggeries in this offer to supply peaking capacity for Medium Term Risk Mitigation. Cape Advanced Engineering is also constructing a 0.6 MW power peaking plant at a large scale commercial dairy and animal feed manufacturer in Darling, Western Cape. Every element of technology, plant and equipment to be used in the proposed peak power generation plants has been operated and validated in our bio-gas power generation projects. (Company Profile attached to hard copy and CD versions.)', '20794081', '19259852', '30135344', 'yes', '', '', '', '', 12, 'Cape Advanced Engineering is a level 4 B-BBEE company which in 2008 to 2011 supported the Whisper Boat Building Academy for the Deaf in Khayelitsha with funding, training and enterprise development initiatives to a value of over R500 000, to promote their commercial boat building projects.\r\n\r\nCape Advanced Engineering, together with SANEDI, also developed the Bela-Bela bio-gas reticulation project for provision of household cooking gas to at least 100 homesteads in an informal settlement.\r\n\r\nCommunity training projects and support of local education will be implemented in the area surrounding each of the generation sites should peaking generation be facilitated.  ', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', '1', 'yes', 'no', 'no', '', 'yes', '29/08/2012', 'yes', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '1', 'project', '', 'no', 'no', 'no', '', '', '', '2', '', 'finalised', 'yes', 'The bio-gas power peaking generation plants will be installed in the form of multiple containerised 0.25 MW bio-gas generator modules located alongside the existing, fully operational bio-digesters built by Cape Advanced Engineering at large scale commercial piggeries located within 100 km from Tshwane, between 2008 and 2011.  Each bio-digester is fed with piggery manure from these piggeries, each containing between 12 000 and 17 000 pigs, which ensures gas production at a rate adequate to achieve base load power generation of 250 kW throughout the year.  The bio-digesters are already equipped with gas storage capable of gas accumulation for 36 hours, which will enable peak power generation for at least 6 to 12 hours per day at levels of 1 MW per unit. All the bio-digesters are operational and are already yielding the expected quality and quantity of gas in relation to the manure outputs from the piggeries.  These piggeries are highly advanced production operations that sustain a consistent output throughout the year, thus the feed-stock supply to the bio-digesters is consistent throughout the year.  The IDC, the lender on Cape Advanced Engineering''s bio-gas peak power generation project with the City of Windhoek, is fully familiar with the these bio-digesters at the piggeries and will not require extensive confirmation of the plant output potential.  These bio-digesters were in fact inspected and evaluated in February 2012 by Dr. Wolfgang Tentscher, a bio-digester expert brought out from Germany by the IDC to evaluate local technology and opportunities.  Dr. Tentscher found the CAE designs to be appropriate for the application at the piggeries.  Our ability to already quantify the gas being generated from our existing bio-digesters greatly reduces the risks for the Lender.', 'Settlers, Limpopo Province, South Africa', '28', '39', '40.52', '24', '55', '7.57', 'yes', 'The owners of the farm, who own the land and the large scale commercial piggery (situated on the farm) which supplies the manure to the bio-digester, have entered into a joint venture agreement with Cape Advanced Engineering.  This agreement sees us producing bio-gas from the piggery manure fed to the bio-digester, which has been built by Cape Advanced Engineering, and generating power for commercial sale.  The joint venture was originally established to operate under the REFIT programme for the sale of power onto the national grid.  CAE then submitted an Offer to Supply under the COP 17 ITO on behalf of the Joint Venture - see documentation attached confirming the agreement.  (Note that the piggery and bio-digester were built in 2011 and 2012 thus they do not appear on Google Earth images of this site which date from 2009.) Similar agreements have been put in place with the other sites for peak power generation as described in this IFRI.', 'yes', 'yes', '', 'no', '', '', 'no', '', '', 'A Environmental Record of Decision (ROD) has been issued authorizing the operation of the piggery, the production of bio-gas and the generation of electric power from the bio-gas.  If awarded a PPA then the project will be required to apply for a generating licence from NERSA - such an application was already submitted in 2011 at the time of submission of the COP 17 ITO - this application is still valid and is still in process with NERSA.', '1', '28', '39', '40.52', '24', '55', '7.57', 'Bingley or Settlers ', 'yes', '14/06/2013', 'yes', 'Eskom has issued a revised quotation for Grid Connection to CAE on 14 June 2013. The original quotation was issued in preparation our COP 17 ITO submission in 2011. Cape Advanced Engineering has had numerous meetings with Eskom to confirm technical aspect', 'The CAE projects in the Pretoria region have been discussed with the team reporting to Wolfgang Bohmer, Grid Access Unit Regional Manager which has been represented by Helen Bezuidenhout, IPP REPRESENTATIVE - GRID ACCESS UNIT, GROUP CUSTOMER SERVICES, 1 Gobie Street, Menlyn Office Block, Pretoria - Tel:  012 421 3117.  Grid analysis engineers have visited the proposed sites and evaluated the capacity of the transmission lines to transmit power as planned.  A revised quotation for Grid Connection was issued to CAE on 14 June 2013.\r\n', 'The projects have been designed to work within the capacity of the existing transmission line capacity.  No upgrade to the system is anticipated at this point in time.', 'We propose to connect onto the Eskom rural distribution network - these lines are already feeding the farms on which the bio-digesters are located.', '6', 'not applicable', '65-75', '27', '75.00', 'CAE has developed all the equipment for local manufacture and this project will provide a valuable opportunity to advance local manufacture - 12 local bio-gas generation units.', '52', '12 new generation units required creates opportunity for increased localisation and further development of local products, 20 engineers, Technicians and operators will also be trained. ', '2013-07-11', '2013-07-12', 'true');
