(153, 350, 'Gledhow Sugar Company', '+27836493866', 'Paul de Robillard', 'Gledhow Sugar Company', '1', 'Gledhow Mill Road', 'Gledhow', 'Kwa-Dukuza', '4450', 'pderobillard@gledhow.co.za', 'The Gledhow Sugar Company Greenfield Energy Generation Project', 'For many years Gledhow Sugar Company (GSC) has been generating only the power it needs to operate its Factory by burning the fibrous residue of processed sugar cane, called bagasse, in boilers to produce the steam for turbine-driven generators and the steam required to produce sugar from the juice extracted from sugar cane. GSC''s thermal efficiency of the Factory, and the efficiency of its boilers and turbine-driven generators, is typical for the industry but can be significantly improved to produce surplus bagasse to be used for the generation of electricity surplus to GSC''s requirements. This surplus could be exported to the grid.\r\n \r\nGSC is unique in the industry in that it is the first BBBEE sugar company in RSA and that 72% of the cane supply area falls under the umbrella of Land Reform. There are currently 30 000 hectares of land under plantation and the intention is to increase this by 5 500 hectares during the next 5 years to provide a crop of 1 500 000 tons cane per annum. A crop of this size will have a material effect on the profitability of GSC and its growers. However, to achieve a sustainable crop of this size GSC must be in a position to offer incentives to growers of sugar cane to supply their cane to GSC for the duration of the Power Purchase Agreement. The incentive will be funded by the sale of surplus bagasse.\r\n\r\nThe required thermal efficiency improvements to the Factory to produce surplus bagasse will be undertaken and financed by GSC. A Special Purpose Vehicle (SPV) will be formed to build a Power Island which will buy surplus bagasse from GSC. This bagasse will generate 75t/h of steam at 65barg in a new high efficiency boiler. The steam will drive a new extraction/condensing turbine 