(167, 313, 'Africary Holdings (Pty) Ltd', '+27824971995', 'Johan Brand', 'Suite 2B Grand Palace', '1', 'Heunis Street', '0', 'Secunda', '2430', 'Johan.Brand@Africary.com', 'Theunissen UCG Project (Phase II)', 'Africary is planning to increase the 50 MW power generation facility situated between Welkom and Theunissen in the Free State by 1,600 MW after the completion of Phase I. \r\nAfricary has acquired the coal rights to the Theunissen coal field (approx 300 sq km) and is proposing to develop underground coal gasification (UCG) as a means of exploiting these coal reserves. AgriCary has acquired the surface rights to the farms strategically located above these reserves.\r\nThe syngas will be used to generate electricity using 6 large high efficiency gas turbines (GT) with Heat Recovery Steam Generators (HRSG). The personnel complement is estimated at about 250 people. The proposed development will include: -- Underground coal gasification of a roughly 3,000 ha coal footprint (200 million tons of coal); -- Infrastructure footprint of about 15 ha; -- Infrastructure to include gas cleaning, power generation, waste handling (but no on-site disposal), administration and maintenance; and -- approximately 30 kilometre Eskom transmission point of common contact (Eskom Perseus near Verginia) ; including a water supply line from Sedibeng Water connecting to the supply line close to Beatrix Gold Mines. \r\nThe coal seams in the project area occur at depths ranging from 320 to 500 metres (m) below the surface and have an average thickness of 3.2 m. UCG is an in-situ gasification process that converts coal deep underground into combustible gas, which is extracted for beneficial use via boreholes. Two boreholes (also referred to as wells) are drilled into the coal seam fairly close to one another. Air enriched with oxygen is delivered into the coal seam via one borehole (the injection well) and the coal is ignited in order to start the chemical mining process. The burning front results in high temperatures that cause the coal ahead of the front effectively to release gas. Groundwater, augmented by water added to the air injection borehole if necessary, reacts with the carbon in the coal to form a combustible gas mixture of mainly carbon monoxide (CO), hydrogen (H2) and methane (CH4). The gas mixture is extracted via the second borehole (the production well). UCG can be applied to coal resources that are otherwise unprofitable or technically difficult to extract by traditional mining methods. The gas produced by this method can be used as a chemical feedstock or as fuel for power generation. Ash and other remnants of the coal remain underground and gets burried. UCG has much lower environmental and safety impacts than traditional coal mining and power generation. This technology eliminates mine safety issues, surface damage, stockpiles of overburden and discard coal, and solid waste discharge like ash dumps, and reduces sulfur dioxide (SO2) nitrogen oxide (NOx) and particulate (PM10) emissions.', 'GasPlant', 'CCGT', 'CoalOther', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Underground coal gasification', '2000', '672', '1600', '86', '1.28', 'CPI of 6%', '56%', '', '', '', 'Quater4', '2020', '', '60', 'baseload', '', '', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', '37500', '25', '1280', 'Rand Price: R1280\r\nTerm: 20', 'The price of R1280 is quoted in 2013 prices and is set to escalate at 6% pa. Expected Indexation : Electricity & water component in PPI as published by Stats SA', 'yes', '', 'commitQ2-2016-Phased', 'See project roadmap', '12', '60', 'Africary Holdings (Pty) Ltd', 'Johan Brand (Ex-Sasol UCG Business Developer)', 'CDE Process (Pty) Ltd & Aqua Alpha Drilling Solutions (Pty) Ltd', 'Wood Group (power plant operator) and GE (CCGT OEM)', 'Eskom has ''n UCG project at Majuba is an example of the technology. Johan Brand and\r\nhis technology team of experts has initiated similar projects in Europe (Hungary) and Australia. Africary is co-owned by Eliphus Monkoe and Johan Brand who came together in order to build the first commercial UCG power station in South Africa.', '0', '0', '0', 'no', '', '', '', '', 50, 'Africary is 50% owned by Eliphus Monkoe.', 'no', 'no', 'yes', 'yes', 'no', '', 'no', '12', 'yes', 'yes', 'no', '01/01/2020', 'no', '01/06/2020', 'no', 'Currently in progress. To be completed Q1/2016', 'no', 'Prospecting rights in place; environmental studies underway. Mining approval in progress for Q2/2014', 'no', 'Learnings from Phase I Plant will be taken into account. ', 'Yes', 'see project road map', 'see milestone schedule', '6', 'project', '', 'yes', 'no', 'no', '', '', '', '12', 'no', 'none', 'no', 'Full Bankable Study under way for Phase I with very promising initial results. The study will have the sign-off from 3rd parties for the following areas: Geology, EIA, Independent Engineers review, Independent Financial audit. Phase II will only proceed after the successful start-up of Phase I and the approval of expansion by all relevant authorities.', 'Between Welkom and Theunissen, Free State', '26', '37', '09', '28', '10', '42', 'yes', 'Owned by subsidiary of Africary Holdings (AgriCary). However the option of modular design allows for review of this.', 'no', 'no', '06/06/2013', 'yes', '01/01/2015', '01/01/2017', 'no', '', '', 'EMP, WUL, EMPR. Eskom', '30', '26', '90', '21.69', '27', '99', '34.57', 'Planned to be Perseus or Everest point of common connection ', 'no', '', '', '', 'none yet', 'not identified yet', 'eskom', '36', 'not applicable', '45-55', '10000', '31.25', 'Develop ucg technology, which can advantage further projects and export. After successful implementation of the first project own-built options will be available', '2000', 'plant and drilling systems', '2013-07-11', '2013-07-12', 'true'),
(168, 351, 'TSS/Hope Energy', '0718547093', 'Susan Lasecki-Coiro', 'P.O. Box 4652', '977', 'Wroxton Dr', 'Dainfern North', 'Fourways', '2174', 'susan.coiro@hopeenergy.co.za', 'Medium Term Risk Mitigation (including Cogeneration and Natural Gas); and Baseload (including Coal, Natural Gas and Hydro)', 'Hope Energy (Pty) Ltd and TSS are currently partnering with the City of uMhlathuze in order to deliver to the municipality renewable energy solutions, based on their specific needs. Such projects are able to provide clean energy, while being economically viable to the municipality. We firmly believe that the success and efficiency of our project with the City of uMhlathuze will be an example, which can be applied throughout the country. \r\n\r\nuMhlathuze requested that several technologies be put forth in order for the municipality to review and evaluate. Through our total solution approach, TSS and Hope Energy were able to put forth solutions based on solar PV, wave technology, bio-mass gasification, and algae/bio-diesel. We believe these are all viable solutions to meet the energy needs of the Department of Energy. However to fulfill this RFRI and to meet its base-load requirement, we will focus only on the utility-scale component of the project. Therefore we propose a 54 MWe wood fired biomass plant, utilising wood from local, sustainable forests. \r\n\r\nBelow are the details of our current municipal project. We offer this project as our proposed solution for nationwide roll to meet the energy initiatives of the Department of Energy.\r\nProject Overview:\r\nHope Energy (Pty) Ltd and TSS recommended the established an Energy Purchasing Agency in the City of uMhlathuze. This was done to allow the municipality to purchase power from various different providers (such as ESKOM and the projects created by Hope Energy and TSS) through one single entity. As a electricity production component of this agreement the 54MW Biomass Power Plant generate clean and renewable energy for the community. While providing power, it will create over 4000 jobs and greatly benefit the surrounding communities. With that in mind, the City of uMhlathuze was given 26% ownership of the plants. Simultaneously, a Community Trust will be created. The trust will utilize the profits from the bio-mass plant on a managed set infrastructure projects. \r\nTechnology Overview:\r\nThe design is collaboration between our independent engineers Black and Veatch, DP Cleantech, SIEMENS and EHL. The above groups will complete installation and construction, with predominantly local labour force underlining the project’s focus on local skills development. The plant has an expected life of 35 years. The operations and maintenance contracts will be committed for the duration of the plant life. The plant will be operated by an experienced Independent Power Producer with many of these plants in operation worldwide.\r\nDelivery 24-30 months after completion of EIA and NERSA requirements are met.\r\nInput Capacity: 500,000 tons of biomass\r\nOutput Capacity: 54 MW of electricity\r\nRate: below Megaflex, below NERSA annual escalation\r\nJob Creation: 55 direct, 4,100 indirect\r\n', 'Thermal', 'NewBiomass', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '60', '60', '54', '89', '0.56', '5%', '91%', '', '', '', 'Quater2', '2017', '', '36', 'baseload', '', '', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', '2000', '20', '1000', '', '5%', 'yes', '', 'commitQ2-2014-Phased', '', '24', '36', 'Hope Energy Developments', 'DP Cleantech', 'TSS, Black Swan, Community Partners (BBBEE)', 'None', 'DP Cleantech has installed 50 biomass plants worldwide and has 30 are being installed. Soon, they will have an installed capacity of over 1.7GW', '0', '0', '0', 'no', '', '', '', '', 26, 'Community involvement: Up to 26% equity participation\r\n\r\nLocal Economic Development:  4,000 jobs in sustainable forestry.\r\n\r\nDividends derived from community involvement to be invested in both critical and social infrastructure investment as identified by the community. \r\n\r\n', 'no', 'no', 'no', 'yes', '', '', '', '9', 'yes', 'no', 'no', '12/07/2013', 'no', '', 'yes', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '1', 'project', '', 'yes', 'no', 'no', '', '', '', '6', '', 'draft', 'yes', 'Yes, there will be additional studies required, namely the Environmental Impact Assessment as well as a fuel source study to confirm a sustainable supply of wood chips over length of the PPA.', 'Richard''s Bay Area', '32', '16', '23.24', '28', '38', '36.7', 'yes', 'We have identified a site and are in the process of securing the agreement. It is within the forestry land of the community trust we have agreements with.', 'no', 'no', '', 'no', '', '', 'no', '', '', 'Environmental Impact Assessment, Water Use License, Emission License, Land Consent Use, CAA Approval - 18 Months', '10', '32', '08', '08.04', '28', '40', '48.71', 'The Rabbit 270kV', 'no', '', '', '', 'Preliminary meeting with Eskom transmission.', 'No transmission upgrade necessary. ', 'Connecting to Eskom.', '36', 'Project located within South Africa', '100+', '800', '40.00', 'All civil and electrical.', '350', 'Skills transfer in engineering, civil, and electrical.', '2013-07-11', '2013-07-12', 'true'),
(169, 210, 'Destiny Corporation Energy', '+27118024036', 'Nkosi Gugushe', '1st Floor, Building 16, The Woodlands Office Park', '20', 'Woodlands Drive', 'Woodmead', 'Johannesburg', '2191', 'nkosi@destinycorporation.co.za', 'Coega IDZ Floating Power Plant', 'The project aims to deploy a 256MW of open cycle gas turbine power plant in the Coega IDZ. The power plant will be barge mounted and will float in the sea moored to a sea wall within the port. It will be fired by LNG sourced from the international markets, including emergent and increasingly proximate African suppliers. LNG storage will be achieved with rapid deployment land side regasification terminals as well as on floating storage and regasification ships. The power plant will be proximate to the proposed diesel fired Dediza peaking power plant in Coega, and will be able to share existing power evacuation infrastructure. \r\n\r\nProximity to the existing Dedisa Peaking Power Plant also offers the Dedisa Peaking Power Plant the opportunity to convert some of this power plant''s gas turbines to gas from diesel and thereby change these units to a base load plant whilst also achieving an improved environmental profile. On this basis, this project can technically be viewed as having the capability to provide 256MW of new power or, 300MW of gross cost effective base load power, if there is conversion to gas of some of the proposed diesel fired turbines at Dediza. This will be achieved by the scaling done of the Coega IDZ Floating Power Plant to 128MW and the utilisation of the excess LNG capacity in up to 172MW of converted Dedisa turbines for base load power.\r\n\r\nThe main cost drivers for the project is the cost of the equipment and the cost of fuel. The major equipment components are priced in hard currency and are therefore subject to exchange rate fluctuations. The fuel is priced in hard currency and is subject to diesel indexation as well as exchange rate fluctuations. There is however, significant regional production of LNG already available, with more expected on stream in the next 10 years. This will provide opportunities for cost reduction through offset intra-regional trading.  \r\n\r\nThe open cycle gas turbines are aero-derivatives that have dual fuel capability, diesel and natural gas, as well as unlimited daily starts. The unlimited daily start capability mean that the power plants are able to perform across the spectrum of generating range, from peaking to base load. This generating flexibility is enhanced by the power plant''s moveable nature. As a moveable asset, the power plant is amenable to short-term peaking contracts, but retains base load capability.\r\n\r\nRapid deployment is achieved by a modular factory construction of the floating power plant that minimises onsite construction and commissioning risks. It is further achieved by utilising modular landside storage. There is significant scope to source land side storage equipment in South Africa. Finally, by locating the projects in harbours and ports, speed of execution is achieved by project''s typically staying within existing EIAs already granted to ports and other industrial facilities. This compliance with existing EIAs provides rational and justifiable opportunities for fast tracking projects through the traditional 18 month EIA processes.\r\n', 'GasPlant', 'OCGT', 'LNG', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '256', '128', '230', '80', '1.85', 'Global Diesel/LNG prices', '42', '', '', '', 'Quater4', '2014', '', '12', 'baseload', '12', '31', '24', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'yes', 'The project has the potential to replace 172MW of diesel fired peaking power at Dediza with 172MW of gas fired base load power', '3500', '20', '2100', '', 'Diesel/LNG and CPI', 'yes', '', 'fastQ2-2013-12Months', '', '2', '12', 'Destiny Corporation Energy (Pty) Ltd', 'Destiny Corporation Energy, ASRY Centrax, Rolls Royce, Waller Marine, Ochre Energy (Pty) Ltd', 'Destiny Corporation Energy', 'Ochre Energy (Pty) Limited', 'Our technology partners have delivered similar projects in numerous countries, as well as similar projects to the oil and gas industry worldwide. A notable project is the 342MW floating OCGT delivered and energised in Venezuela within a 6 month project implementation period.', '0', '0', '0', 'no', '', '', '', '', 69, 'Economic:\r\n\r\nThe project will generate employment both during construction (estimated 130 temporary positions) and operation (estimated 30 permanent positions). The majority of the temporary positions will be skilled artisanal positions, whilst the permanent positions will be highly skilled engineering and technician positions.\r\n\r\nThe project has the potential to catalyze the growth of the cryogenic component manufacturing in South Africa. The project has specifically selected to use technology for the onshore cryogenic storage of LNG that can be manufactured locally. Additionally, there is significant scope in any subsequent projects to localize the fabrication and power plant integration of the power barges. South Africa has a vibrant marine engineering industry, as well as the steel raw materials required to accomplish this. Destiny Corporation Energy’s technical partners and equipment suppliers have expressed an interest in establishing a local manufacturing presence in South Africa, to service the continental market. They are accordingly prepared to provide their proprietary engineering design and fabrication skills in to a localized manufacturing company.\r\n\r\nThe majority of the shares in the project are directly owned by South African entities and therefore will provide financial returns to these parties. The South African ownership is majority black/HDSA owned. The project thereby creates the opportunity for a black champion in the clean and renewable energy sector.\r\n\r\nThere are no existing projects using the envisaged technology in South Africa or Africa and the project will provide an opportunity for technological interaction and knowledge transfer to South African citizens., and the opportunity to export this knowledge from South Africa  in to the rest of the continent. That Destiny has identified a further +1000 MW in South Africa and +2000MW on the rest of the continent bodes well for the country.\r\n\r\nThere are no existing projects using the envisaged technology in South Africa or Africa and the project will provide an opportunity for technological interaction and knowledge transfer to South African citizens., and the opportunity to export this knowledge from South Africa  in to the rest of the continent. That Destiny has identified a further +1000 MW in South Africa and +2000MW on the rest of the continent bodes well for the country.\r\n\r\n2. Social: \r\n\r\nYes, the project will contribute significantly to the social upliftment and development of the people of South Africa and particularly in the project area, through the following: Through the creation of jobs both temporary and permanent, most of which will be from the local communities, the project activity will contribute to alleviation of poverty in the project area.\r\n\r\nBecause there are no similar technology installations in the area, the local people will require education and training in the operation and maintenance of the plant. This will enhance information sharing and skills transfer from foreign parties to the local community.\r\n\r\nThe creation of jobs, together with the wider impact of poverty alleviation will create a distribution of wealth within the local communities, with a direct and measurable improvement of health and quality of life for citizens of the local community.\r\n\r\n3. Environmental: \r\n\r\nThe project activity will take place on an existing industrial/Harbour or Port site, on unused open land within the greater plant operation covered by an original EIA. Therefore:\r\n\r\nThat the disturbance of ecosystems and loss of biological diversity are avoided, or where they cannot be avoided, are minimised and remedied. There will be minimal disturbance of any ecosystem or loss of biodiversity through the project activity. The selected site is on the existing industrial property between existing operational units with no active ecosystem or biodiversity constraints. That pollution and degradation of the environment are avoided, or where they cannot be altogether avoided, are minimised and remedied.\r\n\r\nBy increasing the natural gas based electricity component of the national grid, the project activity will have a positive impact on pollution by lowering national and local CO2, NOx and particulate matter emission levels.  There is scope within the project to recover and utilize the waste heat from the power plant and cooling energy from the LNG regasification.\r\n\r\nTherefore, there will be limited pollution or degradation of the environment through the project activity; in fact, there will be an improvement.\r\niii) That the disturbance of landscapes and sites that constitute the nation’s cultural heritage is avoided, or where it cannot be altogether avoided, is minimised and remedied.\r\nThere will be no disturbance of landscapes and sites that constitute the nation’s cultural heritage through the project activity as the selected site is within the boundary of the existing IFM industrial complex.\r\niv) That waste is avoided, or where it cannot be altogether avoided, minimised and reused or recycled where possible and otherwise disposed of in a responsible manner\r\nThe project activity will not generate any operating waste. Not even the usual inert building rubble typical of construction projects will be generated during construction. \r\nv) That the use and exploitation of non-renewable resources is responsible and equitable, and takes into account the consequences of the depletion of the resource\r\nThe project activity will only consume resources that have of late become abundant in South Africa, in SADC and in Africa. By also recycling waste heat and waste cooling the project will ensure that maximum utility or efficiency is achieved from these resources and thereby have a positive impact on the responsible use of these non-renewable resources.\r\nvii) That a risk averse and cautious approach is applied, which takes into account the limits of current knowledge about the consequences of decisions and actions\r\nPrior to construction the project activity will be scrutinized and monitored by the EIA consultants used by Destiny Corporation Energy for the overall plant development. In addition, a monitoring methodology forming part of the UNFCCC criteria for CDM registration has already been implemented and adhered to during operation. This same methodology will be extended to the proposed project\r\nvii) That negative impacts on the environment and on people’s environmental rights be anticipated and prevented, and where they cannot be altogether prevented, are minimised and remedied. There will be highly negative impacts on the environment and on people’s environmental rights through the project activity, when compared to the alternatives of using coal or diesel/HFO as a primary electricity generating fuel.\r\n', 'yes', 'no', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'no', '3', 'yes', 'yes', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'yes', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '3', 'project', '', 'no', 'yes', 'yes', 'no', '', '', '6', '', 'draft', 'no', 'This is not applicable. LNG is globally traded commodity.', 'Port of Ngqura in the Coega IDZ', '33', '47', '42', '25', '41', '6', 'no', '', 'no', 'no', '', 'no', '', '', 'no', '', '', 'A generating license, and gas importation and hazardous materials storage licenses will be required. Approval and permitting for use of the port may also be required from the National Ports Authority.', '4', '33', '46', '30', '25', '39', '36', 'Dedisa substation', 'no', '', '', '', 'No engagements with Eskom have been held to date.', 'No upgrade is anticipated.', 'Eskom', '12', 'The project is in South Africa.', '75-85', '500', '1