(175, 210, 'Destiny Corporation Energy', '+27118024036', 'Nkosi Gugushe', '1st Floor, Building 16, The Woodlands Office Park', '20 ', 'Woodlands Drive', 'Woodmead', 'Johannesburg', '2191', 'nkosi@destinycorporation.co.za', 'Durban Floating Power Plant', 'The project aims to deploy a 256MW of open cycle gas turbine power plant in the port of Durban. The power plant will be barge mounted and will float in the sea moored to a sea wall within the port. It will be fired by LNG sourced from the international markets, including emergent and increasingly proximate African suppliers. LNG storage will be achieved with rapid deployment land side regasification terminals as well as on floating storage and regasification ships. The floating power plant will be within 45 km proximity to the proposed diesel fired Avon Peaking Power Plant. It will also be within 2-5 km proximity to the Durban gas reticulation network and network servitudes.\r\n\r\nProximity to the existing Avon Peaking Power Plant and the gas network servitudes potentially offers the Avon Peaking Power Plant the opportunity to convert some of this power plant''s gas turbines to gas from diesel and thereby change these units to a base load plant whilst also achieving an improved environmental profile. On this basis, this project can technically be viewed as having the capability to provide 256MW of new power or, 300MW of gross cost effective base load power, if there is conversion to gas of some of the proposed diesel fired turbines at Avon. This will be achieved by the scaling done of the Durban Floating Power Plant to 128MW and the utilisation of the excess LNG capacity in up to 172MW of converted Avon turbines for base load power.\r\n\r\nProximity to the Durban gas reticulation network and servitudes also means that gas can be supplied into the network, and thereby encourage grid replacement through onsite distributed generation by industrial customers.\r\n\r\nThe main cost drivers for the project is the cost of the equipment and the cost of fuel. The major equipment components are priced in hard currency and are therefore subject to exchange rate fluctuations. The fuel is priced in hard currency and is subject to diesel indexation as well as exchange rate fluctuations. There is however, significant regional production of LNG already available, with more expected on stream in the next 10 years. This will provide opportunities for cost reduction through offset intra-regional trading.  \r\n\r\nThe open cycle gas turbines are aero-derivatives that have dual fuel capability, diesel and natural gas, as well as unlimited daily starts. The unlimited daily start capability mean that the power plants are able to perform across the spectrum of generating range, from peaking to base load. This generating flexibility is enhanced by the power plant''s moveable nature. As a moveable asset, the power plant is amenable to short-term peaking contracts, but retains base load capability.\r\n\r\nRapid deployment is achieved by a modular factory construction of the floating power plant that minimises onsite construction and commissioning risks. It is further achieved by utilising modular landside storage. There is significant scope to source land side storage equipment in South Africa. Finally, by locating the projects in harbours and ports, speed of execution is achieved by project''s typically staying within existing EIAs already granted to ports and other industrial facilities. This compliance with existing EIAs provides rational and justifiable opportunities for fast tracking projects through the traditional 18 month EIA processes.\r\n', 'GasPlant', 'OCGT', 'LNG', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '256', '128', '230', '80', '1.85', 'Global Diesel/LNG', '42', '', '', '', 'Quater4', '2014', '', '12', 'baseload', '12', '31', '24', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'yes', 'Has the potential the replace 172MW of diesel fired peaking capacity at the proposed Avon Peaking Power Plant with 172MW of base load g