localized manufacturing company.\r\n\r\nThe majority of the shares in the project are directly owned by South African entities and therefore will provide financial returns to these parties. The South African ownership is majority black/HDSA owned. The project thereby creates the opportunity for a black champion in the clean and renewable energy sector.\r\n\r\nThere are no existing projects using the envisaged technology in South Africa or Africa and the project will provide an opportunity for technological interaction and knowledge transfer to South African citizens., and the opportunity to export this knowledge from South Africa  in to the rest of the continent. That Destiny has identified a further +1000 MW in South Africa and +2000MW on the rest of the continent bodes well for the country.\r\n\r\nThere are no existing projects using the envisaged technology in South Africa or Africa and the project will provide an opportunity for technological interaction and knowledge transfer to South African citizens., and the opportunity to export this knowledge from South Africa  in to the rest of the continent. That Destiny has identified a further +1000 MW in South Africa and +2000MW on the rest of the continent bodes well for the country.\r\n\r\n2. Social: \r\n\r\nYes, the project will contribute significantly to the social upliftment and development of the people of South Africa and particularly in the project area, through the following: Through the creation of jobs both temporary and permanent, most of which will be from the local communities, the project activity will contribute to alleviation of poverty in the project area.\r\n\r\nBecause there are no similar technology installations in the area, the local people will require education and training in the operation and maintenance of the plant. This will enhance information sharing and skills transfer from foreign parties to the local community.\r\n\r\nThe creation of jobs, together with the wider impact of poverty alleviation will create a distribution of wealth within the local communities, with a direct and measurable improvement of health and quality of life for citizens of the local community.\r\n\r\n3. Environmental: \r\n\r\nThe project activity will take place on an existing industrial/Harbour or Port site, on unused open land within the greater plant operation covered by an original EIA. Therefore:\r\n\r\nThat the disturbance of ecosystems and loss of biological diversity are avoided, or where they cannot be avoided, are minimised and remedied. There will be minimal disturbance of any ecosystem or loss of biodiversity through the project activity. The selected site is on the existing industrial property between existing operational units with no active ecosystem or biodiversity constraints. That pollution and degradation of the environment are avoided, or where they cannot be altogether avoided, are minimised and remedied.\r\n\r\nBy increasing the natural gas based electricity component of the national grid, the project activity will have a positive impact on pollution by lowering national and local CO2, NOx and particulate matter emission levels.  There is scope within the project to recover and utilize the waste heat from the power plant and cooling energy from the LNG regasification.\r\n\r\nTherefore, there will be limited pollution or degradation of the environment through the project activity; in fact, there will be an improvement.\r\niii) That the disturbance of landscapes and sites that constitute the nation’s cultural heritage is avoided, or where it cannot be altogether avoided, is minimised and remedied.\r\nThere will be no disturbance of landscapes and sites that constitute the nation’s cultural heritage through the project activity as the selected site is within the boundary of the existing IFM industrial complex.\r\niv) That waste is avoided, or where it cannot be altogether avoided, minimised and reused or recycled where possible and otherwise disposed of in a responsible manner\r\nThe project activity will not generate any operating waste. Not even the usual inert building rubble typical of construction projects will be generated during construction. \r\nv) That the use and exploitation of non-renewable resources is responsible and equitable, and takes into account the consequences of the depletion of the resource\r\nThe project activity will only consume resources that have of late become abundant in South Africa, in SADC and in Africa. By also recycling waste heat and waste cooling the project will ensure that maximum utility or efficiency is achieved from these resources and thereby have a positive impact on the responsible use of these non-renewable resources.\r\nvii) That a risk averse and cautious approach is applied, which takes into account the limits of current knowledge about the consequences of decisions and actions\r\nPrior to construction the project activity will be scrutinized and monitored by the EIA consultants used by Destiny Corporation Energy for the overall plant development. In addition, a monitoring methodology forming part of the UNFCCC criteria for CDM registration has already been implemented and adhered to during operation. This same methodology will be extended to the proposed project\r\nvii) That negative impacts on the environment and on people’s environmental rights be anticipated and prevented, and where they cannot be altogether prevented, are minimised and remedied. There will be highly negative impacts on the environment and on people’s environmental rights through the project activity, when compared to the alternatives of using coal or diesel/HFO as a primary electricity generating fuel.\r\n', 'yes', 'no', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'no', '3', 'yes', 'yes', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'yes', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '3', 'project', '', 'no', 'yes', 'yes', 'no', '', '', '6', '', 'draft', 'no', 'This is not applicable. LNG is a globally traded commodity.', 'Durban Port', '31', '01', '34.6', '29', '53', '25.2', 'no', '', 'no', 'no', '', 'no', '', '', 'no', '', '', 'A generating license, and gas importation and transmission and hazardous materials storage licenses will be required. Approval and permitting to use the port may also be required from the National Ports Authority.', '2', '31', '01', '34.6', '29', '53', '25.2', 'Transnet Durban Port', 'no', '', '', '', 'We have had no engagement with Eskom on this project.', 'Upgrades may be required to interconnection with Ethukwini Municipality Grid', 'Ethukwini Municipality', '12', 'The project is located in South Africa', '75-85', '500', '14.29', 'The project will require cryogenic equipment which can be sourced from South Africa. Such equipment will also require the use of South African Steel. ', '30', 'The project will require cryogenic equipment which can be sourced from South Africa. Such equipment will also require the use of South African Steel. Operations and maintenance will be localised within a 36 month period. This will require the recruitment and training of skilled engineers, mechanics and technicians. A plant monitoring and rapid response facility will be established in South Africa that will also require the recruitment and training of skilled personnel.', '2013-07-11', '2013-07-12', 'true'),
(177, 268, 'Mitochondria Energy Company (Pty) Ltd', '+27834192837', 'Anthea Bath', 'Brolaz Campus', '223', 'Alexandra Avenue', 'Halfway House', 'Midrand', '1685', 'info@mitochondria.co.za', 'CoJ Metropolitan - MQ.13.07.002A', 'The project intends to deliver 200MW of fuel cell based electricity and heat/cooling/steam across multiple selected locations in the Johannesburg complex.  The project requires access to natural gas/ADG/hydrogen as a fuel source.\r\nThe Project develops have been working with various stakeholders across the public and private sector for delivery of the solution and have secured the following:\r\n\r\n- Gas availability for project execution (see Egoli Gas letter of support dated 10/07/13)\r\n- Funding support from the IDC, (see letter of support IDC Ref RG531353 dated 25/06/13)\r\n\r\nThe Project team will work the City of Johannesburg and City Power to identify key areas (5MW - 15MW) where industrial parks/zones can be developed.  This electricity generated from the power plant will be transferred into the appropriate grid connection, the heat and steam byproduct will be made available for industrial users on an agreed structure.  \r\nThe location of the sites will be determined in conjunction with City Power in order to support the infrastructure that is required.\r\nA number of sites have been identified for the power plants and allocated in principle.\r\nThe modularity of the fuel cell plants enable redundancy in the process enabling high availabilities of demand.\r\nThe technology can also be used as a peaking power solution where hydrogen is available.\r\nThe project will deliver a combination of off-grid and grid-connected stationary installations with a combined installed capacity of c.200MW to be implemented at National Key Points.\r\n\r\nOn the back of this demand, transfer of technology from offshore countries will occur for local manufacturing in a phased approach.\r\n\r\nSA intends to introduce Fuel Cell (FC)and related clean technologies into the South African energy system. The FC technology has been developed for numerous end-use applications throughout the world and is now available off-the-shelf from established FC technology providers. \r\nThis project will deliver a step-change in the uptake of the fuel cell-derived power with a target of 200MW installed capacity by 2016/1017.\r\n\r\nThe project will realize a fuel infrastructure in South Africa and ensure the security of electricity supply for each of the installations. Priority will be placed on the utilization of renewable energy to deliver sources of carbon emission-free hydrogen where feasible.\r\n\r\nThe project will also aim to establish South Africa as a significant hub for the development of a FC technology production centre to be called the Platinum Valley. The project will therefore help stimulate downstream industrial activities using local minerals (including platinum group metals) which are a  key resource required in the manufacture of FC technology. This will further enable growth and demand in the domestic mining sector.\r\n\r\nThe project meets a number of the policy objectives of the South African government and specifically the beneficiation,  renewable and Hydrogen South Africa  strategies including the new growth path and commitment to reduce green house gas emissions. Ultimately the project aims to contribute towards South Africa’s   “cogent energy security plan” which will make energy accessible, reliable, clean, sustainable and affordable in the medium to long term.\r\n\r\nThe Fuel Cell Energy Generation  Project’s objective is to:\r\n\r\n• Deliver a step-change in FC technology in South Africa to a variety of end-users across the South African economy\r\n• To have FC technology incorporated into the Integrated Resource Plan \r\n• Support and grow domestic FC technology production for domestic and export markets\r\n• Support the beneficiation of  Platinum Group Metals (PGMs) and other minerals in South Africa  through the establishment of the Platinum Valley initiative\r\n• Assess the feasibility of producing emissions-free hydrogen sources by linking up with renewable energy providers\r\n• Contribute towards the creation of a low carbon economy and help mitigate the effects of climate change by increasing the efficiency of electricity production and  the reduction of  greenhouse gas emissions  \r\n•  Contribute towards job creation by facilitating skills and technology transfer and in particular, the training of young  graduates for the installation and maintenance of the FC solution \r\n', 'Other', '', '', '', 'Fuel Cells', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '200', '1.4', '190', '95', '1.4', 'CPI', '47', '', '', '', 'Quater3', '2014', 'Due to the modularity of fuel cell technology, the project can come on stream quickly and ramp up at a rate as required.  The complete project delivery period will 3-4 years (ie steady state 200MW 2016/2017, but generation will begin as early as 2014)', '12', 'mid-merit', '12', '347', '24', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', '7000', '20', '1300', '', 'SA CPI', 'yes', '', 'fastQ2-2013-24Month', '', '3', '12', 'Mitochondria Energy Company (Pty) Ltd', 'Multiple', 'N/A', 'N/A', 'The Mitochondria Energy Company team has previous experience when in industry (CEO - Anglo Platinum/Engineering Head - Vodacom)', '0', '0', '0', 'yes', '', '', '', '', 33, 'Terracotta Resources (Pty) Ltd which is 100% BEE and will also include women, youth and  other black owned entities. The Mitochondria Energy Company shareholder split will be 33:33:33 between the 3 shareholders, thereby possessing a proportion of 33% BEE participation. Mitochondria Energy Company (Pty) Ltd, will be the long-term operator of the project.', 'yes', 'no', 'yes', 'no', 'no', '', 'no', '3', 'yes', 'no', 'no', '11/07/2013', 'no', '', 'yes', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '3', 'project', '', 'no', 'yes', 'no', '', '', '', '3', '', 'none', 'no', 'N/A', 'Johannesburg', '28', '2', '50.35', '26', '12', '14.57', 'no', '', 'no', 'no', '', 'no', '', '', 'no', '', '', 'The projects are small distributed generation systems.  Less intrusive than diesel generator installations.  Timelines will thus be shorter (6 months) to finalize legal environmental arrangements and will run parallel to the contractual negotiations.', '0', '28', '2', '50.35', '25', '12', '14.57', 'Johannesburg', 'no', '', '', '', 'At a high level the concept of fuel cell deployments have been discussed but no project progress made.', 'N/A', 'Eskom\r\nCity Power\r\nEkurhuleni Metropolitan Municipality', '6', 'N/A', '65-75', '4000', '57.14', 'Backward integration of fuel cell equipment manufacture into the Platinum Valley is a core objective of the project.\r\nPreliminary discussions have already taken place with core technology partners, Industrial Development Corporation (IDC) and local partners', '1000', 'Component manufacturing core objective of the project.\r\nPreliminary discussions already taken place with core technology partners, IDC and local partners', '2013-07-11', '2013-07-12', 'true'),
