(195, 386, 'Whitfield Agri', '0824577311', 'Rex Zietsman', 'PO Box 166', '100000000000', 'not applicable', 'not applicable', 'Rosetta', '3301', 'rex@whitfieldfarm.co.za', 'Phalaborwa Cactus', '“Cactus Pear to Biogas”\r\nThe project is based upon growing cactus pear (“prickly pear”) in arid areas where there is no competition with growing food. The cactus pear “leaves” or cladodes are harvested and liquidized into a pulp. The pulp is pumped into anaerobic digesters that produce biogas with a dry gas methane content of >70% by volume. After digestion the digestate is filtered to remove solids with the liquid pumped back to the cactus pear orchards as irrigation water. The solids can be composted back into the soil or used for other products.\r\n\r\nAfter taking roads, water courses and provision for protecting endangered species into consideration, approximately 200 ha of cactus pear are required to generate 1MWe continuously. This increases in areas with rainfall <250mm/year. With manual harvesting, approximately 150, mostly unskilled jobs, are created for a 5MWe project. If mechanical harvesting is carried out, the number of jobs drops to 65. The 85 fewer jobs are all in the unskilled category. The differential in production cost of power is approximately 10% higher with manual harvesting vs mechanical harvesting. That said, the project lends itself to buying cladode from emerging farmers/co-operatives at a pre-negotiated price. This provides for entrepreneurial and enterprise development. It is foreseen that harvesting teams will be formed to harvest cladode on a contract basis – this model works successfully in the sugar industry. The objective is to move from time based income to productivity based income. \r\n\r\nThe technology is scalable to the >100MWe level by use of gas transfer pipelines to send gas from multiple digestion points to a common generation site. The largest logical digestion size is approximately 50MWe. However, it is competitive at the 5MWe level. This generates opportunities for rural towns, particularly in the Karoo, Western Free State and Northern Cape, to set up generation capacity tieing into existing Eskom supply structures. \r\n\r\nThe selling cost of power, using a 10 year PPA basis, is approximately R1000/MWh using mechanical harvesting. It will rise to approximately R1100/MWh with manual harvesting. Due to the high labour component of the fuel cost, the power cost index will run approximately 2% above CPI as provision is made for labour to increase real earnings. Based on a targeted 6% CPI, power will therefore rise at 8%. This is in line with the current NERSA ruling. \r\n\r\nThe capital cost of a 50MWe plant with GE gas turbine will peak at R1 700m. The capital cost of a 5MWe is R150m using gas engines. Roll out of projects can be carried out on a modular basis. Consequently, a project destined for 50MWe can begin at 5MWe. Discussions have been held with IDC, PIC, DBSA and OPIC for funding. A preliminary business plan was submitted to IDC.\r\n\r\nRoll out is initially dependent on the availability of planting material. It takes approximately 3 years for the cactus pear to reach harvesting maturity. Consequently, the critical path is the establishment of a nursery to produce planting material and then the subsequent planting of orchards. Cactus pear is reproduced by cuttings. Therefore, once a sufficient amount of cactus pear is planted, part of the production can be used as planting material for new orchards. Realistically, it will take 4 years from start to produce biogas at full capacity. Follow on ramp up will then be exponential. It follows, that EIA’s, IWULA applications and DoE registrations can happen in parallel with the growing of the plants.\r\n\r\nDiscussions have been held with Bosch Projects and Group 5 Energy with respect to the building of the project. Both have indicated willingness to participate. Nijhuis from the Netherlands have agreed to supply digestion and gas cleaning technology to the project.\r\n\r\nBy its very nature, the process is able to supply base load power. However, with adequate gas storage, peaking power can be produced. It would not be unrealistic to run from 6am to 10pm daily for example. Gas engines in particular are able to start up and be on line within a very short period. At the 2MWe size envisaged, these engines have a 44% energy to power conversion. \r\n\r\nIn this model, the biogas will be washed, cooled and fed into reciprocating gas engines. Besides power production, the biogas can be upgraded to meet end user requirements including pipeline methane, methane as a chemical feedstock or methane as a metallurgical energy source. Examples are: ammonia, nitric acid and urea production, replacement of LPG in copper production, use of methane for DRI/HBI in the iron ore industry, etc. \r\n\r\nThe selling cost of pipeline quality gas will be profitable using the natural gas pricing mechanism laid down for Sasol gas. Consequently, tieing into existing natural gas pipelines is feasible. To achieve pipeline quality, the biogas has to be scrubbed of primarily of carbon dioxide. The recovered carbon dioxide can be scrubbed, chilled and sold as liquid CO2 into the beverage market.\r\n\r\nCo-products\r\nExcess cladode can be harvested, dried and sold as fodder in animal feed. Up to 40% of ruminant ration can be replaced with cladode. The fruit can be harvested with high quality fruit exported. The remaining (or all if the export market fails) fruit is pulped and deseeded. The seeds are crushed to produce a valuable essential oil while the fruit pulp can be made into food products such as chutney. Alternatively, the pulp can be fermented to a potable alcohol. The "Amarula" success comes to mind.\r\n', 'Reciprocating', 'Gas', 'other33', '', '', '', '', '', 'biogas to be produced from farmed biomass', '', '', '', '6', '2', '5', '95', '1', 'CPI + 2%', '44% gross, 42% net', '', '', '', 'Quater3', '2018', '', '48', 'mid-merit', '12', '365', '16', 'yes', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', '560', '10', '1000', '', 'CPI +2%', 'yes', '', 'commitQ2-2016-Phased', 'first power would be 48 months from PPA', '6', '48', 'Whitfield Agri CC', '', 'not applicable, ', 'Advanced African Solutions LLC', 'One of the members of the CC (Rex Zietsman) has been in the engineering design and construction industry since 1995. During this time he has, with a partner, led a management buy out of IMS Process Plant to form AR Process Projects (Pty) Ltd in 2001. He left Process Projects in 2011 to become an independent consultant and to concentrate on developing renewable energy projects. During his period with Process Projects he was involved with the following renewable projects:\r\n\r\n• Cape Clean Energy – a 8MWe biomass fired, Rankine cycle power station funded by CEF; capital >R200m\r\n\r\n• The engineering and cost estimation of an 8.8MWe biomass co-generation power station for Sappi Barberton; capital >R320m\r\n\r\n• Conceptual engineering and cost estimation of a 6MWe gasification with gas engine power station using Johannesburg City Parks biomass as feedstock; capital >R70m. \r\n\r\nDuring the period 2001 to 2010, Process Projects, with a German partners, designed and engineered the nuclear fuel plant for PBMR. At its peak, there were over 30 engineers working on this project.\r\n', '2600000', '2400000', '2000000', 'no', '', '', '', '', 26, 'Discussions are underway with the Phalaborwa Community for them to form a Community Property Association that will oversee the growing and supply of the cactus pear to the project. Two meetings have been held with representatives of the local tribal authorities, the ba Phalaborwa Municipality, Limpopo Economic Development and potential partners.', 'no', 'no', 'no', 'no', 'no', '', '', '6', 'no', '', '', '', '', '', 'no', 'Testwork has been carried out on local varieties of cactus to establish their gas production capability. Discussions have been held with Limpopo cactus pear farmers on the growing and harvesting of cactus pear in the region. We are in negotiation with the University of the Free State to draw on their cactus pear experience. The intention is to fund germplasm research at UFS to identify and hybridize cactus pear varieties for maximum gas production.', 'no', 'A quotation has been obtained to carry out the biodiversity study on the land to be used for planting. Until the land has been identified by the tribal authority (with DRD consent), this cannot be carried out.', 'no', 'Plant has not been constructed as yet.', 'It takes 3 years for the plant to reach a maturity that will allow consistent harvesting.', '', '', '6', 'project', '', 'no', 'no', 'no', '', '', '', '6', 'no', 'draft', 'no', 'EIA required for the production site; IWULA required, DoE registration required. Note: Due to the period between planting and harvesting maturity being 3 years, these applications will be carried out and approved.', 'Phalaborwa, Limpopo', '23', '51', '22', '30', '58', '44', 'no', '', 'no', 'no', '', 'no', '', '', 'no', '', '', 'EIA for primary production site - digesters, gas cleaning, power production. Biodiversity study on land to be planted to identify sensitive areas and endangered species. IWULA for the pumping of cactus pulp and water and the irrigation of digestate. Potential gas pipeline to supply mines in area. Overhead transmission line route.', '20', '23', '58', '36', '31', '5', '50', 'Unknown; on Bosveld Phosphates property', 'no', '', '', '', 'None', 'Transmission line will be required; potentially a gas pipeline will be required to supply PMC, Foskor and Bosveld Phosphates with gas.', 'Eskom', '48', 'not applicable', '100+', '420', '75.00', 'other than the engines, all other equipment can be locally fabricated; engineering fees will go to technology provided', '600', 'Co-products can produce animal feed fodder, food products, beverage grade CO2, potable alcohol, essential oil', '2013-07-11', '2013-07-12', 'true');
