elContractTime`, `financeType`, `nameOfLenders`, `commitmentNone`, `commitmentMandate`, `commitmentDeveloped`, `commitmentAgreed`, `commitmentUnderwritten`, `commitmentLevel`, `lenderContractTime`, `feasibilityStudy`, `feasibilityStudyCompleted`, `bankableModel`, `resourceStudy`, `siteLocation`, `siteGPSLongDD`, `siteGPSLongMM`, `siteGPSLongSS`, `siteGPSLatDD`, `siteGPSLatMM`, `siteGPSLatSS`, `rightsSecured`, `rightsSecuredDetails`, `environmentalAuthorisationRecieved`, `environmentalAuthorisationApplied`, `environmentalAuthorisationAppliedDate`, `zoningApplication`, `zoningApplicationSubmissionDate`, `zoningApplicationAnticipatedApproval`, `subdivisionApplication`, `subdivisionApplicationSubmissionDate`, `subdivisionApplicationAnticipatedApproval`, `authorizationOverview`, `couplingDistance`, `couplingGPSLongDD`, `couplingGPSLongMM`, `couplingGPSLongSS`, `couplingGPSLatDD`, `couplingGPSLatMM`, `couplingGPSLatSS`, `couplingName`, `eskomEstimateSubmitted`, `eskomEstimateSubmittedDate`, `eskomEstimateReceived`, `eskomEstimateReceivedRef`, `eskomSummary`, `upgradeSummary`, `eskomConnection`, `connectionTime`, `hostCountry`, `contributorStatus`, `localSpendings`, `localSpendingsPercentage`, `opportunitiesSummary`, `numberOfJobs`, `componentManufacturing`, `created`, `modified`, `done`) VALUES
(197, 210, 'Destiny Corporation Energy (Pty) Ltd', '+27118024036', 'Nkosi Gugushe', '1st Floor, Building 16, The Woodlands Office Park', '20 ', 'Woodlands Drive (Cnr. Kelvin Drive)', 'Woodmead', 'Johannesburg', '2191', 'nkosi@destinycorporation.co.za', 'Cape Town Floating Power Plant', 'The project aims to deploy a 256MW of open cycle gas turbine power plant in the port of Cape Town. The power plant will be barge mounted and will float in the sea moored to a sea wall within the port. It will be fired by LNG sourced from the international markets, including emergent and increasingly proximate African suppliers. LNG storage will be achieved with rapid deployment land side regasification terminals as well as on floating storage and regasification ships. The floating power plant will be within 10 km proximity to the diesel fired Acacia Peaking Power Plant, in Goodwood. It will also be within a 200 km radius to the Ankerlig Peaking Power Plant in Atlantis Industria.\r\n\r\nProximity to the existing Acacia and Ankerlig Peaking Power Plants potentially offers the these Peaking Power Plants the opportunity to convert some of their turbines to gas from diesel and thereby change these units to a base load plant whilst also achieving an improved environmental profile. On this basis, this project can technically be viewed as having the capability to provide 256MW of new power or, 300MW of gross cost effective base load power, if there is conversion to gas of some of the proposed diesel fired turbines at Acacia and/or Ankerlig. This will be achieved by the scaling done of the proposed Cape Town Floating Power Plant to 128MW and the utilisation of the excess LNG capacity in up to 400 MW of converted Acacia (171 MW) and Ankerlig (230 MW) turbines for base load power.\r\n\r\nThe main cost drivers for the project is the cost of the equipment and the cost of fuel. The major equipment components are priced in hard currency and are therefore subject to exchange rate fluctuations. The fuel is priced in hard currency and is subject to diesel indexation as well as exchange rate fluctuations. There is however, significant regional production of LNG already available, with more expected on stream in the next 10 years. This will provide opportunities for cost reduction through offset intra-regional trading.  \r\n\r\nThe open cycle gas turbines are aero-derivatives that have dual fuel capability, diesel and natural gas, as well as unlimited daily starts. The unlimited daily start capability mean that the power plants are able to perform across the spectrum of generating range, from peaking to base load. This generating flexibility is enhanced by the power plant''s moveable nature. As a moveable asset, the power plant is amenable to short-term peaking contracts, but retains base load capability.\r\n\r\nRapid deployment is achieved by a modular factory construction of the floating power plant that minimises onsite construction and commissioning risks. It is further achieved by utilising modular landside storage. There is significant scope to source land side storage equipment in South Africa. Finally, by locating the projects in harbours and ports, speed of execution is achieved by project''s typically staying within existing EIAs already granted to ports and other industrial facilities. This compliance with existing EIAs provides rational and justifiable opportunities for fast tracking projects through the traditional 18 month EIA processes.\r\n', 'GasPlant', 'OCGT', 'LNG', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '256', '128', '230', '80', '1.85', 'LNG / Diesel (Global traded prices)', '42', '', '', '', 'Quater4', '2014', 'From order with supplier to COD is 6 months', '12', 'baseload', '12', '31', '24', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'yes', 'Has the potential the replace up to 171 MW of diesel fired peaking capacity at the Acacia Peaking Power Plant (and potentially at the Ankerlig Peaking Power Plant), with 171 MW of base load gas fired power. Alternatively, has the potential to displace 171 MW of grid power consumed by industry by encouraging the development 172 MW of gas fired distributed generation through the development of a new gas reticulation network, initially in the Port of Cape Town, and surrounding commercial / industrial enterprises.', '3500', '20', '2100', '', 'LNG International prices / Diesel and CPI', 'yes', '', 'fastQ2-2013-12Months', '', '2', '12', 'Destiny Corporation Energy (Pty) Ltd', 'Destiny Corporation Energy, ASRY Centrax; Rolls Royce, Waller Marine, Ochre Energy Africa', 'Destiny Corporation Energy', 'ASRY Centrax; Rolls Royce, Waller Marine, Ochre Energy Africa', 'Our technology providers have delivered similar projects in numerous countries, as well as to the oil and gas industry worldwide. A notable project is the 342MW floating OCGT delivered and energised in Venezuela within a 6 month project implementation period.', '0', '0', '0', 'no', '', '', '', '', 69, 'Economic:\r\n\r\nThe project will generate employment both during construction (estimated 130 temporary positions) and operation (estimated 30 permanent positions). The majority of the temporary positions will be skilled artisanal positions, whilst the permanent positions will be highly skilled engineering and technician positions.\r\n\r\nThe project has the potential to catalyze the growth of the cryogenic component manufacturing in South Africa. The project has specifically selected to use technology for the onshore cryogenic storage of LNG that can be manufactured locally. Additionally, there is significant scope in any subsequent projects to localize the fabrication and power plant integration of the power barges. South Africa has a vibrant marine engineering industry, as well as the steel raw materials required to accomplish this. Destiny Corporation Energy’s technical partners and equipment suppliers have expressed an interest in establishing a local manufacturing presence in South Africa, to service the continental market. They are accordingly prepared to provide their proprietary engineering design and fabrication skills in to a localized manufacturing company.\r\n\r\nThe majority of the shares in the project are directly owned by South African entities and therefore will provide financial returns to these parties. The South African ownership is majority black/HDSA owned. The project thereby creates the opportunity for a black champion in the clean and renewable energy sector.\r\n\r\nThere are no existing projects using the envisaged technology in South Africa or Africa and the project will provide an opportunity for technological interaction and knowledge transfer to South African citizens., and the opportunity to export this knowledge from South Africa  in to the rest of the continent. That Destiny has identified a further +1000 MW in South Africa and +2000MW on the rest of the continent bodes well for the country.\r\n\r\nThere are no existing projects using the envisaged technology in South Africa or Africa and the project will provide an opportunity for technological interaction and knowledge transfer to South African citizens., and the opportunity to export this knowledge from South Africa  in to the rest of the continent. That Destiny has identified a further +1000 MW in South Africa and +2000MW on the rest of the continent bodes well for the country.\r\n\r\n2. Social: \r\n\r\nYes, the project will contribute significantly to the social upliftment and development of the people of South Africa and particularly in the project area, through the following: Through the creation of jobs both temporary and permanent, most of which will be from the local communities, the project activity will contribute to alleviation of poverty in the project area.\r\n\r\nBecause there are no similar technology installations in the area, the local people will require education and training in the operation and maintenance of the plant. This will enhance information sharing and skills transfer from foreign parties to the local community.\r\n\r\nThe creation of jobs, together with the wider impact of poverty alleviation will create a distribution of wealth within the local communities, with a direct and measurable improvement of health and quality of life for citizens of the local community.\r\n\r\n3. Environmental: \r\n\r\nThe project activity will take place on an existing industrial/Harbour or Port site, on unused open land within the greater plant operation covered by an original EIA. Therefore:\r\n\r\nThat the disturbance of ecosystems and loss of biological diversity are avoided, or where they cannot be avoided, are minimised and remedied. There will be minimal disturbance of any ecosystem or loss of biodiversity through the project activity. The selected site is on the existing industrial property between existing operational units with no active ecosystem or biodiversity constraints. That pollution and degradation of the environment are avoided, or where they cannot be altogether avoided, are minimised and remedied.\r\n\r\nBy increasing the natural gas based electricity component of the national grid, the project activity will have a positive impact on pollution by lowering national and local CO2, NOx and particulate matter emission levels.  There is scope within the project to recover and utilize the waste heat from the power plant and cooling energy from the LNG regasification.\r\n\r\nTherefore, there will be limited pollution or degradation of the environment through the project activity; in fact, there will be an improvement.\r\niii) That the disturbance of landscapes and sites that constitute the nation’s cultural heritage is avoided, or where it cannot be altogether avoided, is minimised and remedied.\r\nThere will be no disturbance of landscapes and sites that constitute the nation’s cultural heritage through the project activity as the selected site is within the boundary of the existing IFM industrial complex.\r\niv) That waste is avoided, or where it cannot be altogether avoided, minimised and reused or recycled where possible and otherwise disposed of in a responsible manner\r\nThe project activity will not generate any operating waste. Not even the usual inert building rubble typical of construction projects will be generated during construction. \r\nv) That the use and exploitation of non-renewable resources is responsible and equitable, and takes into account the consequences of the depletion of the resource\r\nThe project activity will only consume resources that have of late become abundant in South Africa, in SADC and in Africa. By also recycling waste heat and waste cooling the project will ensure that maximum utility or efficiency is achieved from these resources and thereby have a positive impact on the responsible use of these non-renewable resources.\r\nvii) That a risk averse and cautious approach is applied, which takes into account the limits of current knowledge about the consequences of decisions and actions\r\nPrior to construction the project activity will be scrutinized and monitored by the EIA consultants used by Destiny Corporation Energy for the overall plant development. In addition, a monitoring methodology forming part of the UNFCCC criteria for CDM registration has already been implemented and adhered to during operation. This same methodology will be extended to the proposed project\r\nvii) That negative impacts on the environment and on people’s environmental rights be anticipated and prevented, and where they cannot be altogether prevented, are minimised and remedied. There will be highly negative impacts on the environment and on people’s environmental rights through the project activity, when compared to the alternatives of using coal or diesel/HFO as a primary electricity generating fuel.\r\n', 'yes', 'no', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'no', '3', 'yes', 'yes', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'yes', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '3', 'project', '', 'no', 'yes', 'yes', 'no', '', '', '6', '', 'draft', 'no', 'LNG is a globally traded commodity, available in the quantities we need from our supplier', 'Cape Town, Western Cape', '18', '26', '17.63', '33', '54', '36.24', 'no', '', 'no', 'no', '', 'no', '', '', 'no', '', '', 'A generating license, and gas importation and transmission and hazardous materials storage licenses will be required. Approval and permitting to use the port may also be required from the National Ports Authority.', '20', '18', '32', '11.80', '33', '53', '03.91', 'Acacia, Goodwood', 'no', '', '', '', 'There has been no engagement with Eskom', 'Upgrades to the transmission lines may be required to evacuate the power', 'Eskom', '12', 'Located inside South Africa', '75-85', '500', '14.29', 'The project will require cryogenic equipment which can be sourced from South Africa. Such equipment will also require the use of South African Steel. Cabling to connect to the grid network would also be provided locally', '30', 'The project will require cryogenic equipment which can be sourced from South Africa. Such equipment will also require the use of South African Steel. Operations and maintenance will be localised within a 36 month period. This will require the recruitment and training of skilled engineers, mechanics and technicians. A plant monitoring and rapid response facility will be established in South Africa that will also require the recruitment and training of skilled personnel.', '2013-07-11', '2013-07-12', 'true'),
(199, 297, 'Vuselela Energy', '+27825686295', 'Jacques Malan', '1st Floor, Building A', ' 48', 'Sovereign Drive', 'R21 Corporate Park, Irene', 'Centurion', '0157', 'JMalan@Vuselela-Energy.com', 'Xstrata Lion ICE Project', 'Potential of generating up to 10 MW of electrical power from FeCr Furnace Offgas.\r\n\r\nProject can be generated within 10 Months from Financial Close', 'Reciprocating', 'Gas', 'ExistingGas', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '10.2', '1.7', '9.2', '90', '0.75', '8% per year', '37%', '', '', '', 'Quater4', '2014', '', '12', 'none', '12', '350', '24', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', 'Client is a large power user and power produced will offset consumption from Eskom', '190', '15', '750', 'PPA Term could be shorter e.g. 5 years but associated pricing to be negotiated.', '8% per year over the tearm', 'yes', '', 'fastQ2-2013-12Months', '', '2', '12', 'Vuselela Energy', 'GE Jenbacher', 'EPS Environmental and Process Solutions', 'GE', 'Vuselela''s personnel and Consortium Partners have been responsible for establishment of the 17MW plant for International Ferro Metals which has been operational since 2010 and the 8MW plant for SA Calcium Carbide which has been operational since 2012. Both of these are based on GE Jenbacher Engine Technology. Vuselela is also constructing a 5MW plant for Anglo Platinum at present based on ORC Technology. Profiles attached.  ', '0', '153000', '1860000', 'no', '', '', '', '', 26, 'Depending on the BEE partner selected and the financing arrangements, a portion of equity may be dedicated to a community trust.\r\n\r\nLocal communities will benefit from additional job creation in the project area.', 'no', 'no', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'no', '1', 'yes', 'no', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'yes', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '2', 'project', '', 'no', 'yes', 'no', '', '', '', '2', '', 'draft', 'yes', 'Current Studies are sufficient for the lenders, based on previous projects', 'Steelpoort, South Africa', '30°', '7''', '5.58"', '24°', '49''', '5.57"', 'yes', 'The site is located within the current operational borders of the FeCr smelter, with existing infrastructure and environmental compliance. Draft Deed of Use for identified plant location exists & can be executed within 2 months from bankable PPA.', 'no', 'no', '', 'no', '', '', 'no', '', '', 'Because of the plant size (10MW) a full EIA is not required but a BAR may be required. Nersa and Eskom Approval is also required.', '1', 'n/a', 'n/a', 'n/a', 'n/a', 'n/a', 'n/a', 'Proposal is to connect to internal grid on site.', 'no', '', '', '', 'No meetings was held but current proposal is based on similar experience on three other sites that was connect to the grid.', 'No', 'Internal Grid of Xstrata Lion', '12', 'n/a', '65-75', '90', '47.37', 'All peripheral equipment for the site will be manufactured in SA. Includes Civil, Structural, Platework, Ducting, Piping, Mechanical Equipment.', '200', 'If the population of Engines grow large enough, a local training centre will be set up to train South Africans to maintain these Engines. Operators for the project need to highly educated and local training will be created by the project.', '2013-07-11', '2013-07-12', 'true'),
(200, 260, 'William Ntsoana', '082-440-0661', 'Mandla Mthembu', 'Maxprop House, Office 1 & 2A', '98 ', 'Bulwer Road', 'Glenwood', 'Durban', '4001', 'mthembu.man@gmail.com', 'Coega Gas Plant', 'HFMT Investment Group (Pty) Ltd in collaboration with its technical partner and investor Southern California Telephone and Energy company (through its subsidiary called North Energy Central) intend to develop two 300 MW Gas Fired Power Plants at Coega Industrial Park and Richards Bay near the Coal Terminal. We plan to import natural gas from Mozambique and Namibia through the pipeline. The projects will be financed with debt and equity from OPIC, Power Africa Fund, and Private Equity Funds. The balance, if any, will be obtained from Southern California Telephone and Energy Company.\r\n\r\nRecent natural gas discoveries have energy experts forecasting Mozambique as the largest future producer of natural gas by 2020. These vast new supplies form the foundation for one of the single biggest opportunities for South Africa to introduce the next era of electric generation technologies. As a pioneer of the deregulated telecommunications industry of the nineties, Southern California Telephone & Energy (“SCT&E” or “Company”) emerged as one of the first successful privately held telephone companies in the United States. \r\nThe deregulation of the energy market today is nearly identical to the powerful events that occurred within the telecom industry. With key management personnel, an established customer base, clear vision to know exactly what direction to take, SCT&E has a road map for the coming changes in the energy markets. SCT&E has implemented high-impact innovations and improvements to the way energy is utilized. With an impeccable state and federal regulatory record and nineteen years of success, SCT&E is a:\r\n\r\nPrivately held and financially secure Utility;\r\nRegistered Electric Service Provider (ESP), one of only a handful in the State of California, the ninth largest economy in the world;\r\nCompany that maintains a Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) Authority, which entitles SCT&E to buy and sell energy nationwide in both the wholesale and retail markets, and;\r\nAuthorized provider of Natural Gas.\r\n\r\nUnderlying SCT&E’s push into electricity markets is the Company’s patent-pending Decentralized Energy Management System and Method, known as “Virtual Power Plant®” (VPP). Developed by savvy visionaries, industry-leading engineers and energy experts, the VPP is an artificial intelligence platform and method that offers energy load management, analytics and the ability to transform load into virtual generation resources.\r\n\r\nSCT&E’s new process patented “Battery Energy Reservoir™” (BER), and the VPP, together will assist customers to reduce costs by optimizing their energy usage and reselling surplus electricity to the grid when prices are high. Implementation of the VPP/BER system is scalable and can be deployed in mid-size businesses or entire cities. \r\n\r\nVirtual generators are quick to deploy, cost-effective and represent the most efficient readily available form of "green energy". SCT&E will turn energy expenses into new revenue resources, including the ability to develop “Micro-Grids” creating measurable income to customers 24 hours a day, seven days a week.\r\nNorth Energy Central (NEC)\r\n\r\nSCT&E acquired a majority interest in North Energy Central (NEC), a spinoff of ESA Associates Inc., an engineering, construction, and management firm with expertise in the deployment of environmentally friendly medium-to-large energy generation facilities. 4 The acquisition accelerated Company plans to build electric generation in both the United States and abroad.  With over forty years of expertise and credentials including construction and operation of nearly eighty power generation projects to the world’s electric power markets, NEC is a perfect fit.\r\n\r\nPrior to the acquisition, NEC had been working with the Dominican Republic towards the development of a 400 Megawatt (MW) power and Liquefied Natural Gas (LNG) receiving and storage facility. Two years in development with permitting, public hearings, environmental studies, land acquisitions, engineering, negotiations with public officials and fuel suppliers, NEC has signed contracts.\r\n\r\nNEC’s earliest years date back to 1983, helping public utilities address rising energy costs and critical environmental requirements. NEC has strategically combined this design and engineering expertise with the ability to develop independent power production and secure project financing. Integrating the company’s proprietary designs with proven technologies enables NEC to self-develop, build, own and operate efficient clean power projects. The NEC team of engineers and experts has developed a reputation of excellence.\r\n\r\nThe NEC acquisition complements SCT&E’s plans to acquire and build electric generation in both the United States and abroad. NEC’s projects include a diverse portfolio of resources that range from 3 to 1,100 MW using fossil (coal, gas, and oil) and alternative fuels, such as solar, gasification, biomass, LNG, hydro, geothermal and waste-to-energy, as well as advanced power storage technologies. NEC projects span over 25 US states and more than dozen countries world-wide.\r\n\r\nThe company seeks to develop projects that deliver reliable power, meeting the demand for new power generation while responding directly to the growing issues of the environment. NEC delivers without the expensive overhead or burdensome corporate red-tape, commonly associated with competitors’ solutions and generation.\r\nNEC incorporates advanced technology and equipment to significantly reduce air pollution to meet strict air standards anywhere in the world, regardless of the fuel type. NEC has developed power plants under some of the world''s toughest environmental mandates including the US Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), the California Air Resources Board (CARB), and South Coast Air Quality Management District (AQMD).  \r\n\r\nwww.northenergycentral.com\r\n \r\nSCT&E believes that “steel in the ground” such as generation facilities, energy storage and VPP optimization systems form the physical cornerstone of the Company’s energy business model. Built upon this foundation, SCT&E offers project financing, LNG manufacturing and innovative Maritime Solutions. SCT&E Maritime technologies include LNG delivery, floating storage, floating generation, and off-shore resource development. \r\n\r\nTogether with the Company’s FERC authority to buy and sell energy nationwide in both the wholesale and retail markets directly from the grid ensures the Company’s future as a bright prospect as a multi-national power house. With an accumulation of over 100 years of combined experience in the energy industry, the Company’s key executives and engineers developed specialized generation plant designs, structured electrical grids, and created energy efficiency technologies that meet the toughest emissions standards with the highest energy results. SCT&E and its subsidiary NEC continue to be at the forefront of energy intelligent design delivering large power generation and small distributed generation solutions that best fit the need of South Africa.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n', 'GasPlant', 'CCGT', 'LNG', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '400', '300', '375', '100', '1.99', '1', '100', '', '', '', 'Quater1', '2015', '', '3', 'baseload', '', '', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', '1000', '25', '1500', '', '3', 'yes', '', 'commitQ2-2014-Phased', '', '6', '3', 'Southern California Telephone & Energy', '', 'HFMT Investment Group (Pty) Ltd', 'Southern California Telephone & Energy', 'Recent natural gas discoveries have energy experts forecasting Mozambique as the largest future producer of natural gas by 2020. These vast new supplies form the foundation for one of the single biggest opportunities for South Africa to introduce the next era of electric generation technologies. As a pioneer of the deregulated telecommunications industry of the nineties, Southern California Telephone & Energy (“SCT&E” or “Company”) emerged as one of the first successful privately held telephone companies in the United States. \r\nThe deregulation of the energy market today is nearly identical to the powerful events that occurred within the telecom industry. With key management personnel, an established customer base, clear vision to know exactly what direction to take, SCT&E has a road map for the coming changes in the energy markets. SCT&E has implemented high-impact innovations and improvements to the way energy is utilized. With an impeccable state and federal regulatory record and nineteen years of success, SCT&E is a:\r\n?	Privately held and financially secure Utility;\r\n?	Registered Electric Service Provider (ESP), one of only a handful in the State of California, the ninth largest economy in the world;\r\n?	Company that maintains a Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) Authority, which entitles SCT&E to buy and sell energy nationwide in both the wholesale and retail markets, and;\r\n?	Authorized provider of Natural Gas.\r\nUnderlying SCT&E’s push into electricity markets is the Company’s patent-pending Decentralized Energy Management System and Method, known as “Virtual Power Plant®” (VPP). Developed by savvy visionaries, industry-leading engineers and energy experts, the VPP is an artificial intelligence platform and method that offers energy load management, analytics and the ability to transform load into virtual generation resources.\r\nSCT&E’s new process patented “Battery Energy Reservoir™” (BER), and the VPP, together will assist customers to reduce costs by optimizing their energy usage and reselling surplus electricity to the grid when prices are high. Implementation of the VPP/BER system is scalable and can be deployed in mid-size businesses or entire cities. Virtual generators are quick to deploy, cost-effective and represent the most efficient readily available form of "green energy". SCT&E will turn energy expenses into new revenue resources, including the ability to develop “Micro-Grids” creating measurable income to customers 24 hours a day, seven days a week.\r\nNorth Energy Central (NEC)\r\n\r\nSCT&E acquired a majority interest in North Energy Central (NEC), a spinoff of ESA Associates Inc., an engineering, construction, and management firm with expertise in the deployment of environmentally friendly medium-to-large energy generation facilities. 4 The acquisition accelerated Company plans to build electric generation in both the United States and abroad.  With over forty years of expertise and credentials including construction and operation\r\nof nearly eighty power generation projects to the world’s electric power markets, NEC is a perfect fit.\r\n\r\nPrior to the acquisition, NEC had been working with the Dominican Republic towards the development of a 400 Megawatt (MW) power and Liquefied Natural Gas (LNG) receiving and storage facility. Two years in development with permitting, public hearings, environmental studies, land acquisitions, engineering, negotiations with public officials and fuel suppliers, NEC has signed contracts.\r\n\r\nNEC’s earliest years date back to 1983, helping public utilities address rising energy costs and critical environmental requirements. NEC has strategically combined this design and engineering expertise with the ability to develop independent power production and secure project financing. Integrating the company’s proprietary designs with proven technologies enables NEC to self-develop, build, own and operate efficient clean power projects. The NEC team of engineers and experts has developed a reputation of excellence.\r\n\r\nThe NEC acquisition complements SCT&E’s plans to acquire and build electric generation in both the United States and abroad. NEC’s projects include a diverse portfolio of resources that range from 3 to 1,100 MW using fossil (coal, gas, and oil) and alternative fuels, such as solar, gasification, biomass, LNG, hydro, geothermal and waste-to-energy, as well as advanced power storage technologies. NEC projects span over 25 US states and more than dozen countries world-wide.\r\nThe company seeks to develop projects that deliver reliable power, meeting the demand for new power generation while responding directly to the growing issues of the environment. NEC delivers without the expensive overhead or burdensome corporate red-tape, commonly associated with competitors’ solutions and generation.\r\nNEC incorporates advanced technology and equipment to significantly reduce air pollution to meet strict air standards anywhere in the world, regardless of the fuel type. NEC has developed power plants under some of the world''s toughest environmental mandates including the US Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), the California Air Resources Board (CARB), and South Coast Air Quality Management District (AQMD).  \r\n \r\nwww.northenergycentral.com\r\n\r\nSCT&E believes that “steel in the ground” such as generation facilities, energy storage and VPP optimization systems form the physical cornerstone of the Company’s energy business model. Built upon this foundation, SCT&E offers project financing, LNG manufacturing and innovative Maritime Solutions. SCT&E Maritime technologies include LNG delivery, floating storage, floating generation, and off-shore resource development. Together with the Company’s FERC authority to buy and sell energy nationwide in both the wholesale and retail markets directly from the grid ensures the Company’s future as a bright prospect as a multi-national power house.\r\nWith an accumulation of over 100 years of combined experience in the energy industry, the Company’s key executives and engineers developed specialized generation plant designs, structured electrical grids, and created energy efficiency technologies that meet the toughest emissions standards with the highest energy results. SCT&E and its subsidiary NEC continue to be at the forefront of energy intelligent design delivering large power generation and small distributed generation solutions that best fit the need and environment as described in the following paragraphs.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n', '1000000000', '5000000000', '8000000000', 'no', '', '', '', '', 40, 'Local Communities of Richards Bay and Nelson Mandela Municipalities will have shares in the project. In addition, they will participate in the construction, operations, and maintenance of the projects.', 'no', 'no', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', '6', 'yes', 'no', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'yes', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '6', 'project', '', 'no', 'yes', 'no', 'yes', '', '', '6', '', 'draft', 'yes', 'There is no need for additional studies as the power plants will be assembled in the US. It takes about 12-18 months to assemble each power plant. The power plants will be temporarily installed on a barge until land has been made available. Each power plant requires 50 acre of land, next to the grid. The land has already been identified and secured.', 'Port Elizabeth, Northern Cape Province & Richards Bay, KZN Province, South Africa', '25', '1', 'S27 50.1551', '35', '1', 'S 27° 50'' 9.3084', 'yes', 'We have identified the land on which the power plants will be installed. However, we are still negotiating the lease agreements with both the Richards Bay IDZ and Coega IDZ. Furthermore, the power plants will be temporarily installed on a barge. This will give the project developers the ability to commission the power plant on time and within budget. In addition, it will allow them to move the power plants to any preferred locations. Once the land has been secured and approved, the power plant will be moved from the barge and permanently installed on the land.', 'no', 'no', '', 'no', '', '', 'no', '', '', 'The power plant will be based on a barge on a temporary or permanent basis depending on the agreements with the Richards Bay IDZ and Coega IDZ. Therefore, it is not necessary to install or develop the power plant on land. The land will be needed as a last resort. The power plant is designed to be operated from a barge or on land. It works effectively from both locations. The advantage of keeping it on a barge is that it will be commissioned quickly and cost effectively. Furthermore, it will give the owners the ability to move it to any location with ease.', '5', '25', '1', 'S 27° 50'' 9.3084', '35', '1', 'S 27° 50'' 9.3084', 'Richards Bay IDZ Sustation and Coega IDZ Substation', 'no', '', '', '', 'We had a conference call with Mr. Yousuf Haffejee, the Senior Development and Marketing Manager at Eskom. Mr. Haffejee guaranteed that the power plants on a barge will be approved by Eskom on condition we apply for the necessary licensing with the Department of Energy. Mr. Haffejee indicated that a gas fired power plant on a barge is the technology which Eskom supports and recommended Richards Bay IDZ and Coega IDZ as the best locations for such projects. Therefore, Eskom''s formal approval for these projects depends on IPP licensing by the Department of Energy.', 'None', 'Eskom', '3', 'N/A', '30-40', '400', '40.00', 'Project management, operations, and maintenance will be performed by South Africans. Fuel will be obtained from South African sources for the life of the projects.', '1500', 'Replacement parts will be manufactured in South Africa. Training centers will be established near the plants to transfer skills and technology. We will also provide scholarships for electrical engineers systems developers. Ultimately, we hope to manufacture these types of power plants and the barges on which they are installed under license in South Africa for distribution throughout the continent of Africa, South America, and Asia.', '2013-07-12', '2013-07-12', 'true'),
(201, 348, 'West Coast Power Consortium', '082-8892550', 'Chris Haines', 'Block D, Sunnyside Park', '1', 'Sunnyside Drive', 'Parktown', 'Johannesburg', '2194', 'chris.haines@novopower.co.za', 'Saldanha LNG terminal and CCGT Power Station', 'BRIEF DESCRIPTION\r\n\r\nThe West Coast Power Consortium (WCPC) comprising consortium members Samsung C&T, Novo Power (Pty) Ltd and KYD Consulting Engineers as the project developers submitted a response the the March 2012 RFI from the Dept of Energy (DoE) which comprised an LNG receiving terminal, and a 1 200MW baseload CCGT IPP proposal, \r\n\r\nThis proposal is now amended to include the LNG Receiving Terminal on a tolling basis, linked to a 2 000MW baseload CCGT IPP proposal, which would receive LNG, store the LNG and regasify the gas and use the gas in the CCGT power station as the anchor tenant. It is proposed that the WCPC assists the DoE in securing the LNG which will be procured on a government-to-government basis, and then uses the gas to sell power under a standard Power Purchase Agreement, which includes the tolling fee for the LNG terminal.\r\n\r\nSamsung C&T is proposed as the EPC contractor and Kepco and Kogas will be invited to join as potentially the equity and O&M partners for the CCGT IPP and the LNG terminal respectively. Samsung is confident that vendor financing can be secured from Korean ECAs.\r\n\r\nMAIN COST DRIVERS\r\n\r\nThe LNG terminal needs to be land based due to the proposed volume of LNG required, the need for both a marine and land based EIA process and the grid connection for the 2 000MW are the initial project cost drivers. \r\n\r\nThe design and construction of the LNG terminal and CCGT power station are well understood projects within the WCPC and its proposed partners, so the costs can be quickly provided under a direct procurement process.\r\n\r\nKEY DECISION POINTS\r\n\r\nAccess to suitable land is a key decision point. Land is currently being rented and discussions are underway with Accelor Mittal to procure some land, biut clarity from the DoE on the tender process is needed first.The ZAR/USD exchange rate and any need from the DoE to hedge would be a major concern. A decision from the DoE on how they wish to handle this aspect, including the escalation clause in the PPA is a major decision point.It is assumed at this point that National Treasury would provide the usual guarantees for the LNG procurement and the baseload PPA.\r\n\r\nUNUSUAL FEATURES\r\n\r\n\r\n', 'GasPlant', 'CCGT', 'LNG', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '2000', '400', '2000', '95', '1.20', 'ZAR/USD and CPI', '>60%', '', '', '', 'Quater4', '2017', 'A 12 month EIA process is planned, with a 36 month construction time for both the LNG terminal and the CCGT power station.', '48', 'baseload', '', '', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', '35000', '20', '1200', 'The above price does not include the tolling cost of the LNG terminal and needs to be added; more details will be provided later.', 'ZAR/USD', 'no', '', 'commitQ3-2013-Phased', '', '3', '48', 'West Coast Power Consortium ', '', 'Novo Power and KYD Consulting Engineers', 'Samsung C&T ', 'See attached Samsung C&T company profile', '0', '0', '0', 'no', '', '', '', '', 5, 'Local Community Trust to be established as part of the final bid', 'no', 'no', 'yes', 'no', 'no', '', 'no', '9', 'no', '', '', '', '', '', 'no', 'Detailed discussions have been held with the following potential suppliers: Anadarko, Cheniere, Kogas, AngolaLNG, Qatar, but all require better clarity from DoE on the way forward, including a decision on the LNG receiving terminal', 'no', '', 'no', 'LNG would be secured from an international supplier that has an existing LNG liquefaction train or is planning to produce LNG for export within the proposed project timeframes', 'From 2017/8 onwards in the region. Spot LNG can be secured prior to this.', '', '', '9', 'project', '', 'no', 'no', 'no', '', '', '', '9', 'no', 'draft', 'yes', 'No, additional studies would be needed for lenders. A high level pre-feasibility study has bene done and a detailed feasibility study will be completed shortly after positive feedback from the DoE on the tender process going forward. Additional studies would include the EIA process, the initial design and selection of the gas turbine supplier based on the site, the grid connection and servitude studies and initial feedback on the type of PPA offered.', 'Saldanha Bay, Western Cape', '18', '04', '45.9', '32', '51', '5.20', 'yes', 'There is an option to purchase a 150ha site within the Saldanha Bay IDZ and land rental is being paid, but land closer to the port would be beneficial. Discussions are in process with Accelor Mittal and TNPA and will be fast tracked based on a positive decision from the DoE.', 'no', 'no', '', 'yes', '31/08/2013', '28/02/2014', 'yes', '31/08/2013', '31/08/2014', 'The submission date will be dependent upon positive feedback from the DoE on the submission. Twelve months is proposed for the EIA process, which will include the water usage application and licence, the specialist studies and public participation required under the EIA process and rezoning from agricultural land to industrial use. The EIA process will be in two parts, one for the LNG receiving terminal which will be both marine and land based and which requires support from TNPA and the CCGT power station which will be only land based. TNPA and Eskom consultation  with DoE would be needed on such a large capital project. NERSA licences for gas storage, gas transmisison and power generation would also be needed.', '3.5', '18', '02', '55', '32', '58', '54.8', 'Blouwater Substation', 'no', '', '', '', 'ONly high level discussions with Eskom Western Cape previously. Also discussed the possibility with the Western Cape Provincial government', 'A transmission upgrade would be necessary for the full 2000MW, but can possibly be done in two phases. Upgrades to the transmission network in the area, including the line to the Aurora substation are planned in the latest Eskom Transmission Network Upgrade Plan.', 'Connection to Eskom is planned', '48 ', 'Located in South Africa', '30-40', '12500', '35.71', 'Steel fabrication, manufacturing of key components for the power station, civil works, balance of plant and detailed engineering design and support to these items', '5000', 'A centre of excellence for LNG, natural gas and gas power skills training and transfer is needed', '2013-07-12', '2013-07-12', 'true'),
(202, 218, 'Bio2Watt', '27794966725', 'Sean Thomas', 'Cedar Lakes', '584', 'Cedar Avenue', 'Fourways', 'Johannesburg', '2191', 'sean@bio2watt.com', 'Cape Dairy Biogas Project', 'The Cape Dairy Biogas Project is a waste to energy project making use of well proven anaerobic digestion technology.\r\n\r\nThe project will be situated on the largest dairy farm in South Africa just outside Malmesbury, the primary fuel supply which is cattle manure and the land has been secured via an agreement with the owner of the farm. Discussions are underway with Roelcor and various other large waste producers in the area to secure other feedstock. The  facility is proposed as a sustainable solution to dispose of waste so other than the cattle manure the project will not pay for feedstock. The distance from the main waste producers will determine the viability for the waste producers as transportation plays a significant cost with regards to waste disposal.\r\n\r\nWe are now 2/3 into the EIA and are due to complete the specialist environmental studies by end of September, the EIA will be issued early 2014 after which we expect to take less than 6 months to reach financial closure and start construction.\r\n\r\nThe power capacity from the manure on site is 1MW and we intend to provide a baseload of power of at least 3MW by co-digesting with other feedstocks. A 100 000 head pig farm will also be built at less than 5km from the biogas plant.\r\n\r\nSupporting documents are available to the Department.', 'Other', '', '', '', 'Anaerobic Digestion - biogas', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '4.2', '1', '4', '95', '0.75', 'CPI', '42%', '', '', '', 'Quater1', '2015', 'For biogas technology it is extremely difficult to have an accurate COD given that reaching a steady state is dependent on the bacteria within the digester', '14', 'baseload', '', '', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', '100', '20', '1200', '', 'CPI', 'yes', '', 'commitQ2-2014-Phased', '', '4', '15', 'Bio2Watt', 'Combigas', 'Bosch Projects', 'Combigas', 'Bio2Watt is due to start construction of the first commercial scale biogas in August this year in Bronkhorstspruit, the project will have an installed capacity of 4.2MW and will be a baseload supply in the national grid to BMW in Rosslyn. The plant will be operation mid-2014.', '2000000', '4000000', '4000000', 'no', '', '', '', '', 25, 'Not yet identified but is most definitely an option with farm workers', 'yes', 'yes', 'yes', 'no', 'no', '', 'no', '3', 'yes', 'yes', 'no', '', 'yes', '31/03/2015', 'yes', '', 'no', 'currently we are 2/3 into the EIA', 'yes', '', '', '', '', '3', 'project', '', 'yes', 'no', 'no', '', '', '', '3', 'yes', 'draft', 'yes', 'Bio2Watt has completed most of the pre-feasibility studies which included high level availability of feedstock over and above the manure, has confirmed with Eskom access to the grid, and confirmed the availability of spent water from farms internal processes to use in the digestion process. However, commercial arrangements need to be finalised with waste producers to secure the full feedstock required to operate the plant and this will be required by lenders.', 'Malmesbury, Western Cape, South Africa', '33', '21', '46.98', '18', '36', '55.35', 'yes', 'An agreement has indeed been signed with the owner of the farm to secure the site, the cattle manure as well as the spent water from the farms operations. Hard copy will be made available to DoE.', 'no', 'yes', '31/01/2012', 'no', '', '', 'no', '', '', 'The project will need a Consent of Use from the municipality as we will be doing a non-agricultural activity on agricultural land. A Generation License which will be applied for once PPA is signed. A Waste License in order to be able to receive and process the waste. an Air Emission License from the municipality which only takes a couple of months to receive. Water Use License where we have done initial consultation and appointed an officer.', '3', '18', '37', '50.9', '33', '21', '25.4', 'Vyvlei Substation, Malmesbury', 'yes', '01/02/2011', 'yes', 'reference 416975723', 'The original cost estimate included a proportional cost for the substation which the project cannot afford. Following discussions with Eskom this request has been shelved given the stage of the project official meetings have not yet taken place with Eskom.', 'The project will be able to connect at full capacity once the new Vyvlei Substation has been built before end of 2013.', 'The project will be connecting to Eskom Distribution.', '15', 'Project is in South Africa', '65-75', '54', '54.00', 'Local content will be greater than 50% so there will be opportunities for local manufacturing we have not yet identified which ones', '30', 'Bio2Watt has been working very closely with UCT and will continue to do so in the future in order to showcase biogas as a viable renewable energy technology to develop in communities and around large cities in order to sustainably dispose of waste while generating power and creating green jobs.', '2013-07-12', '2013-07-12', 'true');
