(203, 379, 'Phindile Masangane', '0102014744', 'Phindile Masangane', 'Block C, CEF House', '152 ', 'Ann Crescent ', 'Strathavon', 'Johannesburg', '2031', 'phindilem@cefgroup.co.za', 'Cape Cleaner Energy Solutions ', 'The George Woodwaste Project is an 8.8MW biomass (wood waste) to electricity generation project (“the Project”).\r\nThe Project is being developed by  CEF (SOC) Ltd currently a 81.5% shareholding partner in the Project’s special purpose vehicle called Cape Clean Energy Solutions PTY) Ltd  (“CCE”).  CEF (SOC) Ltd is a state owned entity solely owned by the Department of Energy. The remaining 18.5 % of CCE is owned by C&EO the original Project developers. CCE will sell its project rights to an IPP compliant with the bid requirements.\r\nThe Project site is the Sonae Novobord stand at the industrial area of George in the Eastern Cape. The project requires 110 000 tonnes (at 45% moisture content, assuming an energy content of 12.7 MJ/kg) of woodwaste per year to generate 8.8 MW of electricity, therefore  CCE need to secure a long term (at least 10 years) fuel supply agreements with potential suppliers of woodwaste. \r\n\r\nForestry Solutions (PTY) Ltd has been retained by CCE to undertaken an independent study on the woodwaste availability from the three classes of supply for the Project:\r\n1.	Commercial sawmills – these companies will supply uniform, readily prepared fuel for the plant.  The supply is from a fixed site, making transport logistics easy to plan for.  In-principal agreements for fuel supply have been secured from PG Bison, Geelhoutvlei and PSP timbers for a total of 50,000 tonnes per annum has been secured. Fuel supply agreements are being finalised with these companies. \r\n\r\n2.	Working for Water – the Department of  Environmental Affairs supports the CCE Project. The department has two contractors engaged for the Working for Water initiative in the George areas. Negotiations for the off-take of the biomass to the Project will commence shortly with the Working for Water contractors, both of whom have confirmed that the biomass is available. \r\n\r\nInitial indications are that as much as 250,000 tonnes of biomass is available from accessible, high dense areas of invasive alien plants within 150km radius of the Project site. If harvested over a 5 year period, this biomass can supply 25% of the Project requirements. The biomass needs to be treated (chipped to the plant size requirement) and transported from different areas. The logistical arrangements for this class of supply is challenging and needs to be carefully managed. This supply though brings the opportunity for massive job creation for the George area. \r\n\r\n \r\n3.	Forest thinning and forest waste – the commercial pine plantations are periodically thinned and after harvesting, a significant amount of biomass from the branches, tree stumps and leaves is left behind in the forest. Negotiations with two companies specialising in the harvesting of forest thinnings and forest waste are underway to have these companies supply the biomass to the Project. \r\n\r\nLike the Working for Water initiative, the biomass from forest thinning and forest waste needs preparation (chipping to small sizes) and logistics needs to be planned carefully. \r\nForestry Solutions (PTY) Ltd will review the biomass availability from these 3 classes of supply as well as its sustainability for the next 15 years. Forestry Solutions (PTY) Ltd is a reputable forestry planning/consulting company that has undertaken forestry planning of operations and resource requirements, integrated resource management systems for forestry and sawmill operations, alien invasive weeds: planning and clearing productivity standards for blue-chip companies and national government departments. The woodwaste supply report will be reviewed by a different reputable woodwaste supply chain consulting company as per the RE IPP bid requirements.\r\n\r\nkey decision points for the project are that CEF, 