(210, 132, 'Satarem', '0827634630', 'Thea Venter', 'None', '23', 'Loofboom', 'Terenure', 'Kempton Park', '1619', 'thea.venter@satarem.com', 'WTE Satarem', 'The Ultimate Renewable Energy Alternative\r\n\r\nSatarem is hoping to introduce and highlight a sustainable renewable energy resource that has not yet been seriously considered in South Africa, which is Waste To Energy (WTE) technology. A typical WTE plant involves feeding waste of at least 1200kcal/kg calorific value to combustion units where it is ignited using oil burners (running on diesel as supplemental fuel) before being transferred to boilers as fumes. High pressure steam generated by the boilers will be used to drive condensing steam turbines and electric generators to produce power.\r\n\r\nAs a result of continuous economic growth, urbanization and industrialization, both municipal solid waste management and electricity availability, for example, are becoming burgeoning problems in this country. Waste collection has been well recorded but not efficiently managed. \r\nOnly a few landfills in Gauteng, where about 45% of South Africa’s municipal waste is managed (DEA, 2012), have more than a 10 year lifespan remaining (GDACE, 2008). The City of Cape Town, contributing 70% of the municipal waste in the Western Cape, is also running out of landfill airspace (DEADP, 2011). \r\n\r\nFigures from the DEA (2012) (National Waste Information Baseline Report)\r\n108 million tonnes - Total waste generated\r\n98 million tonnes- Waste landfilled\r\n59 million tonnes- General waste\r\n48 million tonnes – Unclassified waste\r\n1 million tonnes - Hazardous waste\r\nApproximate 10 percentage of total waste that is recycled\r\nAccording to these statistics and working conservatively at 100 000 tons of waste a day Satarem could produce 1200MW of power through WTE technology.\r\nIt should be noted that protecting the environment is a precondition of efficient economic growth. Most waste that is collected is either burnt or dumped in landfills. Studies have been done for power generation from landfill gas but landfills have the following disadvantages: they are environmental and health hazards through land, ground water and air pollution. They also lead to safety hazards because of spontaneous burning of the garbage; a major source of dioxin emission, as well as landfill gas explosions. In addition, landfills are not highly sustainable because they occupy large ground area, require leach prevention and need leachate treatment. Using WTE helps eliminate landfills while utilizing fuel (waste) that is guaranteed to increase in volume because waste generation rates increase with the population increase.\r\n\r\nThe most common solution to landfills are compromised incinerators which are advantageous because they lead to energy recovery while reducing the waste volume and occupy less space than landfills. Studies have shown that it is possible to generate power from the landfill gas (methane) but this is disadvantageous because of the following reasons:\r\n\r\n-dioxin re-formation in flue gas\r\n-toxic fly ash to manage\r\n-high CAPEX and OPEX\r\n-Not flexible in throughput\r\n-usually dedicated for specific waste types\r\n\r\nSATAREM Enterprises, however, developed the ultimate WTE system known as M-WTE (Multipurpose Reactor enhanced Waste-to-Energy). M-WTE is a WTE process enhanced by cement processing technology through adoption of cement calcination process, a one-step secondary combustion and, high temperature acid gas scrubbing of the flue gas.     SATAREM  uses  a  multipurpose  reactor  based  on  an  advanced  technology  that  was developed over years of research and development in the early 2000s.\r\nThe technology is a WTE process enhanced with a calcination process to create a Multi- Purpose Reactor (MPR). It is a combination of proven technologies and can be divided into four major sections namely: incineration, energy recovery,Flue Gas Treatment (and Waste water treatment. - Full explanations and references will be in presentation attached \r\n\r\nThis technology has been tested and patented and carries all required certification to treat waste and generate green power. It is designed for low cost maintenance and high availability and has the following advantages over conventional WTE processes:\r\nIt offers Enhanced energy conversion efficiency from waste calorific value to electricity\r\nthrough an elevated heat exchange temperature at the super-­?heater.\r\nIt eliminates the independent acid scrubber through a one-step secondary combustion chamber with a high temperature acid gas scrubbing function for the flue gas.\r\nStudies showed that it more than meets EU emission standards.\r\n It prevents dioxin reformation instead of management of dioxins upon formation. This leads to lower operating costs as there’s no need for an active carbon injection unit (needed for dioxin removal).\r\nIt incurs lower capital Costs as it is versatile-a single facility for destruction of a variety of waste types, amounts and quality: MSW, sludge, (and even woodchips).\r\nIt offers upside income potentials, i.e. re-­?use of combined ash (bottom ash + MPR reagent + dioxin free fly ash) as construction material to brick making or cement processing raw material thus avoiding need for stabilization and secure landfilling.\r\n\r\n  \r\n', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '2013-07-12', '0000-00-00', ''),
(211, 79, 'Cennergi', '00 27 12 675 66', 'Wendy Green', 'Block A Lakefield Office Park', '272', 'West Avenue', 'Centurion', 'Centurion', '0157', 'wendy.green@cennergi.com', 'Kotongweni Hydro', 'This RFRI presents the findings of a pre-feasibility study into establishing a hydro power station on the Tugela River at Kotongweni, 40km east of Tugela Ferry in KwaZulu-Natal province.\r\nThe project involves the construction of a 100m high dam to generate hydro-electricity through the continuous release of between 36.7 m³/s and 41.4 7 m³/s of water. The amount of power generated is dependent on the number of turbines installed; initial analysis has indicated that the Hydro power station will be able to generate 146 MW of power. This will translate into 511 GWh per annum of energy at a uniform selling price.  \r\nWhile the preliminary study has shown the project to be technically and economically viable, the hydrology analysis needs to be extended to confirm the available yield from the dam. It will furthermore also be necessary to investigate water use rights, environmental impacts as well as the social and political viability of the Project', 'Hydro', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '146', '100', '146', '40', '1.05', 'full indexation', '', '', 'Greater than six hours', '', 'Quater2', '2018', '', '48', 'mid-merit', '12', '365', '9', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', '2600', '30', '1050', '', 'Full', 'yes', '', 'commitQ2-2014-Phased', '', '3', '48', 'Cennergi with SMEC providing technical support', 'Not determined yet', 'Cennergi', 'SMEC through its local subsidiary', 'Cennergi is currently constructing two wind farms in South Africa.\r\nSMEC is an internationally known Engineering consultancy with significant hydro power project development experience.', '0', '0', '0', 'no', '', '', '', '', 20, 'There will be Community Involvement - structure still to be determined.', 'no', 'no', 'no', 'no', 'no', 'no', 'no', '6', 'no', 'no', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'yes', 'This is a h