(216, 191, 'Ubu Investment Holdings Pty Ltd', '012 940 0266', 'Ms Portia Molefe', '8 Cambridge Office Park ', '5 ', 'Bauhinia Road', 'Centurion', 'Pretoria', '0046', 'portiam@ubuholdings.co.za', 'Ubu Holdings Eastern Cape Power Generation Project ', 'Ubu Investment Holdings has pleasure in submitting the high-level description of the Development Plan for a power station in the Eastern Cape. \r\n\r\nUBU HOLDINGS DEVELOPMENT OF A 600MW COAL-FIRED POWER STATION IN EASTERN CAPE \r\n\r\n1	SUMMARY\r\n\r\nUbu Investment Holdings in partnership with Vuwa Investments (Pty) Ltd plans to develop a thermal coal-fired power project which will utilise coal derived from the Elitheni coal project in the Indwe/Molteno area of the Eastern Cape located within the Chris Hani district Municipality. \r\n\r\nThe project is currently at concept stage and this report provides a high level strategic overview of the various project development stages that have been planned to bring the project to fruition in the context of the Department of Energy’s future plans in respect of Independent Power Production from coal, hydro and gas sources. \r\n\r\n\r\n2	PROJECT BACKGROUND\r\n\r\n2.1	Overview \r\n\r\nThe Eastern Cape coalfields have recently been redeveloped by Elitheni Coal of which Vuwa, Ubu’s partner in the project, is a shareholder. \r\n\r\nIn the context of the national strategic power development plans as promulgated through the IRP 2010, which envisages the need for additional Independent Power Production, a portion of which will be derived from thermal/coal, Ubu has embarked on the investigation and development of a coal fired power plant which would utilise this resource.\r\n\r\nIt is envisaged that the project would be in the range 200-600 MwTh.\r\n\r\nThe location of such a project in the northern part of the Eastern Cape in addition to addressing the primary power demands both on a national and regional basis will have numerous additional developmental benefits and is entirely consistent with the National Infrastructure Plan.\r\n\r\nThe project is intended as a Built-Own-Operate project in which the Ubu/Vuwa Partnership would stay on as an active shareholder beyond the investment stage.  \r\n\r\n2.2	Fuel source \r\n\r\nVuwa, Ubu’s partner in the project, is a shareholder in Elitheni Coal. Through Vuwa, the power station would ensure fuel supply security. The current Elitheni coal resources are around 150 million tonnes with a potential additional 50 million tonnes based on recent drilling results. The table below indicates coal qualities. \r\n\r\n\r\n	 \r\nElitheni Coal\r\n \r\n	 \r\nTypical Coal Specification Sheet\r\n \r\n 	Analysis	Symbol	Unit	4000 kcal/kg (GAD)	5000-5500 kcal/kg (NAR)	6000 kcal/kg NAR)\r\nProximate Analysis	Ash (Air dried)	Aad	%	40-45	25-30	<18\r\n	Volatile (Air dried)	Vad	%	8-12	8-12	8-12\r\n	Inherit Moisture	Mad	%	2.3	1.6	1.6\r\n	Fixed Carbon (Air dried)	FCad	%	40-45	60-65	68-72\r\n						\r\n\r\n\r\nThe power station will be built around the Elitheni coal quality.  \r\n\r\nThe project is currently at basic concept stage and this report provides a summary of the work planned to develop the project to implementation.\r\n\r\n2.3	Water source \r\n\r\nThe plans for the Eastern Cape Province include the building of a new dam with a potential capacity of 600 million cubic meters in the Ntabelanga area on the Tsitsa River, with construction starting in 2014. Water available in the area of the power plant site will be augmented by water from the dam. \r\n\r\n2.4	Transmission\r\n\r\nIn order to ensure easy access to the transmission grid, the project will target a location in proximity of the nearest main transmission substation at Delphi. \r\n\r\n2.5	Tariff\r\n\r\nOur high-level financial modelling study has revealed a tariff cost of USDc10.9/kWh (based on an exchange rate of R9.5/USD) for a 250MW station.\r\n\r\n2.6	Partners\r\n\r\nAlong with Vuwa, Ubu has struck strategic alliances with GIBB Engineering and Basil Read Energy, who will be the technical partners on the project and will assist with the project work in the following phases of the preparation. \r\n  \r\n2.7	Request from Department of Energy \r\n\r\nThe Ubu/Vuwa Partnership would like to request that, on condition that the project parameters and scope meet the required expectations, the Department of Energy issue a letter of intent indicating interest in the project. Based on this, the Partnership would be able to progress to the next project preparation phase. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n3	PROJECT DEVELOPMENT PLAN\r\n\r\nThe proposed project will be developed in four discrete phases \r\n\r\n•	Pre-feasibility\r\n•	Full feasibility leading to “bankable” status\r\n•	Construction/commissioning\r\n•	Commercial Operations\r\n\r\nThe envisaged total project development duration up to grid synchronisation and commercial operation in is conservatively expected to be 3-5 years (as illustrated in Fig 1.0 at the end of the document) though the potential for fast tracking is being evaluated.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n3.1	Pre-feasibility \r\n\r\nDuring the pre-feasibility stage the project will be subject to a further options analysis and review so as to eliminate the possibility of fatal flaws and to identify high level project-risks and mitigation strategies. This stage will also provide confirmation on the economic viability and developmental benefits of the project. Specifically it will address:\r\n\r\n3.1.1	Siting and Fuel Supply: \r\nAnalysis of the feasibility of mine mouth location versus other options (i.e. coastal) and associated fuel transport and logistics implications\r\n\r\n3.1.2	Technology and Phasing Analysis: \r\nAnalysis of the cost/benefits of competing technologies will be undertaken including but not limited to\r\n\r\n•	comparison between supercritical or sub-critical technology\r\n•	air cooled versus hybrid versus water cooled technology\r\n•	boiler/module numbers/sizes and options for project phasing\r\n•	pollution abatement options\r\n•	transmission grid connection assessments\r\n\r\n3.1.3	Economic and Financial Analysis:\r\nEstimation of capital costs including land costs, generation plant costs and pollution control equipment to meet regulations, fuel and operations/maintenance costs. Estimation of levelised costs of energy and the determination of economic and cost reflective tariffs to ensure financial viability.\r\n\r\n3.1.4	Environmental Analysis: \r\nPreliminary environmental analysis and impact scoping covering all project activities from construction of the power plant transmission, connections associated works, to  its eventual operation. Scoping would also cover qualitative assessment of the impacts on air, flora and fauna, land (ash dumps) and ground/surface water bodies and comparison with legislative standards.\r\n\r\nIt is proposed that, in order to assess the environmental feasibility of the power plant, transmission connections and associated networks, a desktop environmental scan would be undertaken to identify potential environmental issues of concern. This environmental scan can further be utilised as a planning tool by incorporating the environmental constraints identified into the proposed layout. \r\n\r\nThe environmental scan will also assist in identifying listed activities in terms of relevant environmental legislation requiring authorisation. Potential issues that may trigger listed activities along the proposed route may include:\r\n\r\n•	    Wetland habitats\r\n•	    Indigenous vegetation\r\n•	    Water courses\r\n•	    Rerouting of services (electrical cabling, pipelines)\r\n•	    Waste management (ash dumps)\r\n\r\n3.1.5	Social Impact Analysis: \r\nHigh level assessment of the social impact including but not limited to employment opportunities, economic development, fuel supply issues, localisation considerations, construction labour issues, residual impacts associated with temporary employment, and any other development benefits that could result from the project.\r\n\r\nThe findings will be subjected to a sensitivity analysis exercise, especially regarding its sensitivity to key variables such as the levelised cost as a determinant of the project’s economically viable tariff structure.\r\n\r\nIt is estimated that this stage would take about 3-6 months.\r\n\r\nFollowing this stage a determination will be made to proceed to full feasibility.\r\n\r\n\r\n3.2	Full Feasibility Leading to Bankable Status\r\n\r\nAssuming a positive pre-feasibility result the project will be taken to full feasibility. During this stage all the above aspects will be developed to the stage necessary to reach bankable status and include specifically:\r\n\r\n \r\n•	Development of the project structure\r\n•	Development of funding structure and arrangements\r\n•	Selection of EPC and O&M partner\r\n•	Selection of equipment suppliers\r\n•	Development of concept/basic design and production of class A cost \r\nestimates\r\n•	Full Environmental Impact Assessments and associated record of decisions\r\n•	Agreement of Power Purchase agreements\r\n•	Grid connection agreements and code compliance demonstration\r\n\r\nIt is estimated that this stage would take 6-12 months dependent largely on the time for the Environmental Impact Assessment process.\r\n\r\nFollowing the above it is anticipated the project would be in aposition to reach financial close.\r\n\r\n3.3	Construction/Commissioning and Operations \r\n\r\nFollowing financial close it is expected that the project would be able to proceed rapidly to construction which is expected would have a duration of approximately 2-3 years  until it reaches the point of grid synchronisation.\r\n\r\nFull power and commercial operation can be expected 6-12 months later.\r\n\r\n\r\n', 'Cogeneration', 'Coal', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '600', '200', '600', '65', '103.8', 'tbd', 'tbd', '', '', '', 'Quater2', '2016', '', '36', 'baseload', '12', '365', '24', 'yes', '', 'no', '', 'no', '', '2000', '25 ', '1030', '', '7', 'no', '', 'commitQ2-2014-Phased', '', '3', '6', 'Ubu Investment Holdings ', 'GIBB Engineering, Basil Read Energy ', 'Vuwa Investments, GIBB, Basil Read Energy ', '0', 'see company profiles', '11000000', '1100000', '4500000', 'no', '', '', '', '', 75, 'There will be extensive community invovlement and local supplier procurement plans in place after the prefeasibility and high level environmental scoping study done. ', 'no', 'yes', 'no', 'no', 'no', 'no', 'no', '6', 'yes', 'no', 'no', '', 'no', '', 'yes', '', 'yes', '', 'no', '', '', '', '', '6', 'project', '', 'no', 'no', 'no', 'no', 'no', '', '6', 'no', 'none', 'no', 'Upon receiving a letter of intent from the DOE we will be abel to progress into the prefeasibility stage. ', 'Eastern Cape, Indwe', '0', '0', '0', '0', '0', '0', 'no', '', 'yes', 'no', '', 'yes', '', '', 'no', '', '', 'to be determined', '100', '0', '0', '0', '0', '0', '0', 'Delphi', 'no', '', '', '', 'not applicable', 'to be determined', 'Eskom', '24', 'not appplicable', '55-65', '200', '10.00', 'balance of plant ', '150', 'to be determined ', '2013-07-12', '2013-07-12', ''),
